%TITLE Help on how to use %w%l"feeling" commands%x
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l<FEELING> <NAME> [= <PARAMETERS>]
        <FEELING> [<PARAMETERS>]%]%x

There are two types of "feeling" commands on %@%n:

%4%r%l*  %xFeeling commands which require a character's name ('%g%l<FEELING> <NAME> [= <PARAMETERS>]%x'), such as '%g%lmoose <NAME>%x', '%g%lhug <NAME>%x', etc. (These feeling commands are listed in '%g%l%<feelings%>%x' with a '%y%l*%x' to left of their name, and most of these can be given an optional second parameter, e.g:  '%g%lhug <NAME> = warmly%x', etc.

%4%y%l*  %xFeeling commands which can be typed without any parameters ('%g%l<FEELING> [<PARAMETERS>]%x'), such as '%g%lwave%x', '%g%lwibble%x', '%g%llaugh%x', '%g%lgiggle%x', etc. (Most of these can be given an optional parameter, e.g:  '%g%lwibble excessively%x', '%g%llaugh loudly%x', '%g%lgiggle happily%x', etc.)

The best way to find out how feeling commands work, is to try them out for yourself:  Have a look at '%g%l%<feelings%>%x' and then try out those which appeal to you.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<feelings%>%x'.

