%c%l%$Miscellaneous...
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xTCZ has exceeded all of my original expectations, and there's very little in my original dream of writing the 'ultimate' MUD which hasn't been achieved.  Even after so many years of development, TCZ still presents a steady stream of new programming challenges, along with the enjoyment of implementing them  -  I look forward to continuing the development of the TCZ source code for many years to come, along with help from others now that TCZ is public open source code released under the %c%lGNU General Public License (%c%lGPL%x)  -  See '%g%l%<gpl%>%x'.

%PAGE

%c%l%$TCZ facts...
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~
%4%y%l*  %xTCZ is pronounced "%y%ltea-sea-zed%x"!

%4%r%l*  %xTCZ's first ever users were:  %y%lJC Digita%x, %y%lRatty%x, %y%lDiceman%x, %y%lUK1%x and %y%lThe Captain%x.

%4%y%l*  %xTCZ's first ever overseas user to be promoted to Admin (%y%lApprentice Wizard%x) status was:  %y%lPrice%x (Now known as %c%lSteve%x.)

%4%r%l*  %xTCZ went on-line for the first time at its %c%lLasermoon%x site on %y%l28th November 1994%x at %y%l6pm%x (%y%lGMT%x)

%4%y%l*  %xTCZ's first ever peak of over %c%l100 users%x occurred on %y%l28th November 1995%x at %y%l5:26pm%x (%y%lGMT%x)  -  Almost exactly one year after TCZ first opened to the public.

%PAGE
%4%r%l*  %xAs of %y%l12th August 1996%x, there were over %c%lhalf a million%x connections to TCZ, and over %c%l35,000%x characters created since %y%lMarch 1995%x (When recording of statistical data was first implemented.)  The highest ever peak so far is currently %y%l122 users simultaneously%x.

%4%y%l*  %xOn %y%lSunday 22nd June 1997%x, %c%lone million connections%x to %@%m was reached.

%4%r%l*  %xThe longest recorded uptime of TCZ (Total running time, without being shutdown for a code update, shutdown by a power failure or crashing) is well over %y%l7 months%x.

%4%y%l*  %xThe %y%lTCZ 2000 Project%x commenced on %c%l11th April 1999%x.  This ended nearly %c%lfive years%x of sole maintenance and development by %y%lJ.P.Boggis%x (Aka %y%lJC Digita%x) by introducing %y%lSimon A. Boggis%x (Aka %y%lBadpenny%x) to the source code and the creation of plans for TCZ's long term future.

%PAGE
%4%r%l*  %xAs of %y%l22nd March 2000%x, the TCZ v4.3.0 source code consists of %c%l51%x source files, totaling %c%l3665kb%x in size and %c%l61,327%x lines.

%4%y%l*  %xOn %y%lWednesday 30th May 2000%x, the original %y%lThe Chatting Zone%x (%y%lTCZ%x) MUD was finally closed after over %c%lsix years%x of running.

%4%r%l*  %xOn %y%lWednesday 23 May 2001%x, the original %y%lThe Chatting Zone%x (%y%lTCZ%x) MUD database was re-opened as part of an official research project of the %c%lInformation, Media and Communication (IMC) Research Group%x in the %c%lDepartment of Computer Science, Queen Mary, University of London%x.

%4%y%l*  %xOn %y%lThursday 20th November 2003%x, TCZ was moved to a new dedicated machine in the Department of Computer Science, Queen Mary, University of London.

%4%r%l*  %xThe %y%lTCZ source code%x was released publicly under the %c%lGNU General Public License%x (%c%lGPL%x) on %y%l02/12/2004%x (See '%g%l%<gpl%>%x' and visit %b%l%u%{@?link "" "https://github.com/smcvey/tcz" "Click to visit the TCZ project web site..."}%x)

