%TITLE Features of %w%l%@%n%x

%c%l%$%@%n has the following features...
%~%c%{@?pad {@?strlen "{%@%n}"} "~"}~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%4%y%l*  %xThe TCZ source code is publicly released under the %c%lGNU General Public License%x (%c%l%(GPL%)%x) (See '%g%l%<tcz%>%x' and '%g%l%<gpl%>%x') and is available for download from:

      %7%m%l%u%{@?link "" "https://github.com/smcvey/tcz" "Click to visit the TCZ project web site..."}%x

%4%r%l*  %xExtensive, detailed built-in On-line Help System (You're using it now %m%l:)%x)

%4%y%l*  %xTutorials for new users (Teaches you the basics of %@%m (Talking, moving around, using the internal mail system, %@%n BBS, etc.))  -  See '%g%l%+index%>%x'.

%PAGE
%4%r%l*  %xWorld Wide Web Interface that allows you to connect to %@%m using an ordinary World Wide Web browser (I.e:  Netscape Navigator, Microsoft Internet Explorer, etc.), giving you graphics, links and most other features and advantages of HTML from within %@%m.  No additional software is required (The most recent versions of Netscape Navigator or Microsoft Internet Explorer (Version 4.0 or better) are recommended for best results)  -  See '%g%l%<html%>%x'.

%4%y%l*  %xOptional ANSI %r%lc%g%lo%y%ll%b%lo%m%lu%c%lr%x for Telnet connections, along with a substitution system that allows you to easily use ANSI colour in speech, descriptions, etc.  The original TCZ-based MUD (%y%lThe Chatting Zone%x) was one of the first social orientated multi-user environments to implement ANSI colour support.  (ANSI colour support was implemented in %y%lTCZ v2.2%x (%c%l27/06/1994%x))  -  See '%g%l%<ansi colour%>%x'.

%4%r%l*  %xClear and easy to read output (E.g:  Room descriptions, user lists, object details (When examined), etc.)  (Type '%g%l%(look%)%x'!)

%PAGE
%4%y%l*  %xBuilt-in word-wrapping facility (Handles ANSI colour/terminal high-light codes and indents text correctly (For example in lists))  -  See '%g%l%<set wrap%>%x'.

%4%r%l*  %xChatting Channels (Which can optionally be made private)  -  See '%g%l%<chat%>%x'.

%4%y%l*  %xLocalised yelling system (Allows Builders to let Mortals yell messages across their area(s))  -  See '%g%l%<yell%>%x'.

%4%r%l*  %xName prefixes and suffixes (Ask an administrator to set them for you)  -  See '%g%l%<@prefix%>%x' and '%g%l%<@suffix%>%x'.

%4%y%l*  %xPowerful (But easy to use) editor for editing descriptions, compound commands, etc.  The editor can be used to edit any type of object in %@%m  -  See '%g%l%<editor%>%x'.

%PAGE
%4%r%l*  %xInformative and easy to read statistics command ('%g%l%(@stats%)%x'), '%g%l%(@contents%)%x' command (Displays a summary of the contents of a object) and '%g%l%(@quota%)%x' command (Displays summary on what you've used your Building Quota on)  -  See '%g%l%<@stats%>%x', '%g%l%<@contents%>%x' and '%g%l%<@quota%>%x'.

%4%y%l*  %xUser ranking facility ('%g%l%(@rank%)%x'.)  Ranks all users in the database by %c%ltotal connect time%x, %c%llongest connect time%x, %c%llast connect time%x, %c%lscore%x, %c%lamount of credit%x, etc.  (See '%g%l%<@rank%>%x'.)

%4%r%l*  %xGrouping/range operators (Unique to TCZ-based MUD's)  -  A powerful feature that allows lists of items to be paged and restricted to a given range)  -  See '%g%l%<group%>%x' and '%g%l%<range%>%x'.

%4%y%l*  %xString/list/sentence processing queries  -  See '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x'.

%4%r%l*  %x'%g%l%(@if%)%x', '%g%l%(@case%)%x', '%g%l%(@while%)%x' and '%g%l%(@for%)%x' selection/iteration commands  -  See '%g%l%<@if%>%x', '%g%l%<@case%>%x', '%g%l%<@while%>%x' and '%g%l%<@for%>%x'.

%PAGE
%4%y%l*  %x'%g%l%(@break%)%x', '%g%l%(@breakloop%)%x', '%g%l%(@goto%)%x' and '%g%l%(@return%)%x' flow control commands  -  See '%g%l%<@break%>%x', '%g%l%<@breakloop%>%x', '%g%l%<@goto%>%x' and '%g%l%<@return%>%x'.

%4%r%l*  %xPowerful '%g%l%(@with%)%x' command with indexing feature which makes the processing of linked lists (Attached to objects), the list of connected characters and the elements of dynamic arrays a breeze  -  See '%g%l%<@with%>%x'.

%4%y%l*  %x'%g%l%(@foreach%)%x' command for processing lists of items  -  See '%g%l%<@foreach%>%x'.

%4%r%l*  %xPronoun, ANSI %r%lc%g%lo%y%ll%b%lo%m%lu%c%lr%x, text attribute, text formatting and query command/calculation substitutions which can be used in most text (E.g:  '%g%l%(say%)%x', '%g%l%(emote%)%x', '%g%l%(@desc%)%x', '%g%l%(@succ%)%x', '%g%l%(@fail%)%x', '%g%l%(@drop%)%x', '%g%l%(@odesc%)%x', '%g%l%(@osucc%)%x', '%g%l%(@ofail%)%x', '%g%l%(@odrop%)%x', '%g%l%(@echo%)%x', '%g%l%(@oecho%)%x', '%g%l%(@oemote%)%x', etc.)  -  See '%g%l%<substitutions%>%x'.

%4%y%l*  %xLast command recalling facility  -  See '%g%l%<!!%>%x'.

%PAGE
%4%r%l*  %xBetter Telnet protocol handling and terminal support (When not using ANSI colour, hi-lights will be used instead (If your terminal supports them))  -  See '%g%l%<set%>%x'.

%4%y%l*  %xUser definable aliases for commands  -  See '%g%l%<@alias%>%x' and '%g%l%<aliases%>%x'.

%4%r%l*  %xPersonal friends lists, friend flags and friends chatting channel facility  - See '%g%l%<friends%>%x'.

%4%y%l*  %xDynamic arrays with optional element indexing  -  See '%g%l%<@array%>%x'.

%4%r%l*  %xAbility to page/tell messages to a list of people rather than just a single person  -  See '%g%l%<page%>%x' and '%g%l%<tell%>%x'.

%PAGE
%4%y%l*  %xFacility for recalling and replying to the last 8 pages/tells sent to you  -  See '%g%l%<recall%>%x'.

%4%r%l*  %xInheritance  -  Standard fields (Description, success, failure, etc.), locks, aliases (Characters only) and object lists (Contents, exits, compound commands, etc.) of an object may be inherited from a parent object  -  See '%g%l%<inheritance%>%x'.

%4%y%l*  %xUnique Building Quota system  -  Each character has a Building Quota that restricts the maximum amount of stuff they can have built at any one time (Of course, the character must be a Builder to build anything in the first place.)  Building Quotas replace the old and obsolete Building Points system  -  See '%g%l%<@quota%>%x'.

%4%r%l*  %xDatabase of registered Internet sites, which Internet sites can be added to, modified, listed, modified, deleted, etc. on-line.  Flags can also be set on individual sites to implement bans, create bans, etc.  -  See '%g%l%<@site%>%x'.

%PAGE
%4%y%l*  %xEasy to use, built-in topic-based Bulletin Board System (BBS)  -  See '%g%l%<bbs%>%x'.

%4%r%l*  %xTemporary variables  -  These may be created within compound commands for temporary storage, use as counters, etc.  -  See '%g%l%<@temp%>%x' and '%g%l%<@desttemp%>%x'.

%4%y%l*  %xTwo distinctive types of administrator  -  %c%lWizard%x ranks (Building orientated), who should be your first choice for building help and advice, and %c%lDruid%x ranks (Non-building orientated), who are there to help out new users, non-building related questions/problems from existing users and to sort out problems between users and abusive users, etc.  See '%g%l%<druid%>%x' and '%g%l%<wizard%>%x'.

%4%r%l*  %xArticle support  -  Article specific flags may be set on objects to add the correct article ('%c%la%x', '%c%lan%x' or '%c%lsome%x') to the object automatically, and to all references to it (E.g:  '%r%l%uA%y%l chair%x', '%r%l%uAn%y%l oak chest%x', '%r%l%uSome%y%l sweets%x')  -  See '%g%l%<articles%>%x'.

%PAGE
%4%y%l*  %x'Interactive' prompting via the '%g%l%(@prompt%)%x' command  -  Allows creation of menus, knowledge tests, etc. where the user can enter their choice/answer at a prompt, rather than having to type a command followed by their choice/answer  -  See '%g%l%<@prompt%>%x'.

%4%r%l*  %xUsers can tie the knot virtually and be 'net' married to each other  -  See '%g%l%<@partner%>%x'.

%4%y%l*  %xSystem for handing out '%c%lread%x', '%c%lwrite%x', %c%lcreate%x and %c%ldestroy%x permissions to other characters (Allowing them access to your objects) via friend flags.  Both full and restricted access may be given, allowing other users to help you with your building projects and/or work on them with you, and large building projects to be worked on by groups of users  -  See '%g%l%<fset%>%x' and '%g%l%<group building%>%x'.

%4%r%l*  %xAbility to recover accidentally destroyed objects  -  See '%g%l%<@undestroy%>%x'.

%PAGE
%4%y%l*  %xAutomatic maintenance of unused characters and objects in the database, helping keep the database free of redundant objects.  Redundant characters and objects are destroyed on a weekly basis  -  See '%g%l%<expiry%>%x', '%g%l%<@expiry%>%x', '%g%l%<junked objects%>%x', '%g%l%<date stamps%>%x', '%g%l%<@admin%>%x' and '%g%l%<@maintenance%>%x'.

%4%r%l*  %xUser creatable vehicles, which can be driven/ridden around the world of %@%n (In locations which allow transport, such as streets, etc.)  -  See '%g%l%<transport%>%x'.

%4%y%l*  %xE-mail forwarding facility for users of %@%m  -  See '%g%l%<@email%>%x'.

%4%r%l*  %xAutomatically generated user home pages list and gallery of user pictures.  This is generated by %@%m through its World Wide Web Interface (See '%g%l%<html%>%x'), and is available from %@%m's web site (See '%g%l%<www%>%x'.)  Scans (See '%g%l%<scan%>%x') and profiles (See '%g%l%<profile%>%x') of users are also available too through the World Wide Web Interface.

%PAGE
%4%y%l*  %xSystem and user log files, making administration easy by allowing administrators to browse categorised log files without requiring access to the server machine.  User log files allow %(Builders%) to see failed commands typed by users within their areas, as well as logging their own custom entries using '%g%l%(@logentry%)%x'.  (See '%g%l%<@log%>%x' and '%g%l%<@logentry%>%x'.)

%4%r%l*  %xLow maintenance  -  Automatic database consistency checking and maintenance (Such as deleting unused characters) makes life easier for the administrators of %@%n.  (See '%g%l%<@maintenance%>%x'.)

%4%y%l*  %xZero Memory Database Dumping  -  Allows the %@%m database to be dumped to disk in the background without forking a separate process or using any extra memory on the server machine, preventing %@%m from 'lagging' when the database dumps.

%PAGE
%4%r%l*  %xForked database dump for operating systems which properly support copy-on-write memory pages (Such as recent versions of %y%lLinux%x.)  This has the advantage of being quick (Taking only a few minutes to dump a large database) and subject to no inconsistencies.  This is recommended rather than the Zero Memory dump.  Falls back to the Zero Memory dump if the forked dump fails for any reason.

%4%y%l*  %xCommand-line start-up options and configuration file support, allowing many parameters to be changed without needing to recompile the source code.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<version info%>%x', '%g%l%<bug fixes%>%x', '%g%l%<history%>%x', '%g%l%<acknowledgements%>%x', '%g%l%<modules%>%x' and '%g%l%<authors%>%x'.

