%TITLE Help on %w%l%@%n Editor%x
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%ledit <OBJECT TYPE> [<FIELD>] <OBJECT NAME>
        edit [<FIELD>] <OBJECT>%]%x

Starts %@%n's built in editor.

The first form creates an object of the type %y%l<OBJECT TYPE>%x with the name %y%l<OBJECT NAME>%x.  If %y%l<FIELD>%x is specified, that field of the new object will be edited, otherwise it will assume you want to edit its description.

The second form starts editing the object %y%l<OBJECT>%x, which must already exist.  If %y%l<FIELD>%x is specified, that field of the object will be edited, otherwise it will assume you want to edit its description.

The editor can be used to edit the elements of a dynamic array (Only one element may be edited at a time though.)  To do this, simply specify the name of the array along with the element number to edit in square brackets, e.g:  '%g%l%(edit%) myarray[2]%x' will start editing %c%lelement 2%x of the dynamic array '%y%lmyarray%x'.

%PAGE
You can use the '%g%l%(.element%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<.element%>%x') to start editing other elements of the dynamic array without leaving the editor (Works in a similar way to '%g%l%(.field%)%x' (See '%g%l%<.field%>%x'.))

%y%l<FIELD>%x can be one of the following...

%g%l%(description%)%x ('%g%l%(desc%)%x'), %g%l%(failure%)%x ('%g%l%(fail%)%x'), %g%l%(success%)%x ('%g%l%(succ%)%x'), %g%l%(drop%)%x, %g%l%(odescription%)%x ('%g%l%(odesc%)%x'), %g%l%(ofailure%)%x ('%g%l%(ofail%)%x'), %g%l%(osuccess%)%x ('%g%l%(osucc%)%x'), %g%l%(odrop%)%x.

%y%l<OBJECT TYPE>%x can be one of the following...

%g%l%(Array%)%x, %g%l%(command%)%x, %g%l%(exit%)%x, %g%l%(property%)%x, %g%l%(room%)%x, %g%l%(thing%)%x, %g%l%(variable%)%x.

%PAGE

%c%l%$How to use the editor...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
To begin with (Providing you don't move to a different line), any text you type that doesn't begin with a '%y%l.%x' will be added to the end of the edit text (The text of the field you're currently editing.)

If you move to a different line, any text you type (Which doesn't begin with a '%y%l.%x') will be inserted above the current line (Or will overwrite the current line if overwrite mode is %c%lon%x.)  '%g%l%(.overwrite%) on%x' turns overwrite mode %c%lon%x and '%g%l%(.overwrite%) off%x' turns it %c%loff%x.

By default, the editor %c%lWILL NOT%x evaluate any %y%l{}%x's, %y%l$%x's or %y%l\%x's, meaning you can edit compound commands without having to put a '%g%l\%x' in front of every '%y%l{%x' and '%y%l$%x'.  This feature makes the editor perfect for editing/creating compound commands without any of the confusion usually involved due to all those annoying %y%l\%x's!

%PAGE
You %c%lCAN%x however make the editor evaluate %y%l{}%x's, %y%l$%x's and %y%l\%x's by typing '%g%l%(.evaluate%) yes%x' (And stop it again by typing '%g%l%(.evaluate%) no%x'.)

Don't confuse '%g%l%(.evaluate%)%x' with '%g%l%(@evaluate%)%x'  -  They're two completely different commands.

The '%g%l%(.view%)%x' or '%g%l%(.display%)%x' command displays the edit text around the current line you're editing (Try it 'n' see)  -  The line that begins with something looking like '%g%l[001->%x' is the line you're currently editing (This is highlighted too if you're taking advantage of %@%m's %c%lANSI colour support%x (See '%g%l%<ansi colour%>%x') or have have your terminal type set correctly (See '%g%l%<set termtype%>%x'.))

'%g%l%(.view%)%x' can be shortened to '%g%l%(.v%)%x', and both '%g%l%(.view%)%x' and '%g%l%(.display%)%x' can be given an optional line number to display from, e.g:  '%g%l%(.v%) 1%x' to view the edit text from line %y%l1%x, regardless of the line you're currently editing.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Moving around the text...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
You can either use '%g%l%(.up%)%x' and '%g%l%(.down%)%x', or '%g%l%(.prev%)%x' and '%g%l%(.next%)%x' to move up and down the text by one line ('%g%l%(.up%)%x' and '%g%l%(.down%)%x' are the most easiest to use, as they can be shortened to '%g%l%(.u%)%x' and '%g%l%(.d%)%x'.)

You can move up/down by more than one line by typing '%g%l%(.up%) <COUNT>%x' and '%g%l%(.down%) <COUNT>%x', where %y%l<COUNT>%x is the number of lines to move up/down by.

'%g%l%(.home%)%x' and '%g%l%(.end%)%x' can be used to move to the beginning and end of the text respectively.

'%g%l%(.goto%)%x', '%g%l%(.line%)%x' or '%g%l%(.position%)%x' can be used to go to any line in the edit text (So you can edit it.)  All of these can be shortened, e.g:  '%g%l%(.g%)%x', '%g%l%(.l%)%x' and '%g%l%(.p%)%x'  -  If you don't specify which line number to go to, the current line number you're editing is displayed along with details of whatever you're currently editing.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Saving or abandoning your changes...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
If you want to abandon the changes you've made to whatever field you're editing, you can do this by typing '%g%l%(.abort%) = yes%x' or '%g%l%(.cancel%) = yes%x'.

If you're happy with your changes, you can save them by typing '%g%l%(.exit%)%x', '%g%l%(.quit%)%x', '%g%l%(.save%)%x' or '%g%l%(.leave%)%x'.


%c%l%$Editing a different field without leaving the editor...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
You can edit a different field of the object you're currently editing by typing '%g%l%(.field%) <FIELD>%x', e.g:  '%g%l%(.field%) fail%x' to start editing the %y%lfail message%x of the object.

Before editing the specified field, any changes you've made to the current field will be saved.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Line ranges...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
Any editor command that has %y%l<LINE RANGE>%x as one of its parameters can accept a range of lines (Or a single line) to operate on.

A line range is specified as follows...

%[%c%l3-8%x       ...Line range from line %y%l3%x to line %y%l8%x.
%c%l3..8%x      ...Same as above.
%c%l3%x         ...Line %y%l3%x only (Equivalent to %c%l3-3%x.)%]

%PAGE
Instead of specifying line numbers, you can use one of the following five special keywords instead  -  These are...

%[%c%lCURRENT   %x...Current line that you're editing.
%c%lFIRST     %x...First line of edit text.
%c%lLAST      %x...Last line.
%c%lEND       %x...Same as above.
%c%lALL       %x...The whole edit text (Equivalent to %c%lFIRST-LAST%x.)%]

%c%lNOTE:%x  You don't have to type them in capitals if you don't want to.


%c%l%$The Editor Prompt...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
When using the editor, you should get a prompt that looks something like this...

%c[%c%l4%c:%c%l7%c]-->%x

%PAGE
The number on the left-hand side of the '%c:%x' is the line number you're currently editing, and the number on the right-hand side is the total number of lines in the text you're editing.  Don't worry if the number on the left is greater than the one on the right  -  This just means you're adding to the end of the text.


%c%l%$Editor commands...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
For a complete list of all editor commands, see '%g%l%<edit commands%>%x' or '%g%l%<editcmds%>%x' (Type '%g%l%(.help%)%x' instead of '%g%l%(help%)%x' if you're using the editor!)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<editcmds%>%x'.

