%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l.append [<LINE NO.> =] <TEXT>%]%x

If %y%l<LINE NO>%x isn't specified, %y%l<TEXT>%x will be appended to the end of the current line you're editing, otherwise %y%l<TEXT>%x will be appended to line number %y%l<LINE NO.>%x

This editor command is especially useful if your Telnet client restricts the amount of text you can type on a single line.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<.set%>%x', '%g%l%<.insert%>%x' and '%g%l%<editcmd%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC .c
%TOPIC .copytext
%TOPIC .copyregion
%TITLE Help on '%w%l.copy%x' (%w%l.c%x) (Editor)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l.copy [<LINE RANGE> =] <DESTINATION>%]%x

When overwrite mode is %c%lon%x, '%g%l.copy%x' overwrites the line %y%l<DESTINATION>%x with the range of lines %y%l<LINE RANGE>%x.

When overwrite mode is %c%loff%x, '%g%l.copy%x' inserts the range of lines %y%l<LINE RANGE>%x above the line %y%l<DESTINATION>%x.

If %y%l<LINE RANGE>%x isn't specified, the current line is assumed.

%[%c%lExamples:  %g%l.c 3-5 = 10     %x...copies lines %y%l3 to 5%x to line %y%l10%x.
           %g%l.c 2 = 4        %x...copies line %y%l2%x to line %y%l4%x.%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<.move%>%x', '%g%l%<.delete%>%x' and '%g%l%<editcmd%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC .element
%TITLE Help on '%w%l.element%x' (Editor)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l.element [<ELEMENT>]%]%x

Without a parameter, '%g%l.element%x' will save all changes you've made to the current dynamic array element you're editing without leaving the editor.

If %y%l<ELEMENT>%x is specified (Which can either be an %c%lelement number%x, %c%lelement index name%x, '%y%lnext%x' (Next element), '%y%lprev%x' (Previous element) or one of the keywords '%y%lFIRST%x', '%y%lLAST%x' or '%y%lEND%x'), the changes you've made to the current dynamic array element will be saved, and the current element being edited will be changed to that specified.  This allows you to edit other elements of the dynamic array without leaving the editor.

'%g%l.element%x' is an alias for '%g%l%(.field%)%x', and will function in the same way as '%g%l%(.field%)%x' if a dynamic array isn't currently being edited (This means that you can use '%g%l%(.field%)%x' to move around the elements of a dynamic array too.)

%[%c%lExample:  %g%l.element 5     %x...changes current element of dynamic array being
                         edited to element number %y%l5%x.%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<.field%>%x' and '%g%l%<editcmd%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC .eraseline
%TOPIC .deleteline
%TITLE Help on '%w%l.delete%x' and '%w%l.erase%x' (Editor)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l.delete [<LINE RANGE>]
        .erase [<LINE RANGE>]%]%x

Deletes the range of lines %y%l<LINE RANGE>%x.

If %y%l<LINE RANGE>%x isn't specified, the current line is assumed.

%[%c%lExamples:  %g%l.d 2-8     %x...deletes lines %y%l2 to 8%x.
           %g%l.d 1       %x...deletes line %y%l1%x.%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<.copy%>%x', '%g%l%<.move%>%x' and '%g%l%<editcmd%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC .evaluate
%TOPIC evaluateflag
%TITLE Help on '%w%l.evaluate%x' (Editor)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l.evaluate [yes|no]%]%x

By default, the editor %c%lWILL NOT%x evaluate any %y%l{}%x's, %y%l$%x's or %y%l\%x's, meaning you can edit compound commands without having to put a '%g%l\%x' in front of every '%y%l{%x' and '%y%l$%x'.  This feature makes the editor perfect for editing/creating compound commands without any of the confusion usually involved due to all those annoying %y%l\%x's!

You %c%lCAN%x however make the editor evaluate %y%l{}%x's, %y%l$%x's and %y%l\%x's by typing '%g%l.evaluate yes%x', and stop it by typing '%g%l.evaluate no%x'.

Typing '%g%l.evaluate%x' without any parameters will toggle it between '%y%lyes%x' and '%y%lno%x'.  Don't confuse '%g%l.evaluate%x' with '%g%l%(@evaluate%)%x'  -  They're two completely different commands.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<.overwrite%>%x', '%g%l%<.numbering%>%x' and '%g%l%<editcmd%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC .x
%TOPIC .execute
%TOPIC .executecommand
%TITLE Help on '%w%l.execute%x' (%w%l.x%x) (Editor)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l.execute <%@%m COMMAND>%]%x

Executes %@%m command %y%l<%@%m COMMAND>%x.  Any %y%l{}%x's and %y%l\%x's in the command will be evaluated, regardless of the current setting of '%g%l%(.evaluate%)%x'.

For example, if someone paged you while you were editing something, you could page them back with your reply by typing '%g%l.x %(page%) <NAME> = <MESSAGE>%x'.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<editcmd%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC .q
%TOPIC .savetext
%TOPIC .exiteditor
%TOPIC .quiteditor
%TOPIC .leaveeditor
%TOPIC .saveedittext
%TITLE Help on '%w%l.exit%x', '%w%l.quit%x' (%w%l.q%x), '%w%l.save%x' and '%w%l.leave%x' (Editor)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l.leave
        .exit
        .quit
        .save%]%x

Saves changes to the field you're currently editing and exits the editor (Returning you to %@%m.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<.abort%>%x' and '%g%l%<editcmd%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC .f
%TOPIC .field
%TOPIC .editorfield
%TITLE Help on '%w%l.field%x' (%w%l.f%x) (Editor)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l.field <FIELD>%]%x

Without a parameter, '%g%l.field%x' will save all changes you've made to the current field you're editing (E.g:  %c%lDescription%x) without leaving the editor.  If %g%l<FIELD>%x is specified, the changes you've made to the current field will be saved, and the current field will be changed to that specified.  This allows you to move between the various fields of an object without leaving the editor.

%y%l<FIELD>%x can be one of the following:

%g%l%(description%)%x ('%g%l%(desc%)%x'), %g%l%(failure%)%x ('%g%l%(fail%)%x'), %g%l%(success%)%x ('%g%l%(succ%)%x'), %g%l%(drop%)%x, %g%l%(odescription%)%x ('%g%l%(odesc%)%x'), %g%l%(ofailure%)%x ('%g%l%(ofail%)%x'), %g%l%(osuccess%)%x ('%g%l%(osucc%)%x'), %g%l%(odrop%)%x.

%[%c%lExample:  %g%l.f fail     %x...changes current field to the %c%lfail message%x of the
                      object you're editing.%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<.element%>%x' and '%g%l%<editcmd%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC .help
%TOPIC .manual
%TITLE Help on '%w%l.help%x' and '%w%l.manual%x' (Editor)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l.manual [<SUBJECT>]
        .help [<SUBJECT>]%]%x

Calls %@%n On-line Help System and displays help on %y%l<SUBJECT>%x.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<editcmd%>%x' and '%g%l%<index%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC .i
%TOPIC .inserttext
%TOPIC .insertregion
%TITLE Help on '%w%l.insert%x' (%w%l.i%x) (Editor)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l.insert [<LINE NO.> =] <TEXT>%]%x

Inserts %y%l<TEXT>%x above the line %y%l<LINE NO.>%x (Regardless of whether overwrite mode is %c%lon%x or %c%loff%x.)

If %y%l<LINE RANGE>%x isn't specified, the current line is assumed.

%[%c%lExample:  %g%l.i 3 = Hello World!     %x...Inserts "%y%lHello World!%x" above line %y%l3%x.%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<.set%>%x', '%g%l%<.append%>%x', '%g%l%<.value%>%x', '%g%l%<.replace%>%x' and '%g%l%<editcmd%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC .m
%TOPIC .movetext
%TOPIC .moveregion
%TITLE Help on '%w%l.move%x' (%w%l.m%x) (Editor)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l.move [<LINE RANGE> =] <DESTINATION>%]%x

When overwrite mode is %c%lon%x, %g%l.move%x moves the range of lines %y%l<LINE RANGE>%x to the line %y%l<DESTINATION>%x, overwriting it.

When overwrite mode is %c%loff%x, %g%l.move%x moves the range of lines %y%l<LINE RANGE>%x above the line %y%l<DESTINATION>%x.

If %y%l<LINE RANGE>%x isn't specified, the current line is assumed.

%[%c%lExamples:  %g%l.m 5-7 = 1     %x...moves lines %y%l5 to 7%x to line %y%l1%x.
           %g%l.m 6 = 3       %x...moves line %y%l6%x to line %y%l3%x.%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<.copy%>%x', '%g%l%<.delete%>%x' and '%g%l%<editcmd%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC .number
%TOPIC .numbers
%TOPIC .numbering
%TOPIC .linenumbers
%TOPIC numberingflag
%TOPIC linenumberflag
%TOPIC .linenumbering
%TOPIC linenumbersflag
%TOPIC linenumberingflag
%TITLE Help on '%w%l.numbering%x' (Editor)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l.numbering [on|off]%]%x

Turns line numbering %c%lon%x (If '%y%lon%x' is specified), or %c%loff%x (If '%y%loff%x' is specified), or toggles them %c%lon%x and %c%loff%x if no parameter is given.

When line numbering is %c%lon%x, the number of each line will be displayed when using the '%g%l%(.view%)%x' (See '%g%l%<.view%>%x') editor command to display the text you're editing, e.g:

%[%g[001]  %wThis is the first line.
%g%l[002-> %w%lEditing this line.%]%x

%PAGE
When line numbers are off, the number of each line will not be displayed.  Instead, the beginning of each line is marked with a '%g~%x' symbol, and the line you're currently editing is marked with a '%g%l>%x' symbol, e.g:

%[%g~%wThis is the first line.
%g%l>%w%lEditing this line.%]%x

%[%c%lExample:  %g%l.numbering off     %x...turns line numbering %y%loff%x.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<.view%>%x', '%g%l%<.overwrite%>%x', '%g%l%<.evaluate%>%x' and '%g%l%<editcmd%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC .o
%TOPIC overwriteflag
%TOPIC .overwritemode
%TITLE Help on '%w%l.overwrite%x' (%w%l.o%x) (Editor)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l.overwrite [on|off]%]%x

Turns overwrite mode %c%lon%x (If '%y%lon%x' is specified), or %c%loff%x (If '%y%loff%x' is specified), or toggles it %c%lon%x and %c%loff%x if no parameter is given.

When in overwrite mode, any text you type will overwrite the current line you're on (Unless you're at the end of text, in which case it will be added to the end of the text) instead of being inserted above it.

Overwrite mode also affects the %g%l%(.move%)%x and %g%l%(.copy%)%x commands, making them overwrite the destination line instead of inserting above it.

Overwrite mode is %c%loff%x by default.

%[%c%lExample:  %g%l.o on     %x...turns overwrite mode %y%lon%x.%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<.numbering%>%x', '%g%l%<.evaluate%>%x' and '%g%l%<editcmd%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC .r
%TOPIC .replace
%TOPIC .replacetext
%TOPIC .replaceregion
%TOPIC .searchandreplace
%TITLE Help on '%w%l.replace%x' (%w%l.r%x) (Editor)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l.replace [<LINERANGE> =] "<SEARCHSTR>" "<REPLACESTR>" [[+]<OCCURENCE>]%]%x

'%g%l.replace%x' replaces the specified %y%l<OCCURENCE>%x of %y%l<SEARCHSTR>%x (Within the given %y%l<LINERANGE>%x) with %y%l<REPLACESTR>%x.

If %y%l<LINERANGE>%x isn't specified, the current line is assumed.

For %y%l<OCCURENCE>%x, an occurence number can be given (I.e:  '%y%l2%x' for the %c%lsecond%x occurence, '%y%l3%x' for the %c%lthird%x, etc.), or one of the keywords '%y%lFIRST%x', '%y%lLAST%x' or '%y%lALL%x' (Replace %c%lALL%x occurences within given %y%l<LINERANGE>%x.)  If %y%l<OCCURENCE>%x is prefixed with a '%y%l+%x', the given %y%l<OCCURENCE>%x will be replaced on %c%lEVERY%x line in the %y%l<LINERANGE>%x.

If %y%l<OCCURENCE>%x is omitted, the first occurence of %y%l<SEARCHSTR>%x will be assumed.

%PAGE
Using '%g%l.replace%x' saves you from having to type an entire line out all over again if you make a mistake, e.g:

%g%l[005->  %xThis line has a mitsake in it!

...To correct the above line, you can just simply type...

%g%l.r "mitsake" "mistake"%x     ...Or...     %g%l.r 5 = "mitsake" "mistake"%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<.set%>%x', '%g%l%<.insert%>%x', '%g%l%<.value%>%x' and '%g%l%<editcmd%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC .s
%TOPIC .setline
%TITLE Help on '%w%l.set%x' (%w%l.s%x) (Editor)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l.set [<LINE NO.> =] <TEXT>%]%x

If %y%l<LINE NO.>%x isn't specified, the current line you're editing will be set to %y%l<TEXT>%x, otherwise the line number %y%l<LINE NO.>%x will be set to %y%l<TEXT>%x.

The main use of this command (Along with %g%l%(.insert%)%x) is to allow you to insert lines in your edit text which begin with a '%y%l.%x' (Trying to do this in the normal way would fail, because %@%m would assume that you are trying to execute an editor command.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<.append%>%x', '%g%l%<.insert%>%x', '%g%l%<.value%>%x', '%g%l%<.replace%>%x' and '%g%l%<editcmd%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC .tutor
%TOPIC .tutorial
%TOPIC .tutorials
%TITLE Help on '%w%l.tutorial%x' (Editor)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l.tutorial [<SUBJECT>]%]%x

Calls %@%n On-line Tutorial System and displays the tutorial on %y%l<SUBJECT>%x (If available.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<tutorials%>%x', '%g%l%+index%>%x', '%g%l%<editcmd%>%x' and '%g%l%<index%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC .value
%TOPIC .returnvalues
%TITLE Help on '%w%l.value%x' (Editor)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l.value [<LINE NO.> =] <%@%m COMMAND>%]%x

Executes %@%m command %y%l<%@%m COMMAND>%x and substitutes its return value on the current line you're editing (Or if %y%l<LINE NO.>%x is specified, the return value is substituted on that line.)  If overwrite mode is on, the current line (Or %y%l<LINE NO.>%x) is overwritten with the return value, otherwise, the return value is inserted above the current line (Or %y%l<LINE NO.>%x)

Any %y%l{}%x's, %y%l$%x's and %y%l\%x's in the command will be evaluated, regardless of the current setting of '%g%l%(.evaluate%)%x'.

For example, you can substitute your description by typing '%g%l.val {@?desc me}%x'.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<.set%>%x', '%g%l%<.insert%>%x', '%g%l%<.replace%>%x' and '%g%l%<editcmd%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC .editfail
%TOPIC .editfailure
%TITLE Help on '%w%l.editfail%x' (Editor)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l.editfail <COMMAND>%]%x

'%g%l.editfail%x' sets an optional compound command which will be executed when you leave the editor and %c%lABANDON%x your changes (Typing '%g%l%(.abort%) = yes%x' or '%g%l%(.cancel%) = yes%x' will do this.)


%c%l%$Example:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l.editfail abandoncmd     %x(The compound command '%g%labandoncmd%x' will be ran when
                         you exit the editor and %c%lABANDON%x your changes.)%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<.editsucc%>%x', '%g%l%<.permanent%>%x' and '%g%l%<editcmd%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC .editsucc
%TOPIC .editsuccess
%TITLE Help on '%w%l.editsucc%x' (Editor)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l.editsucc <COMMAND>%]%x

'%g%l.editsucc%x' sets an optional compound command which will be executed when you leave the editor and %c%lSAVE%x your changes (Typing '%g%l%(.exit%)%x', '%g%l%(.save%)%x' or '%g%l%(.leave%)%x' will do this.)


