%TITLE Help on '%w%lsearch%x' (Or '%w%lfind%x') (BBS)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] search [next|prev] <TEXT> [= subjects|messages|all]
        [bbs] find [next|prev] <TEXT> [= subjects|messages|all]%]%x

By default, the BBS '%g%lsearch%x'/'%g%lfind%x' command searches for the next occurence of %y%l<TEXT>%x in the subject and message text of messages on the BBS.  If a matching message is found, it will be shown (As though you read it, using the '%g%l%(^bbs read%)%x'/'%g%l%(^bbs view%)%x' BBS command (See '%g%l%<bbs read%>%x'.))  E.g:  '%g%lsearch fred%x' will search for the next message with the text '%y%lfred%x' in its subject or message text.

You can search for the previous matching message using '%g%lsearch prev%x', e.g:  '%g%lsearch prev fred%x' will search for the previous message with the text '%y%lfred%x' in its subject or message text.

You can restrict the searching to either the message subject or message text only by specifying the second parameter.  E.g:  '%g%lsearch fred = subjects%x' will search for the next message with the text '%y%lfred%x' in its subject only.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<bbs read%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs summary%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs latest%>%x' and '%g%l%<bbscmds%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC bbsdetails
%TOPIC bbssettings
%TOPIC bbspreferences
%TITLE Help on '%w%lsettings%x' (BBS)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] settings [<TOPIC>]%]%x

The '%g%lsettings%x' BBS command displays information about the topic/sub-topic you're currently browsing on the BBS (Or the topic %y%l<TOPIC>%x, if specified, e.g:  '%g%lsettings news%x'.)

You can use this BBS command to see the owner of a particular topic/sub-topic and the restrictions imposed on it (I.e:  Message limit, whether messages can be added, level required to access topic, etc.), even if you can't access the topic/sub-topic yourself.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<bbs topic%>%x' and '%g%l%<bbscmds%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC bbssubtopic
%TITLE Help on '%w%lsubtopic%x' (BBS)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] subtopic <NAME>%]%x

If a BBS topic is divided up into several sub-topics, you can use the '%g%lsubtopic%x' BBS command to pick a sub-topic to browse from the topic.

Sub-topics are used to group and organise related topics on the BBS.  For example, the topic %y%lNEWS%x could contain the sub-topics %y%lEVENTS%x, %y%lGENERAL%x, %y%lMISCELLANEOUS%x and %y%l%{@?upper "{%@%m}"} MEETS%x.

You can choose a sub-topic from a topic by either first choosing the topic ('%g%l%(^bbs topic%) <NAME>%x') and then typing '%g%lsubtopic <NAME>%x' or by typing '%g%l%(^bbs topic%) <SUBTOPIC>/<TOPIC>%x', where %y%l<SUBTOPIC>%x is the name of the sub-topic and %y%l<TOPIC>%x is the name of the topic, e.g:  '%g%l%(^bbs topic%) news/general%x'.

You can list the sub-topics within a topic using the '%g%l%(^bbs subtopics%)%x' BBS command.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<bbs subtopics%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs topics%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs topic%>%x', '%g%l%<subtopics%>%x' and '%g%l%<bbscmds%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC bbssubtopics
%TITLE Help on '%w%lsubtopics%x' (BBS)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] subtopics [page] [<PAGE NO>] [<TOPIC>]%]%x

Sub-topics are used to group and organise related topics on the BBS.  For example, the topic %y%lNEWS%x could contain the sub-topics %y%lEVENTS%x, %y%lGENERAL%x, %y%lMISCELLANEOUS%x and %y%l%{@?upper "{%@%m}"} MEETS%x.

You can list the sub-topics in a topic by either first choosing the topic ('%g%l%(^bbs topic%) <NAME>%x', where %y%l<NAME>%x is the name of the topic) and then typing '%g%lsubtopics%x' or by typing '%g%lsubtopics <TOPIC>%x', where %y%l<TOPIC>%x is the name of the topic.

If %y%l<PAGE NO>%x is specified and the list of sub-topics spans more than one page, that page of sub-topics will be displayed, e.g:  '%g%lsubtopics 2%x' to view the %c%l2nd%x page, '%g%lsubtopics 3%x' to view the %c%l3rd%x, etc.

You can choose a sub-topic from a topic by using the '%g%l%(^bbs subtopic%)%x' BBS command.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<bbs subtopic%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs topics%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs topic%>%x', '%g%l%<subtopics%>%x' and '%g%l%<bbscmds%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC summary
%TOPIC bbssummary
%TITLE Help on '%w%lsummary%x' (BBS)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] summary [page] [<PAGE NO>]%]%x

The '%g%lsummary%x' BBS command displays a list of topics and sub-topics which currently contain messages which you haven't read yet, along with a count of the total number of unread messages and the subject and message number of the most recent message in each.

This command can be used to get an overview of unread messages currently on the BBS and can help you find topics/sub-topics with new messages you may be interested in.

If %y%l<PAGE NO>%x is specified and the summary spans more than one page, that page of the summary will be displayed, e.g:  '%g%lsummary 2%x' to view the %c%l2nd%x page, '%g%lsummary 3%x' to view the %c%l3rd%x, etc.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<latest%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs topics%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs ignore%>%x' and '%g%l%<bbscmds%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC bbstopic
%TITLE Help on '%w%ltopic%x' (BBS)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] topic <TOPIC>%]%x

The '%g%ltopic%x' BBS command is used to select a topic that you're interested in from the list of available topics on the BBS.  You can list the available topics on the BBS by typing '%g%l%(^bbs topics%)%x' (See '%g%l%<bbs topics%>%x'.)

Once you've selected a topic, you can use the '%g%l%(^bbs read%)%x'/'%g%l%(^bbs view%)%x' BBS command (See '%g%l%<bbs read%>%x') to list and read the messages it contains.

%9%6%c%lFor example:  %x'%g%ltopic news%x' will select the topic %y%lNEWS%x from the list of available topics on the BBS.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<bbs topics%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs read%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs subtopics%>%x' and '%g%l%<bbscmds%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC bbstopics
%TITLE Help on '%w%ltopics%x' (BBS)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] topics [page] [<PAGE NO>]%]%x

The '%g%ltopics%x' BBS command lists the available topics on the BBS.  Some of these topics may also contain further related sub-topics (These can be listed and selected using the '%g%l%(^bbs subtopics%)%x' and '%g%l%(^bbs subtopic%)%x' BBS commands respectively (See '%g%l%<subtopics%>%x' and '%g%l%<subtopic%>%x'.))

If %y%l<PAGE NO>%x is specified and the list of topics span more than one page, that page of the list of topics will be displayed, e.g:  '%g%ltopics 2%x' to view the %c%l2nd%x page, '%g%ltopics 3%x' to view the %c%l3rd%x, etc.

The numbers in brackets (E.g:  'News %c(%g%l12%c/%x100%c)%x' after each topic name in the list tell you how many unread messages (In this case, %y%l12%x) and the total number of messages altogether (In this case, %y%l100%x) the topic and its sub-topics (If it has any) contain.

%PAGE
If a topic name in the list is preceeded by a '%r%l!%x', it means that you cannot access that topic (E.g:  '%r%l!%xAdmin'.)  You can use the '%g%l%(^bbs settings%)%x' BBS command (See '%g%l%<bbs settings%>%x') to find out exactly what restrictions are imposed on a topic/sub-topic, e.g:  '%g%l%(^bbs settings%) admin%x'.

A topic name in the list preceeded by a '%y%l*%x' is a topic that's considered important (The name of the topic hilighted and prefixed with a '%y%l*%x' to make it stand out from the rest of the topics in the list.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<bbs topic%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs read%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs subtopics%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs ignore%>%x' and '%g%l%<bbscmds%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC bbsvote
%TOPIC bbsvoting
%TITLE Help on '%w%lvote%x' (BBS)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] vote <NUMBER> [=] majority|normal
        [bbs] vote <NUMBER> [=] yes|no|abstain
        [bbs] vote <NUMBER> [=] secret|public
        [bbs] vote <NUMBER> [=] expiry <DAYS>
        [bbs] vote <NUMBER> [=] on|off|reset
        [bbs] vote <NUMBER> [=] list%]%x

The '%g%lvote%x' BBS command can be used to register your vote on a votable message, or to make a message votable, so other users may vote on it.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Registering your vote
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] vote <NUMBER> [=] yes|no|abstain%]%x

To register your vote on a votable message, simply type '%g%lvote <NUMBER> for%x', '%g%lvote <NUMBER> against%x' or '%g%lvote <NUMBER> abstain%x' (If appropriate) to register your vote appropriately on the message.  For example, you could vote %c%lFOR%x the message number %y%l71%x in your current selected topic/sub-topic by typing '%g%lvote 71 for%x'.

Once you've voted, you can change the direction of your vote, if you decide otherwise before the vote is closed.  To change your vote, simply cast it again on the message, in the appropriate direction.  Your previous vote will be erased, and your new vote registered in its place.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Making a message votable
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] vote <NUMBER> [=] on|off|reset%]%x

Any message can be made votable by typing '%g%lvote <NUMBER> on%x'.  This will allow users to vote on the message appropriately.  You can 'close' the vote (So that no-one else can vote or change their vote) by typing '%g%lvote <NUMBER> off%x'.  If you wish to clear the results of the vote (I.e:  To start the vote again), you can do this by typing '%g%lvote <NUMBER> reset%x'.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Making votes subject to a secret ballot
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] vote <NUMBER> [=] secret|public%]%x

Voting on a message can be made subject to a secret ballot (I.e:  The current results of the vote are not shown to users reading the message) by typing '%g%lvote <NUMBER> secret%x'.  The results can be revealed (I.e:  Once you've closed the vote) by typing '%g%lvote <NUMBER> public%x'.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Making votes subject to the majority factor
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] vote <NUMBER> [=] majority|normal%]%x

Voting on a message can also be made subject to the %(majority factor%).  This weights votes according to the rank of the user casting the vote (I.e:  So that higher ranking users have more influence.)  Please see '%g%l%<majority factor%>%x' for further details, including how the weighting is organised.  Voting on a message can be made subject to the majority factor by typing '%g%lvote <NUMBER> majority%x'.  Voting can also be made subject to normal majority (Equal weighting) again by typing '%g%lvote <NUMBER> normal%x'.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Setting an expiry time for voting
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] vote <NUMBER> [=] expiry <DAYS>%]%x

An expiry time can be set for voting on a message.  Once set, voting on the message will remain open for that period of time, after which it will automatically close.  If the vote has been made subject to a secret ballot, the results of the vote will be made public when it closes.

To set an expiry time for voting on a message, simply type '%g%lvote <NUMBER> expiry <DAYS>%x', where %y%l<DAYS>%x is the time in days (Up to a maximum of %c%l7%x), after which voting on the message will close.

Once an expiry time has been set, it cannot be reduced or removed.  Voting on the message cannot be turned on/off, and the votes on the message cannot be reset.  The voting can be made subject to a secret ballot, but cannot be made public again.  These restrictions apply until the expiry time for voting on the message has passed.

%PAGE
However, the expiry time can be increased, if more time is required for the vote (To do this, simply set an expiry time higher than the current time remaining.)


%c%l%$Listing the votes on a message
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] vote <NUMBER> [=] list%]%x

%m%lDeities%x and the %m%lSupreme Being%x can use the '%g%lvote <NUMBER> list%x' command to list the names of users who have cast votes in each direction.  This BBS command is restricted to %m%lDeities%x and the %m%lSupreme Being%x to prevent the privacy and confidentiality of users casting votes being breached.  It's main use is to check for possible vote rigging in important votes.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<majority factor%>%x' and '%g%l%<bbscmds%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?bbsrtd
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?bbsrtd}%x' (BBS)
The '%g%l{@?bbsrtd}%x' query command is used %c%linternally%x by %@%m to show the correct time that a user appended to a BBS message (In relation to the user reading the message, taking their time difference (If set) into account.)

It is only functional when called internally by the BBS '%g%l%(^bbs read%)%x'/'%g%l%(^bbs view%)%x' commands, and is of no use elsewhere.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<bbs append%>%x' and '%g%l%<bbs%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC bbsappend
%TOPIC bbsappendanon
%TOPIC bbsappendmessage
%TOPIC bbsappendanonymous
%TITLE Help on '%w%lappend%x' and '%w%lappendanon%x' (BBS)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] append[anon] <NUMBER> [= <MESSAGE>]
        [bbs] append <NUMBER> [=] on|off%]%x

The '%g%lappend%x' BBS command appends to the bottom of a BBS message.

If %y%l<MESSAGE>%x (Your message) is specified, it will be appended to the message on the BBS immediately.  Otherwise, %@%n Editor (See '%g%l%<editor%>%x') will be started, so you can write your message (Type it in a line at a time, and then type '%g%l%(.save%)%x' on a line by itself to exit the editor and append it to the message on the BBS.)

The main use of the '%g%lappend%x' BBS command is to make additions to a message you've posted on the BBS at a later date, after it has been read by a number of other users.

Appending to the message will also mark it as unread again (For everyone), so that people who have already read the message in the past know to read it again (So that they can see your append to the message.)

%PAGE
If you need to add to or change a message straight after posting, you should use the '%g%l%(^bbs modify%)%x' BBS command (See '%g%l%<bbs modify%>%x'.)  Otherwise, you should append to the message, so that it's marked as being unread again (The '%g%l%(^bbs modify%)%x' BBS command doesn't do this.)

%y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above may append to any message, regardless of who posted it (Even if it was posted by a higher level administrator.)

You can use '%g%lappendanon%x' instead of '%g%lappend%x' to anonymously append to a message on the BBS.

You can prevent a message from being appended to by using '%g%l[bbs] append <NUMBER> = off%x', where %y%l<NUMBER>%x is the number of the message.  No user (Including yourself) will be able to append to the message, unless '%g%l[bbs] append <NUMBER> = on%x' is used to allow appending again.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<editor%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs modify%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs reply%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs anon%>%x' and '%g%l%<bbscmds%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC bbsrm
%TOPIC bbserase
%TOPIC bbsdelete
%TOPIC bbsremove
%TOPIC bbserasemessage
%TOPIC bbsdeletemessage
%TOPIC bbsremovemessage
%TITLE Help on '%w%ldelete%x' (BBS)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] delete <RANGE> [= yes]
        [bbs] delete <NUMBER>%]%x

The '%g%ldelete%x' BBS command will delete a message (Or range of messages) from your current selected topic/sub-topic on the BBS, e.g:  '%g%ldelete 14%x' will delete message number %y%l14%x.

In addition to deleting a single message, several messages can be deleted all in one go by giving a range.  To do this, the parameter '%g%l= yes%x' must also be given.  For example, '%g%ldelete 43-47 = yes%x' will delete messages %y%l43%x, %y%l44%x, %y%l45%x, %y%l46%x and %y%l47%x.

%9%6%c%lPLEASE NOTE:  %xDeleting a message is %r%lpermanent%x.  You can't retrieve a message once it's been deleted.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<bbs modify%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs move%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs timelimit%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs cyclic%>%x' and '%g%l%<bbscmds%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC bbsvi
%TOPIC bbsedit
%TOPIC bbsmodify
%TOPIC bbseditmessage
%TOPIC bbsmodifymessage
%TITLE Help on '%w%lmodify%x' (BBS)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] modify <NUMBER>%]%x

The '%g%lmodify%x' BBS command allows you to edit and make changes to a message you've posted on the BBS (After you've posted it), e.g:  '%g%lmodify 32%x' will put you into %@%n Editor (See '%g%l%<editor%>%x'), editing message %y%l32%x in your current selected topic/sub-topic on the BBS.

Once you've finished making your changes, type '%g%l%(.save%)%x' to save them and exit the editor, or (If you're unhappy with them, or have made a serious mistake (Such as wiping the whole message)) type '%g%l%(.abort%)%x' to abandon them.

If you need to add to or change a message straight after posting, you should use the '%g%lmodify%x' BBS command.  Otherwise, you should append to the message (Using the '%g%l%(^bbs append%)%x' BBS command (See '%g%l%<bbs append%>%x')), so that it's marked as being unread again (The '%g%lmodify%x' BBS command doesn't do this.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<editor%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs append%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs subject%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs reply%>%x' and '%g%l%<bbscmds%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC bbsmv
%TOPIC bbsmove
%TITLE Help on '%w%lmove%x' (BBS)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] move <NUMBER> = <TOPIC>%]%x

The '%g%lmove%x' BBS command moves a message from your current selected topic/sub-topic to another topic/sub-topic on the BBS, e.g:  '%g%lmove 52 = general%x' will move message number %y%l52%x to the topic %y%lGENERAL%x on the BBS.

The main use of this BBS command is to move a message you've accidentally added to the wrong topic/sub-topic to the correct topic/sub-topic.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<bbs copy%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs delete%>%x' and '%g%l%<bbscmds%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC bbsrename
%TOPIC bbssubject
%TOPIC bbsrenmessage
%TOPIC bbsrenamemessage
%TITLE Help on '%w%lsubject%x' (BBS)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] subject <NUMBER> = <SUBJECT>%]%x

The '%g%lsubject%x' BBS command changes the subject of a message in your current selected topic/sub-topic on the BBS, e.g:  '%g%lsubject 24 = My message%x' will change the subject of message number %y%l24%x to '%y%lMy message%x'.

The main use of this BBS command is to correct the title of a message you've added (If it's incorrect or contains typing errors.)

The subject of a reply to a message can't be changed.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<bbs modify%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs delete%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs reply%>%x' and '%g%l%<bbscmds%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC bbssecurity
%TOPIC bbsprivileges
%TOPIC bbsaccesslevel
%TITLE Help on '%w%laccesslevel%x' (BBS)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] accesslevel <TOPIC> = <LEVEL>%]%x

The '%g%laccesslevel%x' BBS command sets the level (Rank) required to access the topic/sub-topic %y%l<TOPIC>%x on the BBS.

In order to access the topic/sub-topic, the user must be of the given rank or above.  The default access level of a topic/sub-topic is Mortal.

%y%l<LEVEL>%x can be one of the following ranks:  %m%lSupreme Being%x, %m%lDeity%x, %g%lElder%x, %c%lWizard%x, %y%lApprentice%x, %r%lExperienced Builder%x, Builder, Mortal, %b%lMoron%x.

%[%c%lExample:  %g%laccesslevel admin = apprentice%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<bbs topics%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs settings%>%x' and '%g%l%<bbscmds%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC bbsmd
%TOPIC bbsmkdir
%TOPIC bbsaddtopic
%TOPIC bbsnewtopic
%TITLE Help on '%w%laddtopic%x' (BBS)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] addtopic [<TOPIC>/]<NAME> = <DESCRIPTION>%]%x

The '%g%laddtopic%x' BBS command adds a new topic or sub-topic to the BBS.

%y%l<NAME>%x is the name of the new topic/sub-topic (Which must not exceed %c%l13%x characters in length) and %y%l<DESCRIPTION>%x is a short description for the topic (This will appear at the top of the message list ('%g%l%(^bbs read%)%x'/'%g%l%(^bbs view%)%x'.))

For example, '%g%laddtopic Admin = The Admin only area of the BBS%x' will add a new topic to the BBS called '%y%lAdmin%x'.  The sub-topic '%y%lSocial%x' could then be added to the topic '%y%lAdmin%x' by typing '%g%laddtopic Admin/Social = Social area for the administrators of %@%m%x'.

Sub-topics can't be created within other sub-topics  -  They can only be created within the top-level topics (As listed by the '%g%l%(^bbs topics%)%x' BBS command.)  The maximum number of sub-topics allowed within a topic can be set using the '%g%l%(^bbs subtopiclimit%)%x' BBS command (The default is %y%l16%x  -  See '%g%l%<bbs subtopiclimit%>%x'.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<bbs topics%>%x', '%g%l%<subtopics%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs subtopiclimit%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs ownertopic%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs deletetopic%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs settings%>%x' and '%g%l%<bbscmds%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC bbsallowadd
%TOPIC bbsallowadding
%TITLE Help on '%w%lallowadd%x' (BBS)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] allowadd <TOPIC> = yes|no%]%x

The '%g%lallowadd%x' BBS command sets whether new messages may be posted to a topic/sub-topic or not.  The default for a new topic/sub-topic is to allow new messages to be added.

%[%c%lExample:  %g%lallowadd information = no%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<bbs add%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs mortaladd%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs settings%>%x' and '%g%l%<bbscmds%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC bbsallowanon
%TOPIC bbsallowanonymous
%TITLE Help on '%w%lallowanon%x' (BBS)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[bbs] allowanon <TOPIC> = yes|no%]%x

The '%g%lallowanon%x' BBS command sets whether messages within a topic/sub-topic may be made anonymous or not, and whether the '%g%l%(^bbs addanon%)%x', '%g%l%(^bbs replyanon%)%x' and '%g%l%(^bbs appendanon%)%x' BBS commands (See '%g%l%<addanon%>%x', '%g%l%<replyanon%>%x' and '%g%l%<appendanon%>%x') may be used to leave anonymous messages/replies/appends to messages within the topic/sub-topic.

The default for a new topic/sub-topic is to allow anonymous message.

