%TITLE Help on %w%lsub-topics%x
%c%l%8NOTE:  %xPlease see '%g%l%<bbs subtopics%>%x' for help on the BBS '%g%l%(^bbs subtopics%)%x' command.

Topics on %@%n BBS may contain sub-topics.  This allows topics on the BBS to be organised, with topics containing related sub-topics.

In general, all BBS commands which need to be given a %y%l<TOPIC>%x as one of their parameters can also be used to create and maintain sub-topics.  A sub-topic is refered to in the following format:  %y%l<TOPIC>/<SUB-TOPIC>%x

For example, you could refer to the sub-topic '%y%lGeneral%x' in the topic '%y%lNews%x' using '%y%lNews/General%x'.

To add a new sub-topic, you'd simply use '%g%l%(^bbs addtopic%) <TOPIC>/<SUB-TOPIC> = <DESCRIPTION>%x', where %y%l<TOPIC>%x is the name of the topic to add it to, %y%l<SUB-TOPIC>%x is the name to give the sub-topic and %y%l<DESCRIPTION>%x is the short description to give the sub-topic.

%PAGE
All of the settings and restrictions which can be applied to topics can also be applied to individual sub-topics, such as whether messages can be added, the access level required, etc.  In order to access a sub-topic, you must have access to the topic in which it's located.

%8%c%lNOTE:  %xSub-topics can't contain further sub-topics.

If a topic contains sub-topics, it's usual practise to leave the topic itself empty (I.e:  Move any of the messages in it into its sub-topics) and prevent new messages being added to it, using the '%g%l%(^bbs allowadd%) <TOPIC> = no%x' BBS command (See '%g%l%<bbs allowadd%>%x'.)  By doing this, users selecting the topic (Using the '%g%l%(^bbs topic%) <TOPIC>%x' BBS command  -  See '%g%l%<bbs topic%>%x') will be automatically presented with a list of sub-topics in the topic, to choose from.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<bbs%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs subtopic%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs subtopics%>%x', '%g%l%<bbs addtopic%>%x' and '%g%l%<bbscmds%>%x'.

