%TITLE Help on %w%l%@%n World Wide Web Interface%x
%@%n features a %c%lWorld Wide Web Interface%x, through which you can connect using a standard web browser (Such as %y%lNetscape Navigator%x or %y%lMicrosoft Internet Explorer%x) without the need for any additional software.

To use the World Wide Web Interface, you will need a %c%lrecent%x version of either %y%lNetscape Navigator%x or %y%lMicrosoft Internet Explorer%x (Ideally version %c%l4.0%x or better of either), or any other browser capable of supporting %m%lforms%x, %m%lframes%x, %m%ltables%x and %m%lJAVA Script%x.

If your browser isn't quite up-to-date, please visit either %y%l%{@?link "Netscape" "http://www.netscape.com" "Netscape's Web Site"}%x or %y%l%{@?link "Microsoft" "http://www.microsoft.com" "Microsoft's Web Site"}%x's web site and download the latest browser for free.  Not only will the latest browser enhance your %@%m World Wide Web Interface session, you'll also find browsing the rest of the World Wide Web easier.

%8%c%lNOTE:  %xSupport for %m%lJAVA Script%x is advisable, because this will make the World Wide Web Interface more user-friendly by automatically scrolling the output window.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Advantages of the World Wide Web Interface
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xThe World Wide Web Interface offers many advantages over a text-only Telnet connection, including the following:

%4%r%l*  %xSimple and easy to use:  Just start your browser, type in the URL of %@%m's web site ('%b%l%u%{@?link "" "{%@%w}" "{%@%n}'s Web Site"}%x') and follow the links from there.

%4%y%l*  %xEasy fill-in forms to connect or create a new character.

%4%r%l*  %xFull 16 %r%lc%g%lo%y%ll%b%lo%m%lu%c%lr%x ANSI emulation with support for %fflashing%x, %uunderlined%x, %z%l%i%winverted%x text and %i%rtext%x %i%gbackground%x %i%bcolours%x.

%4%y%l*  %xFull hypertext edition of the On-line Help System%| (You're using it now!)%|, complete with links between topics and search facility.  It can also be used externally from %@%m, without even connecting a character.

%4%r%l*  %xSplit windows for input (Typing commands) and output with scroll back and automatic scrolling (JAVA Script required.)

%PAGE
%4%y%l*  %xFull editing on command line (So you can correct typing mistakes, etc.) and recall/edit of previous typed command.

%4%r%l*  %xHTML support within %@%m  -  You can use HTML in your description, building projects, etc.  Most HTML features supported by web browsers can be used, including hyperlinks and images.

%4%y%l*  %xAll internal ('hard coded') commands within %@%m have been coded to take advantage of the World Wide Web Interface, using text formatting, tables, clickable links and buttons, etc.

%4%r%l*  %xUnlike some 'Web Chat' programs, you do not need to continuously reload the page to get output.  The output window stays connected to %@%m (Just like a Telnet connection) with output being delivered as and when it occurs.

%4%y%l*  %xSSL (Secure Socket Layer) connections are supported for increased privacy and security (Providing your browser supports SSL and it is legal to use encryption software in your country.)

%PAGE
%9%6%c%lPLEASE NOTE:  %xThe above features are subject to the World Wide Web browser you are currently using.  Some web browsers may implement some (Or all) of the above features differently or may not support them at all.


%c%l%$Connecting through the World Wide Web Interface...
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xConnecting to %@%m through the World Wide Web Interface is simple:  Just type the URL of %@%n's web site ('%b%l%u%{@?link "" "{%@%w}" "{%@%n}'s Web Site"}%x') into your browser.

Once the web site has loaded, simply click on %y%lConnect Character%x menu item and you will be presented with a fill-in form.  Simply type in your character's %c%lname%x and %c%lpassword%x and then click on the '%y%lConnect to %@%m...%x' button to connect.

Before connecting your character, you should check the %y%lWorld Wide Web Interface Preferences%x at the bottom of the form, which are as follows:

%PAGE

%c%l%$Use your saved preferences.
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%9%6%c%lPLEASE NOTE:  %xThis option doesn't appear on the character creation form.

%@%m remembers the options you first used for connecting through the World Wide Web Interface.  If you leave this option checked, %@%m will ignore any options you set on the connect/create forms and use your saved preferences instead.  This saves you from having to set your options and/or alternative background image every time you connect.

If you wish to change your preferences, simply uncheck this option and then set the rest of the options to your preferred settings.  On connecting, your saved preferences will be updated to the new settings.

You can also change your saved preferences within %@%m.  Typing '%g%l%(set%)%x' (See '%g%l%<set%>%x') will display your usual %@%m preferences, along with a fill-in form (Similar to that found on the character connection form) which shows you your current saved preferences.  You can change these on the form appropriately and then click on the '%y%lSave preferences...%x' button to save your new preferences.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Enable SSL (Secure Socket Layer) connections.
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xIf your browser supports %m%lSSL%x (%y%lSecure Socket Layer%x) connections, you can enable this option to use secure encrypted connections while connected to %@%m, ensuring complete confidentiality and security of information sent to/received from %@%m.  Ideal safeguard against 'packet sniffing' on your network.

%9%4%r%l%uIMPORTANT%r%l:  %y%lUse of encryption software may be %r%l%uillegal%y%l in some countries.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Enable JAVA Script enhancements.
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xIf your web browser supports %m%lJAVA Script%x, you can enable this option to make the World Wide Web Interface easier and more user-friendly to use.

   %4%c%l%$Use new scrolling method (Requires JAVA Script 1.2)
   %~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   %4%xThis option will automatically scroll the output window when activity occurs in it (I.e:  Speech from another user, or output from command you send to %@%m.)  You will need a recent browser with support for %m%lJAVA Script 1.2%x to use this option.

   %4%c%l%$Use old scrolling method (Recommended for older browsers.)
   %~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   %4%xThis option also automatically scrolls the output window, but uses an older method, which should work with many older browsers.  It is not perfect though, and may scroll incorrectly in some browsers (Especially newer ones, where you should be using the new scrolling method instead.)

%PAGE

   %4%c%l%$Automatically set focus to '%@%m command:' box.
   %~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%{@?pad {@?strlen "{%@%m}"} "~"}
   %xThis option automatically sets the focus back to the '%y%l%@%m command:%x' box, so that you do not need to click on it or %g%lTAB%x to it every time you send a command to %@%m (Highly recommended.)

   %8%4%c%lNOTE:  %xIf you get JAVA Script error messages, you will need to obtain a more recent browser, or disable the JAVA enhancements altogether (Not recommended.)


%c%l%$Enable Cascading Style-Sheets enhancements.
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xIf your browser supports %y%lCascading Style-Sheets%x, you can enable this option to take advantage of some page layout enhancements, along with %y%l%i%r%|%h<FONT STYLE="background:#FF0000;">%h%|text background colours%|%h</FONT>%h%|%x (Ensure that you also enable %y%lcoloured text%x.)

%PAGE

%c%l%$Enable coloured text.
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xIf this option is checked, %y%l<FONT COLOR>%x tags will be used to display %r%lc%g%lo%y%ll%b%lo%m%lu%c%lr%r%le%g%ld%x text.  Coloured text simulates ANSI colour, which is supported and used extensively throughout %@%m.

To use this option (Enabled by default), your browser must be able to support %y%l<FONT COLOR>%x tags (Such as %c%lNetscape Navigator 2.0%x and %c%lMicrosoft Internet Explorer 2.0%x and better.)

If you have a slow connection to %@%m, you may wish to turn off this option to improve the performance of your connection (The simulation of ANSI colour generates a suitable %y%l<FONT COLOR>%x tag for each colour change.)

%8%c%lNOTE:  %xYou may also wish to enable %y%lCascading Style-Sheets%x, which will also give you text background colours.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Enable automatically formatted links.
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xIf this option is checked, you will see properly formatted hyperlinks that you can click on, whereever the following link styles are used:

%b%l%uwww.domain%x
%b%l%uhttp://www.domain%x
%b%l%umailto:user@domain%x


%c%l%$Enable graphical smileys (Emoticons.)
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xIf this option is checked, you will see graphical icon smileys (Emoticons) instead of their text-based equivalents (E.g:  %|:-) instead of %|'%m%l:%l-%l)%x'.)  Smileys are used by users to express emotions in conversation.  See '%g%l%<smileys%>%x' for a list of graphical smileys you can use on %@%m.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Italic text instead of underlined text.
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xSome old browsers do not support and ignore the %|%h<U>%h%|%uunderline%x%|%h</U>%h%| (%y%l<U>%x ... %y%l</U>%x) tag.  For this reason, %|%h<I>%h%|italics%x%|%h</I>%h%| (%y%l<I>%x ... %y%l</I>%x) tags can be used instead as an alternative to %|%h<U>%h%|%uunderlined%x%|%h</U>%h%| text.  If your browser supports %|%h<U>%h%|%uunderlined%x%|%h</U>%h%| text, you should not enable this option.


%c%l%$Use alternative background image.
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xBy default, %@%m will usually use a standard background image (Such as a dark hexagonal %@%m logo) behind the text in the output window.

You may wish to disable using a background image altogether (Especially if your computer cannot display at least %c%l256 colours simultaneously%x, which will result in a grainy looking background.)  To do this, simply check the '%y%lUse alternative background image%x' option and leave the box blank.

%PAGE
Alternatively, you can use your own custom background image.  This can be a local image stored on your computer or an image stored on any public World Wide Web server you have access to.  Simply check the '%y%lUse alternative background image%x' option and type the URL of your preferred background into the box, e.g:

%[   %g%lfile:/mypics/mybackground.gif
   http://www.webserver.com/myhomepage/mybackground.gif%]%x

If the background image you use is light in colour, you may need to check the '%y%lReverse foreground and background text colours%x' option, otherwise some text in the output window may be difficult to read.

%c%l%8NOTE:  %xIf the '%y%lUse alternative background image%x' option is unchecked, the default background will always be used.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Reverse foreground and background text colours.
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xThe default colours for the World Wide Web Interface is white and coloured text on a black background.  If you are using an alternative background image which is light in colour, you may need to check this option to switch the colours black and white, so that you are given black and coloured text on a white background.  If you don't do this, you may find some text hard to read.


%c%l%$Width of '%@%m command:' input box.
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%{@?pad {@?strlen "{%@%m}"} "~"}
%xIf you have a high-resolution display, you may like to increase the width of the '%c%l%@%m command:%x' input box to take full advantage of it.  Alternatively, you may need to reduce the width.

%PAGE

%c%l%$How to use the World Wide Web Interface...
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xWhen you connect to %@%m through the World Wide Web Interface, your browser screen will split into two windows:  A small input window (Small lower section), into which you type your commands to %@%m, and a large output window (Large upper section), where you will see output resulting from your commands and activity of other users.


%c%l%$Creating a new character through the World Wide Web Interface...
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xCreating a character through the World Wide Web Interface is simple:  Just type the URL of %@%m's web site ('%b%l%u%{@?link "" "{%@%w}" "{%@%n}'s Web Site"}%x') into your browser.

Once the web site has loaded, simply click on %y%lCreate Character%x menu item and you will be presented with a fill-in form.

%c%l%8NOTE:  %xYou will need to fill in %r%l%uall%x of the options below in-order to create a new character.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Connect as a Guest Character.
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xCheck this option if you would like to connect as a %c%lGuest Character%x rather than creating a new character for yourself.  This option is useful if your Internet site has been banned from creating new characters (Due to abuse.)


%c%l%$Your preferred name.
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xEnter your preferred name for your new character.  This must be %y%l4%x or more letters in length (Maximum of %y%l20%x.)  You can also use %c%lspaces%x (' '), %c%lnumbers%x and %c%lunderscores%x ('%g%l_%x') in your name.

%c%lE.g:  %g%lFred Bloggs

%PAGE

%c%l%$Password.
%~%c~~~~~~~~~
%xEnter a password for your new character (%y%l6%x or more letters or numbers) that you will use in future to connect your character.  This should be something that others will not be able to easily guess to prevent unauthorised/malicious use of your character.

%c%lE.g:  %g%lxfjemcks   %r%l%f(IMPORTANT:  PLEASE DO NOT USE THIS AS YOUR PASSWORD!!!)

%c%l%8NOTE:  %xYour password is %y%lcase-sensitive%x (If you have trouble connecting in future, check that %g%lCAPS-LOCK%x isn't on.)  You can change your password to something else by typing '%g%l%(@password%)%x' (See '%g%l%<@password%>%x') at any time while connected to %@%m.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Verify password.
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xType your password in again, %c%l%uexactly%x as you typed it the first time.  This is to ensure that you have entered it correctly, so that you will be able to connect your character the next time you want to use %@%m.

%c%lE.g:  %g%lxfjemcks   %r%l%f(IMPORTANT:  PLEASE DO NOT USE THIS AS YOUR PASSWORD!!!)


%c%l%$Gender.
%~%c~~~~~~~
%xChoose the gender (Sex) of your character from the three available options:  %y%lMale%x, %y%lFemale%x or %y%lNeuter%x.

%c%l%8NOTE:  %xPlease be honest when choosing your gender.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Disclaimer.
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~
%xPlease read this %r%lcarefully%x, and then check the box below it if you accept its terms and conditions, which your usage of %@%m is subject to.


%c%l%$Your character's race.
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xEnter a race for your character.

%c%lE.g:  %g%lHuman%x, %g%lAlien%x, etc.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Your full E-mail address.
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xEnter your %r%lFULL%x and %m%lvalid%x E-mail address.  This is required to ensure that you are a %r%lgenuine%x new user, and to allow Admin. to contact you should the need arises.

%c%lE.g:  %g%lFred.Bloggs@email.com

%xIf you wish to obtain %(Builder%) privileges to build your %(rooms%) and areas, you will need a valid private E-mail address ('Free' E-mail addresses from %c%lHotmail%x and similar services are not acceptable, because these can be obtained anonymously by anybody.)

%c%l%8NOTE:  %xYour E-mail address will be kept %r%lstrictly private and confidential%x unless you choose to make it public.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Time difference.
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xIf you live in a different %y%ltime zone%x from that of %@%m (%c%l%@%z%x), you should enter your time difference here, in hours.

%c%lE.g:  %g%l3    %c(%y%l3%x %c%lhours ahead of time shown.%c)
      %7%g%l-5   %c(%y%l5%x %c%lhours behind time shown.%c)


%xBefore creating your new character, you should check the %y%lWorld Wide Web Interface Preferences%x at the bottom of the form (See the earlier section on %c%lConnecting through the World Wide Web Interface%x for full details of these options.)

%PAGE

%c%l%$How to use the World Wide Web Interface...
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xWhen you connect to %@%m through the World Wide Web Interface, your browser screen will split into two windows:  A small input window (Small lower section), into which you type your commands to %@%m, and a large output window (Large upper section), where you will see output resulting from your commands and activity of other users.


%c%l%$The input window
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xThe small lower section is where you type your commands to %@%m (This is mainly refered to as the '%c%lcommand-line%x'.)  In addition to sending commands to %@%m, a number of buttons are also provided, which perform several useful functions (These are described in more detail further on in this text.)

%PAGE
Unlike most standard Telnet software, you can fully edit the text you type by using the cursor keys to move along the line.  This means you can easily correct typing mistakes.  You can also recall the last command you typed and edit it by clicking on the %y%lRECALL%x button.

You don't need to click on the %y%lSEND%x button every time you type a command (Unless you prefer to do this)  -  Simply type your command and then press %c%lRETURN%x or %c%lENTER%x to send it to %@%m.

To speak to other users in the same room as you, you usually need to type '%g%l%(say%)%x' (See '%g%l%<say%>%x') in front of your message.  However, if you click on the %y%l%(CONVERSE%)%x button, so that the text in it changes from %r%lred%x to %g%lgreen%x (Indicating that it is switched on), you can just type your message and it will automatically be spoken to other users in the room.  To enter commands again, simply click on the %y%l%(CONVERSE%)%x button again to switch it off.  Alternatively, you can simply type a '%g%l.%x' in front of your command, i.e:  '%g%l.help html%x'.

%PAGE
The %y%lHELP%x and %y%lTUTORIAL%x buttons will call up the On-line Help and Tutorial systems respectively.  When you click on these buttons, a new browser window will open (So that your connection to %@%m isn't interrupted), in which you can browse the On-line Help and Tutorials.  If you have a printer connected to your computer, you can also print out the On-line Help and Tutorial pages.

The %y%l%(USERLIST%)%x button will open a new browser window and display a list of currently connected users, in the same format as the '%g%l%(who%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<who%>%x'.)  This window will automatically refresh itself every %y%l30%x seconds if left open.

The %y%lLOGOUT%x button is used to disconnect your character from %@%m and close your connection (Alternatively, you can type '%g%l%(QUIT%)%x' on %@%m (See '%g%l%<QUIT%>%x'.))  Once you have finished using %@%m, and wish to log out, you should click on this button to close your connection and then exit your web browser (See below for why you need to do this.)

%PAGE
%9%4%c%lIMPORTANT:  %r%l%f%uALWAYS%x completely exit your web browser after you have finished using %@%m (If you still need to use it, you can easily run it again.)  If you fail to do this, somebody else could come along (Especially if you are using a computer which is publicly accessible, such as a library or university computer room) and click on the %y%lBACK%x button to get back to the connect form and connect as your character.

            %9%4Please %m%lDON'T%x click on the %y%lSTOP%x button or close your browser without logging out of %@%m first, because this will leave your character still connected for %c%l5 minutes%x (%@%m thinks that you've lost your connection, so keeps your character connected to give you time to reconnect and resume it again (This can be done by either reloading the page or using the connect form to reconnect.)

%PAGE

%|%h<A NAME="OutputWindow">%h%|%c%l%$The output window
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xThe large upper section is where output from %@%m will be displayed (Such as descriptions of rooms you enter, speech/actions from other users, etc.)

This window stays connected to %@%m, so that you get output as and when it occurs without needing to reload the page.  As the output is effectively like downloading an infinitely sized web page, you may need to click on %y%lRELOAD%x from time to time to clear the output and free up the memory of your computer.  How often you need to do this depends on how much memory and hard disk space your computer has, and the quantity of output you receive.

If you are on slow Internet connection (Low speed modem) or your computer doesn't have much memory (I.e:  Less than 8Mb), it's advisable to turn off downloading of images in your browser (This can be found in the browser's menus.)

%PAGE
If your web browser supports %c%lJAVA script%x, you can have it automatically scroll the output window for you each time activity occurs in it.  If not, you will need to scroll it yourself manually.  For more information, please see the earlier section entitled '%y%lEnable JAVA Script enhancements%x'.


