%c%l%$Common problems and solutions
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%|%h<BR>%h%|%9%3%r%l%uPROBLEM:%x%|%h<BR>%h%|%^   %^Attempting to connect gives '%y%lSorry, corrupt HTML data received...%x' or '%y%lSorry, your browser sent a query that cannot be understood by this server...%x'

%9%3%g%l%uSOLUTION:%x%|%h<BR>%h%|%^  %^Please ensure you are attempting to connect to %@%m through the proper official web pages, which can be found at:  %9%3%b%l%u%{@?link "" "{%@%w}" "{%@%n}'s Web Site"}

%9%3%r%l%uPROBLEM:%x%|%h<BR>%h%|%^   %^Attempting to connect gives a page saying '%y%lSorry, your browser doesn't support frames...%x'

%9%3%g%l%uSOLUTION:%x%|%h<BR>%h%|%^  %^%@%m's World Wide Web Interface requires a browser capable of supporting %c%lframes%x, %c%lfill-in forms%x and %c%ltables%x at minimum.  Many older browsers do not support these features.  You will need to download a more recent browser, such as %y%lNetscape Navigator%x or %y%lMicrosoft Internet Explorer%x (Ideally %c%lversion 4.0%x or better of either.)

%PAGE
%9%3%r%l%uPROBLEM:%x%|%h<BR>%h%|%^   %^%@%m ignores or doesn't respond to any of the commands I type in the input window ('%y%l%@%m command:%x'), although I am connected and the output window is still updating.

%9%3%g%l%uSOLUTION:%x%|%h<BR>%h%|%^  %^The input window isn't connected to %@%m properly.  To solve this problem, simply click on your browser's %y%lRELOAD%x button to reload the page.

%9%3%r%l%uPROBLEM:%x%|%h<BR>%h%|%^   %^After sending a command to %@%m, I get '%y%lSorry, corrupt HTML data recieved...%x'

%9%3%g%l%uSOLUTION:%x%|%h<BR>%h%|%^  %^In rare cases, you may get the '%y%lSorry, corrupt HTML data recieved...%x' message in your input window after sending a command to %@%m.  This is a fault with some browsers and can be resolved simply by clicking on the browser's %y%lRELOAD%x button to reload the page.

%PAGE
%^           %^%9%3If this problem persists, try exiting your browser altogether and then starting it again.  If the problem still persists after that, you may need to download a more recent or different web browser (Preferably %y%lNetscape Navigator%x or %y%lMicrosoft Internet Explorer%x.)

%9%3%r%l%uPROBLEM:%x%|%h<BR>%h%|%^   %^The output window doesn't scroll automatically when new output occurs in it.

%9%3%g%l%uSOLUTION:%x%|%h<BR>%h%|%^  %^You need a web browser capable of supporting %c%lJAVA Script%x for the output window to scroll automatically whenever activity occurs in it.  For more information, please see the earlier section entitled '%y%l'Enable JAVA Script enhancements%x'.

%PAGE
%9%3%r%l%uPROBLEM:%x%|%h<BR>%h%|%^   %^The output window does not scroll all the way down to the bottom.

%9%3%g%l%uSOLUTION:%x%|%h<BR>%h%|%^  %^This is a common problem with the %c%lold JAVA scrolling%x method.  Ensure that you have a web browser installed that is capable of supporting %y%lJAVA Script 1.2%x (The latest versions of %y%lNetscape%x and %y%lMicrosoft Internet Explorer%x both do) and enable the %c%lnew JAVA scrolling%x method rather than the old one.

%9%3%r%l%uPROBLEM:%x%|%h<BR>%h%|%^   %^The World Wide Web Interface is extremely slow.

%9%3%g%l%uSOLUTION:%x%|%h<BR>%h%|%^  %^In order to use the World Wide Web Interface, you will ideally need a computer with a minimum of %y%l16Mb%x memory (%y%l64Mb%x or more recommended.)  Your computer should at least be equivalent to a %c%l486 PC%x (%y%lPentium%x or better recommended.)

%PAGE
%^           %^%9%3World Wide Web browsers, such as %y%lNetscape Navigator%x and %y%lMicrosoft Internet Explorer%x use a lot of memory, and can cause a lot of disk activity on computers with insufficient memory.

%^           %^%9%3If your computer is short on memory or has a slow processor, try closing down any other applications you have running first (With the exception of your Internet connection software.)

%^           %^%9%3The speed of your Internet connection also effects your connection through the World Wide Web Interface.  If you have a slow modem, or your Internet connection to %@%m is slow or poor, you will not be able to use the World Wide Web Interface.

%^           %^%9%3Either upgrade your modem (If it is the cause of the problem) or use Telnet (%c%lText-only%x) software to connect.

%PAGE
%^           %^%9%3If your computer is low on memory or your connection speed is slow, turning off loading of images in your web browser may help considerably, as these can be quite large in size, slowing down your connection and using up a lot of memory.

%^           %^%9%3A useful tip is to click on the %y%lRELOAD%x button every once in a while to clear the output window, which frees up the memory used by it.  The output window contains all the output (Including images) which occurred since you connected to %@%m or last clicked on the %y%lRELOAD%x button of your browser.%x

%PAGE
%9%3%r%l%uPROBLEM:%x%|%h<BR>%h%|%^   %^ASCII Art in people's '%g%l%(scan%)%x' (See '%g%l%<scan%>%x') and room descriptions is messed up when using the World Wide Web Interface, but looks fine when using Telnet.

%9%3%g%l%uSOLUTION:%x%|%h<BR>%h%|%^  %^Ask the owner to enclose the ASCII Art in %g%l%%[%x ... %g%l%%]%x substitution codes (See '%g%l%<substitutions%>%x'), which will instruct the World Wide Web Interface to format the ASCII Art correctly, so that it displays properly in your web browser (%c%lNOTE:  %xTo find out the owner of a room, type '%g%l%(settings%)%x' (See '%g%l%<settings%>%x') while in the room.)


%r%l%f%$!IMPORTANT!   %m%l%$*****  Security considerations  *****   %r%l%f%$!IMPORTANT!
%~%r%f~~~~~~~~~~~   %m~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~   %r%f~~~~~~~~~~~
%xIf you are using the World Wide Web Interface on a computer which can or will be used by other people (Such as a %c%luniversity computer room%x, %c%llibrary%x or %c%lInternet Cafe%x), there are a number of precautions you will need to take to prevent somebody else from maliciously hacking into your %@%m character:

%PAGE
%6%g%l(1)  %xDon't leave your computer/browser unattended at %r%l%f%uany time%x (Even in %g%l%(AFK%)%x mode (See '%g%l%<afk%>%x')), unless your computer is somewhere where nobody else will be able to get access to it and play around with it.  If you need to leave your computer unattended, you should disconnnect from %@%m (Click %y%lLOGOUT%x or type '%g%l%(QUIT%)%x') and exit your browser altogether (See %g%l(2)%x and %g%l(3)%x.)

%6%g%l(2)  %xMake sure you disconnect from %@%m by clicking on the %y%lLOGOUT%x button or typing '%g%l%(QUIT%)%x', otherwise your character will remain connected for up to %c%l5 minutes%x (This is to give you the opportunity to resume your connection if you lose it for some reason, such as visiting a link to another page which hasn't been set to open a new web browser window.)

%PAGE
%6%g%l(3)  %xOnce you have finished using %@%m, clear the disk cache (If you know how to  -  This option is usually in the %y%lPREFERENCES%x menu of the browser) and then completely exit the browser altogether.  If you fail to at least exit the browser, another person could come along and click the %y%lBACK%x button to get back to the connect form (Still complete with the character name and password you entered to connect to %@%m) and connect as your character.

If you fail to take the above precautions, you are opening the door for hackers to maliciously hack into your %@%m character, giving them the opportunity to ruin your building work or use your character for malicious purposes.

%|%h<CENTER>%h%|%r%l%f%uYou ignore these precautions at your own risk!%x%|%h</CENTER>%h%|
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<ssl%>%x', '%g%l%<substitutions%>%x' and '%g%l%<www%>%x' (Details of %y%l%@%n Web Site%x.)

