%TOPIC safeguard
%TITLE Help on '%w%l|%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l|<COMMAND>%]%x

Normally, when you type a command, %@%m searches up the area tree for a compound command of that name first, before testing to see if it's a built in command.  This means that if someone created a compound command with the same name as an internal command, that command would get executed instead of the internal command.

To get round this, type a vertical bar '%g%l|%x' followed by the command you want to execute.  This forces %@%m to ignore all compound commands of the same name (If they exist) and execute the command as an internal one.  If you can't get an internal command to work, or it doesn't do what it should, put a vertical bar in front of it.  Write down/remember the room you're in and the command you were trying to execute, and let a %c%lWizard/%cDruid%x or above know as soon as possible (Whoever created the command (If it's malicious) will have their %y%l%(BUILDER%)%x flag and building privileges removed from them.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@command%>%x'.

