%TITLE Help on '%w%lafk%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%lafk <MESSAGE>
        afk on|off
        afk <TIME>%]%x

This command puts you into AFK (%c%lAway From Keyboard%x (See '%g%l%<abbreviations%>%x')) mode.  To enter AFK mode, simply type '%g%lafk%x' followed by an AFK message, e.g:  '%g%lafk Getting something eat - back soon...%x', etc.  Once in AFK mode, you'll appear in the '%g%l%(who%)%x' list with the title '%y%lis AFK and idle%x' (Don't worry, your original title will return when you leave AFK mode) and people will get your AFK message if they try to '%g%l%(page%)%x'/'%g%l%(tell%)%x' messages to you.

To leave AFK mode, simply type in your character's password at the '%r%l[AFK]%x  Please enter your password:' prompt.

AFK mode is perfect when you're going to be AFK for a short period of time and don't want anyone to fiddle with your character.  However, even though no-one can do anything malicious with your character, someone could still exit your Telnet client and fiddle around in your user area.

%PAGE
%@%m also features an auto-AFK facility, which (By default) sends you AFK automatically when you idle for %c%l10%x or more minutes.  This time can be changed by typing '%g%lafk <TIME>%x', where %y%l<TIME>%x is the time in minutes.  The auto-AFK facility can also be turned off, by typing '%g%lafk off%x'.

Your new auto-AFK setting is not permanent.  However, you can place '%g%lafk%x' in your '%y%l.login%x' compound command (See '%g%l%<.login%>%x'), so that your AFK preference is set automatically when you connect to %@%m.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<set afk%>%x'.

