%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%lassist [<NAME>] [= <RESPONSE>]
        assist list [<PAGE NO>]
        assist <REASON>%]%x

The '%g%lassist%x' command is used to ask for assistance from %@%n's administrators (And %r%lExperienced Builders/%rAssistants%x, if there are %c%l3%x or less %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above connected.)

To ask for assistance, simply type '%g%lassist%x' followed by the reason you are asking for assistance/what you need assistance on, e.g:  '%g%lassist Can someone show me how to use the BBS%x', '%g%lassist Can someone help me with one of my compound commands?%x', etc.

Your request for assistance will be sent to %@%n's administrators  -  Usually, someone will be available to help you within a few minutes.  If you do not receive assistance after %c%l5 minutes%x or more, you can ask again by typing '%g%lassist%x' followed by your reason (As detailed above.)

%PAGE
%r%lExperienced Builders/%rAssistants%x and above can use '%g%lassist list%x' to display a list of users who need assistance  -  You can give assistance to one of these users by typing '%g%lassist <NAME>%x', or give assistance to the first user in the list by typing '%g%lassist%x' on its own.

%8%c%lNOTE:  %r%lExpererienced Builders/%rAssistants%x above can give assistance to users who have not received a response for over %c%l2 minutes%x, or when there are %c%l3%x or less %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above connected.

Giving assistance to a user will teleport you to their current location and let them know that you are available to help them.  Alternatively, you can give your %y%l<RESPONSE>%x ('%g%lassist <NAME> = <RESPONSE>%x'), which will be sent to them without teleporting you to their current location (Ideal for dealing with requests for assistance which can be answered with a single message.)

%PAGE
If %y%l<PAGE NO>%x is specified, the list of users who need welcoming will be split up into pages and the page number specified will be displayed, e.g:  '%g%lassist list 1%x', '%g%lassist list 2%x', etc.

Usage of the '%g%lassist%x' command is logged to the '%c%lAssist%x' log file (See '%g%l%<@log%>%x'.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<welcome%>%x', '%g%l%<@log%>%x' and '%g%l%<admin%>%x'.

