%TOPIC @?protect
%TOPIC @?protected
%TOPIC @?protecting
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?protect}%x'
%c%l%[USAGE:  %g%l{@?protect <SUBST> "<STRING>"}%]%x

Protects substitution characters in the string %y%l<STRING>%x.

%y%l<SUBST>%c%l can be one of the following keywords:

  %[%g%lCMD  %xProtects '%y%l\%x', '%y%l{%x' and '%y%l$%x' against substitution.
  %g%lALL  %xProtects '%y%l%%%x', '%y%l\%x', '%y%l{%x' and '%y%l$%x' against substitution.%]

%m%l...Or a string containing one or more of the following characters...

  %[%g%lS    %xProtects '%y%l%%%x' against substitution (Replaces with '%y%l%%%%%x'.)
  %g%lB    %xProtects '%y%l\%x' against substitution (Replaces with '%y%l\\%x'.)
  %g%lC    %xProtects '%y%l{%x' against substitution (Replaces with '%y%l\{%x'.)
  %g%lV    %xProtects '%y%l$%x' against substitution (Replaces with '%y%l\$%x'.)%]

%PAGE
'%y%lS%x' is useful for protecting %c%l%%-type substitutions%x (I.e:  %(ANSI%) colour codes (See '%g%l%<ansi colour%>%x')), so that they are not evaluted (I.e:  Turned into colours.)

'%y%lCMD%x' and '%y%lALL%x' are useful for protecting a string passed to '%g%l%(@force%)%x' (See '%g%l%<@force%>%x') to guard against unwanted substitutions (Particularly useful in soft-coded commands, where substitutions are not wanted and can be a security risk  -  The forced character can be forced to execute substituted commands otherwise.)

%PAGE

%c%l%$Example:
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@echo%) {@?protect S "%%r%%lYou will see %%y%%lcolour codes%%r%%l in this string!"}

%(@command%) forcetest = \
   %(@force%) me = %(@echo%) PROTECTED:  \{@?protect ALL "$3"}\
   %(@force%) me = %(@echo%) UNPROTECTED:  $3

forcetest %%r%%l\{%(page%) me = %%m%%l%%fHi!} - $variable \\ Backslash%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?filter%>%x', '%g%l%<@force%>%x', '%g%l%<substitutions%>%x' and '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x'.

