%TOPIC @?cmdname
%TOPIC @?commandname
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?cmdname}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?cmdname}%]%x

For compound commands which have multiple names (Separated by '%y%l;%x's, e.g:  '%g%l%(@command%) sit;stand;relax%x'), '%g%l{@?cmdname}%x' returns the name by which the compound command was executed.  Returns '%y%l*NOTHING*%x' if not called from within a compound command.


%c%l%$Example compound command '%w%l%$sit;stand;relax%c%l%$':
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@if%) {%(@eval%) "{@?cmdname}" = "sit"} do
    %(@echo%) You sit down and rest.
    %(@oemote%) sits down and rests.
%(@else%) {%(@eval%) "{@?cmdname}" = "relax"} do
    %(@echo%) You sit back and relax.
    %(@oemote%) sits back and relaxes.
%(@else%) {%(@eval%) "{@?cmdname}" = "stand"} do
    %(@echo%) You stand up.
    %(@oemote%) stands up.
%(@end%)%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@command%>%x', '%g%l%<@if%>%x', '%g%l%<@else%>%x', '%g%l%<@end%>%x' and '%g%l%<@eval%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------

%TOPIC @?csize
%TOPIC @?compresssize
%TOPIC @?compressedsize
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?csize}%x'
%[%c%LUSAGE:  %g%l{@?csize [<OBJECT>]}%]%x

Returns the compressed size of %y%l<OBJECT>%x (Or yourself, if %y%l<OBJECT>%x isn't specified) in bytes.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?size%>%x' and '%g%l%<@size%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?cstring
%TOPIC @?contentstring
%TOPIC @?contentsstring
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?cstring}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?cstring <OBJECT>}%]%x

Returns the contents string of the room or thing %y%l<OBJECT>%x.  If it does not have a contents string, the default of '%y%l%uContents:%x' will be returned.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found, or is not a room or thing.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@cstring%>%x', '%g%l%<@estring%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?estring%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?csucc
%TOPIC @?csuccess
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?csucc}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?csucc <COMMAND>}%]%x

Returns the ID of the compound command that the csuccess of the compound command %y%l<COMMAND>%x is linked to.  If %y%l<COMMAND>%x isn't specified, the current compound command being executed is assumed.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<COMMAND>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@csucc%>%x', '%g%l%<@cfail%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?cfail%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?commands
%TOPIC @?compoundcommands
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?commands}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?commands <OBJECT> [= <NUMBER>]}%]%x

Returns the name (Or ID if you control it) of the first (Or %y%l<NUMBER>%x'th, if %y%l<NUMBER>%x is specified) compound command in %y%l<OBJECT>%x's compound command list.  Returns '%y%l*NOTHING*%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x has no compound commands.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?next%>%x' and '%g%l%<@command%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?connected
%TOPIC connectedflag
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?connected}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?connected <NAME>}%]%x

Succeeds if the character %y%l<NAME>%x is currently connected to %@%n.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if they aren't connected, or the character %y%l<NAME>%x isn't found.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?contents
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?contents}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?contents <OBJECT>}%]%x

Returns the name (Or ID if you control it) of the first object in %y%l<OBJECT>%x's contents list.  Returns '%y%l*NOTHING*%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x has no contents.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?next%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?controller
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?controller}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?controller [<NAME>]}%]%x

Returns the controller of the character %y%l<NAME>%x (Or your controller, if %y%l<NAME>%x isn't specified.)  If %y%l<NAME>%x isn't a puppet, their controller will be themselves.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@controller%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?erase
%TOPIC @?delete
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?delete}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?delete <NUMBER> "<SEPARATOR>" "<LIST>"}%]%x

Removes the item number %y%l<NUMBER>%x from the list %y%l<LIST>%x, and returns the resulting new list.  If the item number specified doesn't exist, the list remains the same.  %y%l<SEPARATOR>%x is the string used to separate the items in the list from each other.

If you use the word '%y%lLAST%x' instead of specifing a number for %y%l<NUMBER>%x, it deletes the last item in the list.  Using the word '%y%lFIRST%x' deletes the first item in the list.


%c%l%$Example:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l{@?delete 2 ";" "eggs;bacon;sausage;chips;mushrooms"}%]%x

...returns '%y%leggs;sausage;chips;mushrooms%x' ('%y%lbacon%x' (The 2nd item) has been deleted.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?insert%>%x', '%g%l%<@?modify%>%x' and '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?modify
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?modify}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?modify "<NEW ITEM>" <NUMBER> "<SEPARATOR>" "<LIST>"}%]%x

Replaces item number %y%l<NUMBER>%x in the list %y%l<LIST>%x with %y%l<NEW ITEM>%x and returns the resulting new list.  If the item number specified doesn't exist, the list remains the same.  %y%l<SEPARATOR>%x is the string used to separate the items in the list from each other.

If you use the word '%y%lLAST%x' instead of specifing a number for %y%l<NUMBER>%x, it replaces the last item in the list.  Using the word '%y%lFIRST%x' replaces the first item in the list.


%c%l%$Examples:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l{@?modify "tomato" 2 ";" "eggs;bacon;sausage;chips;mushrooms"}%]%x

...returns '%y%leggs;tomato;sausage;chips;mushrooms%x' ('%y%lbacon%x' (The 2nd item) has been been replaced with '%y%ltomato%x'.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?insert%>%x', '%g%l%<@?delete%>%x' and '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?delay
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?delay}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?delay [<NAME>]}%]%x

If the character %y%l<NAME>%x isn't specified, your combat delay (The amount of time in seconds until you can next fight/use a weapon), otherwise the character %y%l<NAME>%x's combat delay is returned, providing you're of a higher level than them, or they're one of your puppets.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<combat%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?date
%TOPIC @?datetime
%TOPIC convertingdates
%TOPIC convertingtimes
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?datetime}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?datetime <DATE> [= [epoch|longdate] [date|time]]}%]%x

Converts the string %y%l<DATE>%x to a date/time in either the %c%lEPOCH%x (See '%g%l%<epoch%>%x') or %c%lLONGDATE%x (See '%g%l%<longdate%>%x') numeric date/time format.  '%g%l{@?datetime}%x' fully validates the given date, taking the number of days per month and leap years into account.

The date/time must be given in the following order:  %y%l<DAY> <MONTH> <YEAR> <HOUR> <MINUTE> <SECOND>%x, e.g:  The date '%y%lTuesday 11th June 1996, 3:10.21 pm%x' could also be specified in the following formats:  '%y%l11 June 1996, 3:10.21pm%x', '%y%l11/6/1996 - 15:10.21%x', '%y%lMon 11 Jun 1996; 3-10-21pm%x', etc.  The time may optionally be omitted (%c%l12:00.00 am%x will be assumed if the time is omitted.)

%PAGE
If '%y%llongdate%x' is specified, the converted date will be returned in the %c%lLONGDATE%x date format, otherwise it will be returned in %c%lEPOCH%x date/time format.  Please see '%g%l%<epoch%>%x' and '%g%l%<longdate%>%x' for more information on the %c%lEPOCH%x and %c%lLONGDATE%x date/time formats.

If '%y%ldate%x' is specified, %y%l<DATE>%x will be converted as a date only, otherwise if '%y%ltime%x' is specified, %y%l<DATE>%x will be converted as a time only.  If neither are specified, %y%l<DATE>%x will be converted as date and time.

For more information on the %c%lEPOCH%x and %c%lLONGDATE%x date/time formats, please see '%g%l%<epoch%>%x' and '%g%l%<longdate%>%x'.

%c%l%8NOTE:  %xTCZ is %y%lYear 2000%x complient (Y2K) because all dates stored internally use either the %c%lEPOCH%x or %c%lLONGDATE%x format.
%PAGE

%[%c%l%$Two-digit dates are handled as follows:
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%y%l00 %y- %y%l37  %c=  %m%l2000 %m- %m%l2037
%y%l38 %y- %y%l69  %c=  %m%l2038 %m- %m%l2069  %c(%w%l%(LONGDATE%) %c%lonly%c)
%y%l38 %y- %y%l69  %c=  %m%l1938 %m- %m%l1969  %c(%w%l%(EPOCH%) %c%lonly%c)
%y%l70 %y- %y%l99  %c=  %m%l1970 %m- %m%l1999%]%x


%c%l%$Examples:
%~%c~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@echo%) {%(@?realtime%) {@?datetime Tuesday 11th June 1996, 3:10.21 pm}}
%(@echo%) {%(@?realtime%) {@?datetime 11/6/1996 3:10.21pm}}
%(@echo%) {%(@?realtime%) {@?datetime 29/02/00}}%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?realtime%>%x', '%g%l%<@?interval%>%x', '%g%l%<@?time%>%x', '%g%l%<@?timediff%>%x', '%g%l%<epoch%>%x' and '%g%l%<longdate%>%x'.

