%[%c%l%$Code:%x  %c%l%$Description%x                                             %c%l%$Example
%~%c~~~~~  ~~~~~~~~~~~                                             ~~~~~~~
%y%lw      %xWeek of year without leading zero (%c%l0%x - %c%l53%x)              %g%l%{@?realtime = epoch = w}
%y%lww     %xWeek of year with leading zero (%c%l00%x - %c%l53%x)                %g%l%{@?realtime = epoch = ww}
%y%lwww    %xWeek of year with leading space (%c%l 0%x - %c%l53%x)               %g%l%{@?realtime = epoch = www}
%y%lW      %xAbbreviated name of weekday (%c%lSun%x - %c%lSat%x)                 %g%l%{@?realtime = epoch = W}
%y%lWW     %xFull name of weekday (%c%lSunday%x - %c%lSaturday%x)                %g%l%{@?realtime = epoch = WW}

%y%ly      %x1-digit year (%c%l0%x - %c%l9%x)                                    %g%l%{@?realtime = epoch = y}
%y%lyy     %x2-digit year (%c%l00%x - %c%l99%x)                                  %g%l%{@?realtime = epoch = yy}
%y%lyyy    %x3-digit year (%c%l000%x - %c%l999%x)                                %g%l%{@?realtime = epoch = yyy}
%y%lyyyy   %x4-digit year (%c%l0000%x - %c%l9999%x)                              %g%l%{@?realtime = epoch = yyyy}

%y%lZ      %xServer time zone.                                       %g%l%{@?realtime = epoch = Z}

%PAGE

%c%l%$Examples:
%~%c~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l@dateformat long = W d M yyyy
@dateformat short = mm/dd/yyyy
@dateformat time = H:nn Z%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<date%>%x', '%g%l%<@?realtime%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?datetime%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @delay
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@delay%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@delay <NAME> = [+/-]<TIME>%]%x

This command can only be used from within a compound command with its %y%l%(COMBAT%)%x flag set (See '%g%l%<combat flag%>%x'), in a location which also has its %y%l%(COMBAT%)%x flag set.  Both must be owned by the same character.

'%g%l@delay%x' increases (Or decreases, if a negative %y%l<TIME>%x is specified) the character %y%l<NAME>%x's combat delay by %y%l<TIME>%x seconds, and is ideal for creating 'stun' weapons, e.g:  '%g%l@delay *fred = 10%x' will increase the character "%c%lFred%x"'s combat delay by %y%l10 seconds%x.

A character subject to a combat delay can't fight again (I.e:  Use '%g%l%(@damage%)%x') until the time of their delay has passed.

%PAGE
%c%l%8NOTE:  %x'%g%l@delay%x' cannot be used on yourself if you own the compound command or location in which it is used, or the character %y%l<NAME>%x is not in the same location as you.  These restrictions can be removed by setting %y%l%(WIZARD%)%x or %y%l%(ELDER%)%x flags on the combat commands respectively (See '%g%l%<wizard flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<elder flag%>%x'.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@damage%>%x', '%g%l%<@heal%>%x', '%g%l%<substitutions%>%x', '%g%l%<combat flag%>%x', '%g%l%<wizard flag%>%x', '%g%l%<elder flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<combat%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @dolist
%TOPIC @?dolist
%TOPIC @foreach
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@foreach%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@foreach [<GRP/RANGE>] "<SEPARATOR>" "<LIST>" do [<COMMAND>]
                 [<COMMANDS>]
        [@end]%]%x

The '%g%l@foreach%x' command can be used in two forms:  The first form may only be used on a %c%lSINGLE LINE%x.  '%g%l@foreach%x' is used to process the items in a list (In left to right order), executing %y%l<COMMAND>%x for each item processed.

%y%l<SEPARATOR>%x is the string used to separate the items in the list from each other.

%[%c%lExample:  %g%l@foreach ";" "eggs;bacon;sausage;chips;mushrooms" do @echo Item:  $6%]%x

%PAGE
The reserved variables %y%l$4%x, %y%l$5%x and %y%l$6%x are useful in an '%g%l@foreach%x' statement  -  These substitute the following...

%4%y%l$4 %xsubstitutes the current item number in the list being processed (Most useful when using grouping/range operators with '%g%l@foreach%x'.)
%4%y%l$5 %xsubstitutes the total number of items processed so far.
%4%y%l$6 %xsubstitutes the item in the list currently being processed.

%8%c%lNOTE:  %x'%g%l@foreach%x' can only be used from within compound commands (Unless you're an %r%lExperienced Builder%x or above.)

The second form of '%g%l@foreach%x' allows you to execute a 'block' of commands.

When using '%g%l@foreach%x' in this form, it %c%lMUST%x be spread over multiple lines and terminated with '%g%l%(@end%)%x'.  '%g%l@foreach%x' and '%g%l%(@end%)%x' %c%lMUST NOT%x be preceeded by any text other than blank space, or used within %y%l{}%x's (I.e:  '%g%l{@foreach ...}%x'.)  The '%y%ldo%x' keyword %c%lMUST NOT%x be followed with a %y%l<COMMAND>%x.

%PAGE
The usage of '%g%l@foreach%x' in this form is identical to the single lined version of '%g%l@foreach%x', except it is spread over multiple lines, e.g:

%[%g%l@foreach ";" "eggs;bacon;sausage;chips;mushrooms" do
         %(@echo%) Item:  $6
         %(@echo%) Item number:  $4
@end%]%x

%9%6%c%lPLEASE NOTE:  %xYou can 'nest' further '%g%l%(@if%)%x', '%g%l%(@case%)%x', '%g%l%(@for%)%x', '%g%l%(@with%)%x', '%g%l%(@while%)%x' and '%g%l%(@foreach%)%x' statements (Both single and multiple lined) within a multiple line '%g%l@foreach%x' statement.

%PAGE

%c%l%$[<GRP/RANGE>]
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xGrouping/range operators may optionally be used with '%g%l@foreach%x' to process a given page or range of items in a list.  For example, you can process the %c%lfirst page%x of items in a list using '%g%l@foreach 1:default <SEPARATOR> <LIST> do ...%x' or process the %c%l2nd%x to %c%l5th%x items in a list using '%g%l@foreach 2-5 <SEPARATOR> <LIST> do ...%x'

See '%g%l%<group%>%x' and '%g%l%<range%>%x' for more details on grouping/range operators and how to use them.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<group%>%x', '%g%l%<range%>%x', '%g%l%<@end%>%x', '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x', '%g%l%<@if%>%x', '%g%l%<@case%>%x', '%g%l%<@for%>%x', '%g%l%<@with%>%x', '%g%l%<@while%>%x', '%g%l%<@skip%>%x', '%g%l%<@breakloop%>%x', '%g%l%<@break%>%x', '%g%l%<@return%>%x' and '%g%l%<@goto%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?drop
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?drop}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?drop <OBJECT>}%]%x

Returns the drop message of %y%l<OBJECT>%x.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@drop%>%x', '%g%l%<@odrop%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?odrop%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?element
%TOPIC @?elementno
%TOPIC @?elementnumber
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?elementno}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?elementno <ARRAY>[<ELEMENT>]}%]%x

Returns the description (Or contents if you like) of an element (Or range of elements) of a dynamic array, e.g:  '%g%l{@?elementno myarray[2]}%x' returns the description of the %c%l2nd%x element of the dynamic array '%y%lmyarray%x' and '%g%l{@?elementno myarray[test]}%x' returns the description of the element with the index name '%y%ltest%x' of '%y%lmyarray%x'.

If a range of elements is specified, the descriptions of these elements will be returned, separated by %c%lNEWLINE%x's, e.g:  '%g%l{@?elementno myarray[4..7]}%x' will return the descriptions of elements %c%l4%x, %c%l5%x, %c%l6%x and %c%l7%x of the dynamic array '%y%lmyarray%x'.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<ARRAY>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?index%>%x', '%g%l%<@?noelements%>%x', '%g%l%<@?indexno%>%x' and '%g%l%<@array%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?email
%TOPIC @?emailaddresses
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?email}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?email [<NAME>] [= public|private|<NUMBER>|all]}%]%x

Returns the specified E-mail address of the character %y%l<NAME>%x (Or your specified E-mail address, if %y%l<NAME>%x is omitted.)  If the second parameter is omitted, the user's private E-mail address will be returned by default.

If '%y%lpublic%x' is specified, the user's first public E-mail address will be returned.  Likewise, '%y%lprivate%x' will return the user's private E-mail address (You must have 'write' permission or be an %y%lApprentice Wizard/%yDruid%x or above to query the private E-mail address of another character.)

The user's other public E-mail addresses can be returned by giving a %y%l<NUMBER>%x between %c%l3%x and %c%l5%x.

%PAGE
Specifying '%y%lall%x' will return all of the user's E-mail addresses, separated by NEWLINE's (For Mortals, the private E-mail address (%c%l2%x) will be blanked in the returned list of E-mail addresses.)  You can process this list by using list processing query commands (See '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x'), using '%g%l{%(@?newline%)}%x' as the separator (See '%g%l%<@?newline%>%x'.)

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found or the specified E-mail address isn't currently set.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@email%>%x' and '%g%l%<emaillist%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?enemy
%TOPIC @?enemies
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?enemy}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?enemy <NAME> [= flist|fothers]}%]%x

Succeeds if %y%l<NAME>%x is one of your enemies (I.e:  Either you've set their %y%lENEMY%x friend flag on your own personal friends list ('%g%l%(fset%) <NAME> = ENEMY%x'), or they've set your %y%lENEMY%x friend flag on theirs.)

Alternatively, if '%y%lflist%x' is specified, '%g%l{@?enemy}%x' will only succeed if you have the user %y%l<NAME>%x as an enemy on your friends list.  If '%y%lfothers%x' is specified, it will only succeed if the user %y%l<NAME>%x has you as an enemy on their friends list.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<NAME>%x isn't one of your enemies.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?friend%>%x' and '%g%l%<friends%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?estring
%TOPIC @?exitstring
%TOPIC @?exitsstring
%TOPIC @?obviousexitstring
%TOPIC @?obviousexitsstring
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?estring}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?estring <OBJECT>}%]%x

Returns the obvious exits string of the room or thing %y%l<OBJECT>%x.  If it does not have an obvious exits string, the default of '%c%l%uObvious exits:%x' will be returned.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found, or is not a room or thing.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@estring%>%x', '%g%l%<@cstring%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?cstring%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?evallock
%TOPIC @?evaluatelock
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?evallock}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?evallock <LOCK>}%]%x

Evaluates the lock %y%l<LOCK>%x and succeeds if the lock is satisfied by the current character (I.e:  The character executing the query/compound command with the query in), otherwise it fails.


%c%l%$Example:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l{@?evallock @builder|*fred bloggs}%]%x

...Succeeds if character is '%y%lFred Bloggs%x' or a %y%lBuilder%x, otherwise fails.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@lock%>%x', '%g%l%<@unlock%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?lock%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?execlimit
%TOPIC @?execution
%TOPIC @?executionlimit
%TOPIC @?recursionlimit
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?execution}%x' (Or '%w%l{@?executionlimit}%x')
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?executionlimit}
        {@?execution}%]%x

Returns the current execution time limit (Set using '%g%l%(@execution%)%x'  -  See '%g%l%<@execution%>%x') of the current compound command being executed, in seconds.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?executed%>%x', '%g%l%<@?nested%>%x' and '%g%l%<@execution%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?executed
%TOPIC @?commandsexecuted
%TOPIC @?compoundcommandsexecuted
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?executed}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?executed}%]%x

Returns the total execution time so far (In microseconds) of the current compound command(s) being executed.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?execution%>%x', '%g%l%<@?nested%>%x' and '%g%l%<@execution%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?exists
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?exists}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?exists <ARRAY>[<ELEMENT>]}
        {@?exists <OBJECT>}%]%x

Returns '%y%lOk%x' (%c%lSuccess%x) if %y%l<OBJECT>%x exists (Or element %y%l<ELEMENT>%x of the dynamic array %y%l<ARRAY>%x exists), otherwise returns '%y%lError%x' (%c%lFailure%x.)


%c%l%$Examples:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@if%) {@?exists box:myproperty} do %(@echo%) Found 'myproperty' attached to object
    'box'.; else %(@echo%) Property 'myproperty' isn't attached to object 'box'.

%(@if%) {@?exists myarray[5]} do %(@echo%) Element 5 of 'myarray' exists.; else %(@echo%)
    Element 5 of 'myarray' doesn't exist.%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@if%>%x' and '%g%l%<@test%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?exits
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?exits}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?exits <OBJECT> [= <NUMBER>]}%]%x

Returns the name (Or ID if you control it) of the first (Or %y%l<NUMBER>%x'th, if %y%l<NUMBER>%x is specified) exit in %y%l<OBJECT>%x's exits list.  Returns '%y%l*NOTHING*%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x has no exits.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?next%>%x' and '%g%l%<@open%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?expenses
%TOPIC @?expences
%TOPIC @?spendings
%TOPIC @?expenditure
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?expenditure}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?expenditure [<NAME>] [= day|week|month]}%]%x

Returns your (Or the character %y%l<NAME>%x's, if %y%l<NAME>%x is specified) expenditure this quarter.

You can alternatively return average expenditure per %c%lday%x, %c%lweek%x or %c%lmonth%x by specifying the second parameter of '%y%lday%x', '%y%lweek%x' or '%y%lmonth%x' respectively.


%c%l%$Examples
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@echo%) Expenditure this quarter:  {@?expenditure}
%(@echo%) Average per day:  {@?expenditure = day}
%(@echo%) Average per week:  {@?expenditure = week}
%(@echo%) Average per month:  {@?expenditure = month}%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?income%>%x', '%g%l%<@?profit%>%x', '%g%l%<@?quarter%>%x' and '%g%l%<bank%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?expiry
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?expiry}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?expiry <OBJECT>}%]%x

Returns the expiry time (In days) of %y%l<OBJECT>%x.  An expiry time of %c%l0 days%x indicates that no expiry time is set on %y%l<OBJECT>%x.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@expiry%>%x', '%g%l%<@destroy%>%x' and '%g%l%<junked objects%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?fail
%TOPIC @?failure
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?fail}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?fail <OBJECT>}%]%x

Returns the failure message of %y%l<OBJECT>%x.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@fail%>%x', '%g%l%<@ofail%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?ofail%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?false
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?false}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?false}%]%x

'%g%l{@?false}%x' returns '%y%lOK%x' if the last command executed failed, otherwise it returns '%y%lError%x'.

'%g%l{@?false}%x' is of most use when used in the %y%l<CONDITION>%x part of an '%g%l%(@if%)%x' or '%g%l%(@while%)%x' command, e.g:

%[%g%l%(@if%) {@?false} do @echo Failure.%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@false%>%x', '%g%l%<@?true%>%x', '%g%l%<condition%>%x' and '%g%l%<queries%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?feeling
%TOPIC @?feelings
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?feeling}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?feeling [<NAME>]}%]%x

If the character %y%l<NAME>%x isn't specified, your current feeling (Set using the '%g%l@feeling%x' (See '%g%l%<@feeling%>%x') command) is returned, otherwise the character %y%l<NAME>%x's feeling is returned.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@feeling%>%x' and '%g%l%<feelings%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC first
%TOPIC @?firstname
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?firstname}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?firstname <OBJECT>}%]%x

Returns the first name of %y%l<OBJECT>%x, if it has several (Separated by semi-colons ('%y%l;%x')), e.g:  if it's an exit or a compound command.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?name%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?flags
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?flags}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?flags <OBJECT> [= short]}%]%x

Returns the flags set on the object %y%l<OBJECT>%x.  If the optional second parameter ('%g%lshort%x') isn't specified, long format is assumed, and the full names of the flags set will be returned (Similar to the way flags are listed by '%g%l%(scan%)%x', '%g%l%(examine%)%x' and '%g%l%(settings%)%x', e.g:  '%y%lYell, Warp, Visit%x'.)

Otherwise, the flags will be returned in short form (Similar to the way flags are listed after an object name, when examining it, e.g:  '%y%lywV%x' for '%y%lYell, Warp, Visit%x'.)

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<scan%>%x', '%g%l%<examine%>%x', '%g%l%<settings%>%x', '%g%l%<@?name%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?id%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?friend
%TOPIC @?friends
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?friend}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?friend <NAME> [= flist|fothers]}%]%x

Succeeds if %y%l<NAME>%x is one of your friends (I.e:  Either you have them on your own personal friends list, or they have you on theirs.)

Alternatively, if '%y%lflist%x' is specified, '%g%l{@?friend}%x' will only succeed if you have the user %y%l<NAME>%x as a friend on your friends list.  If '%y%lfothers%x' is specified, it will only succeed if the user %y%l<NAME>%x has you as a friend on their friends list.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<NAME>%x isn't one of your friends.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?enemy%>%x' and '%g%l%<friends%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?fullname
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?fullname}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?fullname <NAME> [= indefinite|INDEFINITE|definite|DEFINITE]}%]%x

Matches to the closest character name in the database which contains %y%l<NAME>%x.  If %y%l<NAME>%x doesn't match to any character name in the database, '%y%l*NOTHING*%x' is returned.

%c%lNOTE:  %xUnlike '%g%l{%(@?namec%)}%x', connected characters %c%lDO NOT%x have priority.

If '%y%lindefinite%x' or '%y%ldefinite%x' is specified as the second parameter to '%g%l{@?fullname}%x', the appropriate article will be added to the matched character's name (See table on next page), providing the %y%l%(CONSONANT%)%x, %y%l%(VOWEL%)%x or %y%l%(PLURAL%)%x flag is set on them.  If '%g%l@?fullname%x' or '%y%lindefinite%x'/'%y%ldefinite%x' are given in capital letters (E.g:  '%g%l@?FULLNAME%x', '%y%lINDEFINITE%x', '%y%lDEFINITE%x'), the first letter of the added article will be capitalised...
%PAGE

%c%lArticle flag:   %g%lindefinite  INDEFINITE  definite  DEFINITE
%c==========================================================
%y%l%(CONSONANT%)       %xa           A           the       The
%y%l%(VOWEL%)           %xan          An          the       The
%y%l%(PLURAL%)          %xsome        Some        the       The
%c==========================================================


%c%l%$Example:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~%x
Suppose only %y%lFred Bloggs%x and %y%lJoe Bloggs%x exist in the database...

'%g%l{@?fullname fr}%x' would return '%y%lFred Bloggs%x'.
'%g%l{@?fullname ed blog}%x' would return '%y%lFred Bloggs%x'.
'%g%l{@?fullname joe}%x' would return '%y%lJoe Bloggs%x'.
'%g%l{@?fullname john}%x' would return '%y%l*NOTHING*%x'.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?namec%>%x', '%g%l%<@?name%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?realname%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?fuses
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?fuses}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?fuses <OBJECT> [= <NUMBER>]}%]%x

Returns the name (Or ID if you control it) of the first (Or %y%l<NUMBER>%x'th, if %y%l<NUMBER>%x is specified) fuse in %y%l<OBJECT>%x's fuses list.  Returns '%y%l*NOTHING*%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x has no fuses.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?next%>%x' and '%g%l%<@fuse%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?head
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?head}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?head "<SUBSTRING>" "<STRING>"}%]%x

Returns text in %y%l<STRING>%x that preceeds the first occurrence of %y%l<SUBSTRING>%x.


%c%l%$Example:
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l{@?head "@" "%@%e"}%]%x

...returns '%y%l%{@?head "@" "{%@%e}"}%x'.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?tail%>%x' and '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?health
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?health}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?health [<NAME>]}%]%x

If the character %y%l<NAME>%x isn't specified, your current health is returned, otherwise the character %y%l<NAME>%x's current health is returned.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<combat%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?id
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?id}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?id [<OBJECT>]}%]%x

Returns the ID number of %y%l<OBJECT>%x in the form of %y%l#<ID>%x.  If %y%l<OBJECT>%x isn't specified, it returns your ID number.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?idletime
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?idletime}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?idletime [<NAME>]}%]%x

Returns the amount of time in seconds that character %y%l<NAME>%x has been idle for, if %y%l<NAME>%x is specified, otherwise returns amount of time you've been idle.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?img
%TOPIC @?image
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@?image%x'
%c%l%[USAGE:  %g%l{@?image "<IMAGE URL>" "<DESCRIPTION>" ["<DESTINATION URL>"]}%]%x

Inserts a properly formatted HTML image and an optional link to a web site (When the image is clicked on.)  The link is opened a new browser window so that it doesn't interfere with the connection of a user using the World Wide Web Interface.

%y%l<IMAGE URL>%x is the URL of the image, e.g:  %b%l%u%@%wimages/tczlogo3.gif%x

%y%l<DESCRIPTION>%x is a text description of the image, which will be seen by users who have images switched off, or are using a text-only browser.

%y%l<DESTINATION URL>%x is the URL of an optional web site link for when the image is clicked on by the user, e.g:  %b%l%u%@%w%x

%PAGE
The best way to insert an image into a description is using query substition, i.e:  '%g%l%%{@?image ...}%x' (%c%lNOTE:  %xIf you type this on the command-line, you will need to protect the opening '%g%l{%x' with '%g%l\%x' to prevent it from being evaluated.)

%9%4%c%lIMPORTANT:  %xIf you do not use query substitution, the HTML part of the link will be 'hard' substituted and will be difficult to edit or remove without deleting the entire line.


%c%l%$Example:
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%g%l%(@desc%) me = %%\{@?image "%@%wimages/tczlogo3.gif" "TCZ City Picture" "%@%w"}%x

%y%l%{@?image "{%@%w}images/tczlogo3.gif" "TCZ City Picture" "{%@%w}"}%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?link%>%x', '%g%l%<@?tczlink%>%x' and '%g%l%<html%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?income
%TOPIC @?earnings
%TOPIC @?incomings
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?income}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?income [<NAME>] [= day|week|month]}%]%x

Returns your (Or the character %y%l<NAME>%x's, if %y%l<NAME>%x is specified) income this quarter.

You can alternatively return average income per %c%lday%x, %c%lweek%x or %c%lmonth%x by specifying the second parameter of '%y%lday%x', '%y%lweek%x' or '%y%lmonth%x' respectively.


%c%l%$Examples
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@echo%) Income this quarter:  {@?income}
%(@echo%) Average per day:  {@?income = day}
%(@echo%) Average per week:  {@?income = week}
%(@echo%) Average per month:  {@?income = month}%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?expenditure%>%x', '%g%l%<@?profit%>%x', '%g%l%<@?quarter%>%x' and '%g%l%<bank%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?index
%TOPIC @?indexnames
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?index}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?index <ARRAY>[<ELEMENT>]}%]%x

Returns the index name of an element (Or range of elements) of a dynamic array, e.g:  '%g%l{@?index myarray[2]}%x' returns the index name of the %c%l2nd%x element of the dynamic array '%y%lmyarray%x'.  If a range of elements is specified, the index names of these elements will be returned, separated by %c%lNEWLINE%x's, e.g:  '%g%l{@?index myarray[4..7]}%x' will return the index names of elements %c%l4%x, %c%l5%x, %c%l6%x and %c%l7%x of the dynamic array '%y%lmyarray%x'.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<ARRAY>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?elementno%>%x', '%g%l%<@?noelements%>%x', '%g%l%<@?indexno%>%x' and '%g%l%<@array%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?indexno
%TOPIC @?indexnumber
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?indexno}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?indexno <ARRAY>[<INDEX>]}%]%x

Returns the element number of the element with the index name %y%l<INDEX>%x in the dynamic array %y%l<ARRAY>%x, e.g:  '%g%l{@?indexno myarray[myindex]}%x'.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<ARRAY>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?noelements%>%x' and '%g%l%<@array%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?insert
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?insert}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?insert "<ITEM>" <NUMBER> "<SEPARATOR>" "<LIST>"}%]%x

Inserts %y%l<ITEM>%x %c%lIN FRONT%x of item number %y%l<NUMBER>%x in the list %y%l<LIST>%x.  If %y%l<NUMBER>%x doesn't exist (E.g:  List with 4 items and you specify 9 as %y%l<NUMBER>%x), %y%l<ITEM>%x will be added to the end of the list.  %y%l<SEPARATOR>%x is the string used to separate the items in the list from each other.

If you use the word '%y%lLAST%x' instead of specifing a number for %y%l<NUMBER>%x, it inserts %y%l<ITEM>%x in front of the last item in the list.  Using the word '%y%lFIRST%x' inserts %y%l<ITEM>%x in front of the first item in the list.

%PAGE
The word '%y%lEND%x' can also be used with '%g%l{@?insert}%x' (But not with any of the other list processing queries)  -  This adds %y%l<ITEM>%x to the end of the list.


%c%l%$Example:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l{@?insert "bread" 3 ";" "eggs;bacon;sausage;chips;mushrooms"}%]%x

...returns '%y%leggs;bacon;bread;sausage;chips;mushrooms%x' ('%y%lbread%x' has been inserted in front of the 3rd item in the list ('%y%lsausage%x'.))
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?modify%>%x', '%g%l%<@?delete%>%x' and '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?internal
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@?internal%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?internal <COMMAND>}%]%x

Matches %y%l<COMMAND>%x against the internal command tables built into %@%m and returns the type(s) of internal command it matches in a '%g%l;%x' separated list.  The types are as follows:

%[%y%lShort      %xShort symbolic commands (E.g:  '%g%l%("%)%x' for '%g%l%(say%)%x', etc.)
%y%lGeneral    %xGeneral commands ('%g%l%(say%)%x', '%g%l%(tell%)%x', '%g%l%(look%)%x', etc.)
%y%lDatabase   %x'%g%l@%x' commands used to modify the database ('%g%l%(@thing%)%x', '%g%l%(@set%)%x', etc.)
%y%lQuery      %x'%g%l@?%x' query commands ('%g%l{%(@?name%)}%x', '%g%l{%(@?description%)}%x', etc.)
%y%lEditor     %xEditor commands ('%g%l%(.view%)%x', '%g%l%(.exit%)%x', etc.)
%y%lBBS        %xBBS commands ('%g%l%(^bbs topic%)%x', '%g%l%(^bbs read%)%x', '%g%l%(^bbs add%)%x', etc.)
%y%lBank       %xBank commands ('%g%l%(statement%)%x', '%g%l%(withdraw%)%x', etc.)%]%x

Returns '%y%l*NOTHING*%x' if %y%l<COMMAND>%x does not match any internal commands.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Example:
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@command%) InternalTest = %(@temp%) result = \{@?internal "$3"}\
%(@if%) \{%(@eval%) "$(result)" <> "*NOTHING*"} do\
    %(@echo%) %%g%%l'%%w%%l$3%%g%%l' matches internal command types: %%y %%l$(result)\
%(@else%)\
    %(@echo%) %%g%%l'%%y%%l$3%%g%%l' does not match any internal commands.\
%(@end%)%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<commands%>%x' '%g%l%<queries%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?interval
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?interval}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?interval [<NUMBER OF SECONDS>] [= <ENTITIES>]}%]%x

Returns the time in %y%lyears, months, weeks, days, hours, minutes and seconds%x that %y%l<NUMBER OF SECONDS>%x represents.

If %y%l<ENTITIES>%x is specified, the number of entities in the returned time will be restricted to the number you specify.  An entity is a unit of time (E.g:  %y%lHours%x.)


%c%l%$Examples:
%~%c~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@echo%) {@?interval 100000}
%(@echo%) {@?interval 100000 = 3}
%(@echo%) {@?interval 100000 = 2}
%(@echo%) {@?interval 100000 = 1}%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?realtime%>%x', '%g%l%<@?time%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?timediff%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?item
%TOPIC @?itemexact
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?item}%x' and '%w%l{@?itemexact}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?item[exact] "<ITEM>" "<SEPARATOR>" "<LIST>"}%]%x

Returns %y%l0%x if the item %y%l<ITEM>%x isn't found in the list %y%l<LIST>%x, otherwise, it returns the position of the item in the list (%y%l1%x = first item, %y%l2%x = second, and so on.)  %y%l<SEPARATOR>%x is the string used to separate the items in the list from each other.  '%g%l{@?itemexact}%x' exactly matches for %y%l<ITEM>%x, whereas '%g%l{@?item}%x' partially matches.


%c%l%$Examples:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~%x
%[%g%l{@?itemexact "chips" ";" "eggs;bacon;sausage;chips;mushrooms"}%]%x

...returns %y%l4%x  ('%y%lchips%x' is %c%lexactly%x matched with the %y%l4th%x item in the list.)

%[%g%l{@?item "bac" ";" "eggs;bacon;sausage;chips;mushrooms"}%]%x

%9%6...returns %y%l2%x  ('%y%lbac%x' is %c%lpartially%x matched with the item '%y%lbacon%x', which is the %y%l2nd%x item in the list.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?itemno%>%x', '%g%l%<@?noitems%>%x' and '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?itemno
%TOPIC @?itemnumber
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?itemno}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?itemno <NUMBER> "<SEPARATOR>" "<LIST>"}%]%x

Returns the name of item %y%l<NUMBER>%x in the list %y%l<LIST>%x.  If that item doesn't exist (I.e:  %g%l{@?itemno 9 "eggs;bacon;sausage;chips;mushrooms"}%x), it returns an empty string (%y%l""%x.)  %y%l<SEPARATOR>%x is the string used to separate the items in the list from each other.

If you use the word '%y%lLAST%x' instead of specifing a number for %y%l<NUMBER>%x, it returns the name of the last item in the list.  Using the word '%y%lFIRST%x' returns the name of the first item in the list.


%c%l%$Example:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l{@?itemno 4 ";" "eggs;bacon;sausage;chips;mushrooms"}%]%x

...returns '%y%lchips%x'.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?noitems%>%x', '%g%l%<@?item%>%x' and '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?key
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?key}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?key [<OBJECT>]}%]%x

Returns the key required to satisfy the lock of %y%l<OBJECT>%x (Or yourself if you don't specify %y%l<OBJECT>%x.)

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@key%>%x' and '%g%l%<locks%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?last
%TOPIC @?lastcommand
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?lastcommand}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?lastcommand [<NAME>]}%]%x

If %y%l<NAME>%x isn't specified, '%g%l{@?lastcommand}%x' returns the last command you typed, otherwise the character %y%l<NAME>%x's last command is returned, who must either be your puppet or a character who is a lower level than you (If you are Admin.)

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x is specified and can't be found, or you do not have permission to query their last command.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<!!%>%x', '%g%l%<@controller%>%x' and '%g%l%<last%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?lastconnected
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?lastconnected}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?lastconnected [<NAME>] [= epoch|longdate]}%]%x

Returns the time and date when the character %y%l<NAME>%x was last connected in either the %c%lEPOCH%x (See '%g%l%<epoch%>%x') or %c%lLONGDATE%x (See '%g%l%<longdate%>%x') date/time format (If the date/time format is not specified, %c%lEPOCH%x will be assumed.)

%c%lFor example: %x '%g%l%(@echo%) {%(@?realtime%) {@?lastconnected me}}%x' will display the time and date you last connected, and '%g%l%(@echo%) {%(@?interval%) {@eval {%(@?time%)} - {@?lastconnected me}}}%x' will display how long ago that was in hours, minutes, seconds, etc.

For more information on the %c%lEPOCH%x and %c%lLONGDATE%x date/time formats, please see '%g%l%<epoch%>%x' and '%g%l%<longdate%>%x'.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?totaltime%>%x', '%g%l%<@?longesttime%>%x', '%g%l%<@?longestdate%>%x', '%g%l%<@?realtime%>%x', '%g%l%<@?interval%>%x', '%g%l%<@eval%>%x', '%g%l%<@?time%>%x', '%g%l%<epoch%>%x' and '%g%l%<longdate%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?lastused
%TOPIC @?lastusage
%TOPIC @?lastusedtimes
%TOPIC @?lastuseddates
%TOPIC @?lastusagetimes
%TOPIC @?lastusagedates
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?lastused}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?lastused [<OBJECT>] [= epoch|longdate]}%]%x

Returns the time and date when the object %y%l<OBJECT>%x was last used (Or when you were last used, if %y%l<OBJECT>%x isn't specified) in either the %c%lEPOCH%x (See '%g%l%<epoch%>%x') or %c%lLONGDATE%x (See '%g%l%<longdate%>%x') date/time format (If the date/time format is not specified, %c%lEPOCH%x will be assumed), e.g:  '%g%l%(@echo%) {%(@?realtime%) {%(@?lastused%) here}}%x' will display the time and date when the room you're currently standing in was last used (%c%lNOTE:  %xYou don't have to own %y%l<OBJECT>%x to use this query command.)

The last usage time/date of an object is updated everytime its text fields (I.e:  '%g%l%(@desc%)%x', '%g%l%(@succ%)%x', '%g%l%(@fail%)%x', etc.) or its lock are accessed/modified (%c%lNOTE:  %xExamining an object or scanning a character does not update the last usage time/date.)

For more information on the %c%lEPOCH%x and %c%lLONGDATE%x date/time formats, please see '%g%l%<epoch%>%x' and '%g%l%<longdate%>%x'.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?created%>%x', '%g%l%<@?realtime%>%x', '%g%l%<@?interval%>%x', '%g%l%<date stamps%>%x', '%g%l%<epoch%>%x' and '%g%l%<longdate%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?latest
%TOPIC @?latestmessage
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?latest}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?latest <TOPIC>}%]%x

Returns the subject of the latest message added to the topic %y%l<TOPIC>%x on %@%n BBS.  If the topic is empty (I.e:  There's no messages in it), '%c%l***  NO MESSAGES  ***%x' is returned.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the topic %y%l<TOPIC>%x doesn't exist, or you can't access it.


%c%l%$Example:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~%x
%[%g%l@echo The latest message in the topic 'News' on %@%n BBS is
'{@?latest news}' (Unread messages:  {%(@?newmessages%) news}.)%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<bbs%>%x', '%g%l%<latest%>%x', '%g%l%<@?newmessages%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?messages%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?lost
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?lost}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?lost [<NAME>]}%]%x

If the character %y%l<NAME>%x isn't specified, the number of battles you've lost are returned, otherwise the number of battles the character %y%l<NAME>%x has lost are returned.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?won%>%x', '%g%l%<@?total%>%x', '%g%l%<@?performance%>%x' and '%g%l%<combat%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?censor
%TOPIC @?censored
%TOPIC @?censorship
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?censor}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?censor "<STRING>"}%]%x

Censors bad language in the string %y%l<STRING>%x, replacing vulgar words with '%y%l*%x's, in a similar way to the %y%l%(CENSORED%)%x flag (See '%g%l%<censored flag%>%x'.)


%c%l%$Example:
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@echo%) {@?censor "shit"}%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<censored flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?filter
%TOPIC @?filteransicodes
%TOPIC @?filtersubstitutions
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?filter}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?filter "<STRING>"}%]%x

Filters %c%l%%-type substitutions%x (I.e:  ANSI codes, etc.) out of the string %y%l<STRING>%x and returns the resulting string.


%c%l%$Example:
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@echo%) {@?filter "%%y%%lThe %%g%%lsubstitutions %%r%%lused %%w%%lin %%m%%lthis %%pstring
%%nwill %%\{@?race}be %%y%%l%%i%%rfiltered %%fout%%x."}%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?protect%>%x', '%g%l%<substitutions%>%x' and '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?format
%TOPIC formatting
%TOPIC @?formattext
%TOPIC @?formatstring
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?format}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?format "<STRING>"}%]%x

Formats the string %y%l<STRING>%x (Auto-capitalises and adds punctuation) and returns resulting string.


%c%l%$Example:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@echo%) {@?format "this text will be auto-formatted"}%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?upper%>%x', '%g%l%<@?lower%>%x', '%g%l%<@?capitalise%>%x' and '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?leftstr
%TOPIC @?leftstring
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?leftstr}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?leftstr <COUNT> "<STRING>"}%]%x

Returns the leftmost %y%l<COUNT>%x characters in the string %y%l<STRING>%x.


%c%l%$Example:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l{@?leftstr 15 "The virtual world of %@%n."}%]%x

...returns '%y%l%{@?leftstr 15 "The virtual world of {%@%n}."}%x'.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?rightstr%>%x', '%g%l%<@?midstr%>%x' and '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x'.

%COMMENT -------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?a
%TOPIC @?o
%TOPIC @?p
%TOPIC @?s
%TOPIC @?v
%TOPIC @?abs
%TOPIC @?obj
%TOPIC @?pos
%TOPIC @?ref
%TOPIC @?sub
%TOPIC @?object
%TOPIC @?absolute
%TOPIC @?objective
%TOPIC @?reflexive
%TOPIC @?possessive
%TOPIC @?subjective
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?absolute}%x', '%w%l{@?objective}%x', '%w%l{@?possessive}%x', '%w%l{@?reflexive}%x' and '%w%l{@?subjective}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?possessive [<NAME>]}
        {@?subjective [<NAME>]}
        {@?objective [<NAME>]}
        {@?reflexive [<NAME>]}
        {@?absolute [<NAME>]}%]%x

The query commands '%g%l{@?absolute}%x', '%g%l{@?objective}%x', '%g%l{@?possessive}%x', '%g%l{@?reflexive}%x' and '%g%l{@?subjective}%x' return an %c%labsolute%x, %c%lobjective%x, %c%lpossessive%x, %c%lreflexive%x or %c%lsubjective%x pronoun respectively, which is correct for the character %y%l<NAME>%x's gender (Or your gender, if %y%l<NAME>%x isn't specified.)

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found.

%PAGE

%[%c%lQuery command:                   Male:     Female:   Neuter:   Unset gender:
%c============================================================================
%g%l{@?absolute},   {@?abs}, {@?a}   %xhis       hers      its       its
%g%l{@?Absolute},   {@?Abs}, {@?A}   %xHis       Hers      Its       Its
%g%l{@?objective},  {@?obj}, {@?o}   %xhim       her       it        it
%g%l{@?Objective},  {@?Obj}, {@?O}   %xHim       Her       It        It
%g%l{@?possessive}, {@?pos}, {@?p}   %xhis       her       its       its
%g%l{@?Possessive}, {@?Pos}, {@?P}   %xHis       Her       Its       Its
%g%l{@?subjective}, {@?sub}, {@?s}   %xhe        she       it        it
%g%l{@?Subjective}, {@?Sub}, {@?S}   %xHe        She       It        It
%g%l{@?reflexive},  {@?ref}, {@?v}   %xhimself   herself   itself    itself
%g%l{@?Reflexive},  {@?Ref}, {@?V}   %xHimself   Herself   Itself    Itself
%c============================================================================%]
%c
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<substitutions%>%x'.

