%TOPIC links
%TOPIC @?link
%TOPIC @?href
%TOPIC @?links
%TOPIC @?hreference
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?link}%x'
%c%l%[USAGE:  %g%l{@?link "<NAME>" "<DESTINATION>" ["<HELPTEXT>"]}%]%x

Inserts a properly formatted HTML link to a web site or any other suitable URL recognised by web browsers.  The link is opened a new browser window so that it doesn't interfere with the connection of a user using the World Wide Web Interface.

%y%l<NAME>%x is the name of the link, which will appear on-screen for the user to click on.

%y%l<DESTINATION>%x is the destination URL of the link, for example:  %b%l%u%{@?link "" "{%@%w}" "@?link example"}%x

%y%l<HELPTEXT>%x is optional quick help text that will be displayed in recent browsers if the user holds their mouse pointer still over the link.

%PAGE
The best way to insert a link into a description is using query substition, i.e:  '%g%l%%{@?link ...}%x' (%c%lNOTE:  %xIf you type this on the command-line, you will need to protect the opening '%g%l{%x' with '%g%l\%x' to prevent it from being evaluated.)

%9%4%c%lIMPORTANT:  %xIf you do not use query substitution, the HTML part of the link will be 'hard' substituted and will be difficult to edit or remove without deleting the entire line.


%c%l%$Example:
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%g%l%(@desc%) me = Visit %@%m's web site by clicking %%\{@?link "HERE" "%@%w" "Click to visit %@%m's Web Site..."}.%x

Visit %@%m's web site by clicking %{@?link "HERE" "{%@%w}" "Click to visit {%@%m}'s Web Site..."}.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?image%>%x', '%g%l%<@?tczlink%>%x' and '%g%l%<html%>%x'.

