%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?child
%TOPIC @?myleaf
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?myleaf}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?myleaf [<OBJECT NAME> [= <OBJECT TYPES> [= <PREFERRED TYPES>]]]}
        {@?myleaferror [<OBJ. NAME> [= <OBJ. TYPES> [= <PREF. TYPES]]]}%]%x

Returns the effective location (Taking inheritance into account) of the object %y%l<OBJECT NAME>%x (Or the current compound command being executed, if %y%l<OBJECT NAME>%x is not specified.)

If %y%l<OBJECT NAME>%x is specified, '%g%l{@?myleaf}%x' will display appropriate error messages if the match is unsuccessful.  '%g%l{@?myleaferror}%x' does not display appropriate error messages (The usage of '%g%l{@?myleaf}%x' and '%g%l{@?myleaferror}%x' are identical.)

When %y%l<OBJECT NAME>%x is specified, %y%l<OBJECT TYPES>%x can be used to restrict matching to particular object types only, and %y%l<PREFERRED TYPES>%x can be used to set the preferred object types during the match.  See '%g%l%<@?match%>%x' for further details on these parameters.

%PAGE
For example, the room '%y%lMyRoom%x' contains the object '%y%lMyThing%x'.  Its parent is set to the room '%y%lMyParentRoom%x', which contains the object '%y%lMyInheritedThing%x'.


%[  %c%l%$In '%w%l%$MyRoom%c%l%$':
  %~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~
  %x'%g%l{@?myleaf mything}%x' returns '%y%lMyRoom%x'.
  '%g%l{@?myleaf myinheritedthing}%x' returns '%y%lMyRoom%x'.
  '%g%l{@?location myinheritedthing}%x' returns '%y%lMyParentThing%x'.%]

%PAGE
%c%l%8NOTE:  %xRather than using '%g%l{@?myleaf}%x' without parameters to get the effective location of a compound command, you can use the matching keyword '%y%lmyleaf%x'.  This gives exactly the same result with the added benefit of being easier to use, more readable and more efficient.

       The '%y%lmyleaf%x' matching keyword is used in the example below (Which shows you how to take advantage of '%y%lmyleaf%x' within inherited compound commands.  Replacing '%y%lmyleaf%x' with '%g%l{@?myleaf}%x' will give exactly the same results.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Example use of '%w%l%$myleaf%c%l%$'...
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xSay you wanted to create a number of guns, each which can be 'shot' by typing '%g%lshoot%x'.  This can be done easily using inheritance and '%g%lmyleaf%x':

Firstly, create the first gun, which will act as the parent object, e.g:  '%g%l%(@thing%) Shotgun = A large, double-barrelled shotgun.%x' (See '%g%l%<@thing%>%x'.)

Next, create the '%g%lshoot%x' compound command:  

%[   %g%l%(edit%) command desc shoot;fire
   %(@echo%) %%g%%lYou aim the %%y%%l{%(@?name%) myleaf}%%g%%l at %%w%%l%3%%g%%l and pull the
         trigger %%c- %%r%%l%%f*BANG*%%x
   %(@oemote%) %%g%%laims %%p %%y%%l{%(@?name%) myleaf}%%g%%l at %%w%%l$3%%g%%l and pulls the
         trigger %%c- %%r%%l%%f*BANG*%%x
   %(.exit%)%]%x

%PAGE
...Now teleport the '%g%lshoot%x' compound command to the shotgun by typing '%g%l%(@tel%) shoot = shotgun%x'.  You can now create further guns simply by creating an object with the appropriate name and description and setting its parent to the shotgun using '%g%l%(@parent%)%x' (See '%g%l%<@parent%>%x'), e.g:

   %[%g%l%(@thing%) Pistol = A small automatic pistol.
   %(@parent%) pistol = shotgun%]%x

...Now drop the shotgun.  When you type '%g%lshoot <NAME>%x', you'll get '%y%lYou aim the Pistol at <NAME>...%x'  If you drop the pistol and pick up the shotgun again and type '%g%lshoot <NAME>%x', you'll get '%y%lYou aim the Shotgun at <NAME>...%x'
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, '%g%l%<@parent%>%x', '%g%l%<@?parent%>%x', '%g%l%<inheritable flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?myself%>%x'.

