%TOPIC @?name
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?name}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?name <OBJECT> [= indefinite|INDEFINITE|definite|DEFINITE]}%]%x

Returns the name of %y%l<OBJECT>%x (Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found.)

If '%y%lindefinite%x' or '%y%ldefinite%x' is specified as the second parameter to '%g%l{@?name}%x', the appropriate article will be added to the object's name (See table below), providing the %y%l%(CONSONANT%)%x, %y%l%(VOWEL%)%x or %y%l%(PLURAL%)%x flag is set on the object.  If '%g%l@?name%x' or '%y%lindefinite%x'/'%y%ldefinite%x' are given in capital letters (E.g:  '%g%l@?NAME%x', '%y%lINDEFINITE%x', '%y%lDEFINITE%x'), the first letter of the added article will be capitalised...


%c%lArticle flag:   %g%lindefinite  INDEFINITE  definite  DEFINITE
%c==========================================================
%y%l%(CONSONANT%)       %xa           A           the       The
%y%l%(VOWEL%)           %xan          An          the       The
%y%l%(PLURAL%)          %xsome        Some        the       The
%c==========================================================
%c
%PAGE
%8%c%lNOTE:  %xIf %y%l<OBJECT>%x is a character, their prefixed/suffixed (See '%g%l%<@prefix%>%x' and '%g%l%<@suffix%>%x') name will be returned rather than their real name.

       %8Use the '%g%l{%(@?realname%)}%x' query command to return the real name of a character (I.e:  Their name without their prefix/suffix.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?realname%>%x', '%g%l%<@?namec%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?fullname%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?nested
%TOPIC @?cmdnested
%TOPIC @?commandnested
%TOPIC commandnestinglevel
%TOPIC compoundcommandnestinglevel
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?nested}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?nested}%]%x

Returns the current nesting level of the current compound command being executed.  This will usually be %y%l1%x, but if used in a compound command which has been called from within another compound command (I.e:  Via '%g%l%(@if%)%x', '%g%l%(@case%)%x', '%g%l%(@for%)%x', '%g%l%(@while%)%x', '%g%l%(@with%)%x', etc. or directly (%c%lNOTE:  %y%lNOT%x '%g%l%(@csuccess%)%x'/'%g%l%(@cfailure%)%x')), the nesting level will be %y%l2%x or more, depending on how many compound commands are currently recursed into.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?executed%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?execution%>%x'.

