%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?pad[left|right|centre] <LENGTH> "<PADTEXT>" "<TEXT>"}
        {@?pad <LENGTH> "<CHARACTER>"}%]%x

In the first form, '%g%l{@?pad}%x' pads out %y%l<TEXT>%x with the text %y%l<PADTEXT>%x to make it %y%l<LENGTH>%x characters long.  If %y%l<TEXT>%x is longer than %y%l<LENGTH>%x, %y%l<TEXT>%x will be truncated to %y%l<LENGTH>%x characters long.  If '%y%l0%x' is given for %y%l<LENGTH>%x, your screen width will be assumed (Or if used within a compound command, the screen width of the character executing it), e.g:  '%g%l%(@echo%) {@?pad 10 "-" "hello!"}%x' displays '%c%lhello!----%x' and '%g%l%(@echo%) {@?padcentre 41 "-=" "[ Hello ]"}%x' displays '%c%l-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=[ Hello ]=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-%x'.

You can left, right or centre justify %y%l<TEXT>%x by using '%g%l{@?padleft}%x', '%g%l{@?padright}%x' or '%g%l{@?padcentre}%x' instead of '%g%l{@?pad}%x', e.g:  '%g%l%(@echo%) {@?padright 10 "-" "hello!"}%x' displays '%c%l----hello!%x'.

%PAGE
In the second form, '%g%l{@?pad}%x' returns a string of length %y%l<LENGTH>%x padded out with the text %y%l<PADTEXT>%x, e.g:  '%g%l%(@echo%) {@?pad 0 "="}%x' will display a line of '%c%l=%x's across the width of your screen.

If you wish to use %c%l%%-type substitutions%x (I.e:  ANSI codes, etc.) in %y%l<TEXT>%x, please place them within %y%l{}%x's (E.g:  '%y%l{%%g%%l}%x'), otherwise they will affect the justification of '%g%l{@?pad}%x', e.g:  '%g%l%(@echo%) %%g%%l{@?padcentre 0 "-" ">{%%y%%l}Hello!{%%g%%l}<"}%x'.  The '%g%l{%(@?filter%)}%x' (See '%g%l%<@?filter%>%x') string processing query command may be used to filter %%-type substitions out of a given string, e.g:  '%g%l%(@echo%) {@?padcentre 0 "-" "{%(@?filter%) $3}"}%x' within a compound command.

ANSI colour substitutions %r%l%fARE NOT%x supported in the %y%l<PADTEXT>%x part.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<{@?separator}%>%x', '%g%l%<@?filter%>%x', '%g%l%<substitutions%>%x' and '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x'.

