%TOPIC @?tczlink
%TOPIC @?tczlinks
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@?tczlink%x'
%c%l%[USAGE:  %g%l{@?tczlink "<NAME>" "<COMMAND>" "<DESCRIPTION>" "<IMAGE URL>"}
        %g%l{@?tczlink "<NAME>" "<COMMAND>" ["<HELPTEXT>"]}%]%x

Inserts a properly formatted HTML link which will allow users of the World Wide Web Interface to execute a compound command simply by clicking on the link.

%y%l<NAME>%x is the name of the link, which will appear on-screen for the user to click on.

%y%l<COMMAND>%x is a compound command (See '%g%l%<@command%>%x') to execute when the link is clicked on, just as though the user had typed it at the command-line.

%r%lTo prevent abuse, only compound commands can be executed using '%y%l{@?tczlink}%r%l'.%x

%PAGE
%y%l<HELPTEXT>%x is optional quick help text that will be displayed in recent browsers if the user holds their mouse pointer still over the link.

%y%l<IMAGE URL>%x is an optional image, which will be used instead of a hyperlink (The user clicks on the image to execute the compound command.)

%8%c%lNOTE:%x  %y%l<DESCRIPTION>%x must also be specified, if %y%l<IMAGE URL>%x is used.
       %8%y%l<NAME>%x is not used (You can specify %g%l""%x for this if you wish.)

%y%l<DESCRIPTION>%x is a text description of the image (If %y%l<IMAGE URL>%x is specified), which will be seen by users who have images switched off, or are using a text-only browser.

%PAGE
The best way to insert a compound command link into a description is using query substition, i.e:  '%g%l%%{@?tczlink ...}%x' (%c%lNOTE:  %xIf you type this on the command-line, you will need to protect the opening '%g%l{%x' with '%g%l\%x' to prevent it from being evaluated.)

%9%4%c%lIMPORTANT:  %xIf you do not use query substitution, the HTML part of the link will be 'hard' substituted and will be difficult to edit or remove without deleting the entire line.


%c%l%$Example:
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%g%l%(@desc%) me = Click %%\{@?tczlink "HERE" "pub" "Click to go to the Pub..."} to go to the PUB.%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?link%>%x', '%g%l%<@?image%>%x' and '%g%l%<html%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?things
%TOPIC @?objects
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?things}%x' (Or '%w%l{@?objects}%x')
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?things <OBJECT> [= <NUMBER>]}
        {@?objects <OBJECT> [= <NUMBER>]}%]%x

Returns the name (Or ID if you control it) of the first (Or %y%l<NUMBER>%x'th, if %y%l<NUMBER>%x is specified) thing in %y%l<OBJECT>%x's contents list.  Returns '%y%l*NOTHING*%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x has no things.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?next%>%x' and '%g%l%<@thing%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?total
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?total}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?total [<NAME>]}%]%x

If the character %y%l<NAME>%x isn't specified, the total number of battles you've fought are returned, otherwise the total number of battles the character %y%l<NAME>%x has fought are returned.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?won%>%x', '%g%l%<@?lost%>%x', '%g%l%<@?performance%>%x' and '%g%l%<combat%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?totalitems
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?totalitems}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?totalitems [<GRP/RANGE>] [<INDEX>] <OBJECT TYPE> [<OBJECT>]}%]%x

The '%g%l{@?totalitems}%x' query command is similar in usage to the '%g%l%(@with%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<@with%>%x'), except that no command (Or block of commands) to execute is specified.  Instead, '%g%l{@?totalitems}%x' counts the total number of items that would be processed (If the same parameters were given to '%g%l%(@with%)%x', along with a command (Or block of commands) to execute) and returns this number.

For example, you can count the total number of things you are carrying and then display this number by typing '%g%l%(@echo%) {@?totalitems things me}%x'.

For further details on the parameters that can be used with the '%g%l{@?totalitems}%x' query command, please see '%g%l%<@with%>%x'.

%PAGE
%c%l%9%6PLEASE NOTE:  %xIf grouping/range operators are used with this command, they will have no effect on the number of items returned  -  To count the total number of items taking grouping/range operators into account, you will need to either use the '%g%l{%(@?rangeitems%)}%x' or '%g%l{%(@?groupitems%)}%x' query commands (See '%g%l%<@?rangeitems%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?groupitems%>%x'.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?rangeitems%>%x', '%g%l%<@?groupitems%>%x' and '%g%l%<@with%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC group
%TOPIC grouping
%TOPIC groupingoperators
%TITLE Help on %w%lgrouping operators%x
%[%c%lFORMAT:  %g%l<GROUP NO>:<GROUP SIZE>%]%x

When you type '%g%l%(who%) 1%x', '%g%l%(who%) 2%x' to page the '%g%l%(who%)%x' list, etc., you're using a powerful feature of %@%n  -  A grouping operator.  A grouping operator basically splits a list of items into groups of %y%l12%x (The default, which is determined from your current set screen height (See '%g%l%<set screenheight%>%x'.))

%y%l<GROUP SIZE>%x (As explained above) is the size of each group in list items  -  If %y%l<GROUP SIZE>%x or the '%y%l:%x' are omitted, the default group size is assumed.  %y%l<GROUP NO>%x is which group of list items you'd like to display/access, e.g:  '%g%l%(who%) 1:5%x' displays the first group of %c%l5 characters%x in the '%g%l%(who%)%x' list.  If %y%l<GROUP NO>%x is ommitted (The '%y%l:%x' %c%lMUST%x be included if you do this, e.g:  '%g%l%(who%) :5%x') or the keyword '%y%lDEFAULT%x' is used, the last %c%lFULL%x group of items is displayed (I.e:  In this case, the last %c%l5 characters%x in the '%g%l%(who%)%x' list will be displayed.)

%PAGE
You can also use the keywords '%y%lFIRST%x', '%y%lLAST%x', '%y%lDEFAULT%x' and '%y%lALL%x' (%c%lNOTE:%x  You don't have to type them in capitals!) for both %y%l<GROUP SIZE>%x and %y%l<GROUP NO>%x.

Grouping operators can be used in all %@%m commands that produce lists  -  These include:  '%g%l%(who%)%x', '%g%l%(swho%)%x', '%g%l%(lwho%)%x', '%g%l%(where%)%x', '%g%l%(emaillist%)%x', '%g%l%(hosts%)%x', '%g%l%(last%)%x', '%g%l%(chat%) who%x', '%g%l%(@list%)%x', '%g%l%(@find%)%x', '%g%l%(@entrances%)%x', '%g%l%(@with%)%x', etc.

A grouping operator %c%lMUST%x be declared before the first parameter given to any of the above commands (E.g:  '%g%l%(@list%) 1 me = things%x' is OK, '%g%l%(@list%) me = 1 things%x' isn't.)


%c%l%$Grouping operator related commands/query commands:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@?display%)   %(@?groupitems%)   %(@?groupno%)   %(@?grouprange%)   %(@?groupsize%)   %(@?nogroups%)%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<range%>%x' (Help on range operators) and '%g%l%<7%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC range
%TOPIC rangeoperators
%TITLE Help on %w%lrange operators%x
%[%c%lFORMAT:  %g%l<FROM ITEM>-<TO ITEM>
         <FROM ITEM>..<TO ITEM>%]%x

Range operators are most useful to Builders.  They allow you to display/access a range of items in a list (E.g:  The contents list of a room or the characters in the '%g%l%(who%)%x' list), e.g:  '%g%l%(@command%) rangetest = @with 2-5 contents here do @echolist $4 = {@?name $6}%x'  -  Executing this command would list the 2nd, 3rd, 4th and 5th items in the contents list of the room you're currently in.

%y%l<FROM ITEM>%x is the item number the range starts from and %y%l<TO ITEM>%x is the item number the range finishes at.  You can either use a '%y%l-%x' or '%y%l..%x' to separate %y%l<FROM ITEM>%x and %y%l<TO ITEM>%x (the choice is yours!)  Items are processed in %c%lASCENDING ORDER%x so make sure %y%l<FROM ITEM>%x is less than, or equal to %y%l<TO ITEM>%x, otherwise no items will be processed.

%PAGE
As with grouping operators, you can use the keywords '%y%lFIRST%x', '%y%lLAST%x', '%y%lDEFAULT%x' and '%y%lALL%x' (%c%lNOTE:%x  You don't have to type them in capitals!) for both %y%l<FROM ITEM>%x and %y%l<TO ITEM>%x.

You can use a range operator %c%lAND%x a grouping operator together if you like, however the range operator will be processed first, and then the grouping operator (Meaning the range will be split up into groups rather than the whole item list.)

%8%c%lHINT:%x  You can use a range operator to return any given item number in a list of items (When using '%g%l%(@with%)%x') by using '%y%l<ITEM NO>-<ITEM NO>%x' as your range operator, e.g:  '%g%l%(@with%) 2-2 contents here do...%x' gets the %y%l2nd item%x in the contents list of the room you're in.

%PAGE
Range operators can be used in all %@%m commands that produce lists  -  These include:  '%g%l%(who%)%x', '%g%l%(swho%)%x', '%g%l%(lwho%)%x', '%g%l%(where%)%x', '%g%l%(emaillist%)%x', '%g%l%(hosts%)%x', '%g%l%(last%)%x', '%g%l%(chat%) who%x', '%g%l%(@list%)%x', '%g%l%(@find%)%x', '%g%l%(@entrances%)%x', '%g%l%(@with%)%x', etc.

A range operator %c%lMUST%x be declared before the first parameter given to any of the above commands (E.g:  '%g%l%(@list%) 2-5 me = things%x' is OK, '%g%l%(@list%) me = 2-5 things%x' isn't.)


%c%l%$Range operator related commands/query commands:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@?display%)   %(@?grouprange%)   %(@?rangefrom%)   %(@?rangeitems%)   %(@?rangeto%)%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<group%>%x' (Help on grouping operators) and '%g%l%<7%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?grouprange
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?grouprange}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?grouprange <STRING>}%]%x

Returns '%c%lOK%x' if the string %y%l<STRING>%x is a grouping operator, range operator or both, otherwise returns '%c%lError%x'.


%c%l%$Example:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l{@?grouprange test}%x   ...returns '%y%lError%x'.
%g%l{@?grouprange 2-5}%x    ...returns '%y%lOK%x'.%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<7%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?groupitems
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?groupitems}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?groupitems [<GRP/RANGE>] [<INDEX>] <OBJECT TYPE> [<OBJECT>]}%]%x

The '%g%l{@?groupitems}%x' query command is identical in usage to the '%g%l{%(@?totalitems%)}%x' query command (See '%g%l%<@?totalitems%>%x'), except that instead of returning the total number of items, it returns the total number of items in the given group, e.g:  If you had %c%l5 things%x in your inventory, '%g%l{@?groupitems 1:3 things me}%x' would return %y%l5%x and '%g%l{@?groupitems 1:4 things me}%x' would return %y%l4%x (There are %c%l4 items%x in the first group of items.)

For further details on the parameters that can be used with the '%g%l{@?groupitems}%x' query command, please see '%g%l%<@with%>%x'.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<group%>%x', '%g%l%<@?rangeitems%>%x', '%g%l%<@?totalitems%>%x', '%g%l%<@with%>%x' and '%g%l%<7%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?rangeitems
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?rangeitems}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?rangeitems [<GRP/RANGE>] [<INDEX>] <OBJECT TYPE> [<OBJECT>]}%]%x

The '%g%l{@?rangeitems}%x' query command is identical in usage to the '%g%l{%(@?totalitems%)}%x' query command (See '%g%l%<@?totalitems%>%x'), except that instead of returning the total number of items, it returns the total number of items in the given range, e.g:  If you had %c%l5 things%x in your inventory, '%g%l{@?rangeitems 2-4 things me}%x' would return %y%l5%x and '%g%l{@?rangeitems 2-4 things me}%x' would return %y%l3%x (There are %c%l3 items%x in the range %y%l2-4%x.)

For further details on the parameters that can be used with the '%g%l{@?rangeitems}%x' query command, please see '%g%l%<@with%>%x'.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<range%>%x', '%g%l%<@?groupitems%>%x', '%g%l%<@?totalitems%>%x', '%g%l%<@with%>%x', '%g%l%<@?nogroups%>%x' and '%g%l%<7%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?nogroups
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?nogroups}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?nogroups <GROUPING OP> connected}
        {@?nogroups <GROUPING OP> <LINKED LIST TYPE> <OBJECT>}%]%x

'%g%l{@?nogroups}%x' returns the number of groups that the list of connected characters (In the first form) or the linked list attached to the object %y%l<OBJECT>%x (In the second form) will be split into if the given grouping operator (%y%l<GROUPING OP>%x  -  See '%g%l%<group%>%x') is used.

%y%l<LINKED LIST TYPE>%x can be any of the following:  %y%lcommands%x, %y%lcontents%x, %y%lexits%x, %y%lfuses%x or %y%lvariables%x.


%c%l%$Examples:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~%x
Suppose there are 23 items in the room you're currently in (Including yourself of course!)  -  '%g%l{@?nogroups 1:10 contents here}%x' will return %y%l3%x (I.e:  Using the grouping operator '%y%l1:10%x' will split the items in the current room up into a total of %y%l3 groups%x.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?groupitems%>%x', '%g%l%<@?rangeitems%>%x' and '%g%l%<7%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?groupno
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?groupno}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?groupno <STRING>}%]%x

If the given string (%y%l<STRING>%x) contains a grouping operator, '%g%l{@?groupno}%x' returns the %c%lGROUP NUMBER%x part of it, otherwise it returns the default of '%y%lALL%x'.


%c%l%$Example:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l{@?groupno 3:10}%x     ...returns %y%l3%x.%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?groupsize%>%x' and '%g%l%<7%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?groupsize
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?groupsize}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?groupsize <STRING>}
        {@?groupsize <NAME>}%]%x

If used in the first form and the given string (%y%l<STRING>%x) contains a grouping operator, '%g%l{@?groupsize}%x' returns the %c%lGROUP SIZE%x part of it, otherwise it returns the default of '%y%l10%x'.

If used in the second form, '%g%l{@?groupsize}%x' returns the default group size of the character %y%l<NAME>%x, e.g:  '%g%l{@?groupsize me}%x' to return your default group size.


%c%l%$Example:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l{@?groupsize 3:12}%x     ...returns %y%l12%x.%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?groupno%>%x' and '%g%l%<7%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?rangefrom
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?rangefrom}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?rangefrom <STRING>}%]%x

If the given string (%y%l<STRING>%x) contains a range operator, '%g%l{@?rangefrom}%x' returns the %c%lFROM ITEM NUMBER%x part of it, otherwise it returns the default of '%y%lFIRST%x'.


%c%l%$Example:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l{@?rangefrom 4-12}%x     ...returns %y%l4%x.%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?rangeto%>%x' and '%g%l%<7%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?rangeto
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?rangeto}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?rangeto <STRING>}%]%x

If the given string (%y%l<STRING>%x) contains a range operator, '%g%l{@?rangeto}%x' returns the %c%lTO ITEM NUMBER%x part of it, otherwise it returns the default of '%y%lLAST%x'.


%c%l%$Example:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l{@?rangeto 4-12}%x     ...returns %y%l12%x.%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?rangefrom%>%x' and '%g%l%<7%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?display
%TOPIC @?displayeditems
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?display}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?display}%]%x

'%g%l{@?display}%x' returns the number of items processed after using a grouping/range operator with '%g%l%(@with%)%x', '%g%l%(@find%)%x', etc.

To get an idea of what '%g%l{@?display}%x' does, create the following compound command...

%[%g%l%(@command%) display = %(@echo%)\
%(@echo%) %%g%%lThis room contains...\
%(@echo%) %%g~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\
%(@with%) $1 contents here do %(@echo%) %%w\{%(@?name%) $6}\
%(@echo%)\
%(@echo%) %%w%%lTotal items listed:  %%w\{%(@?display%)}\
%(@echo%)%]

%PAGE
...Now find a room with lots of things in it (Such as '%y%lThe Swan Pub%x' or '%y%lSt. Peter's Shelter for the Homeless%x') and try typing the following...

%[%g%ldisplay%x                     (Displays entire list of room's contents)
%g%ldisplay 1%x                   (Displays first page)
%g%ldisplay 2-7%x                 (Displays the 2nd to the 7th item)%]

%9%6%c%lPLEASE NOTE:  %xOnce you've finished experimenting with the above command, please destroy it (Type '%g%l%(@dest%) display%x'.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<7%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?separator
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?separator}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?separator [single|double]}%]%x

Returns a separating line of the width of the current character's screen.  By default, the line will be in the standard '%y%l-=-=-=-=-=-%x' style, however if the parameter '%y%lsingle%x' is specified, the line will be in the style '%y%l-----------%x'.  If the parameter '%y%ldouble%x' is specified, the line will be in the style '%y%l===========%x'.

If the user is using the World Wide Web Interface, '%y%l%%h<HR>%%h%x' will be returned instead, generating a standard HTML horizontal rule.


%c%l%$Examples:
%~%c~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@echo%) %%c{@?separator}
%(@echo%) %%m{@?separator single}
%(@echo%) %%g{@?separator double}%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?pad%>%x', '%g%l%<substitutions%>%x', '%g%l%<html%>%x' and '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?set
%TOPIC @?fset
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?set}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?set <OBJECT> = [!]<FLAG> [[!]<FLAG>] [...] [= flist|fothers]}%]%x

Succeeds if %y%l<OBJECT>%x has the specified flag(s) set/reset on it.  If %y%l<OBJECT>%x is a character, you can also test whether the specified friend flags are set/reset on them in your friends list (If the 3rd parameter '%y%lflist%x' is specified), or whether they have set/reset the specified friend flags on you in their friends list (If the 3rd parameter '%y%lfothers%x' is specified.)

If the character %y%l<OBJECT>%x is not on your friends list (Or you're not on theirs, and '%y%lfothers%x' is specified), the standard (Initial) friend flags will be assumed to be set on them (%y%l%(^friend FCHAT%)%x, %y%l%(^friend LINK%)%x, %y%l%(^friend MAIL%)%x, %y%l%(^friend PAGETELL%)%x and %y%l%(^friend PAGETELLFRIENDS%)%x.)
%PAGE
Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if specified flag(s) aren't set/reset on %y%l<OBJECT>%x, or %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found.


%c%l%$Examples:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@echo%) {@?set *fred bloggs = %(HAVEN%) %(LISTEN%)}
%(@echo%) {@?set *fred bloggs = PAGETELL}
%(@echo%) {@?set mything = %(STICKY%)}
%(@echo%) {@?set here = !%(ABODE%)}%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@set%>%x', '%g%l%<fset%>%x', '%g%l%<flags%>%x', '%g%l%<friends%>%x', '%g%l%<@?friend%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?enemy%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?size
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?size}%x'
%[%c%LUSAGE:  %g%l{@?size [<OBJECT>]}%]%x

Returns the total uncompressed size of %y%l<OBJECT>%x (Or yourself, if %y%l<OBJECT>%x isn't specified) in bytes.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?csize%>%x' and '%g%l%<@size%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?sort
%TOPIC @?sortalpha
%TOPIC @?sortalphabetically
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?sortalpha}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?sort[alpha] ascending "<SEPARATOR>" "<LIST>"}
        {@?sort[alpha] descending "<SEPARATOR>" "<LIST>"}%]%x

Sorts the list %y%l<LIST>%x into alphabetical order, removing any blank (Empty) items.  The first form (%c%lAscending%x) sorts the items into ascending alphabetical order.  The second (%c%lDescending%x) sorts the items into descending alphabetical order.

%y%l<SEPARATOR>%x is the string used to separate the items in the list from each other.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Examples:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l{@?sortalpha ascending ";" "eggs;bacon;sausage;chips;mushrooms"}%]%x

...returns '%y%lbacon;chips;eggs;mushrooms;sausage%x'.

%[%g%l{@?sortalpha descending ";" "eggs;bacon;sausage;chips;mushrooms"}%]%x

...returns '%y%lsausage;mushrooms;eggs;chips;bacon%x'.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?sortnumeric%>%x', '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x' and '%g%l%<@sort%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?sortnum
%TOPIC @?sortnumber
%TOPIC @?sortnumeric
%TOPIC @?sortnumerically
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?sortnumeric}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?sortnumeric ascending <KEY> "<SEPARATOR>" "<LIST>"}
        {@?sortnumeric descending <KEY> "<SEPARATOR>" "<LIST>"}%]%x

Sorts the list %y%l<LIST>%x into numerical order, removing any blank (Empty) items.  The first form (%c%lAscending%x) sorts the items into ascending numerical order.  The second (%c%lDescending%x) sorts the items into descending numerical order.

%y%l<KEY>%x is the numerical value in each item which will be taken as the sort value (I.e:  '%y%l1%x' means the %c%l1st%x numerical value found in each item will be taken as the sort value, '%y%l2%x' means the %c%l2nd%x numerical value found in each item will be taken as the sort value, etc.)  If an item doesn't contain any numbers, %y%l0%x is assumed as the sort value.

%y%l<SEPARATOR>%x is the string used to separate the items in the list from each other.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Examples:
%~%c~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l{@?sortnumeric ascending 1 ";" "56;2;524;37;10;128;42"}%]%x

...returns '%y%l2;10;37;42;56;128;524%x'.

%[%g%l{@?sortnumeric descending 1 ";" "56;2;524;37;10;128;42"}%]%x

...returns '%y%l524;128;56;42;37;10;2%x'.

%[%g%l{@?sortnumeric ascending 2 ";" "a5b2;a9b1;a4b6;a7b9;a1b3"}%]%x

...returns '%y%la9b1;a5b2;a1b3;a4b6;a7b9%x'.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?sortalpha%>%x', '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x' and '%g%l%<@sort%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?level
%TOPIC @?status
%TOPIC @?statuses
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?status}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?status [<NAME> =] [short|colour]}
        {@?level [<NAME> =] [short|colour]}%]%x

Returns the full status (Rank) of the character %y%l<NAME>%x (If %y%l<NAME>%x is specified, otherwise your status is returned.)

By default, the full status (I.e:  '%y%lApprentice Druid%x', '%y%lWizard%x', etc.) is returned.  However, if the optional parameter '%y%lshort%x' is specified, the status will be returned as a single letter (In a similar style to the '%g%l%(who%)%x' list (See '%g%l%<who%>%x'), i.e:  '%y%la%x' for an %yApprentice Druid%x, '%y%lW%x' for a %c%lWizard%x, etc.)

If the optional parameter '%y%lcolour%x' is specified, the correct colour for the user's status will be returned (I.e:  %yYellow%x for an %yApprentice Druid%x, %c%llight cyan%x for a %c%lWizard%x, etc.)

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?privs%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?strpos
%TOPIC @?strposition
%TOPIC @?stringposition
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?strpos}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?strpos "<SUBSTRING>" "<STRING>"}%]%x

Returns the position of %y%l<SUBSTRING>%x within the string %y%l<STRING>%x.  If %y%l<SUBSTRING>%x isn't found in %y%l<STRING>%x, it returns 0.


%c%l%$Examples:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l{@?strpos "world" "The virtual world of %@%n."}%]%x

...returns the position %y%l%{@?strpos "world" "The virtual world of {%@%n}."}%x.

%[%g%l{@?strpos "ual" "The virtual world of %@%n."}%]%x

...returns the position %y%l%{@?strpos "ual" "The virtual world of {%@%n}."}%x.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?strprefix%>%x' and '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?strpre
%TOPIC @?strprefix
%TOPIC @?stringprefix
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?strprefix}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?strprefix "<SUBSTRING>" "<STRING>"}%]%x

Succeeds if the string %y%l<SUBSTRING>%x prefixes the string %y%l<STRING>%x.  Fails otherwise.


%c%l%$Examples:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l{@?strprefix "fr" "Fred Bloggs"}%]%x

...command %y%lsucceeds%x.

%[%g%l{@?strprefix "joe bloggs" "Fred Bloggs"}%]%x

...command %y%lfails%x.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?strpos%>%x' and '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?succ
%TOPIC @?success
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?succ}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?succ <OBJECT>}%]%x

Returns the success message of %y%l<OBJECT>%x.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@succ%>%x', '%g%l%<@osucc%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?osucc%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?tail
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?tail}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?tail "<SUBSTRING>" "<STRING>"}%]%x

Returns text in %y%l<STRING>%x that follows the first occurrence of %y%l<SUBSTRING>%x.


%c%l%$Example:
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l{@?tail "@" "%@%e"}%]%x

...returns '%y%l%{@?tail "@" "{%@%e}"}%x'.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?head%>%x' and '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?termtype
%TOPIC @?terminaltype
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?termtype}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?termtype}%]%x

If the character %y%l<NAME>%x isn't specified, your current terminal type is returned (E.g:  '%y%lvt100%x'), otherwise the character %y%l<NAME>%x's terminal type is returned.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<set termtype%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?time
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?time}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?time [=] [epoch|longdate]}%]%x

Returns the current date and time in either the %c%lEPOCH%x or %c%lLONGDATE%x date/time format (If the date/time format is not specified, %c%lEPOCH%x will be assumed.)

For more information on the %c%lEPOCH%x and %c%lLONGDATE%x date/time formats, please see '%g%l%<epoch%>%x' and '%g%l%<longdate%>%x'.


%c%l%$Example:
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l@echo The time is {@?realtime {@?time}}.%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?realtime%>%x', '%g%l%<@?interval%>%x', '%g%l%<@?datetime%>%x', '%g%l%<@?timediff%>%x', '%g%l%<epoch%>%x' and '%g%l%<longdate%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?timediff
%TOPIC @?timedifference
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?timediff}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?timediff <NAME>}%]%x

If the character %y%l<NAME>%x isn't specified, your time difference (In hours, set using '%g%lset timediff <DIFFERENCE>%x') is returned, otherwise the character %y%l<NAME>%x's time difference is returned.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?realtime%>%x', '%g%l%<@?time%>%x' and '%g%l%<queries%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?totalactive
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?totalactive}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?totalactive [<NAME>]}%]%x

Returns the total time that the character %y%l<NAME>%x has spent active (Not idling) whilst connected to %@%n in seconds, e.g:  '%g%l%(@echo%) {%(@?interval%) {@?totalactive me}}%x' will display your total active time in hours, minutes, seconds, etc.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?totalidle%>%x', '%g%l%<@?totaltime%>%x', '%g%l%<@?averageactive%>%x', '%g%l%<@?averageidle%>%x', '%g%l%<@?averagetime%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?interval%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?totalidle
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?totalidle}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?totalidle [<NAME>]}%]%x

Returns the total time that the character %y%l<NAME>%x has spent idle whilst connected to %@%n in seconds, e.g:  '%g%l%(@echo%) {%(@?interval%) {@?totalidle me}}%x' will display your total idle time in hours, minutes, seconds, etc.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?totalactive%>%x', '%g%l%<@?totaltime%>%x', '%g%l%<@?averageidle%>%x', '%g%l%<@?averageactive%>%x', '%g%l%<@?averagetime%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?interval%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?totallogins
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?totallogins}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?totallogins [<NAME>]}%]%x

Returns the character %y%l<NAME>%x's total number of logins since they created their character, e.g:  '%g%l@echo {@?totallogins me}%x' will display your total number of logins.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?averagelogins%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?created%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?totaltime
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?totaltime}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?totaltime [<NAME>]}%]%x

Returns the total time that the character %y%l<NAME>%x has been using %@%n for in seconds, e.g:  '%g%l%(@echo%) {%(@?interval%) {@?totaltime me}}%x' will display your total time connected in hours, minutes, seconds, etc.

%c%l%8NOTE:  %xTotal time includes time spent idle.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?totalactive%>%x', '%g%l%<@?totalidle%>%x', '%g%l%<@?averagetime%>%x', '%g%l%<@?averageactive%>%x', '%g%l%<@?averageidle%>%x', '%g%l%<@?longesttime%>%x', '%g%l%<@?longestdate%>%x', '%g%l%<@?lastconnected%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?interval%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?true
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?true}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?true}%]%x

'%g%l{@?true}%x' returns '%y%lOK%x' if the last command executed succeeded, otherwise it returns '%y%lError%x'.

'%g%l{@?true}%x' is of most use when used in the %y%l<CONDITION>%x part of an '%g%l%(@if%)%x' or '%g%l%(@while%)%x' command, e.g:

%[%g%l%(@if%) {@?true} do @echo Success!%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@true%>%x', '%g%l%<@?false%>%x', '%g%l%<condition%>%x' and '%g%l%<queries%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?typeof
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?typeof}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?typeof <OBJECT>}
        {@?typeof <OBJECT> = <TYPE>}%]%x

The first form returns the type of %y%l<OBJECT>%x as a string, e.g:  '%y%lExit%x'.

The second form succeeds and returns '%c%lOK%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x is of %y%l<TYPE>%x,  e.g:

   %g%l%[%(@if%) {%(@?typeof%) mything = thing} do %(@echo%) Thing!; else %(@echo%) Not a thing!%]%x

Both forms fail and return '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found.


%c%l%$The types of objects returned are:
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%y%l%(Alarm%)%x, %y%l%(Array%)%x, %y%l%(Character%)%x, %y%lCommand%x, %y%l%(Exit%)%x, %y%l%(Fuse%)%x, %y%l%(Thing%)%x, %y%l%(Property%)%x, %y%l%(Room%)%x, %y%l%(Variable%)%x.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?uid
%TOPIC @?chuid
%TITLE help on '%w%l{@?uid}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?uid [<NAME>]}%]%x

Returns the name (Or ID if you control them) of the character you (Or the character %y%l<NAME>%x, if specified) are currently building as.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<fset%>%x', '%g%l%<@chuid%>%x', '%g%l%<group building%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?uptime
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?uptime}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?uptime [dbcreated|dbuptime|dbaverage]}
        {@?uptime [longesttime|longestdate]}
        {@?uptime [uptime|startdate]}%]%x


%c%l%$The '%w%l%${@?uptime}%c%l%$' query command returns one of the following:
%~%m~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%5%9%y%luptime       %]%xThe time (In seconds) %@%n has been running for since it was last restarted ('%c%l%{@?interval {@?uptime uptime}}%x'.)

%[%5%9%y%lstartdate    %]%xThe time and date when %@%m was last restarted ('%c%l%{@?realtime {@?uptime startdate}}%x'.)

%[%5%9%y%ldbcreated    %]%xThe time and date when the database was created ('%c%l%{@?realtime {@?uptime dbcreated}}%x'.)

%[%5%9%y%ldbuptime     %]%xThe accumulated up-time (In seconds) since the database was created (The total accumulated time %@%m has been running for since the database was created, excluding periods when it was down.) ('%c%l%{@?interval {@?uptime dbuptime}}%x'.)

%PAGE
%[%5%9%y%ldbaverage    %]%xThe average up-time (In seconds, worked out by dividing the accumulated up-time by the number of times %@%m has been restarted.) ('%c%l%{@?interval {@?uptime dbaverage}}%x'.)

%[%5%9%y%llongesttime  %]%xThe longest recorded up-time (In seconds.) ('%c%l%{@?interval {@?uptime longesttime}}%x'.)

%[%5%9%y%llongestdate  %]%xThe time and date when the longest uptime occurred ('%c%l%{@?realtime {@?uptime longestdate}}%x'.)


%c%l%8NOTE:  %xIf no parameters are specified, '%y%luptime%x' is assumed.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Example:
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@command%) UptimeTest =\
   %(@echo%)\
   %(@echo%) %%y%%l%%@%%n %%g%%l(%%y%%l%%@%%m%%g%%l) was restarted on %%y%%l\{%(@?realtime%)
      \{@?uptime startdate}} %%g%%land has been running for %%w%%l\{%(@?interval%0
      \{@?uptime uptime}}%%g%%l.\
   %(@echo%)\
   %(@echo%) %%g%%lThe database was created on %%y%%l\{%(@?realtime%) \{@?uptime
      dbcreated}} %%g%%land has been running for an accumulated time of
      %%w%%l{%(@?interval%) {@?uptime dbuptime}} %%g%%l(Average is %%y%%l\{%(@?interval%)
      {@?uptime dbaverage}}%%g%%l.)\
   %(@echo%)\
   %(@echo%) %%g%%lThe longest recorded uptime of %%w%%l\{%(@?interval%) \{@?uptime
      longesttime}} %%g%%loccurred on %%y%%l\{%(@?realtime%) \{@?uptime
      longestdate}}%%g%%l.\
   %(@echo%)%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<uptime%>%x', '%g%l%<@?realtime%>%x', '%g%l%<@?interval%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?peak%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?variables
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?variables}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?variables <OBJECT> [= <NUMBER>]}%]%x

Returns the name (Or ID if you control it) of the first (Or %y%l<NUMBER>%x'th, if %y%l<NUMBER>%x is specified) variable in %y%l<OBJECT>%x's variables list.  Returns '%y%l*NOTHING*%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x has no variables.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?next%>%x' and '%g%l%<@variable%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?ver
%TOPIC @?version
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?version}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?version [codebase|codedesc|codename|compiled]}
        {@?version [version|os|website]}%]%x

With no parameters, '%g%l{@?version}%x' returns the %c%lname%x and %c%lshort name%x of %@%m, along with the %c%lversion%x, %c%lcode base%x, %c%lproject name%x, %c%loperating system%x and the %c%lsource code compilation date/time%x, e.g:

%4%[   %y%l%{@?version}%]%x

Alternatively, one of the following parameters can be specified to return specific version information:

%PAGE
%[%9%3%g%lCodeBase   %xReturns the code base name (E.g:  '%y%l%{@?version codebase}%x')
%9%3%g%lCodeDesc   %xReturns the code base description (E.g:  '%y%l%{@?version codedesc}%x')
%9%3%g%lCodeName   %xReturns the code base project name (E.g:  '%y%l%{@?version codename}%x')
%9%3%g%lCompiled   %xReturns the source code compilation date and time (E.g:  '%y%l%{@?version compiled}%x')
%9%3%g%lVersion    %xReturns the code base version number (E.g:  '%y%l%{@?version version}%x')
%9%3%g%lOS         %xReturns the operating system (E.g:  '%y%l%{@?version os}%x'.)
%9%3%g%lWebSite    %xReturns the code base web site (E.g:  '%y%l%{@?version website}%x')%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<version%>%x', '%g%l%<version info%>%x' and '%g%l%<bug fixes%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?volume
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?volume}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?volume <OBJECT>}%]%x

Returns the volume of %y%l<OBJECT>%x in litres (There are %c%l10 litres%x to a %c%lcubic metre%x.)

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@volume%>%x', '%g%l%<@mass%>%x', '%g%l%<@?mass%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?weight%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?title
%TOPIC @?whostring
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?title}%x' (Or '%w%l{@?who}%x')
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?title <NAME>}
        {@?who <NAME>}%]%x

If the character %y%l<NAME>%x isn't specified, your title ('%g%l%(who%)%x' list message) is returned, otherwise the character %y%l<NAME>%x's title is returned.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<title%>%x' and '%g%l%<who%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?weight
%TOPIC objectweights
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?weight}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?weight <OBJECT>}%]%x

Returns the total weight of %y%l<OBJECT>%x in kilograms.  If %y%l<OBJECT>%x is a room, the total weight of its contents will be returned, otherwise the total weight of %y%l<OBJECT>%x and its contents will be returned.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if %y%l<OBJECT>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@mass%>%x', '%g%l%<@volume%>%x', '%g%l%<@?mass%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?volume%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?won
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?won}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?won [<NAME>]}%]%x

If the character %y%l<NAME>%x isn't specified, the number of battles you've won are returned, otherwise the number of battles the character %y%l<NAME>%x has won are returned.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?lost%>%x', '%g%l%<@?total%>%x', '%g%l%<@?performance%>%x' and '%g%l%<combat%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?www
%TOPIC @?worldwideweb
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?www}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?www [<NAME>]}%]%x

If the character %y%l<NAME>%x isn't specified, your web site address is returned, otherwise the character %y%l<NAME>%x's web site address is returned.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@www%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?wildcard
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?wildcard}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?wildcard "<WILDCARD>" "<STRING>"}%]%x

Succeeds if %y%l<STRING>%x matches the wildcard specification %y%l<WILDCARD>%x, otherwise fails.  See '%g%l%<wildcards%>%x' for more details about wildcards.


%c%l%$Examples:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l{@?wildcard "j*digi*" "jc digita"}%]%x

...command %y%lsucceeds%x.

%[%g%l{@?wildcard "j*digi*" "fred bloggs"}%]%x

...command %y%lfails%x.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?word
%TOPIC @?wordexact
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?word}%x' and '%w%l{@?wordexact}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?word[exact] "<WORD>" "<SENTENCE>"}%]%x

Returns 0 if the word %y%l<WORD>%x isn't found in the sentence %y%l<SENTENCE>%x, otherwise, it returns the number of the word in the sentence (1 = first word, 2 = second, and so on.)  '%g%l{@?wordexact}%x' exactly matches for %y%l<WORD>%x, whereas '%g%l{@?word}%x' partially matches.


%c%l%$Examples:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l{@?wordexact "of" "The virtual world of %@%n."}%]%x

...returns %y%l%{@?wordexact "of" "The virtual world of {%@%n}."}%x  ('%y%lof%x' is %c%lexactly%x matched with the %{@?rank {@?word "of" "The virtual world of {%@%n}."}} word in the sentence.)

%[%g%l{@?word "irtu" "The virtual world of %@%n."}%]%x

...returns %y%l%{@?word "irtu" "The virtual world of {%@%n}."}%x  ('%y%lirtu%x' is %c%lpartially%x matched with the word '%y%lvirtual%x', which is the %{@?rank {@?word "irtu" "The virtual world of {%@%n}."}} word in the sentence.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?wordno%>%x', '%g%l%<@?nowords%>%x' and '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?wordno
%TOPIC @?wordnumber
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?wordno}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?wordno <NUMBER> "<SENTENCE>"}%]%x

Returns word number %y%l<NUMBER>%x in the sentence %y%l<SENTENCE>%x.  If that word doesn't exist (I.e:  %g%l{@?wordno 5 "Hello world!"}%x), it returns an empty string (%y%l""%x.)

If you use the word '%y%lLAST%x' instead of specifing a number for %y%l<NUMBER>%x, it returns the last word in the sentence.  Using the word '%y%lFIRST%x' returns the first word in the sentence.


%c%l%$Example:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l{@?wordno 5 "The virtual world of %@%n."}%]%x

...returns '%y%l%{@?wordno 5 "The virtual world of {%@%n}."}%x'.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?nowords%>%x', '%g%l%<@?word%>%x' and '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?scrheight
%TOPIC @?screenheight
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?scrheight}%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?scrheight <NAME>}%]%x

If the character %y%l<NAME>%x isn't specified, your current set screen height (In lines) is returned, otherwise the character %y%l<NAME>%x's current set screen height is returned.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<set scrheight%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?scrwidth%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @?wrap
%TOPIC @?wordwrap
%TOPIC @?scrwidth
%TOPIC @?screenwidth
%TOPIC @?wordwrapping
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@?scrwidth}%x' (Or '%w%l{@?wrap}%x')
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@?scrwidth <NAME>}
        {@?wrap <NAME>}%]%x

If the character %y%l<NAME>%x isn't specified, your current set screen width (In characters) is returned, otherwise the character %y%l<NAME>%x's current set screen width is returned (Or the default of %c%l80 characters%x if they aren't connected.)

%8%c%lNOTE:  %xMost terminals can't actually properly display a line that's exactly their screen width wide  -  The reason why is because the cursor is wrapped to the next line on displaying the rightmost character, creating an unwanted blank line between that and any following text.

       %8You should assume the max. length of text per line is their screen width setting minus 1, e.g:  '%g%l{%(@eval%) {@?scrwidth <NAME>} - 1}%x'.

Fails and returns '%c%lError%x' if the character %y%l<NAME>%x can't be found.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<set wrap%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?scrheight%>%x'.

