%TOPIC alarms
%TOPIC @alarm
%TOPIC timedevents
%TOPIC makingalarms
%TOPIC buildingalarms
%TOPIC creatingalarms
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@alarm%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@alarm <NAME> = <SECONDS> <MINUTES> <HOURS> <DAYS>
        @alarm <NAME> = + <SECONDS> <MINUTES> <HOURS> <DAYS>%]%x

Alarms can only be created by %c%lWizards/%cDruids%x and above.  They allow the compound command linked by their '%g%l%(@csucc%)%x' (See '%g%l%<@csucc%>%x') to be executed automatically at certain time(s) during the week, or every given interval of time.

The first form causes the alarm to go off at the same time each week.

Days are numbered from %y%l1 - 7%x, with day 1 being Monday.  If you enter a '%y%l*%x' in any field instead of a number, the alarm will execute regardless of the value of that field, e.g:  '%g%l0 0 12 *%x' would cause the alarm to go off at midday every day.

The second form causes the alarm to go off every given interval of time, e.g: '%g%l+ 0 10 0 0%x' would cause the alarm to execute every 10 minutes and '%g%l+ 0 0 2 0%x' would cause the alarm to execute every 2 hours. 

%PAGE
You can disable an alarm (Without destroying it), by either resetting its description or csuccess branch ('%g%l%(@csucc%)%x'.)

%9%2%r%lWARNING:  %xAlarms are restricted to %c%lWizards/%cDruids%x and above due to the potential CPU usage and lag they could cause if used incorrectly.  Lots of alarms executing at regular intervals (I.e:  One or more times every 5 minutes) or straight after each other (Because their time of execution is the same) could cause lag and/or slow %@%m down  -  Especially if the compound commands being executed are relatively complex.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@pending%>%x', '%g%l%<@desc%>%x', '%g%l%<@csucc%>%x', '%g%l%<@?pending%>%x' and '%g%l%<building%>%x'.

