%TOPIC @alias
%TOPIC @unalias
%TOPIC @aliases
%TOPIC @unaliases
%TOPIC addingaliases
%TOPIC changingaliases
%TOPIC removingaliases
%TOPIC deletingaliases
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@alias%x' and '%w%l@unalias%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@alias <NAME> [<NAME>] [...] [= <COMMAND>]
        @unalias <NAME> [<NAME>] [...]%]%x

The '%g%l@alias%x' command is used to add or change aliases for %@%m commands.
'%g%l@unalias%x' is used to remove them.

Mortals may have up to %c%l100%x unique aliases, %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and %c%lWizards/%cDruids%x may have up to %c%l200%x, and %g%lElder Wizards/%gDruids%x and above are unrestricted.

%c%l%8NOTE:  %xIf a compound command has its %y%l%(APPRENTICE%)%x or %y%l%(WIZARD%)%x flag set, or is owned by an %y%lApprentice Wizard/%yDruid%x or above, the aliases of the compound command's owner will be taken into account when the compound command is executed.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Adding aliases...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
To add an alias, simply type '%g%l@alias <NAME> = <COMMAND>%x', e.g:  '%g%l@alias bye = %(say%) I'm off now - See ya later!%x' will add an alias '%y%lbye%x' which when typed as a command will make you say "%c%lI'm off now - See ya later!%x" to everyone in the same room.

Multiple aliases may be defined for a command, by specifying more than one name, e.g:  '%g%l@alias bye goodbye seeya = say I'm off now - See ya later!%x'  -  With this alias, you can type '%g%lbye%x', '%g%lgoodbye%x' or '%g%lseeya%x' to say "%y%lI'm off now - See ya later!%x" to everyone in the same room.

Aliases may also be given a parameter, which can be substituted into the alias using '%y%l!*%x', e.g:  '%g%l@alias %(say%) " ' ` = %(say%) %%r%%l!*%x' will alias the '%g%l%(say%)%x' command, so that you speak in colour (%r%lRed%x) everytime you use it.

%PAGE
'%g%l%(@mexec%)%x' (See '%g%l%<@mexec%>%x') can also be used with aliases, allowing you to use them as a %c%lcheap alternative%x to compound commands for performing small tasks, e.g:  '%g%l@alias toparea = %(@mexec%) \{:%%g%%lheads back to %%p Top Area.}\{%(@tel%) me = #12345}\{%(@echo%) %%g%%lYou head back to your Top Area.}%x' (%c%lNOTE:  %x'%y%l\%x's %c%lMUST%x be used in front of '%y%l{%x's on the command line to prevent them from being evaluated)  -  This alias will teleport you back to your Top Area (Replace %y%l#12345%x with the #ID of your Top Area.))


%c%l%$Changing aliases...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
To change an alias, simply type '%g%l@alias <NAME> = <NEW COMMAND>%x', e.g:  '%g%l@alias %(say%) = say %%g%%l!*%x' will change the alias for '%g%l%(say%)%x' so that you speak in %g%lgreen%x text rather than %r%lred%x.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Removing aliases...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
To remove an alias, simply type '%g%l@unalias <NAME>%x', e.g:  '%g%l@unalias %(say%)%x' will remove the alias for '%g%l%(say%)%x'.


%c%l%$Global aliases
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xAn alias may be made global, so that it applies to every character on %@%m, including from within compound commands.  To do this, the global aliases owner must be set by the %m%lSupreme Being%x using '%g%l%(@admin%)%x' (See '%g%l%<@admin%>%x'.)  All aliases of this character (When set) will be global.  See '%g%l%<@admin%>%x' for further information on global aliases.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Example aliases:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
%[%g%l@alias %(say%) " ' ` = say %%r%%l!*
@alias block = %(@if%) \{%(@?set%) me = %(haven%)} do %(@set%) me = !%(haven%); else %(@set%) me =
   %(haven%)
@alias toparea = %(@mexec%) \{:%%g%%lheads back to %%p Top Area.}\{%(@tel%) me = #12345}
   \{%(@echo%) %%g%%lYou head back to your Top Area.}%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<aliases%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?alias%>%x'.

