%TOPIC @areaname
%TOPIC areanames
%TOPIC namedareas
%TOPIC namingareas
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@areaname%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@areaname <OBJECT> [= <NAME>]%]%x

Gives the room or thing %y%l<OBJECT>%x the area name %y%l<NAME>%x (Or clears %y%l<OBJECT>%x's area name if %y%l<NAME>%x isn't specified.)

To have several rooms with the same area name and to have the features described on the next page, here are some basic guidelines:

%4%r%l*  %xThere's no need to set the area name of %y%lALL%x of the rooms in the area (This will prevent the features on the next page from being able to work properly.)

%4%y%l*  %c%lONLY%x set the area name of the %y%lTOPMOST%x room in the area to the desired area name.

%9%2%c%lEXAMPLE:  %y%lRoom #1%x contains:  %c%lRoom #2%x, %c%lRoom #3%x and %c%lRoom #4%x.  To have all these rooms with the same area name and have the features described below, simply type '%g%l@areaname here = <NAME>%x' %c%lONLY%x in %y%lRoom #1%x.

%PAGE

%c%l%$When a room/thing has an area name, it has the following effects...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%4%r%l*%x  Yelled messages only go to rooms/things within the named area instead of every room/thing the owner of the room/thing you're in owns.
 
%4%y%l*%x  '%g%l%(localwho%)%x' (Or '%g%l%(lwho%)%x' for short) lists everyone within the named area rather than everyone who's within a room/thing owned by the owner of your current location.
 
%4%r%l*%x  Many other commands will tell you not only what room/thing a character is in, but also what named area it's within, e.g:  '%g%lPAGING from %y%lA dark cave %g%lin %y%lThe Adventure Zone%g%l:  %w%lFred%w says "%w%lHello!%w"%x' (The named area in this case is '%y%lThe Adventure Zone%x'.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?areaname%>%x', '%g%l%<@?areanameid%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @areaecho
%TOPIC @areawrite
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@areawrite%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@areawrite <MESSAGE>%]%x

'%g%l@areawrite%x' is similar to the '%g%l%(@write%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<@write%>%x'), except that it displays %y%l<MESSAGE>%x in your current location, and all locations within that location.

You must own or have write permission to your current location to use '%g%l@areawrite%x'.  If there are locations owned by other users within the location, the message will be displayed in them, even if you don't have write permission.

Messages sent using '%g%l@areawrite%x' exclude your name, and will not be seen in locations set %y%lQUIET%x or by characters who have set their %y%lQUIET%x flag.


%c%l%$Example:
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@tel%) me = <#ID OF YOUR TOP AREA>
%(@areawrite%) Hello everyone in my area!%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@write%>%x', '%g%l%<@echo%>%x' and '%g%l%<@oecho%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC arrays
%TOPIC @array
%TOPIC dynamicarrays
%TOPIC @dynamicarrays
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@array%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@array <NAME> [= <INITIAL SIZE>]%]%x

Creates a dynamic array called %y%l<NAME>%x (Building Quota used:  %c%l1%x.)  If %y%l<INITIAL SIZE>%x is specified, the new dynamic array is given that number of blank elements (Providing you have sufficient Building Quota (Building Quota used by each element:  %c%l1%x.))

Dynamic arrays are similar to the arrays found in most high-level programming langauges such as Pascal, C, etc.  However, the main difference is that arrays in %@%m are %c%lDYNAMIC%x (I.e:  There's no limit to the the number of elements an array can have (Except your Building Quota limit), and the size of the array can easily be changed by inserting or destroying elements.)

%PAGE
Once a dynamic array has been created, its elements can be referenced either by %c%lnumber%x, %c%lindex name%x or one of the keywords '%y%lFIRST%x' (First element), '%y%lLAST%x' (Last element) or '%y%lEND%x' (Add new element to end of array) enclosed in square brackets after its name (E.g:  You could reference the %c%l2nd%x element of the dynamic array '%y%lmyarray%x' using '%g%lmyarray[2]%x' and reference the indexed element '%y%ltest%x' using '%g%lmyarray[test]%x'.)

You can also specify a range of elements by using '%y%l[<FROM>..<TO>]%x' or '%y%l[<FROM>-<TO>]%x', e.g:  You could reference elements %c%l4%x, %c%l5%x, %c%l6%x and %c%l7%x of '%y%lmyarray%x' by using either '%g%lmyarray[4..7]%x' or '%g%lmyarray[4-7]%x'.  Using ranges allows you to describe, destroy, etc. several elements at once.  You can use the keyword '%y%lALL%x' to reference every element of the dynamic array (This is the same as using '%y%l[FIRST..LAST]%x'), e.g:  You could reference every element of '%y%lmyarray%x' by using '%g%lmyarray[ALL]%x'.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Describing and adding new elements...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
You can set the description of an element by using '%g%l%(@desc%) <ARRAY>[<ELEMENT>] [= <DESCRIPTION>]%x'  -  This sets the description of the given element(s) to %y%l<DESCRIPTION>%x (Or clears the description of the given element(s) if %y%l<DESCRIPTION>%x isn't specified.), e.g:  '%g%l%(@desc%) myarray[2] = element 2%x', '%g%l%(@desc%) myarray[test] = indexed element 'test'%x'.

If the element(s) being described do not exist, they'll be created (Building Quota used by each new element:  %c%l1%x.)  If the element being described is an element with an index name, and an element with that index name doesn't already exist, a new element will be added to the end of the dynamic array and given the specified index name and description.

You can easily add a new element to the end of a dynamic array using the '%y%lEND%x' keyword, e.g:  '%g%l%(@desc%) myarray[END] = a new element%x'.

For further information on describing and adding new elements, see '%g%l%<@desc%>%x'.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Inserting a new element...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
You can insert a new element in front of any element of a dynamic array by using '%g%l%(@insert%) <ARRAY>[<ELEMENT>] [= <DESCRIPTION>%x'  -  This inserts a new element in front of element %y%l<ELEMENT>%x (Or if %y%l<ELEMENT>%x is a range, the new element will be inserted in front of the first element of the range) and sets its description to %y%l<DESCRIPTION>%x (If %y%l<DESCRIPTION>%x is specified), e.g:  '%g%l%(@insert%) myarray[2] = a new inserted element%x', '%g%l%(@insert%) myarray[test] = a new inserted element in front of indexed element 'test'%x'.

For further information on inserting new elements, see '%g%l%<@insert%>%x'.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Destroying an element...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
You can destroy an element and remove it from a dynamic array by using '%g%l%(@destroy%) <ARRAY>[<ELEMENT>]%x'  -  This destroys the element %y%l<ELEMENT>%x (Or range of elements, if a range is specified), e.g:  '%g%l%(@dest%) myarray[2]%x', '%g%l%(@dest%) myarray[test]%x'.  An alternative to destroying an element is simply clearing its description (I.e:  If you purposely want the dynamic array to stay a fixed size.)

For further information on destroying elements, see '%g%l%<@destroy%>%x'.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Returning the description of an element (Or range of elements)...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
You can get the description of an element (Or range of elements) by using the '%g%l{%(@?elementno%)}%x' query command, for example '%g%l%(@echo%) {%(@?elementno%) myarray[2]}%x' will display the description of the %c%l2nd%x element of '%y%lmyarray%x' and '%g%l%(@echo%) {%(@?elementno%) myarray[test]}%x' will display the description of the element with the index name '%y%ltest%x' of '%y%lmyarray%x'.

For further information on returning the description of an element, see '%g%l%<@?elementno%>%x'.


%c%l%$Processing the elements or index names of a dynamic array...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
You can process the elements or index names of a dynamic array (Or a range of specific elements) using the '%g%l%(@with%)%x' command.  For details on how to do this, see '%g%l%<@with%>%x'.  Example:  '%g%l%(@with%) elements myarray do %(@echo%) $6%x', '%g%l%(@with%) indexnames myarray do %(@echo%) $6%x'.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Editing the elements of a dynamic array...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
You can use %@%n's built-in editor to edit the elements of a dynamic array (However, you can only edit a single element at a time.)

To edit the elements of a dynamic array, simply start up the editor in the usual way, referencing the element you'd like to edit, e.g:  '%g%l%(edit%) myarray[2]%x' will start the editor, editing the %c%l2nd%x element of '%y%lmyarray%x' and '%g%l%(edit%) myarray[test]%x' will start the editor, editing the element with the index name '%y%ltest%x' of '%y%lmyarray%x'.

%PAGE
You can move around the elements of the dynamic array you're editing using the '%g%l%(.element%)%x' command, for example, typing '%g%l%(.element%) 3%x' will save the changes you've made to the element you're currently editing and start editing the %c%l3rd%x element.  You can use the keywords '%y%lFIRST%x', '%y%lLAST%x' and '%y%lEND%x' with '%g%l%(.element%)%x' if you like.

For further information on editing dynamic array elements (And using the editor), see '%g%l%<editor%>%x' and '%g%l%<.element%>%x'.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@desc%>%x', '%g%l%<@name%>%x', '%g%l%<@destroy%>%x', '%g%l%<@index%>%x', '%g%l%<@insert%>%x', '%g%l%<@with%>%x', '%g%l%<@sort%>%x', '%g%l%<@?arrays%>%x', '%g%l%<@?elementno%>%x', '%g%l%<@?elements%>%x', '%g%l%<@?index%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?indexno%>%x'.

