%TOPIC ban
%TOPIC @ban
%TOPIC banned
%TOPIC banningplayers
%TOPIC banningcharacters
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@ban%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@ban <NAME> = permanently = <REASON>
        @ban <NAME> = <TIME> = <REASON>
        @ban <NAME> = lift = <REASON>%]%x

This command can only be used by %c%lWizards/%cDruids%x and above on Mortals and %b%lMorons%x and should be used as an %r%l*absolute*%x last resort.

The first form ('%g%l@ban <NAME> = permanently = <REASON>%x') bans a character %c%lpermanently%x from %@%n.

The second form ('%g%l@ban <NAME> = <TIME> = <REASON>%x') bans a character for the %c%lgiven amount of time%x, e.g:

%[%g%l@ban <NAME> = 1 hour = <REASON>   %x...Bans the character %y%l<NAME>%x for 1 hour.
%g%l@ban <NAME> = 3 days = <REASON>   %x...Bans %y%l<NAME>%x for 3 days.%]%x

The third form ('%g%l@ban <NAME> = lift = <REASON>%x') %c%llifts a character's ban%x (Regardless of whether it's permanent or for a specific amount of time), allowing them to connect again and use %@%n.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<moron flag%>%x', '%g%l%<warn%>%x', '%g%l%<@boot%>%x', '%g%l%<@banish%>%x' and '%g%l%<@site%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @banish
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@banish%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@banish add|remove <NAME> = <REASON>
        @banish list [<PAGE NO>] [<NAME>]
        @banish check <NAME>%]%x

This command can only be used by %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above.

'%g%l@banish%x' is used to banish the use of unsuitable, abusive, offensive, racist, etc. character names.  Once a character name has been banished, new users will not be able to be created with a name beginning with the banished name, and existing users will not be able to change their name to the banished name (Or a name which begins with it.)  Banished character names also can't be used in the name prefix or suffix of a character.

'%g%l@banish add <NAME> = <REASON>%x' is used to add a character name to the list of banished names, where %y%l<NAME>%x is the character name to add and %y%l<REASON>%x is the reason for banishing the name.  You can banish character names which currently don't exist in the database to prevent future use/misuse.  For example, '%g%l@banish add crap = some people might be offended by this name%x' will banish the use of the character names beginning with '%y%lCrap%x'.

%PAGE
'%g%l@banish remove <NAME> = <REASON>%x' will remove a character name from the list of banished names, where %y%l<NAME>%x is the character name to remove and %y%l<REASON>%x is reason for removing it from the banished list.  For example, '%g%l@banish remove wibble = this name isn't offensive enough to be banished%x' will remove the character name '%y%lWibble%x' from the banished list (If it has been banished.)

'%g%l@banish list%x' lists character names which are currently banished, sorted into alphabetical order.  If %y%l<NAME>%x is specified, names which contain the text %y%l<NAME>%x will be displayed only (For example, '%g%l@banish list fred%x' will only list banished character names which contain the text '%y%lfred%x'.)

%PAGE
If %y%l<PAGE NO>%x is specified, that page of banished names will be displayed (The first page is displayed by default), e.g:  '%g%l@banish list 2%x' will display the %c%l2nd%x page, '%g%l@banish list 3%x' will display the %c%l3rd%x, etc.

'%g%l@banish check%x' allows you to check for and list characters who have names beginning with %y%l<NAME>%x, i.e:  '%g%l@banish check fred%x' will list all characters who have names beginning with '%y%lFred%x'.  You can even check for names which aren't currently banished.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<moron flag%>%x', '%g%l%<warn%>%x', '%g%l%<@boot%>%x', '%g%l%<@ban%>%x' and '%g%l%<@site%>%x'.

