%TOPIC errorbeep
%TOPIC warningbeep
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@beep%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@beep%]%x

'%g%l@beep%x' causes the person executing it's terminal to beep (Character 7 (BEL.))
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<wake%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @begin
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@begin%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l<CONDITION>:@begin
                       <COMMANDS>
                       ...
                    %(@end%)%]%x

The '%g%l@begin%x' command is used within a %y%l<CONDITION>%x statement of '%g%l%(@case%)%x' (See '%g%l%<@case%>%x') to allow a block of commands to be executed, rather than a single command.  The block of commands %c%l%uMUST%x be followed by '%g%l%(@end%)%x' (See '%g%l%<@end%>%x') on a line by itself.

For further information, please see '%g%l%<@case%>%x' (An example is provided on the next page.)


%PAGE

%c%l%$Example:
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%g%l%[%(@command%) BeginTest =\
%(@case%) $3 do\
   block:@begin\
            %(@echo%) %%w%%l>>>  %%xThis demonstrates executing\
            %(@echo%) %%w%%l>>>  %%xa block of commands.\
         %(@end%)\
   DEFAULT:%(@echo%) USAGE: %%g%%l \{%(@?cmdname%)} block\
%(@end%)%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@case%>%x', '%g%l%<@end%>%x'.

