%TOPIC @boot
%TOPIC nuisance
%TOPIC bootingusers
%TOPIC bootingpeople
%TOPIC chuckingpeopleoff
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@boot%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@boot <NAME> [= <BAN TIME>] = <REASON>%]%x

This command can only be used by %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above, providing their %y%l%(BOOT%)%x flag hasn't been reset.

The '%g%l@boot%x' command can be used (As a last resort) to kick a character off %@%n (I.e:  If they're being abusive/harassive and refuse to stop, even after being given a %b%lMoron%x flag, etc.)

If %y%l<BAN TIME>%x is specified, the booted character will be banned for that amount of time (In minutes.)  This is ideal when booting abusive/problem users, as it can be used to stop them from simply connecting again as soon as they're booted.  The ban time can be between %c%l1%x and %c%l60%x minutes.  The '%g%l%(@ban%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<@ban%>%x') can be used to impose longer bans.

%PAGE
The '%g%l@boot%x' command boots %c%lALL%x connections of the specified character off %@%n.  Connections which have stopped responding should be booted using the '%g%l%(@bootdead%)%x' command.

%c%lNOTE:  %xAll boots are logged to the '%c%lBoot%x' log file (See '%g%l%<@log%>%x'.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@bootdead%>%x', '%g%l%<warn%>%x', '%g%l%<moron flag%>%x', '%g%l%<@ban%>%x', '%g%l%<@site%>%x' and '%g%l%<boot flag%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC crashes
%TOPIC crashing
%TOPIC @bootdead
%TOPIC crashedconnections
%TOPIC lockedupconnections
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@bootdead%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@bootdead [<NAME>]%]%x

'%g%l@bootdead%x' is used to get rid of 'dead' connections when your session has stopped responding.  When your character is connected multiple times (I.e:  Reconnecting after your connection has stopped responding will often result in you being connected twice), you'll need to use the '%g%l@bootdead%x' command to get rid of your connections which have stopped responding.

Simply type '%g%l@bootdead%x' and your connections which have stopped responding will be booted from %@%n (%c%lNOTE:  %xOnly connections with an idle time of more than %c%l1 minute%x will be booted.)

If you're an %y%lApprentice Wizard/%yDruid%x or above, you can optionally specify a %y%l<NAME>%x to boot the connections which have stopped responding of another character (If a user asks you to do this, you should tell them how to use the '%g%l@bootdead%x' command.)

%8%c%lNOTE:  %xUnlike '%g%l%(@boot%)%x', '%g%l@bootdead%x' is %c%lNOT%x logged (There is no need), no reason needs to be given and there is no broadcast message.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@boot%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @break
%TOPIC flowcontrol
%TOPIC @breakstatement
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@break%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@break [true|false|current]%]%x

'%g%l@break%x' stops execution of the current compound command and skips to the end, executing the compound command linked via the cfailure if '%y%lfalse%x' is specified, csuccess if '%y%ltrue%x' or no parameter is specified or the csuccess/cfailure appropriately depending on the return result of the previous executed command if '%y%lcurrent%x' is specified.

%8%c%lNOTE:  %x'%g%l@break%x' does not change the return value from the previous executed command.


%c%l%$Example compound command:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@if%) {%(@eval%) "$3" = "skip"} do @break
%(@echo%) The rest of this command will be skipped if given the parameter 'skip'.%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@skip%>%x', '%g%l%<@breakloop%>%x', '%g%l%<@return%>%x', '%g%l%<@if%>%x', '%g%l%<@case%>%x', '%g%l%<@for%>%x', '%g%l%<@with%>%x', '%g%l%<@while%>%x', '%g%l%<@foreach%>%x' and '%g%l%<@goto%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @breakloop
%TOPIC @breakloopall
%TOPIC @breakloopstatement
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@breakloop%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@breakloop [all]%]%x

'%g%l@breakloop%x' breaks out of the present loop ('%g%l%(@for%)%x', '%g%l%(@foreach%)%x', '%g%l%(@while%)%x' or '%g%l%(@with%)%x') and continues executing the current compound command.  Without the parameter '%y%lall%x', '%g%l@breakloop%x' will only break out of the current loop  -  With the parameter '%y%lall%x', '%g%l@breakloop%x' will break out of %c%lALL%x loops.

%8%c%lNOTE:  %x'%g%l@breakloop%x' does not change the return value or return result (Success/failure) from the previous executed command.


%c%l%$Example compound command:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@for%) 1 to 10 do %(@if%) {%(@eval%) $4 >= 5} do @breakloop
%(@echo%) '%(@for%)' looped $5 times.%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@skip%>%x', '%g%l%<@break%>%x', '%g%l%<@return%>%x', '%g%l%<@if%>%x', '%g%l%<@for%>%x', '%g%l%<@with%>%x', '%g%l%<@while%>%x', '%g%l%<@foreach%>%x' and '%g%l%<@goto%>%x'.

