%TOPIC chattingchannels
%TITLE Help on '%w%lchat%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%lchat join <NAME>|<CHANNEL NUMBER>
        chat on|off|<CHANNEL NUMBER>
        chat subject <SUBJECT>
        chat public|private
        chat <MESSAGE>
        chat who|list
        chat kick%]%x

'%g%lChat%x' is used to join and talk over a chatting channel.

To join a chatting channel, simply type '%g%lchat <CHANNEL NUMBER>%x' or '%g%lchat join <NAME>%x' (Or type '%g%lchat on%x' to join the default channel (%y%l0%x.))  %y%l<CHANNEL NUMBER>%x can be any positive number from %y%l0%x (Default) to %y%l2000000000+%x(!), so you can easily pick your own 'personal' chatting channel to chat to your friends over.

Once you've joined a channel, you can find out who else is on it by typing '%g%lchat who%x'.  If you're the first person on the channel, you become the '%c%lChannel Operator%x' and have a few extra privileges (Read on for details.)
%PAGE
You can speak over the chatting channel in the normal manner (I.e:  '%g%lchat "<MESSAGE>%x', '%g%lchat '<MESSAGE>%x', '%g%lchat :<MESSAGE>%x', etc.)  Only users on the same channel as you will hear what you say.

Typing '%g%lchat off%x' makes you leave the current chatting channel you're joined to and switches chat off.

If you're the '%c%lChannel Operator%x', you can type '%g%lchat private%x' to make your channel private (So no-one else can join it), and '%g%lchat public%x' to make it public again.  If someone's being a nuisance, you can kick them off (By typing '%g%lchat kick <NAME>%x') providing they aren't an %y%lApprentice Wizard/%yDruid%x or above (Of course, %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above can kick people off below their level (Including the '%c%lChannel Operator%x'.))
%PAGE
Typing '%g%lchat list%x' lists all chatting channels with 1 or more users on, the number of users on them, whether they're private or public, etc.

If you're the '%c%lChannel Operator%x', you can give your chatting channel a subject by typing '%g%lchat subject <SUBJECT>%x', e.g:  '%g%lchat subject Building on %@%m.%x'  Providing your chatting channel is %c%lpublic%x, users will see its subject under '%y%lPublic/Private/Subject%x' when they type '%g%lchat list%x'.

'%g%lchat%x' can be used by %c%lANYONE%x (Unlike the %y%lApprentice Wizard/%yDruid%x and above '%g%l%(natter%)%x' channel.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<page%>%x', '%g%l%<tell%>%x' and '%g%l%<fchat%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC case
%TOPIC @case
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@case%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@case[first|random] <VALUE> do
              [<CRITERIA>]:<COMMAND>
              [<CRITERIA>]:%(@begin%)
                              <COMMANDS>
                              ...
                           %(@end%)
        @end%]%x

The '%g%l@case%x' command is used to test %y%l<VALUE>%x to see if it matches one or more %y%l<CRITERIA>%x, executing the specified %y%l<COMMAND>%x or block of %y%l<COMMANDS>%x.

%8%c%lNOTE:  %xAll comparisons performed by '%g%l@case%x' are %c%l%uNOT%x case sensitive.

%y%l<VALUE>%x is the string to match against the various %y%l<CRITERIA>%x, for example, this could be '%y%l$3%x' (See '%g%l%<@command%>%x'), or the contents of a temporary variable (See '%g%l%<@temp%>%x'.)

%PAGE
%y%l<CRITERIA>%x can be one or more of the following, separated by '%g%l,%x':

%[%g%lvalue%x         %xExact match against '%y%lvalue%x', e.g:  '%c%lMyValue%x'.
%g%lfrom-to       %xExact range match between '%y%lfrom%x' and '%y%lto%x', e.g:  '%c%lA-Z%x'.
%g%lfrom..to      %xExact range match between '%y%lfrom%x' and '%y%lto%x', e.g:  '%c%l0-9%x'.
%g%lfrom->to      %xPrefix range match between '%y%lfrom%x' and '%y%lto%x', e.g:  '%c%lA->Z%x'.
%g%lwildvalue     %xWildcard match against '%y%lwildvalue%x', e.g:  '%c%l*and*%x', '%c%lprefix*%x',
              '%c%l*suffix%x', '%c%lt?z%x', etc.
%g%lDEFAULT       %xIf specified, matched if no other %y%l<CRITERIA>%x in the '%g%l@case%x'
              statement is matched.%]%x

%PAGE
%8%c%lNOTE:  %xFor an exact range match, %y%l<VALUE>%x %c%l%uMUST%x be within the range, e.g:  '%c%lAAA%x' will not match '%y%lA-ZZ%x', but '%c%lAB%x' or '%c%lC%x' will.

%8%c%lNOTE:  %xFor a prefix range match, %y%l<VALUE>%x must be prefixed by the range, e.g:  '%c%lTest%x' will match '%y%lA->Z%x' ('%y%lT%x' is within the range, and
       prefixes '%c%lTest%x'.)

The %y%l<CRITERIA>%x must be followed by '%g%l:%x' and the %y%l<COMMAND>%x to execute, or if you wish to execute more than one command, '%g%l%(@begin%)%x' (See '%g%l%(@begin%)%x'), followed by the command(s) on separate lines, and finally, '%g%l%(@end%)%x' (See '%g%l%<@end%>%x') on a line by itself (See example below.)

%PAGE

%c%l%$For example:
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~
%g%l%[%(@command%) CaseTest =\
@case $3 do\
   single:%(@echo%) Single value.\
   one,two,three:%(@echo%) Value '%%w%%l$6%%x'.\
   AA-ZZZ:%(@echo%) Exact range '%%w%%l$6%%c-%%w%%l$7%%x'.\
   B-P:%(@echo%) Exact range '%%w%%l$6%%c-%%w%%l$7%%x'.\
   0..9:%(@echo%) Exact range '%%w%%l$6%%c..%%w%%l$7%%x'.\
   Q->Z:%(@echo%) Prefix range '%%w%%l$6%%c->%%w%%l$7%%x'.\
   *and*:%(@echo%) Contains the wildcard '%%w%%l$6%%x'.\
   a*:%(@echo%) Begins with the wildcard '%%w%%l$6%%x'.\
   block:%(@begin%)\
            %(@echo%) %%w%%l>>>  %%xThis demonstrates executing\
            %(@echo%) %%w%%l>>>  %%xa block of commands.\
         %(@end%)\
   DEFAULT:%(@echo%) %%r%%lNothing matched.\
%(@end%)%]%x

%PAGE
Try executing the above compound command with the following parameters (See if you can work out why you get each result):

   %g%lb  2  Test  two  band  ascii  block  single  wibble  error  ba  tcz  dddd%x

When '%g%l@case%x' is matching against the specified criteria, it first matches against %c%lexact values%x, followed by %c%lranges%x, then %c%lwildcards%x and finally the %c%ldefault%x, if it has been specified.  Bear this in mind when writing '%g%l@case%x' statements, because the order of criteria can make a difference to the results when using it.  Place more important criteria near the %c%ltop%x of the '%g%l@case%x' statement and less important near the %c%lbottom%x.

In addition to '%g%l@case%x', you can also use '%g%l@casefirst%x' or '%g%l@caserandom%x'.  These are identical to '%g%l@case%x', except '%g%l@casefirst%x' stops at the very %c%lfirst%x match it finds, and '%g%l@caserandom%x' picks a %c%lrandom%x condition from all those which match.

%PAGE
When using '%g%l@casefirst%x', order is %r%l%u*extremely*%x important.  If you place a range (E.g:  '%y%lA-Z%x') before an exact value (E.g:  '%y%ltest%x'), the range will %c%l%ualways%x be matched instead of '%y%ltest%x'.  '%g%l@casefirst%x' may be slightly more efficient than '%g%l@case%x', due to the fact that it does not need to match against every condition in the case statement.

With '%g%l@caserandom%x', you can specify multiple identical %y%l<CONDITION>%x statements.  One at %c%lrandom%x will be picked when the condition is matched, e.g:

   %g%l%[%(@command%) CaseRandom =\
   @caserandom $3 do\
      rand:%(@echo%) Random value %%w%%l1%%x.\
      rand:%(@echo%) Random value %%w%%l2%%x.\
      rand:%(@echo%) Random value %%w%%l3%%x.\
      DEFAULT:%(@echo%) USAGE: %%g%%l \{%(@?cmdname%)} rand\
   %(@end%)%]%x

%PAGE
The reserved variables %y%l$6%x and %y%l$7%x are useful in an '%g%l@case%x' statement  -  These substitute the following...

%y%l$6%x substitutes the matched %y%l<CONDITION>%x statement.
%y%l$7%x substitutes the second value of a range, if %y%l<CONDITION>%x is a range.

%8%c%lNOTE:  %x'%g%l@case%x' cannot be used on the command-line, or within %y%l{}%x's, e.g:  '%g%l{@case ...}%x'.

%9%6%c%lPLEASE NOTE:  %xYou can 'nest' further '%g%l%(@if%)%x', '%g%l%(@case%)%x', '%g%l%(@for%)%x', '%g%l%(@with%)%x', '%g%l%(@while%)%x' and '%g%l%(@foreach%)%x' statements (Both single and multiple lined) within a block of commands in a '%g%l@case%x' statement.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@begin%>%x', '%g%l%<@end%>%x', '%g%l%<@if%>%x', '%g%l%<@for%>%x', '%g%l%<@with%>%x', '%g%l%<@while%>%x', '%g%l%<@foreach%>%x', '%g%l%<@skip%>%x', '%g%l%<@break%>%x', '%g%l%<@return%>%x' and '%g%l%<@goto%>%x'.

