%TOPIC @cfail
%TOPIC @cfailure
%TOPIC commandfailure
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@cfail%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@cfail <COMMAND1> = <COMMAND2>%]%x

Sets the cfailure branch of %y%l<COMMAND1>%x to %y%l<COMMAND2>%x if %y%l<COMMAND2>%x is specified, otherwise resets it.

Each individual command in %y%l<COMMAND1>%x either returns success or failure when it's executed.  If the last command in %y%l<COMMAND1>%x returns failure, the cfailure branch will be followed, and the compound command this is set to (If any) will be executed (%y%l<COMMAND2>%x.)

If the cfailure branch of a compound command is set to '%y%lHOME%x', %@%m will continue searching up the area-tree for another compound command with the same name as the compound command currently being executed and execute it.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@csucc%>%x', '%g%l%<@?cfail%>%x', '%g%l%<@?csucc%>%x' and '%g%l%<@command%>%x'.

