%TOPIC @com
%TOPIC coder
%TOPIC coding
%TOPIC mudcoder
%TOPIC @command
%TOPIC mudcoding
%TOPIC programmer
%TOPIC programming
%TOPIC makingcommands
%TOPIC compoundcommands
%TOPIC creatingcommands
%TOPIC makingcompoundcommands
%TOPIC buildingcompoundcommands
%TOPIC creatingcompoundcommands
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@command%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@command <NAME>[;<NAME>][;<NAME>...] [= <COMMANDS>]%]%x

Creates a compound command with the name %y%l<NAME>%x (Building Quota used:  %c%l10%x.)  The compound command can be given multiple names by seperated them with semicolons ('%y%l;%x'), however the names mustn't have spaces in them, e.g:  '%g%l@command gohome;house;residence%x'.

The most easiest and user-friendly way to write/modify a compound command is with the editor (See '%g%l%<editor%>%x' for full details on how to it.)  You can create a new compound command and start entering the commands it should execute by typing '%g%l%(edit%) command desc <NAME>[;<NAME>][;<NAME>...]%x', or edit an existing compound command by typing '%g%l%(edit%) <NAME>%x'.

In its simplest (And probably most easiest to understand) form, a compound command simply holds a list of the commands (Each on a separate line) it should execute (In sequence, as though you typed them yourself on your keyboard) in its description, for example, the compound command '%y%lgohome%x' could be described (Using the editor) as follows (E.g:  '%g%l%(edit%) command desc gohome%x')...

%PAGE
%[%g%l:waves to all %%p friends and heads off to %%p home.
%(home%)
:wanders in from outside.%]%x

On typing '%y%lgohome%x', the above commands would be executed in sequence (As though you actually typed them yourself on your keyboard), making you emote '<YOUR NAME> %c%lwaves to all %p friends and heads off to %p home.%x', then go home and then emote '<YOUR NAME> %c%lwanders in from outside.%x'

%9%6%c%lPLEASE NOTE:  %x'%y%l%%p%x' is a pronoun substitution which returns '%y%lhis%x', '%y%lher%x' or '%y%lits%x' appropriately depending on your gender  -  See '%g%l%<substitutions%>%x' for more details.

The above is fine, but what happens if you wanted to make a compound command that takes a parameter and does something appropriate to whatever parameter it was given?

%PAGE
The compound command system built into %@%m is very powerful and supports most features you'd expect to find in a high-level programming language, including %c%lflow control%x (See '%g%l%<@break%>%x', '%g%l%<@breakloop%>%x', '%g%l%<@return%>%x' and '%g%l%<@goto%>%x'), '%c%lIf...Then...Else%x' selection (See '%g%l%<@if%>%x'), '%c%lFor%x' (See '%g%l%<@for%>%x') and '%c%lWhile%x' (See '%g%l%<@while%>%x') loops, %c%lvariables%x (See '%g%l%<@temp%>%x'), %c%larrays%x (See '%g%l%<arrays%>%x'), etc.  Other features include %c%lstring%x, %c%lsentence%x and %c%llist%x processing (See '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x' and '%g%l%<@foreach%>%x'), %c%llinked list processing%x (See '%g%l%<@with%>%x') and %c%linheritance%x (See '%g%l%<inheritance%>%x'.)

%y%lDON'T WORRY%x if you're not a programmer, and just the thought of programming makes you shiver  -  %@%m's compound command system is designed to be easy for non-programmers to learn and use  -  There's no bewildering command set or programming language to learn;  You just simply use commands similar to the ones you've already used when chatting and exploring in the virtual world of %@%n.

Now it's time to learn how to write slightly more complex compound commands...

%PAGE

%c%l%$'%y%l%${<COMMAND>}%c%l%$' (Substitute return result of %w%l%$<COMMAND>%c%l%$)...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
'%y%l{<COMMAND>}%x' is used to execute the %@%m command %y%l<COMMAND>%x and substitute its return result in place of the '%y%l{<COMMAND>}%x', e.g:  '%g%l%(@echo%) {%(@?name%) me}%x'  -  '%y%l@?name me%x' is executed first and the return result (Your name) is substituted in place of '%y%l{@?name me}%x' (Giving '%g%l%(@echo%) %{@?name}%x'.)  The '%g%l%(@echo%)%x' command simply echoes its parameters to your screen (See '%g%l%<@echo%>%x'.)

Try typing '%g%l%(@echo%) {%(@?name%) me}%x' and watch what happens.  Now replace '%y%l@?name%x' with '%y%l@?desc%x' or '%y%l@?race%x'.  A command that starts with '%y%l@?%x' is called a %c%lQUERY COMMAND%x  -  See '%g%l%<2%>%x' and '%g%l%<5%>%x' for lists of the other main query commands you can use.

Commands in '%y%l{}%x's can be nested, e.g:  '%g%l%(@echo%) {%(@?name%) {%(@?location%) me}}%x'.

%PAGE

%c%l%$'%y%l%$$<NAME>%c%l%$' (Substitute contents of variable %w%l%$<NAME>%c%l%$)...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
A '%y%l$%x' in %@%m is used to reference and substitute the contents of a variable (Either reserved (%c%l$0%x - %c%l$9%x) or user defined (Which can be a %c%l%(temporary variable%)%x (See '%g%l%<@temp%>%x'), %c%l%(property%)%x (See '%g%l%<@property%>%x'), %c%l%(variable%)%x (See '%g%l%<@variable%>%x') or %c%l%(dynamic array%)%x element (See '%g%l%<@array%>%x'), e.g:  '%y%l$myvariable%x'.))

Please see '%g%l%<variable subst%>%x' for further information on how to substitute temporary variables, variables, properties, dynamic array elements, etc.

Reserved variables (%c%l$0%x - %c%l$9%x) are built into %@%m and are mainly used within compound commands.

%PAGE

%[%c%lVariable:   What it substitutes:
%c=============================================================================%x
%g%l$0          %w%lReturn result of last command executed.
%g%l$1          %w%lFirst parameter given to compound command.
%g%l$2          %w%lSecond parameter given to compound command.
%g%l$3          %w%lBoth parameters (Including the '%y%l=%x') given to compound command.
%g%l$4          %w%lThe current loop value ('%g%l%(@for%)%x'/'%g%l%(@while%)%x'), or the item number
            currently being processed ('%g%l%(@with%)%x'/'%g%l%(@foreach%)%x'.)
%g%l$5          %w%lThe total number of loops (Repetitions) so far ('%g%l%(@for%)%x'/'%g%l%(@while%)%x'),
            or the total number of items processed so far ('%g%l%(@with%)%x'/'%g%l%(@foreach%)%x.)
%g%l$6          %w%l('%g%l%(@with%)%x')  The name/#ID number of the object currently being
            processed or the contents/index name of the dynamic array
            element currently being processed.
%g%l$7          %w%l('%g%l%(@with%)%x')  The description of the object currently being
            processed or the index name/contents of the dynamic array
            element currently being processed.
%g%l$8 - $9     %w%lReserved for future development.
%c=============================================================================%]

%PAGE

%c%l%$Protecting '%w%l%$$%c%l%$'s, '%w%l%${%c%l%$'s and '%w%l%$\%c%l%$'s...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
You may have noticed that when you try to say something with a '%y%l{%x' or '%y%l\%x' in it, your message ends up with either '%c%l<UNKNOWN VARIABLE>%x', '%c%lError%x' or absolutely nothing substituted in place of where the '%y%l{%x' or '%y%l\%x' should have been.  This is because %@%n either tried to execute it as a command ('%y%l{%x') or took it as a protecting backslash ('%y%l\%x'.)

To use a '%y%l{%x' or '%y%l\%x' in your spoken messages, etc. you must protect it with a backslash ('%y%l\%x'), e.g:  '%g%l%(say%) \{ = Curly bracket, \\ = Backslash.%x'  Try typing this with and without the protecting backslashes and see what happens.

When using the editor, '%y%l{%x's and '%y%l\%x's are %c%lNOT%x evaluated, which means you %c%lDON'T%x need to precede them with a protecting backslash.  This makes the editor especially ideal for writing compound commands.

'%y%l$%x's also need to be protected within compound commands, otherwise they will be looked up as the name of a variable.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Compound command parameters...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
When a compound command is executed, it can be given up to two parameters, separated with an equals sign ('%y%l=%x'.)  The reserved variables %y%l$1%x, %y%l$2%x and %y%l$3%x are used to return these parameters within the compound command, e.g:

%g%lmycommand param1 = param2%x

If the compound command '%y%lmycommand%x' was executed as above, the first parameter (%y%l$1%x) would be set to the text '%y%lparam1%x' and the second (%y%l$2%x) would be set to '%y%lparam2%x'.  %y%l$3%x would be set to '%y%lparam1 = param2%x' (Both parameters, including the '%y%l=%x'.)

%PAGE

%c%l%$Example...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~%x
Using the editor, create a compound command and describe it as follows...

%[%g%l@echo Parameter 1 (\$1) is:  $1
@echo Parameter 2 (\$2) is:  $2
@echo Both parameters together (\$3) are:  $3%]%x

(Note the use of protecting backslashes)  Now try executing this command, giving it a variety of parameters and watch what happens.  Try giving it a single parameter (E.g:  '%y%lhello%x') as well as two parameters (E.g:  '%y%lparam1 = param2%x'.)

%PAGE

%c%l%$Success and failure...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
Every %@%m command executed either succeeds or fails, returning an appropriate return result (In most cases, '%y%lOK%x' (%g%lCommand succeeded%x) and '%y%lError%x' (%r%lCommand failed%x.))

The last command executed in a compound command determines whether the compound command succeeds or fails.

If it succeeds, the compound command's success (See '%g%l%<@succ%>%x') and others success (See '%g%l%<@osucc%>%x') messages are displayed (If set) and the compound command that the csuccess (See '%g%l%<@csucc%>%x') is linked to is executed.

If it fails, the compound command's failure (See '%g%l%<@fail%>%x') and others failure (See '%g%l%<@ofail%>%x') messages are displayed (If set) and the compound command that the cfailure (See '%g%l%<@cfail%>%x') is linked to is executed.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Compound command basics...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
%[%g%l%(edit%) command desc <COMMAND>   %xCreates new compound command called %y%l<COMMAND>%x
                              and lets you set its description (Commands it
                              will execute.)
%g%l%(edit%) <COMMAND>                %xLets you edit the description of %y%l<COMMAND>%x.

%g%l%(@success%) <COMMAND> = <MESSAGE>    %xDisplayed to user when compound command
%g%l%(@failure%) <COMMAND> = <MESSAGE>    %xsucceeds/fails.
%g%l%(@osuccess%) <COMMAND> = <MESSAGE>   %xDisplayed to other users in same room as
%g%l%(@ofailure%) <COMMAND> = <MESSAGE>   %xuser when compound command succeeds/fails.

%g%l%(@csucc%) <COMMAND> = #<ID OF COMMAND TO EXECUTE WHEN COMP. COMMAND SUCCEEDS>
%(@cfail%) <COMMAND> = #<ID OF COMMAND TO EXECUTE WHEN COMP. COMMAND FAILS>

%g%l%(@lock%) <COMMAND> = <LOCK SPEC>     %xLocks the compound command so only users who
                                  satisfy its lock can execute it.%]

%PAGE
%[%g%l%(@set%) <COMMAND> = %(DARK%)   %xMakes it so compound command %c%lCANNOT%x be executed by
                        typing its name at the '%@%m>' prompt (Useful for
                        sub-compound commands, which should only be executed
                        via the csuccess/cfailure of another compound command,
                        '%g%l%(@if%)%x', '%g%l%(@with%)%x', etc.)%]


%c%l%$Modulising compound commands...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
When creating a compound command which consists of more than just a single compound command, you can teleport all the sub-compound commands (I.e:  Those called via csuccess/cfailure, etc.) into the first compound command (I.e:  The one which users type the name of.)  This helps keep your compound commands neat and managable, and keeps all their related parts together in one place (You can also teleport variables, properties and dynamic arrays into the module.)  E.g:  '%g%l%(@tel%) mycommand.test = mycommand%x'.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Further education...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
The best way to learn how to write compound commands (Especially more complex ones) is to experiment.  If you haven't already got a %y%l%(BUILDER%)%x flag, which allows you to build things (Including compound commands), ask someone who's Admin to give you one (Type '%g%l%(who%) admin%x' to see the names of currently connected %@%m Admin.)

If you get stuck writing a compound command, or need any help, don't hesitate to ask someone who's Admin or anyone else who's a Builder (Builders have '%y%lB%x' in their flags on the '%g%l%(who%)%x' list)  -  Most fellow Builders (Especially the more proficient ones) will be happy to help you out if no Admin are connected, or are currently very busy.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<editor%>%x', '%g%l%<@desc%>%x', '%g%l%<@name%>%x', '%g%l%<building%>%x' and '%g%l%<tracing flag%>%x'.

