%TITLE Help on %w%lsubstitutions%x
%@%n has an extensive set of substitutions, which can be used in almost any message/text (Regardless of whether it's said, %(emote%)d, %(page%)d, %(whisper%)ed, etc.)  They can also be used with '%g%l%(@echo%)%x', '%g%l%(@oecho%)%x', '%g%l%(@write%)%x', '%g%l%(@oemote%)%x' and in the '%g%l%(@desc%)%x', '%g%l%(@odesc%)%x', '%g%l%(@succ%)%x', '%g%l%(@osucc%)%x', '%g%l%(@fail%)%x', '%g%l%(@ofail%)%x', '%g%l%(@drop%)%x' and '%g%l%(@odrop%)%x' of %(rooms%), %(objects%), %(compound commands%), %(exits%), etc.

All substitutions consist of a '%y%l%%%x' followed by a letter/digit which denotes which substitution is to be used (With the exception of '%g%l%%{<CMD>}%x', which substitutes the return result of a query command.)  For example, if you put '%y%lHello, %%n!%x' in your description ('%g%l%(@desc%) me = Hello, %%n!%x'), then when other users '%g%l%(scan%)%x' you, they will see '%c%lHello, <NAME>!%x' (Where %c%l<NAME>%x is the name of the character scanning you.)

Substitutions may also be used in a similar way to query commands (See '%g%l%<queries%>%x') by placing them inside %y%l{}%x's, e.g:  '%g%l%(@echo%) The substitution "%%@%%n" is {%(@?length%) "{%%@%%n}"} characters in length.%x' (Displays '%c%lThe substitution "%@%n" is %{@?length "{%@%n}"} characters in length.%x' on your screen.)

%PAGE
%8%c%lNOTE:  %x'%y%l%%%%%x' is a special substitution, which simply returns '%y%l%%%x', allowing you to use a '%y%l%%%x' followed by text which would otherwise be seen as a substitution, e.g:  '%g%l%(@echo%) %%%%r%%%%l gives %%r%%lred%%x text.%x'

There are 6 different types of substitutions available on %@%n  -  These are as follows...

%r%l*  %c%lPronoun%x substitutions ('%g%l%<subst 3%>%x'.)
%y%l*  %c%lText %r%lc%g%lo%y%ll%b%lo%m%lu%c%lr%x and %c%lattribute%x substitutions ('%g%l%<subst 5%>%x'.)
%r%l*  %c%lText formatting%x substitutions ('%g%l%<subst 10%>%x'.)
%y%l*  %c%lHTML%x (World Wide Web) substitutions ('%g%l%<subst 11%>%x'.)
%r%l*  %c%lQuery command/calculation%x substitutions ('%g%l%<subst 15%>%x'.)
%y%l*  %c%lMiscellaneous%x substitutions ('%g%l%<subst 16%>%x'.)
%r%l*  %c%lVariable%x substitutions (See '%g%l%<variable subst%>%x'.)

Each type of substitution is explained in more detail on the following pages...

%PAGE

%c%l%$Pronoun substitutions...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
Pronoun substitutions return an appropriate pronoun in relation to the user involking the text, e.g:  '%g%l%(say%) %%S%x' will make you say "%y%lHe%x" to everyone in the same room as you, if you're male.  The returned pronoun can be either %c%labsolute%x (%g%l%%a%x), %c%lobjective%x (%g%l%%o%x), %c%lpossessive%x (%g%l%%p%x), %c%lsubjective%x (%g%l%%s%x) or %c%lreflexive%x (%g%l%%v%x), depending on the substitution used (See table on the next page.)


%c%l%$Examples:%c%l%[                      %]%$Output:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~                      ~~~~~~~%x
%[%g%l:looks at %%p watch.            %w%lFred Bloggs%w looks at his watch.
%g%l:thinks %%s's the greatest!     %w%lFred Bloggs%w thinks he's the greatest!
%g%l"%%a %%o %%p %%s %%v %%n             %w%lFred Bloggs%w says "%w%lHis him his he himself Fred
                                 Bloggs.%w"%]

%PAGE

%[%c%lSubstitution:  Pronoun:    Male:    Female:  Neuter:  Unset gender:
%c===================================================================
%g%l%%a             %w%lAbsolute    %y%lhis      hers     its      its
%g%l%%A             %w%lAbsolute    %y%lHis      Hers     Its      Its
%g%l%%o             %w%lObjective   %y%lhim      her      it       it
%g%l%%O             %w%lObjective   %y%lHim      Her      It       It
%g%l%%p             %w%lPossessive  %y%lhis      her      its      its
%g%l%%P             %w%lPossessive  %y%lHis      Her      Its      Its
%g%l%%s             %w%lSubjective  %y%lhe       she      it       it
%g%l%%S             %w%lSubjective  %y%lHe       She      It       It
%g%l%%v             %w%lReflexive   %y%lhimself  herself  itself   itself
%g%l%%V             %w%lReflexive   %y%lHimself  Herself  Itself   Itself
%c-------------------------------------------------------------------
%g%l%%n             %w%lSubstitutes character's name.
%c===================================================================%]
%c
%PAGE

%c%l%$Text colour and attribute substitutions...
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xSubstitutions can be used to change the %r%lc%g%lo%y%ll%b%lo%m%lu%c%lr%x of text (For users using an ANSI colour compatible terminal or a World Wide Web browser which supports font colour tags), %c%lembolden%x, %c%l%uunderline%x, %c%l%i%cinverse%x and make the text %c%l%fflash%x...

%[%c%lSubstitution:  Colour:          Substitution:  Colour:
%c=====================================================================
%g%l%%z             %wBlack            %g%l%%r             %r%lRed
%g%l%%g             %g%lGreen            %g%l%%y             %y%lYellow
%g%l%%b             %b%lBlue             %g%l%%m             %m%lMagenta
%g%l%%c             %c%lCyan             %g%l%%w             %w%lWhite
%g%l%%x             %wDefault colour
%c=====================================================================
%c%lExample:  %g%l%(say%) Here's some %%r%%lred%%x, %%g%%lgreen%%x and %%b%%lblue%%x text.%]
%c
%PAGE

%[%c%lSubstitution:  Effect:    Comments:
%c=============================================================================
%g%l%%l             %xLight      Hilights (Emboldens) text/%r%llight colour%x.
%g%l%%d             %wDark       %xNormal text/%rdark colour%x (Default.)
%g%l%%f             %x%fFlashing%x   Makes text flash (E.g:  '%g%l%(say%) %%fFlashing text%x'.)
%g%l%%u             %x%uUnderline%x  Underlines text (E.g:  '%g%l%(say%) %%uUnderlined text%x'.)
%g%l%%i             %x%iInverse%x    Inverses text  -  If followed by a colour code, the
                          inverse (Or text background if you like) will be
                          that colour, e.g:  '%c%l%%i%%g%x' gives a %w%l%i%ggreen background%x,
                          and '%c%l%%y%%l%%i%%r%x' gives %y%lbright yellow%x text on a %y%l%i%rred
                          background%x.
%c=============================================================================
%c%lExample:  %g%l%(say%) Here's some %%fflashing%%x and %%iinverse%%x text.%]
%c
%PAGE
%8%c%lNOTE:  %xYou don't need to put a '%y%l%%x%x' on the end of your text to ensure the colour of your screen returns to normal (White text on a black background) after using text colour or attribute substitutions, as this is done automatically.

%8%c%lHINT:  %xYou should put text attribute substitutions %c%lAFTER%x colour substitutions, because the colour substitutions will cancel out these effects, e.g:  '%y%l%%r%%l%x' for %r%llight red%x text, '%y%l%%w%%l%%f%x' for %fbright white flashing text%x, etc.
%PAGE

%c%l%$Examples...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~%x
%g%l%(@echo%) Normal colours:  %%zBlack%%x, %%rRed%%x, %%gGreen%%x, %%yYellow%%x, %%bBlue%%x, %%mMagenta%%x, %%cCyan%%x and %%wWhite%%x.

%(@echo%) Hilighted colours:  %%z%%lBlack%%x, %%r%%lRed%%x, %%g%%lGreen%%x, %%y%%lYellow%%x, %%b%%lBlue%%x, %%m%%lMagenta%%x, %%c%%lCyan%%x and %%w%%lWhite%%x.

%(@echo%) %%y%%l%%f%%i%%r!!! WARNING !!!
%PAGE

%c%l%$Text formatting substitutions...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
Text formatting substitutions allow you to set a hanging indent on a single line, so that if that line is longer than the screen width, it will be indented correctly when it's wrapped to the left hand side of the screen on the next line down.  To increment the hanging indent for a single line, you should use the '%y%l%%1%x' - '%y%l%%9%x' substitutions at the %c%lBEGINNING%x of the line, which increment the hanging indent by the given number (E.g:  '%y%l%%1%x' will increment the hanging indent by %c%l1%x, '%y%l%%2%x' by %c%l2%x, etc.)  '%y%l%%0%x' resets the hanging indent back to the far left hand side of the screen.

%9%6%c%lPLEASE NOTE:  %xTo increment the hanging indent by more than 9, you will need to use %c%lTWO%x or more substitutions added together, as only values of %y%l1%x to %y%l9%x can be used.
%PAGE

%[%c%lSubstitution:  Effect:
%c==============================================================================
%g%l%%1 %c- %g%l%%9        %xIncrements hanging indent by the given number.
%g%l%%0             %xResets hanging indent back to the far left hand side of screen.
%c------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%g%l%%#NF#          %xPrevents the following text from being subject to automatic
               formatting and punctuation.
%g%l%%$             %xMarks the following text (Up to next colour change or '%c%l%%x%x') as
               a title/heading, which will be underlined if the user's
               '%g%l%(set underline%)%x' preference is '%y%lon%x'.
%g%l%%~             %xMarks rest of line as a '%c~~~~~%x' or similar-style underline,
               which will %c%lNOT%x be displayed if user's '%g%l%(set underline%)%x'
               preference is '%y%lon%x' (Used in conjunction with '%c%l%%$%x'.)
%c==============================================================================%]
%c
%PAGE

%c%l%$HTML (World Wide Web) substitutions...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
%y%l%@%n World Wide Web Interface%x allows users to connect through a standard World Wide Web browser (Such as %c%lNetscape Navigator%x or %c%lMicrosoft Internet Explorer%x)  -  See '%g%l%<html%>%x' for further details.  Several substitutions are provided to support the use of the HTML language within %@%m.


%c%l%$The '%w%l%$%%h%c%l%$' substitution
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xThe '%y%l%%h%x' substitution toggles the evaluation of HTML tags.  By default, HTML tags are ignored by %@%m and will be relayed to your browser just as though they were ordinary text.

%PAGE
However, by using the '%y%l%%h%x' substitution, you can turn evaluation of HTML tags on, allowing you to use HTML tags in %c%lyour description%x, %c%lroom descriptions%x, etc.  For example, '%g%l%(@echo%) %%h<FONT SIZE=6>Some big text</FONT>%%h%x'.  The first use of '%y%l%%h%x' in a description, etc. will turn evaluation of HTML on, the second will turn it off again, the 3rd on, etc.  After the description has been displayed, evaluation of HTML is automatically turned off again (If it's turned on.)

To prevent abuse (I.e:  Spamming large pictures, JAVA code, etc.) the '%y%l%%h%x' substitution will have no effect when used in communication commands (I.e:  '%g%l%(say%)%x', '%g%l%(tell%)%x', etc.  -  See '%g%l%<communicating%>%x') in areas you do not own or have '%c%lwrite%x' permission to.

%PAGE

%c%l%$The '%w%l%$%%|%c%l%$' and '%w%l%$%%^%c%l%$' substitutions
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xThe '%y%l%%|%x' substitution filters out all text between it and the next '%y%l%%|%x' substitution, if the user is connected through %c%lTelnet%x.  Similarly, the '%y%l%%^%x' substitution filters out all text between it and the next '%y%l%%^%x', if the user is connected through the %c%lWorld Wide Web Interface%x.  These substitutions can be used to provide different descriptions or filter out text/HTML tags depending on whether the user is using %c%lTelnet%x or a %c%lWorld Wide Web browser%x, i.e:

   %4%g%l%%|%%h<CENTER><IMG SRC="http://www.wibble.com/mypic.jpg"><P>This is what I look like IRL!</CENTER>%%h%%|%%^This is a description of what I look like, for those of you using a text-only Telnet connection.%%^%x

If you used the above example for your description, the user would see a picture of you (Providing you gave a valid URL for it) if they were using a %c%lWorld Wide Web browser%x.  Otherwise, they would see a text description of what you look like (Providing you write it.)

%PAGE

%c%l%$The '%w%l%$%%[%c%l%$' and '%w%l%$%%]%c%l%$' substitutions
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xThe above two substitutions are effectively aliases for the '%y%l<PRE>%x' and '%y%l</PRE>%x' HTML tags respectively.  Because web browsers do not use a %c%lfixed width font%x by default, 'ASCII art', descriptions, compound commands, etc. which rely on the fixed width font of %c%lTelnet software%x will look extremely messy.  There is a solution however:  By enclosing the text within a '%y%l%%[%x' and '%y%l%%]%x' substitution, it will be rendered in a fixed width font.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Query command/calculation substitutions...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l%%{%(@calc%) <CALCULATION>}
        %%{%(@eval%) <CALCULATION>}
        %%{<QUERY COMMAND>}%]%x

The above substitutions can be used to substitute the result of a calculation performed with the '%g%l%(@calc%)%x'/'%g%l%(@eval%)%x' command (E.g:  '%g%l%%{%(@eval%) 2 + 2}%x'), or substitute the return result of a standard query command (E.g:  '%g%l%%{%(@?race%)}%x'.)


%c%l%$Example:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~%x
%g%l%(@thing%) clock = Looking at the clock, you see the time is %\{%(@?realtime%)}.

%xThe clock will always display the correct time in its description when you look at it ('%g%l%(look%) clock%x'.)

