%TOPIC substitutingtemporaryvariables
%TITLE Help on %w%lsubstituting temporary variables/properties/variables/dynamic arrays%x
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l$[#<LOCATION>:]<VARIABLE NAME>
        $([#<LOCATION>:]<VARIABLE NAME>)
        {$[#<LOCATION>:]<VARIABLE NAME>}%]%x

Variable substitution can be used to substitute the description of a %c%l%(temporary variable%)%x (See '%g%l%<@temp%>%x')/%c%l%(property%)%x (See '%g%l%<@property%>%x')/%c%l%(variable%)%x (See '%g%l%<@variable%>%x') or element of a %c%l%(dynamic array%)%x (See '%g%l%<@array%>%x') in a compound command.

The first two forms of variable substitution ('%y%l$[#<LOCATION>:]<VARIABLE NAME>%x' and '%y%l$([#<LOCATION>:]<VARIABLE NAME>)%x') can only be used within compound commands.  The third ('%y%l{$[#<LOCATION>:]<VARIABLE NAME>}%x') can also be used on the command line as well as in compound commands.

%PAGE
In the simplest form, a temporary variable can be substituted using '%y%l$<VARIABLE NAME>%x' (E.g:  '%g%l%(@echo%) $mytemp%x').  A property/variable can be substituted using '%y%l$(#<LOCATION>:<VARIABLE NAME>)%x', where '%y%l#<LOCATION>%x' is the #ID number of the property/variable's current location (E.g:  '%g%l%(@echo%) $(#12345:myproperty)%x') and a dynamic array element can be substituted using '%y%l$(#<LOCATION>:<ARRAY NAME>[<ELEMENT>])%x' (E.g:  '%g%l%(@echo%) $(#12345:myarray[1])%x'.)

A '%y%l$()%x' substitution can be used to substitute a property/variable/array which has spaces in its name (E.g:  '%g%l%(@echo%) $(#12345:my property)%x'.  It's also useful in the following case:  '%g%l%(@echo%) $sentence.%x' (Where '%y%l$sentence%x' is a temporary variable containing a sentence of text.)  -  This substitution wont work, because '%y%l.%x' is a valid character for use in a variable substitution, so %@%m tries to find and substitute a temporary variable/property/variable/array with the name '%y%lsentence.%x'  You can get around this by using '%g%l%(@echo%) $(sentence).%x'  -  Only the text in the '%y%l()%x's is taken as the name.

%PAGE
Nested substitutions are possible using '%y%l{$[#<LOCATION>:]<VARIABLE NAME>}%x', e.g:  '%g%l%(@echo%) $(#12345:myarray[{$element}])%x' (Where '%y%l$element%x' is a temporary variable holding the element number to substitute.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<substitutions%>%x', '%g%l%<@variable%>%x', '%g%l%<@property%>%x', '%g%l%<@array%>%x', '%g%l%<@temp%>%x', '%g%l%<@command%>%x' and '%g%l%<advanced%>%x'.

