%TOPIC match
%TOPIC matching
%TOPIC hierarchy
%TOPIC objectmatching
%TOPIC hierarchicalmatching
%TITLE Hierarchical Object Matching
Understanding how hierarchical object matching works on %@%m is an important part of coding compound commands.  It is also important for the usage of many built-in (Hard-coded) commands.)

Nearly all built-in (Hard-coded) compound commands use hierarchical object matching in one form or another.  The following pages detail the various methods of matching supported by %@%m...

%9%3%y%l%$me%x%|%h<HR>%h%|         Matches to yourself.

%[           %c%lE.g:  %g%l%(@set%) me = %(haven%)%]%x

%9%3%y%l%$here%x%|%h<HR>%h%|       Matches to your current location.

%[           %c%lE.g:  %g%l%(examine%) here%]%x

%PAGE

%9%3%y%l%$[!]<NAME>%x%|%h<HR>%h%|  Matches by object name.  Your possessions are searched first, followed by your current location.  Compound commands are also searched up the area tree of your current location and within the global compound commands location.

           For characters and things, matching is %c%lpartial%x (I.e:  Any part of the object's name.)  For most other object types, matching is %c%lexact%x.

%[           %c%lE.g:  %g%l%(look%) at cupboard
                 %(take%) key
                 %(open%) door%]%x

           Sometimes, partial matching of an object name can be a nuisance (I.e:  When there are two objects with similar names.)  You can force an exact match by preceeding the name with '%y%l!%x', e.g:

%PAGE

%[              %y%l%$Contents:
              %~%y~~~~~~~~~
              %xObject2(#12345 Tq)
              Object(#54321 Tq)%]

           In the above example, typing '%g%l%(ex%) object%x', '%g%l%(ex%) obj%x', etc.  will match to '%y%lObject2%x', because it's first in the %y%l%$Contents:%x list.  This makes it difficult to refer to '%y%lObject%x' without knowing and using it's #ID.  Typing '%g%l%(ex%) !object%x' solves this problem by forcing an exact match to the name '%y%lobject%x'.

%9%3%y%l%$*<NAME>%x%|%h<HR>%h%|    Matches exactly to the character name specified, regardless of their current location or whether they are currently connected or not.

%[           %c%lE.g:  %g%l%(look%) at *fred bloggs%]%x

%PAGE

%9%3%y%l%$#<ID>%x%|%h<HR>%h%|      Matches directly to the object with the specified %y%l#<ID>%x number.  This is the fastest method of matching.

%[           %c%lE.g:  %g%l%(@tel%) me = #12345%]%x

%c%l%8NOTE:%x  Within a compound command, all of the above are relative to the user executing the compound command.  For example, '%y%lme%x' refers to the user executing the compound command, '%y%lhere%x' refers to their current location, etc.

%PAGE

%c%l%$The following are functional only from within a compound command:
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%x
%9%1%y%l%$myself%x%|%h<HR>%h%|   Matches to the compound command currently executing (Same functionality as '%g%l{%(@?myself%)}%x' (See '%g%l%<@?myself%>%x'), but easier to use and more efficient.)

%[         %c%lE.g:  %g%l%(@echo%) {%(@?drop%) myself}
               %(@drop%) myself = 1%]%x

%9%1%y%l%$myleaf%x%|%h<HR>%h%|   Matches to effective location of the compound command currently executing (Same functionality as '%g%l{%(@?myleaf%)}%x' with no parameters.)

         See '%g%l%<@?myleaf%>%x' for details of how '%g%l{%(@?myleaf%)}%x' works.

%[         %c%lE.g:  %g%l%(@echo%) You shoot the {%(@?name%) myleaf} - BANG!%]%x

For details on the order of matching, please see '%g%l%<matching order%>%x'

%PAGE

%c%l%$Character Matching
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xFor ease of use and effeciency, most internal commands (Hard-coded) which can %m%lONLY%x be used on characters ('%g%l%(scan%)%x', '%g%l%(page%)%x', '%g%l%(tell%)%x', etc.) use a cut-down matching system.  This is as follows:

%9%1%y%l%$me%x%|%h<HR>%h%|       Matches to yourself.

%[         %c%lE.g:  %g%l%(scan%) me%]%x

%9%1%y%l%$<NAME>%x%|%h<HR>%h%|   Matches by character name.  Names of connected characters are matched first, followed by names of those who are not connected.  Matching is to the closest character name, taking name prefix/suffix into account.

%[         %c%lE.g:  %g%l%(page%) fred bloggs = hello%]%x

%PAGE

%9%1%y%l%$*<NAME>%x%|%h<HR>%h%|  Matches exactly to character name specified.

%[         %c%lE.g:  %g%l%(look%) at *fred bloggs%]%x

%9%1%y%l%$#<ID>%x%|%h<HR>%h%|    Matches directly to the character with the specified %y%l#<ID>%x number.  This is the fastest method of matching.  %c%lNOTE:%x  You need read permission to a character to refer to them by %y%l#<ID>%x.

%[         %c%lE.g:  %g%l%(examine%) #1%]%x

%c%l%8NOTE:%x  Character matching does not support (Or need to support) %c%ltype matching%x or %c%lmultiple matching%x.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Type Matching
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@<TYPE>[;<TYPE>][...]:<MATCH>%]%x

Matching can be restricted to a particular object type (Or particular object types) only by using the above matching format.  To restrict a match to a particular type of object, simply prefix the match with '%y%l@%x' followed by the object type, e.g:  '%y%l@things:mything%x', '%y%l@properties:me:myobject%x', '%y%l@things;commands:myobject%x', etc.

%y%l<TYPE>%x is the object type, which can be one or more of the following:

   %4%y%lAlarms%x, %y%lArrays%x, %y%lCharacters%x, %y%lCommands%x, %y%lExits%x, %y%lFuses%x, %y%lPlayers%x (Same as %y%lCharacters%x), %y%lProperties%x, %y%lRooms%x, %y%lThings%x, %y%lVariables%x.

%PAGE
Type matching is especially useful for preventing matching conflicts between objects of different types with the same name.  For example, if you had a thing and compound command both called '%y%lTest%x', typing '%g%l%(ex%) test%x' will always match to the thing.  Typing '%g%l%(@desc%) test = @echo Hello%x' would change the description of the thing rather than the compound command.

Rather than directly refering to the compound command by it's #ID, you can get around this problem by using '%y%l@command:test%x' to match against compound commands only.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Multiple Matching
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%c%lFORMAT:  %g%l<LOCATION>:<OBJECT NAME>[:<OBJECT NAME>][...]%]%x

The above format is used for multiple matching.  This allows you to refer to an object located within another object, or several objects located within each other in a hierarchical manner.

For example, '%y%l#12345:mycontainer:mything%x' searches the location %y%l#12345%x for the object '%y%lmycontainer%x'.  '%y%lMyContainer%x' is then searched for the object '%y%lmything%x'.

%PAGE
This method of matching is especially useful for refering to variables, properties and dynamic arrays attached to objects, e.g:

%[   %g%l%(@echo%) {%(@?desc%) #12345:myarray[1]}
   %g%l%(@echo%) {%(@?desc%) me:myproperty}
   %g%l%(@echo%) {%(@?desc%) #54321:mything:myvariable}%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<matching order%>%x', '%g%l%<@?match%>%x', '%g%l%<@?myself%>%x', '%g%l%<@?myleaf%>%x' and '%g%l%<advanced%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC order
%TOPIC matchorder
%TOPIC matchingorder
%TOPIC hierarchyorder
%TOPIC hierarchicalorder
%TOPIC objectmatchingorder
%TOPIC hierarchicalmatchingorder
%TITLE Hierarchical Object Matching Order
Hierarchical matching within %@%m is organised into five distinct phases.  Within each of these phases, objects are matched in the order detailed on the following pages:


%9%2%m%l%$Phase 0:%x  %y%lKeywords and direct reference:

          %[%g%lme       %xYourself.
          %g%lhere     %xYour current location.
          %g%lmyself   %xCommand command currently being executed.
          %g%lmyleaf   %xEffective location of current executing compound command.
          %g%l#ID      %xObject or character by #ID number.
          %g%l*<NAME>  %xCharacter by full or real name.%]

%PAGE

%9%2%m%l%$Phase 1:%x  %y%lObjects which you are currently carrying (In your inventory):

          %[%c%l%$Object type:%x       %c%l%$Object types matched within object:
          %~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~       ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
          %g%lCharacter          %xNone.
          %g%lThing              %xCharacters, Things, Compound Commands.
          %g%lExit               %xCompound Commands.
          %g%lCompound Command   %xCompound Commands.
          %g%lVariable           %xVariables, Properties, Dynamic Arrays.
          %g%lProperty           %xVariables, Properties, Dynamic Arrays.
          %g%lDynamic Array      %xVariables, Properties, Dynamic Arrays.
          %g%lFuse               %xNone.
          %g%lAlarm              %xNone.
          %g%lRoom               %xNone.%]

%PAGE

%9%2%m%l%$Phase 2:%x  %y%lObjects which are within your current location:

          %[%c%l%$Object type:%x       %c%l%$Object types matched within object:
          %~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~       ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
          %g%lCharacter          %xNone.
          %g%lThing              %xCharacters, Things, Compound Commands.
          %g%lExit               %xCompound Commands.
          %g%lCompound Command   %xCompound Commands.%]

%PAGE

%9%2%m%l%$Phase 3:%x  %y%lCompound Commands further up the area of your current location for example:

             %[%g%lTown Top Area
              %g|
              `- %g%lThe Town Centre
                  %g|
                  `- %g%lThe Swan Pub%]

          %9%2%xIf you are in '%y%lThe Swan Pub%x', compound commands within locations further up the area ('%y%lThe Town Centre%x', followed by '%y%lTown Top Area%x') will be matched.

          %9%9%c%lHINT:%x  For an overview of the area of your current location, try typing '%g%l%(@echo%) {%(@?address%)}%x' (See '%g%l%<@?address%>%x'.)

%PAGE

%9%2%m%l%$Phase 4:%x  %y%lGlobal compound commands within the global compound commands location.  Compound commands can only be made global by %w%lApprentice Wizards/Druids%y%l and above.


%8%c%lNOTE:  %xWithin a compound command, all references to yourself refer to the character executing the compound command.

In most cases where hierarchical matching is used, a particular object type is given priority.  This object type will be matched individually using the above matching order.  The remaining object types will then be matched together in the above order.

In most cases, %c%lthings%x are given priority.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<matching%>%x', '%g%l%<@?match%>%x', '%g%l%<@?myself>%x', '%g%l%<@?myleaf%>%x' and '%g%l%<advanced%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @par
%TOPIC @parent
%TOPIC inheriting
%TOPIC inheritance
%TOPIC parentobjects
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@parent%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@parent <OBJECT> [= <PARENT>]%]%x

If %y%l<PARENT>%x is specified, the parent object of %y%l<OBJECT>%x is set to the object %y%l<PARENT>%x, providing %y%l<OBJECT>%x is the same type as %y%l<PARENT>%x.  If %y%l<PARENT>%x isn't specified, %y%l<OBJECT>%x's parent object is reset.

Objects may only have one parent, but you can create chains of parent objects (Providing they don't create an endless loop (Which %@%m doesn't allow)), e.g:  '%g%l@parent object1 = object2%x', '%g%l@parent object2 = object3%x'  -  If %c%lobject1%x's description isn't set, it will be inherited from %c%lobject2%x, but if %c%lobject2%x also doesn't have a description, %c%lobject1%x's description will be inherited from %c%lobject3%x.

Fields on the object (Description, (o)success, (o)failure, (o)drop, areaname, contents string, etc.) are inherited from the parent object when they aren't set (E.g:  If the object has no description, it will be inherited from the parent object.)

%PAGE
If the object isn't locked, its lock will be inherited from the parent object (If you don't want the object locked, but want the parent object locked, simply do '%g%l%(@lock%) object = me|!me%x' (This will have the same effect as not locking the object and will prevent the lock from being inherited.))  The lock key of a thing is inherited in the same way.

The object's volume and/or mass may be inherited from the parent object by setting them to %y%lINHERIT%x (E.g:  '%g%l%(@volume%) <OBJECT> = inherit%x' (See '%g%l%<@volume%>%x') and '%g%l%(@mass%) <OBJECT> = inherit%x' (See '%g%l%<@mass%>%x'.))

Object lists of the object's parent object are inherited, so objects in the contents list of the parent object will also appear in the contents list of the object's children, etc.  All object lists are inherited, including compound commands, exits, fuses, etc.

%PAGE
%9%6%c%lPLEASE NOTE:  %xObject lists are inherited regardless of whether the object's various lists are empty or not.  For example, the object's commands list could contain compound commands actually attached to the object as well as compound commands inherited from the parent object.  Type '%g%l%(examine%) <OBJECT>%x' to find out what's been inherited and from where.

If a character is given a parent, the aliases of their parent will be inherited.  This works in the same way as object lists, so the character will not only have their own aliases, but also the aliases of their parent.  Aliases of the parent character can't be modified or removed by the child.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@duplicate%>%x', '%g%l%<examine%>%x', '%g%l%<@volume%>%x', '%g%l%<@mass%>%x', '%g%l%<@?parent%>%x', '%g%l%<@?myleaf%>%x', '%g%l%<inheritable flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<advanced%>%x'.

