%TITLE Help on '%w%l@partner%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@partner [engage|marry|divorce] <NAME1> [= <NAME2>]%]%x

This command can only be used by %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above.

It allows two characters to be first engaged to each other, then subsequently married.  It also allows engaged or married couples to be divorced.

The first step is to propose to your partner, after which (If successful), you can ask a member of Admin to link you both as engaged.  They can do this by typing '%g%l@partner engage <NAME1> = <NAME2>%x', where one name is yours, and the other is your partner.

The next step is marriage.  You can ask a member of Admin to marry you and your partner (A wedding ceremony will usually be held.)  They can do this by typing '%g%l@partner marry <NAME1> = <NAME2>%x'.

%PAGE
If you no-longer wish to be engaged to your partner, or your marriage doesn't go quite as planned, you can ask a member of Admin to divorce you and your partner.  They can do this by typing '%g%l@partner divorce <NAME>%x', where %y%l<NAME>%x is either your name, or your partners (It doesn't matter which.)

Once married, '%y%lMr%x'/'%y%lMrs%x' (Appropriately) will be added to your name prefixes (Unless either you or your partner's gender is neuter.)  Engaged/married characters appear in the '%y%l%$Contents:%x' list of their location with '%c%l(Engaged)%x' or '%c%l(Married)%x' after their name.  The character who they are engaged/married to is also shown to users who '%g%l%(scan%)%x' them (See '%g%l%<scan%>%x'.)


%c%l%$Examples:
%~%c~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l@partner engage fred bloggs = joanne bloggs
@partner marry fred bloggs = joanne bloggs
@partner divorce fred bloggs%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?partner%>%x' and '%g%l%<scan%>%x'.

