%TOPIC interactiveprompting
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@prompt%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@prompt <PROMPT> = <PROCESS CMD> = <SUCC CMD> [= <ABORT CMD>]%]%x

Starts an 'interactive' prompt session.  Basically, the user will be presented with the prompt %y%l<PROMPT>%x.  When they type something and press %c%lRETURN%x, the compound command %y%l<PROCESS CMD>%x will be executed, with what the user typed as its parameters.

If %y%l<PROCESS CMD>%x fails (E.g:  '%g%l%(@return%) false%x'  -  See '%g%l%<@return%>%x'), the user will again be presented with %y%l<PROMPT>%x, and the process repeated.  However, if %y%l<PROCESS CMD>%x succeeds, the compound command %y%l<SUCC CMD>%x will be executed, and the interactive '%g%l@prompt%x' session will end.

If the user types '%g%lABORT%x' during an interactive '%g%l@prompt%x' session, it will be aborted, and the compound command %y%l<ABORT CMD>%x will be executed (If specified.)

%PAGE
During an interactive '%g%l@prompt%x' session, the user may still use the On-Line Help System in the usual way, and can execute %@%m commands by typing '%g%l.<COMMAND>%x' (In a similar way to that used in '%g%l%(converse%)%x' mode (See '%g%l%<converse%>%x')), e.g:  '%g%l.%(tell%) <NAME> [=] <MESSAGE>%x'.

Some example uses of '%g%l@prompt%x' are:  %c%lMenu systems, interactive tutorials/questionaires, etc.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@command%>%x', '%g%l%<@return%>%x', '%g%l%<converse%>%x', '%g%l%<set prompt%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?prompt%>%x'.

