%TOPIC creatingproperties
%TOPIC buildingproperties
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@property%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@property <NAME> [= <INITIAL SETTING>]%]%x

Creates a property called %y%l<NAME>%x attached to yourself (Building Quota used:  %c%l1%x.)  If %y%l<INITIAL SETTING>%x is specified, the description of the property is set to that.

Properties only have a description (Rather than all 8 standard fields), saving DB space and memory.  Because of this, properties use less Building Quota than variables.

You can attach a property to almost any other object (As long as you own/control it) by using '%g%l%(drop%)%x' or '%g%l%(@tel%)%x'.  You can even drop properties within properties.

%PAGE
When a property is on yourself, you can substitute it into any text you're typing by typing '%y%l$%x' followed by the name of the property (E.g:  '%g%l$myprop%x' would substitute the description of the property '%y%lMyprop%x'.)

To reference properties attached to anything else other than yourself, you must use '%y%l#<ID>:<PROPERTY NAME>%x', e.g:  If I had a property called '%y%lstore%x' attached to a thing called '%y%lCabinet%x' with the ID %y%l#12345%x, I could reference that property using '%g%l#12345:store%x', e.g:  To set the property's description, I'd type '%g%l@desc #12345:store = <DESCRIPTION>%x'.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@variable%>%x', '%g%l%<variable subst%>%x', '%g%l%<@tel%>%x', '%g%l%<drop%>%x', '%g%l%<@desc%>%x' and '%g%l%<building%>%x'.

