%TOPIC @request
%TOPIC newbierequests
%TOPIC @requestrefuse
%TOPIC @requestlisting
%TOPIC @requestrefusing
%TOPIC @requestaccepting
%TOPIC @requestnewrequest
%TOPIC @requestcancelling
%TOPIC @requestcancellation
%TOPIC newcharacterrequests
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@request%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@request list [<PAGE NO>] [<EMAIL ADDRESS>] [= <NAME>|all]
        @request refuse <NUMBER> = <REASON>
        @request accept <NUMBER> = <NAME>
        @request cancel <NUMBER>
        @request <NUMBER>
        @request new%]%x

This command can only be used by %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above.

The '%g%l@request%x' command is used to process requests for new characters from Internet sites which have been banned from creating new characters.

When a user attempts to create a character from an Internet site which has been banned from creating new characters, they will be asked if they wish to make a request for a character.  If they choose to do so, they will be asked for their E-mail address, which will be added to the end of the queue of requests for new characters.

%PAGE
To deal with these requests, simply type '%g%l@request new%x'.  This will take a request off the queue (Which hasn't been dealt with yet) and allocate it to you.  On typing '%g%l@request new%x', you will also be warned of any possible existing characters in the database with similar E-mail addresses to the E-mail address of the person making the request.  You will also be given a reference number for the request, which you will need to deal with the request (If you forget this, simply type '%g%l@request list%x' to list the requests you're currently dealing with.)

If other characters with similar E-mail addresses exist, please check these out and then E-mail the person who requested the new character, to determine whether they are trying to obtain duplicate characters or get around a ban placed on their usual character (Which is not allowed), i.e:

%PAGE
   %4%m%lHello, I am %{@?name}, an administrator from %@%n, responding to your request for a new character.  It appears you already have a character (Duplicate characters are not permitted), can you please explain why you are requesting another/new character?%x

If the request appears authentic and genuine, or a reasonable explaination is received from the user (After sending the above E-mail), you should then send an E-mail to the user, asking them which character name(s) they would like for their new character, i.e:

   %4%m%lHello, I am %{@?name}, an administrator from %@%n, responding to your request for a new character.  Your request for a new character has been accepted.  Can you please E-mail me a list of the names you would like for your new character (In order of preference)?%x

On receiving a list of suitable names, you can then create a character for them.  Please reject potentially offensive or abusive names.  If all of the names given by the user are already in use, offensive or invalid, please E-mail the user, requesting alternative names.

%PAGE
Use '%g%l%(@character%)%x' (See '%g%l%<@character%>%x') to create the character, assigning a random (%c%lLowercase%x) password to them (Approximately 8 characters in length), i.e:  '%g%l%(@character%) fred bloggs = djfcntvx%x'.  Once the new character is created, set their private E-mail address to the correct E-mail address of the user, using '%g%l%(@email%)%x' (See '%g%l%<@email%>%x'), i.e:  '%g%l%(@email%) fred bloggs = private fbloggs@wibble.wobble.com%x'.

You can now E-mail the details of their new character, i.e:

   %4%m%lHello, I am %{@?name}, an administrator from %@%n, responding to your request for a new character.  I have created a new character for you (You may like to set a more suitable password for them by typing %(@PASSWORD%) on %@%m):

   Name:  Fred Bloggs
   Password:  djfcntvx%x

%PAGE
Having successfully dealt with the request for the new character, you can now take them off the request queue, using the '%g%l@request accept <NUMBER> = <NAME>%x' command, where %y%l<NUMBER>%x is the reference number of the request (Type '%g%l@request list%x' if you can't remember this) and %y%l<NAME>%x is the full name or #ID number of the new character you created for them, i.e:  '%g%l@request accept 12345 = fred bloggs%x'.

If you need to refuse a request (I.e:  The user making the request already has a character, or the E-mail address they gave is invalid), simply type '%g%l@request refuse <NUMBER> = <REASON>%x', i.e:  '%g%l@request refuse 12345 = This person already has a character on %@%m called Joe Bloggs%x'.  Please make sure you E-mail the user and explain why their request for a new character has been refused.

%PAGE
You can deal with more than one request at a time.  Simply type '%g%l@request new%x' until you have sufficient requests to deal with.  You can then list the requests you're currently dealing with by typing '%g%l@request list%x' (You will need to do this to obtain the reference numbers of the requests.)  If you are dealing with a lot of requests, the list may span several pages.  Simply type '%g%l@request list 2%x' to view the second page, '%g%l@request list 3%x' to view the third, etc.  You can view the E-mail address of an individual request, and check for existing characters with similar E-mail addresses by typing '%g%l@request <NUMBER>%x', where %y%l<NUMBER>%x is the reference number of the request.

Please do not take on an excessive number of requests, or more requests than you can deal with effeciently  -  Please share requests with other administrators.

%PAGE
The second parameter of the '%g%l@request list%x' command can be used to list all requests (Including requests which haven't been dealt with yet), e.g:  '%g%l@request list = all%x'.  It can also be used to list requests currently being dealt with by a particular administrator, e.g:  '%g%l@request list = jc digita%x'.

The '%g%l@request cancel%x' command can be used to cancel a request which you have taken on and no-longer wish to deal with (Or are unable to do so.)  The request will be placed back on the queue for another administrator to deal with.  E.g:  '%g%l@request cancel 12345%x'.

Accepted/refused new character requests are logged to the '%c%lRequest%x' log file for future reference (See '%g%l%<@log%>%x'.)

%c%lNOTE:  %xNew character requests expire after %y%l28 days%x.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@character%>%x', '%g%l%<@email%>%x', '%g%l%<@site%>%x' and '%g%l%<@log%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @return
%TOPIC @returnstatement
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@return%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@return [true|false|current]%]%x

'%g%l@return%x' stops execution of the current compound command and skips to the end.  Unlike '%g%l%(@break%)%x', neither the csuccess or cfailure of the compound command is executed, and the success/failure messages of the compound command are not displayed  -  The compound command will just finish at that point, failing if '%y%lfalse%x' is specified, succeeding if '%y%ltrue%x' or no parameter is specified or leaving the return result unchanged if '%y%lcurrent%x' is specified.

%8%c%lNOTE:  %x'%g%l@return%x' does not change the return value from the previous executed command.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Example compound command:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@command%) ReturnTest =\
%(@if%) \{%(@eval%) "$3" = ""} do\
    %(@echo%) Please specify a parameter.\
    @return\
%(@end%)\
%(rem%) The rest of this command will only be executed if a parameter is given.\
%(@echo%) You specified '%%w%%l$3%%x'.%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@break%>%x', '%g%l%<@skip%>%x', '%g%l%<@breakloop%>%x', '%g%l%<@if%>%x', '%g%l%<@case%>%x', '%g%l%<@for%>%x', '%g%l%<@with%>%x', '%g%l%<@while%>%x', '%g%l%<@foreach%>%x' and '%g%l%<@goto%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC functions
%TOPIC @returnvalue
%TOPIC returnresults
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@returnvalue%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@returnvalue <RETURN VALUE>%]%x

The '%g%l@returnvalue%x' command allows you to write compound commands which return a user-defined value or string instead of the usual '%c%lOK%x' or '%c%lError%x' return strings (Allowing you to use them as '%y%lfunctions%x'.)

'%g%l@returnvalue%x' sets the return value of the current compound command, e.g:

If you had a compound command called '%g%lmultiply%x', with its description set to:

%g%l@returnvalue {@eval $1 * 100}

%PAGE
...You could then type '%g%l%(@echo%) {multiply 10}%x' (This would display %c%l1000%x on your screen.)  The '%g%lmultiply%x' compound command multiplies the parameter given to it by 100 and then returns the resulting number.  In this case, the resulting number is echoed to your screen using the '%g%l%(@echo%)%x' (See '%g%l%<@echo%>%x') command.

The reserved variable %y%l$0%x can also be used to reference the return result of the compound command.  For example, you could put the following in another compound command to achieve the same result:

%[%g%lmultiply 10
@echo $0%]

%8%c%lNOTE:  %x'%g%l@returnvalue%x' does not change the return result (Success/failure) from the previous executed command.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@command%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @destall
%TOPIC @destroyall
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@destall%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@destall <NAME> = yes = <REASON>%]%x

This command can only be used by %c%lWizards/%cDruids%x and above.

'%g%l@destall%x' destroys %c%lALL%x objects owned by the character %y%l<NAME>%x, who must be a Mortal, Builder or %b%lMoron%x and set %y%l%(ASHCAN%)%x.

The main use of '%g%l@destall%x' is to destroy all of the objects owned by a character who was set %y%l%(ASHCAN%)%x by character maintenance, and it should %r%l%fNEVER%x be used without first checking what objects the character owns (They could own public locations.)

%9%6%c%lPLEASE NOTE:  %xObjects destroyed by '%g%l@destall%x' are destroyed %r%l%fPERMANENTLY%x and can't be recovered with the '%g%l%(@undestroy%)%x' command.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@destroy%>%x', '%g%l%<@undestroy%>%x', '%g%l%<@expiry%>%x' and '%g%l%<@maintenance%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @dest
%TOPIC @purge
%TOPIC @destroy
%TOPIC @recycle
%TOPIC recyclingthings
%TOPIC destroyingthings
%TOPIC destroyingobjects
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@destroy%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@destroy <OBJECT> [= yes|permanent]
        @destroy <ARRAY>[<ELEMENT>]
        @purge <OBJECT> [= yes]%]%x

This command destroys (Deletes) the specified %y%l<OBJECT>%x providing you own it, or are of a higher level than its owner, e.g:  '%g%l@destroy mything%x' will destroy the object '%y%lmything%x'.  '%g%l@destroy <OBJECT> = yes%x' must be typed to destroy an object which you do not own.

When you destroy an object, the amount of Building Quota (See '%g%l%<quota%>%x') used by it will be reimbursed to you.

You should destroy objects which are useless, no-longer needed or unwanted, as this will reimbursed the Building Quota used for you to use on something else, free up space in the database and also helps to reduce its size, rate of expansion and the overall total amount of junk/useless objects in it.

%PAGE
If you accidentally destroy an object (Or the wrong object), you can recover the destroyed object by using the '%g%l%(@undestroy%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<@undestroy%>%x'.)

However, if a compound command of yours creates and destroys objects on a temporary basis (I.e:  Properties, variables or dynamic arrays), regular usage would result in the destroyed object queue (Which is a fixed size) becoming 'flooded' with objects which will never need to be recovered.

For this reason, the '%g%l@purge <OBJECT>%x' or '%g%l@destroy <OBJECT> = permanent%x' commands are provided to destroy an object permanently without placing it on the queue.  However, the object must be yours, or owned by the owner of the compound command the '%g%l@purge%x' command is used within (Otherwise, the object will still be placed on the queue.)

%PAGE
'%g%l@destroy%x' can also be used to destroy elements of a dynamic array (See '%g%l%<@array%>%x'), e.g:  '%g%l@destroy myarray[2]%x' will destroy the %c%l2nd%x element of the dynamic array '%y%lmyarray%x' and '%g%l@destroy myarray[test]%x' will destroy the element with the index name '%y%ltest%x' of '%y%lmyarray%x'.

A range of elements can be destroyed all in one go, e.g:  '%g%l@destroy myarray[4..7]%x' will destroy elements %c%l4%x, %c%l5%x, %c%l6%x and %c%l7%x.  When you destroy element(s) of a dynamic array, they are removed from the array altogether.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@undestroy%>%x', '%g%l%<@expiry%>%x', '%g%l%<quota%>%x' and '%g%l%<@destall%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @dig
%TOPIC rooms
%TOPIC @room
%TOPIC diggingrooms
%TOPIC buildingrooms
%TOPIC creatingrooms
%TUTORIAL
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@room%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@room <NAME> [= <DESCRIPTION>]
        @dig <NAME> [= <DESCRIPTION>]%]%x

Creates a new room with the name %y%l<NAME>%x (Building Quota used:  %c%l10%x.)  If %y%l<DESCRIPTION>%x is specified, the new room's description is set to %y%l<DESCRIPTION>%x.

You can get into your newly created room by typing '%g%l%(@tel%) me = #<ID>%x', where %y%l#<ID>%x is the ID number of the room (%@%m displays this when you create it), e.g:  '%g%l%(@tel%) me = #1342%x'.

When you first get your %y%l%(BUILDER%)%x flag, you should create a room to use as your Top Area, and name it something like '%y%l<NAME>'s Top Area%x' (Where %y%l<NAME>%x is your name, of course.)  You should then ask an administrator to teleport it into the main Top Area for Builders.

%PAGE
When you create further rooms, you should use '%g%l%(@tel%)%x' to teleport them into your Top Area by typing '%g%l%(@tel%) <ROOM ID> = <YOUR TOP AREA ID>%x'.  Your Top Area will help you keep your building work properly organised.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@desc%>%x', '%g%l%<@name%>%x', '%g%l%<@link%>%x' and '%g%l%<building%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @drop
%TOPIC dropmessage
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@drop%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@drop <OBJECT> [= <MESSAGE>]%]%x

This command sets the drop message for the %y%l<OBJECT>%x specified.  If %y%l<MESSAGE>%x isn't specified, the drop message is cleared.

The drop message of a thing is displayed when a character drops the thing (After picking it up using '%g%l%(take%)%x'), and is displayed on their screen only.

The drop message of a room is displayed when a character drops a thing in that room, and is displayed on their screen only.

The drop message of an exit is displayed to a character after they've gone through the exit and arrived in its destination room, and is displayed on their screen only.

%PAGE
The drop message of a fuse is the value its description is reset to when it's ticked down to %y%l0%x.

The drop message of a compound command is not used, and can be freely used as a '%c%lfree%x' property (See '%g%l%<@property%>%x') for storing things in.

If %y%l<MESSAGE>%x isn't specified, the drop message is cleared.


%c%l%$When is the drop message displayed?
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%9%2%y%lRoom   %c-  %xDisplayed when an object is dropped in room.

%9%2%y%lThing  %c-  %xDisplayed when object is dropped.

%9%2%y%lExit   %c-  %xDisplayed when a character goes through the exit and arrives in the exit's destination.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@odrop%>%x', '%g%l%<@succ%>%x', '%g%l%<@fail%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?drop%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @dump
%TOPIC dumpingemail
%TOPIC databasedumping
%TOPIC savingthedatabase
%TOPIC dumpingthedatabase
%TOPIC dumpingemailforwards
%TOPIC dumpingemailforwarding
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@dump%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@dump [restart|abort|email|forward]%]%x

This command can only be used by %g%lElder Wizards/%gDruids%x and above.

'%g%l@dump%x' forcefully starts dumping %@%m's database to disk.  The database is automatically dumped at regular intervals, so this command should only ever be used in an emergency (%c%lPLEASE NOTE:  %xThe database is also automatically dumped when %@%m is shutdown.)

If either of the parameters '%y%lrestart%x' ('%g%l@dump restart%x') or '%y%labort%x' ('%g%l@dump abort%x') are given, the current database dump will be aborted and (If '%y%lrestart%x' is specified) restarted from scratch.

%PAGE
'%g%l@dump email%x' dumps the private E-mail address of every character in the database to the file '%c%llib/email.tcz%x', and can only be used by %m%lDeities%x and the %m%lSupreme Being%x.  This file can then be processed externally with a script to send an important E-mail to every user (I.e:  If %@%m moves to a new site, for example.)

%8%c%lNOTE:  %xThe E-mail addresses of permanently banned characters are not dumped.

'%g%l@dump forward%x' dumps the E-mail forwarding address of every character in the database to the file '%c%llib/forward.tcz%x', and can only be used by %g%lElder Wizards/%gDruids%x and above.  This is done automatically on a daily basis, so this command should not need to be used.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@email%>%x' and '%g%l%<@admin%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @dup
%TOPIC @duplicate
%TOPIC duplication
%TOPIC copyingobjects
%TOPIC duplicatingobjects
%TOPIC makingcopiesofobjects
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@duplicate%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@duplicate <OBJECT> [= <NEW NAME>] [= inherit]%]%x

'%g%l@duplicate%x' creates a duplicate of the object %y%l<OBJECT>%x.  If %y%l<NEW NAME>%x is specified, the duplicate will be given that name, otherwise it will be given the name of the object it was duplicated from.

If the optional parameter '%y%linherit%x' is given, the object will be duplicated so that it makes as much use of inheritance (See '%g%l%<inheritance%>%x') as possible, saving on memory usage.  The parent of the duplicated object is automatically set to the object it was duplicated from.

The duplicated object will use the same amount of Building Quota as the object it was duplicated from, so you need sufficient Building Quota to duplicate the object.

%PAGE
The duplicated object will be in the same place as the object was duplicated from (Apart from if the location of the object being duplicated is a character of the same or a higher level than yourself, in which case the duplicated object will be attached to you.)

%8%c%lNOTE:%x  '%g%l@duplicate%x' can't be used to duplicate characters, and %c%lDOESN'T%x duplicate the contents of objects.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<building%>%x' and '%g%l%<inheritance%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @echo
%TOPIC output
%TOPIC textoutput
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@echo%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@echo <MESSAGE>%]%x

'%g%l@echo%x' is only of real use from within a compound command.  It basically echos %y%l<MESSAGE>%x to the command caller's screen (Or your screen if you type it in), e.g:

%g%l@echo Only I will see this!
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@oemote%>%x', '%g%l%<@oecho%>%x', '%g%l%<@write%>%x' and '%g%l%<@areawrite%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @echolist
%TOPIC listoutput
%TOPIC listformatting
%TOPIC listdisplaying
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@echolist%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@echolist <ITEM NO> = <ITEM DESCRIPTION>%]%x

'%g%l@echolist%x' is used to output lists with correct formatting, e.g:

%g%l@echolist 1 = This is the first item in the list!%x

%c...Would display...

%[%g%l(1)    %xThis is the first item in the list!%]


%c%l%$Example:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@with%) contents here do @echolist $4 = {%(@?name%) $6}%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@echo%>%x', '%g%l%<@oemote%>%x', '%g%l%<@oecho%>%x' and '%g%l%<@write%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @else
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@else%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@else [<CONDITION> do]%]%x

'%g%l@else%x' marks a 'block' of alternative commands to execute in an '%g%l%(@if%)%x' statement, if the %y%l<CONDITION>%x command fails (Or succeeds, if the keyword '%y%lfalse%x' is specified), e.g:

%[%g%l%(@if%) {%(@?set%) me = neuter} do
    %(@echo%) You are neuter.
    %(@oemote%) suddenly realises that they're neutered.
@else {%(@?set%) me = male} do
    %(@echo%) You are male.
    %(@oemote%) suddenly realises that %%s's male!
@else
    %(@echo%) You are female.
    %(@oemote%) suddenly realises that %%s's female!
@end%]%x

%PAGE
'%g%l@else%x' statements may optionally be conditional (If a %y%l<CONDITION>%x command is specified.)  If the %y%l<CONDITION>%x command succeeds (Or fails, and the keyword '%y%lfalse%x' is specified), the following 'block' of commands will be executed.

Each '%g%l@else%x' statement %c%lMUST%x be spread over multiple lines and terminated with '%g%l%(@end%)%x'.  '%g%l@else%x' and '%g%l%(@end%)%x' %c%lMUST NOT%x be preceeded by any text other than blank space, or used within %y%l{}%x's (I.e:  '%g%l{@else ...}%x'.)  The '%y%ldo%x' keyword %c%lMUST NOT%x be followed by any text.

%9%6%c%lPLEASE NOTE:  %xYou can 'nest' further '%g%l%(@if%)%x', '%g%l%(@case%)%x', '%g%l%(@for%)%x', '%g%l%(@with%)%x', '%g%l%(@while%)%x' and '%g%l%(@foreach%)%x' statements (Both single and multiple lined) within an '%g%l@else%x' statement.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@if%>%x', '%g%l%<@skip%>%x' and '%g%l%<@end%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @end
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@end%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@end%]%x

'%g%l@end%x' is used to mark the end of a 'block' of commands executed by the multiple line formats of '%g%l%(@if%)%x', '%g%l%(@case%)%x', '%g%l%(@for%)%x', '%g%l%(@with%)%x', '%g%l%(@while%)%x' and '%g%l%(@foreach%)%x', e.g:

%[%g%l%(@if%) {%(@?set%) me = haven} do
    %(@echo%) You will not receive any pages/tells as you're currently set HAVEN.
    %(@oemote%) is currently set HAVEN and can't be contacted via page or tell.
@end%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@if%>%x', '%g%l%<@case%>%x', '%g%l%<@for%>%x', '%g%l%<@with%>%x', '%g%l%<@while%>%x', '%g%l%<@foreach%>%x' and '%g%l%<@begin%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC email
%TOPIC @email
%TOPIC public
%TOPIC private
%TOPIC emailpublic
%TOPIC emailprivate
%TOPIC emailaddress
%TOPIC emailforward
%TOPIC emailforwards
%TOPIC electronicmail
%TOPIC emailforwarding
%TOPIC emailredirecting
%TOPIC publicemailaddresses
%TOPIC privateemailaddresses
%TOPIC emailforwardingfacility
%TOPIC settingyouremailaddress
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@email%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@email [<NAME> =] public|private|<NUMBER> <EMAIL ADDRESS>
        @email [<NAME> =] public|private|<NUMBER> reset
        @email [<NAME> =] public forward%]%x

The '%g%l@email%x' command is used to set your public and private E-mail addresses.


%c%l%$Your private E-mail address
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xYou must at least set your private E-mail address (Especially if you wish to obtain building privileges, which will allow you to build your own rooms, objects, areas, etc. (See '%g%l%<builder%>%x'.)

Your private E-mail address can only be seen by yourself and the adminstrators of %@%m, and will be kept %r%l%fSTRICTLY CONFIDENTIAL%x.  An %c%lanonymous%x or %c%lforwarding%x E-mail address (Widely available on the Internet) %y%l%ucannot%x be accepted as a valid private E-mail address.  Please set your private E-mail address to your %m%lREAL%x E-mail address.

%PAGE
You can set your private E-mail address by typing '%g%l@email private <EMAIL ADDRESS>%x', for example, if your E-mail address is '%y%lfred@wibble.wobble.com%x', you can set your E-mail to this address by typing '%g%l@email private fred@wibble.wobble.com%x'.

If your private E-mail address is already set, you will not be able to change or reset it.  If it is incorrect, please ask an administrator to change it for you (Type '%g%l%(who%) admin%x' (See '%g%l%<who%>%x') for a list of currently connected administrators.)


%c%l%$Your public E-mail addresses
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xIn addition to your private E-mail address, you may set up to four public E-mail addresses, which other users will be able to see and use to contact you if they wish to do so.  Your public E-mail addresses will appear on your '%g%l%(scan%)%x' and '%g%l%(profile%)%x' (See '%g%l%<scan%>%x' and '%g%l%<profile%>%x'.)

%PAGE
Unlike your private E-mail address, you may freely use anonymous or forwarding E-mail addresses for any of your public E-mail addresses.  You may also change or reset any of your public E-mail addresses as often as you wish.

To set your first public E-mail address, simply type '%g%l@email public <EMAIL ADDRESS>%x', e.g:  '%g%l@email public fred@anonymous.email.com%x'.  To set your other public E-mail addresses, simply type '%g%l@email <NUMBER> <EMAIL ADDRESS>%x', where %y%l<NUMBER>%x is a number between %c%l3%x and %c%l5%x (%y%l1%x is your first public E-mail address, and %y%l2%x is your private E-mail address), e.g:  '%g%l@email 3 fred@email.forward.com%x'.

To reset any of your public E-mail addresses, simply type '%g%l@email public reset%x' (To reset your first public E-mail address) or '%g%l@email <NUMBER> reset%x', where %y%l<NUMBER>%x is the number of the public E-mail address you wish to reset (A number between %c%l3%x and %c%l5%x.)

%PAGE

%c%l%$The E-mail forwarding facility...
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xIf your private E-mail address is set correctly, you will also be able to take part in the E-mail forwarding facility built into %@%m.

This will give you an E-mail forwarding address along the lines of '%y%l%{@?lower "{%@%m}"}.user.name@%@%f%x'.  For example, if your name on %@%m was '%y%lFred Bloggs%x', your E-mail forwarding address would be '%y%lfred.bloggs@%@%f%x'.

If you do not wish to initially give your real E-mail address to other users, you can give them your forwarding E-mail address, through which they will be able to send an E-mail to you, without knowing your real E-mail address.

By default, your first public E-mail address will be used as the destination for E-mail sent to your E-mail forwarding address.  However, you can alternatively use your private E-mail address instead, by typing '%g%l@email public forward%x'.  If you do this, you can disable it again by setting (Or resetting your first public E-mail address.)

%PAGE
%c%l%8NOTE:  %xYour E-mail forwarding address will be your %@%m character name (Excluding prefix/suffix) in lowercase with spaces replaced by '%y%l.%x's, e.g:  '%y%lFred Bloggs%x' will be '%y%lfred.bloggs@%@%f%x', '%y%lJC Digita%x' will be '%y%ljc.digita@%@%f%x', etc.

       %xFor E-mail forwarding to work, your private E-mail address must be set.

       %xPlease allow 24 hours for E-mail address changes to take effect (The E-mail forwarding database is updated once daily.)

%9%4%c%lIMPORTANT:  %xWhen your E-mail forwarding address is available, it will appear in your '%g%l%(scan%)%x' and '%g%l%(profile%)%x' (See '%g%l%<scan%>%x' and '%g%l%<profile%>%x'.)  Please don't set any your E-mail addresses to your forwarding E-mail address (This excludes typing '%g%l@email public forward%x'), otherwise the forwarding may no-longer work.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<scan%>%x', '%g%l%<profile%>%x', '%g%l%<emaillist%>%x', '%g%l%<@request%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?email%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @estr
%TOPIC @estring
%TOPIC exitstring
%TOPIC exitsstring
%TOPIC @exitsstring
%TOPIC obviousexitstring
%TOPIC obviousexitsstring
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@estring%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@estring <OBJECT> [= <DESCRIPTION>]%]%x

Sets (Or resets, if %y%l<DESCRIPTION>%x is ommited) an alternative obvious exits string for a room or thing, which will be displayed instead of the standard '%c%l%uObvious exits:%x' when the room/thing has visible exits and is looked at.

%c%l%8NOTE:  %xThe maximum length for an obvious exits string is %c%l79 characters%x.


%c%l%$Examples:
%~%c~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l@estring here = Ways out of this room:
@estring here = Other places you can visit:%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<look%>%x', '%g%l%<@cstring%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?estring%>%x'.

