%TOPIC errors
%TITLE Help on '%w%lOK%x' and '%w%lError%x' return values
A large number of commands and query commands (See '%g%l%<queries%>%x') return a value of either '%y%lOK%x' or '%y%lError%x' to indicate %c%lsuccess%x or %c%lfailure%x appropriately.

Success/failure is returned internally for all commands, regardless of whether they return '%y%lOK%x'/'%y%lError%x' as their return value or something different (As in the case of many query commands.)

Conditional commands such as '%g%l%(@if%)%x' and '%g%l%(@while%)%x' (See '%g%l%<@if%>%x' and '%g%l%<@while%>%x') rely on this result, as do the success/failure links of a compound command (See '%g%l%<@csuccess%>%x' and '%g%l%<@cfailure%>%x'.)

You can test for success/failure by using the '%g%l{%(@?true%)}%x' and '%g%l{%(@?false%)}%x' query commands (See '%g%l%<@?true%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?false%>%x'.)

%PAGE

%c%l%$Example:
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%g%l%(@if%) {%(@?set%) me = male} do %(@echo%) You are male.; else %(@echo%) You are not male.
%(@echo%) {%(@?set%) me = male}%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@eval%>%x', '%g%l%<@true%>%x', '%g%l%<@false%>%x', '%g%l%<@?true%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?false%>%x'.

