%TOPIC evaluating
%TOPIC mathematics
%TITLE Help on '%w%l{@eval}%x' (Or '%w%l{@calc}%x')
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l{@calc <EXPRESSION>}
        {@eval <EXPRESSION>}%]%x

'%g%l{@eval}%x' returns the result of calculating %y%l<EXPRESSION>%x, which can be string, numeric or both.  Most standard comparison, arithmetic, logical and bitwise operators are supported (Including C programming language style ones.)

The result returned by '%g%l{@eval}%x' is usually numeric when doing comparisons, with '%y%l1%x' meaning %c%lTRUE%x and '%y%l0%x' meaning %c%lFALSE%x.  Within compound commands, you will usually use '%g%l{@eval}%x' in conjunction with a selection command such as '%g%l%(@if%)%x' (See '%g%l%<@if%>%x')  -  The general format for this is '%g%l%(@if%) {@eval <EXPRESSION>} do <COMMAND>[; else <COMMAND>]%x'.

%PAGE
Parentheses (Brackets) can be used to group subexpressions.  Precedence is %c%lSTRICTLY LEFT-TO-RIGHT%x, e.g:  '%g%l%(@echo%) {@eval 3 * 5 - 1}%x' gives '%y%l14%x' and '%g%l%(@echo%) {@eval 3 * (5 - 1)}%x' gives '%y%l12%x' (You don't have to separate the operators with spaces, however it does look neater and more readable.)

%8%c%lNOTE:  %xEnclose %c%lALL%x string parameters in double-quotes (%y%l""%x), e.g:  '%g%l%(@if%) {@eval "$1" = "Hello"} do %c...%x'

       %8%c%lDON'T%x enclose numeric parameters in double-quotes, or they'll be taken as strings, and numeric operations on them will fail.  E.g: '%g%l%(@if%) {@eval $1 = 15} do %c...%x'

%PAGE

%c%l%$Arithmetic operators:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%c%l+   ##%x    Addition (Concatenates strings), e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval "Hello " + "world!"}
          %(@echo%) {@eval 2 + 2}%x  ...gives '%y%l4%x'.

%c%l-%x         Subtraction.

%c%l/   div%x   Division.

%c%l*%x         Multiplication.

%c%l%   mod%x   Modulus (Remainer of integer division), e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval 6 % 4}%x  ...gives '%y%l2%x'.%]

%PAGE

%c%l%$Arithmetic operators (Continued):%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%c%l^   **%x    Raise to the power.
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval 2 ^ 8}%x  ...gives '%y%l256%x'.

   %c%lsqrt%x   Square root, e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval sqrt 4}%x    ...gives '%y%l2.0%x'.

    %c%lsin%x   Sine (In radians), e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval sin 2.3}%x   ...gives '%y%l0.7457052122%x'.

    %c%lcos%x   Cosine (In radians), e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval cos 2.3}%x   ...gives '%y%l-0.6662760213%x'.

    %c%ltan%x   Tangent (In radians), e.g
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval tan 2.3}%x   ...gives '%y%l-1.1192136417%x'.%]

%PAGE

%c%l%$Arithmetic operators (Continued):%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[   %c%lasin%x   Arc sine (In radians), e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval asin 0.5}%x      ...gives '%y%l0.5235987756%x'.

   %c%lacos%x   Arc cosine (In radians), e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval acos 0.5}%x      ...gives '%y%l1.0471975512%x'.

   %c%latan%x   Arc tangent (In radians), e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval atan 0.5}%x      ...gives '%y%l0.463647609%x'.

    %c%labs%x   Absolute value, e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval 1 + (abs -3)}%x  ...gives '%y%l4%x'.

    %c%lint%x   Converts from floating point to integer, e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval int 3.45}%x      ...gives '%y%l3%x'.

  %c%lfloat%x   Converts from integer to floating point, e.g:
   %c%lreal   %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval float 2}%x       ...gives '%y%l2.0%x'.%]

%PAGE

%c%l%$Logical operators:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%c%l&&  and%x   Logical %y%lAND%x, e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval 1 && 1}%x   ...gives '%y%l1%x'.
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval 1 and 0)%x  ...gives '%y%l0%x'.

%c%l||  or%x    Logical %y%lOR%x, e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval 1 || 0)%x   ...gives '%y%l1%x'.
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval 0 or 0)%x   ...gives '%y%l0%x'.

%c%l!   not%x   Logical %y%lNOT%x, e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval !1}%x       ...gives '%y%l0%x'.
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval not 0}%x    ...gives '%y%l1%x'.%]

%PAGE

%c%l%$Bitwise operators:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%c%l&%x         Bitwise %y%lAND%x, e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval 255 & 15}%x  ...gives '%y%l15%x'.

%c%l|%x         Bitwise %y%lOR%x, e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval 16 | 32}%x   ...gives '%y%l48%x'.

%c%l~%x         Bitwise %y%lNOT%x, e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval ~1}%x        ...gives '%y%l-2%x'.

%c%l<<  shl%x   Bitwise shift-left, e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval 2 << 1}%x    ...gives '%y%l4%x'.

%c%l>>  shr%x   Bitwise shift-right, e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval 2 >> 1}%x    ...gives '%y%l1%x'.%]

%PAGE

%c%l%$Comparative operators:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%c%l==  =%x     Equal to, e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval "hello" = "hello"}%x   ...gives '%y%l1%x' (%c%lTRUE%x.)

%c%l!=  <>%x    Not equal to, e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval "hello" <> "hello"}%x  ...gives '%y%l0%x' (%c%lFALSE%x.)

%c%l<%x         Less than, e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval 10 < 50}%x             ...gives '%y%l1%x'.

%c%l>%x         Greater than, e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval 5 > 1}%x               ...gives '%y%l1%x'.

%c%l<=  =<%x    Less than or equal to, e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval 3 <= 10}%x             ...gives '%y%l1%x'.

%c%l>=  =>%x    Greater than or equal to, e.g:
          %g%l%(@echo%) {@eval 10 >= 10}%x            ...gives '%y%l1%x'.%]

%PAGE
%8%c%lNOTE:  %x'%g%l{@eval "hello" = "hello" = "hello"}%x' will not give '%y%l1%x' (%c%lTRUE%x)  -  Why?  Well, it first compares "%y%lhello%x" with "%y%lhello%x", giving the result '%y%l1%x', and then compares '%y%l1%x' with "%y%lhello%x", giving '%y%l0%x' (%c%lFALSE%x.) (Remember that precedence is %c%lSTRICTLY LEFT-TO-RIGHT%x.)


%c%l%$Rounding floating point numbers to a number of decimal places...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
Floating point numbers can be rounded to a number of decimal places by using '%g%l<DP>:<NUMBER>%x', where %y%l<DP>%x is the number of decimal places to round to, and %y%l<NUMBER>%x is the floating point number, e.g:  '%g%l%(@echo%) {@eval 2:3.4561}%x' gives '%y%l3.46%x'.

You can round the result of an entire calculation to a given number of decimal places by doing '%g%l{@eval <DP>:(<EXPRESSION>)}%x', e.g:  '%g%l%(@echo%) {@eval 3:(2.14523 + 1.78291 + 5.4382)}%x' gives '%y%l9.366%x'.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Some '%w%l%${@eval}%c%l%$'/'%w%l%${@calc}%c%l%$' tips...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
If you'd like to force the result of your calculation to be returned as an %c%linteger%x, you can do this by doing '%g%l{@eval int (<EXPRESSION>)}%x', e.g:

%[%g%l%(@echo%) {@eval 2 + 1.3 ^ 7}           %x...gives '%y%l4261.8442977%x'.
%g%l%(@echo%) {@eval int (2 + 1.3 ^ 7)}     %x...gives '%y%l4261%x'.%]%x

...Likewise, you can force the result of your calculation to be returned as a %c%lfloating point%x number by doing '%g%l{@eval float (<EXPRESSION>)}%x'.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Using '%w%l%${@eval}%c%l%$'/'%w%l%${@calc}%c%l%$' within compound commands...%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
'%g%l@eval%x' within compound commands is usually used in conjunction with the '%g%l%(@if%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<@if%>%x') when performing comparisons, and '%g%l%(@echo%)%x' (See '%g%l%<@echo%>%x') when you simply want to display the result of a calculation.


%c%l%$Example:
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@command%) evaltest = %(@if%) \{@eval "$3" = ""} do\
   %(@echo%) %%c%%lUSAGE: %%g %%l\{%(@?cmdname%)} <PARAMETERS>\
%(@else%)\
   %(@echo%) %%g%%lYou gave me the parameter(s) '%%w%%l$3%%g%%l'.\
%(@end%)%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<advanced queries%>%x', '%g%l%<@if%>%x', '%g%l%<@case%>%x', '%g%l%<@for%>%x', '%g%l%<@with%>%x', '%g%l%<@while%>%x', '%g%l%<@foreach%>%x', '%g%l%<@?result%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?rand%>%x'.

