%TOPIC @expiry
%TOPIC expirytimes
%TOPIC objectexpiry
%TOPIC objectexpirytimes
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@expiry%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@expiry <OBJECT> [= <TIME>]%]%x

This command is used to set an expiry time (In days) on an object, or reset its expiry time.  %@%n checks the entire database for expired objects on a weekly basis (An object expires when its last used date is greater than the number of days allowed for the object's expiry time.)

If %y%l<TIME>%x is specified, %y%l<OBJECT>%x's expiry time will be set to that number of days, which may be any number between %c%l1%x and %c%l255%x.  If %y%l<TIME>%x is omitted, the expiry time on %y%l<OBJECT>%x will be reset.

By default, the expiry time of an object is based on its last used date, but if the %y%l%(EXPIRY%)%x flag (See '%g%l%<expiry flag%>%x') is set on the object, the expiry time will be based on its %c%lcreation date%x instead.  This means that the object will expire after the specified amount of time, regardless of whether its being used or not.

%PAGE
A global expiry time will usually be set on the entire database, but this will usually be at least 1 year (The global expiry time will override any individual expiry times.)

One of the major uses of expiry times is when object(s) are created by a compound command which is used by users (Creating individual objects each time.)  If a low expiry time (I.e:  %c%l7 days%x (1 week) or %c%l30 days%x (Approx. 1 month) is set on these objects, they will be quickly destroyed if they are no-longer being used, or have been dropped in an obscure location which will be rarely visited.

For example, you have a shop where items can be bought (With the items being created and given to the 'customers'.)  As these items would have very little functionality, and would serve no other purpose other than to clutter the database up with useless objects (In time), a low expiry time could be set on the object when it is created, so if it is dropped somewhere obscure, or never looked at again by its purchaser, it will be destroyed automatically.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<expiry flag%>%x', '%g%l%<date stamps%>%x', '%g%l%<@destroy%>%x', '%g%l%<junked objects%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?expiry%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @fail
%TOPIC @failure
%TOPIC failuremessage
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@fail%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@fail <OBJECT> [= <MESSAGE>]%]%x

This command sets the failure message for the %y%l<OBJECT>%x specified.

An object fails when a character fails to satisfy its lock (If it's a room, thing or exit), or if it's a compound command, it fails when the last command executed in it fails.

If the object fails, the failure message is displayed on the screen of the character who caused it to fail.

If %y%l<MESSAGE>%x isn't specified, the failure message is cleared.

%PAGE

%c%l%$When is the failure message displayed?
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%9%4%y%lCommand  %c-  %xDisplayed when the compound command finishes executing, and the last command executed failed (Not displayed if compound command has its '%g%l%(@cfailure%)%x' branch set (See '%g%l%<@cfail%>%x'.))

%9%4%y%lExit     %c-  %xDisplayed when a character is unable to go through the exit, because they are unable to satisfy its lock (In same room as the exit.)

%9%4%y%lRoom     %c-  %xDisplayed when the lock of the room is not satisfied and a character types '%g%l%(look%)%x' (Underneath the room's description), or if the room has its %y%l%(OPENABLE%)%x flag set, it is displayed when a character is unable to enter the room because they do not satisfy its lock.

%9%4%y%lThing    %c-  %xDisplayed when a character is unable to pick up the object, because they are unable to satisfy its lock.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@ofail%>%x', '%g%l%<@succ%>%x', '%g%l%<@drop%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?fail%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @false
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@false%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@false%]%x

This command only has effect within a compound command.  It basically causes the compound command to fail at that point.

One use for it is right at the end of a compound command to force it to fail and execute the compound command linked via its '%g%l%(@cfail%)%x' regardless of whether the other commands executed failed or not.

%8%c%lNOTE:  %x'%g%l@false%x' does not change the return value from the previous executed command.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@true%>%x', '%g%l%<@cfail%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?false%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @feeling
%TOPIC @feelings
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@feeling%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@feeling [<NAME> =] <FEELING>
        @feeling [<NAME> =] reset
        @feeling list [<PAGE NO>]%]%x

The '%g%l@feeling%x' command allows you to set how you are currently feeling (From a list.)  Once set, users who '%g%l%(scan%)%x' (See '%g%l%<scan%>%x') you will see your current feeling, and it will also be displayed after your name in the '%y%l%$Contents:%x' list of your current location (I.e:  '*Fred Bloggs (Happy)'.)

You can list the available feelings by typing '%g%l@feeling list%x'.  You can then set how you are currently feeling by typing '%g%l@feeling <FEELING>%x', where %y%l<FEELING>%x is one of the feelings in the list, e.g:  '%g%l@feeling happy%x'.

If more than one page of feelings is displayed, you can view the other pages by typing '%g%l@feeling list <PAGE NO>%x', where %y%l<PAGE NO>%x is the page number, e.g:  '%g%l@feeling list 2%x' to view the %c%l2nd%x page, '%g%l@feeling list 3%x' to view the %c%l3rd%x.

You can remove your feeling by typing '%g%l@feeling reset%x'.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<feelings%>%x', '%g%l%<scan%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?feeling%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @find
%TOPIC searching
%TOPIC findingthings
%TOPIC locatingthings
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@find%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@find [<PAGE NO>] <SEARCH SPEC> = <WILDCARD SPEC>
        @find [<PAGE NO>] <WILDCARD SPEC>%]%x

'%g%l@find%x' is used to search for and display objects which match a given search criteria and wildcard specification (See '%g%l%<wildcards%>%x'.)

If %y%l<PAGE NO>%x is specified, the list of objects will be split into pages and the specified page will be displayed (Useful for long lists.)

%y%l<SEARCH SPEC>%x can be one or more of the following (In any order, separated by spaces)...

%6%g%l(1)%x  A %c%lfield name%x to search for %y%l<WILDCARD SPEC>%x in:

     %6%y%lareaname%x, %y%lcstring%x, %y%ldesc%x, %y%ldrop%x, %y%lemail%x, %y%lestring%x, %y%lfail%x, %y%llastsite%x, %y%lname%x, %y%lodesc%x, %y%lodrop%x, %y%lofail%x, %y%losucc%x, %y%lprefix%x, %y%lrace%x, %y%lsucc%x, %y%lsuffix%x, %y%ltitle%x, %y%lwww%x.

%PAGE
%6%g%l(2)%x  An %c%lobject type%x:

     %6%y%lalarms%x, %y%larrays%x, %y%lcharacters%x, %y%lcommands%x, %y%lexits%x, %y%lfuses%x, %y%lplayers%x (Same as characters), %y%lproperties%x, %y%lpuppets%x, %y%lrooms%x, %y%lthings%x, %y%lvariables%x.

%6%g%l(3)%x  A %c%lstandard %@%m flag%x:

     %6%y%labode%x, %y%labort%x, %y%lansi%x, %y%lapprentices%x, %y%lashcan%x, %y%lassistants%x, %y%lbbs%x, %y%lbbs-inform%x, %y%lboot%x, %y%lbuilders%x, %y%lcensored%x, %y%lcombat%x, %y%lconsonant%x, %y%ldark%x, %y%ldeities%x, %y%ldruids%x, %y%lelders%x, %y%lengaged%x, %y%lexperienced%x, %y%lexpiry%x, %y%lfemales%x, %y%lfriends-inform%x, %y%lhaven%x, %y%lhelp%x, %y%lhtml%x, %y%limmovable%x, %y%linheritable%x, %y%linvisible%x, %y%llisten%x, %y%lmail%x, %y%lmales%x, %y%lmarried%x, %y%lmorons%x, %y%lneuter%x, %y%lnumber%x, %y%lopaque%x, %y%lopen%x, %y%lopenable%x, %y%lpagebell%x, %y%lpermanent%x, %y%lplural%x, %y%lprivate%x, %y%lquiet%x, %y%lreadonly%x, %y%lreadonlydesc%x, %y%lretired%x, %y%lsecret%x, %y%lsendhome%x, %y%lsharable%x, %y%lshout%x, %y%lskipobjects%x, %y%lsticky%x, %y%ltom%x, %y%ltracing%x, %y%ltransferable%x, %y%ltransport%x, %y%lvalidated%x, %y%lvisible%x, %y%lvisit%x, %y%lvowel%x, %y%lwarp%x, %y%lwizards%x, %y%lyell%x.

%PAGE
%[%g%l(4)  %y%ladministrators   %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above.
     %y%lbanned           %xCharacters currently banned from using %@%m.
     %y%lcontainers       %c%lThings%x which you can put other objects into.
     %y%lglobal           %xGlobal compound commands.
     %y%ljunked           %xObjects which have been junked.
     %y%Lmortals          %xMortal characters.%]

%6%g%l(5)%x  A %c%lcreation date%x/%c%llast usage date%x specification (See following pages for details.)

%PAGE
If %y%l<SEARCH SPEC>%x isn't specified (I.e:  When '%g%l@find%x' is used in the second form ('%g%l@find [<PAGE NO>] <WILDCARD SPEC>%x')), the name of any type of object is assumed (E.g:  '%g%l@find name = <WILDCARD SPEC>%x'.)


%c%l%$Examples:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l@find *<TEXT>*%x                          Finds and lists every object (Of any
                                        type) that has %y%l<TEXT>%x in it's name.
%g%l@find name desc = *<TEXT>*%x              Finds and lists every object that has
                                        %y%l<TEXT>%x in it's name %c%lOR%x description.
%g%l@find abode rooms = *%x                   Finds and lists rooms set %y%l%(ABODE%)%x.
%g%l@find things commands desc = *<TEXT>*%x   Finds and lists things and commands
                                        that have %y%l<TEXT>%x in their description.%]

%PAGE

%c%l%$Creation date/last usage date specificiations...
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xA creation date or last usage date specification (Or both used together) may be used to restrict the objects listed to those which were created and/or last used between specific dates.  The usage is as follows...

%[%g%l&[c|l][<|>|<=|>=]<NUMBER>[s|m|h|d|w|m|y]
 %c|    |          |       `--->  %y%ls[econds]%x, %y%lm[inutes]%x, %y%lh[ours]%x, %y%ld[ays]%x,
 %c|    |          |              %y%lw[eeks]%x, %y%lm[onths]%x, %y%ly[ears]%x.
 %c|    |          |
 %c|    |          `--->  %xNumber of given time interval (I.e:  %y%l1w%x = %c%l1 week%x.)
 %c|    |
 %c|    `--->  %y%l<%x lists objects created/last used %c%lBEFORE%x given date.
 %c|           %y%l>%x lists objects created/last used %c%lAFTER%x given date.
 %c|
 %c|
 %c`--->  %y%lc[reation]%x date.
        %y%ll[astused]%x date.%]

%PAGE
The '%y%l&%x' marks the beginning of the creation date/last usage date specification.  This is followed by either '%y%lc%x' (%c%lCreation date%x) or '%y%ll%x' (%c%lLast usage date%x.)  This is then followed by '%y%l<%x' (%c%lLess than%x given time interval ago), '%y%l>%x' (%c%lGreater than%x given time interval ago), '%y%l<=%x' (Same as '%y%l<%x', except %c%lless than OR equal%x), '%y%l>=%x' (Same as '%y%l>%x', except %c%lgreater than OR equal%x.)

After '%y%l<%x', '%y%l>%x', '%y%l<=%x' and '%y%l>=%x', a time interval must be given, which is a number of %c%lseconds%x ('%y%ls%x'), %c%lminutes%x ('%y%lm%x'), %c%lhours%x ('%y%lh%x'), %c%ldays%x ('%y%ld%x'), %c%lweeks%x ('%y%lw%x'), %c%lmonths%x ('%y%lm%x') or %c%lyears%x ('%y%ly%x') ago from the present time/date.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Creation date/last usage date specification examples:
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l&c<1w        %xLists objects created %c%lBEFORE%x 1 week ago.
%g%l&c>=1w       %xLists objects created between now and 1 week ago.
%g%l&c>=1y<=6m   %xLists objects created between 1 year and 6 months ago.
%g%l&l>=1d       %xLists objects last used up to 1 day ago.%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<wildcards%>%x', '%g%l%<@list%>%x', '%g%l%<junked objects%>%x' and '%g%l%<date stamps%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC for
%TOPIC @for
%TOPIC looping
%TOPIC forloops
%TOPIC interation
%TOPIC repetition
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@for%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@for <FROM VALUE> to <TO VALUE> [step <STEP VALUE>] do [<COMMAND>]
             [<COMMANDS>]
        [%(@end%)]%]%x

The '%g%l@for%x' command can be used in two forms:  The first form may only be used on a %c%lSINGLE LINE%x.  '%g%l@for%x' starts at %y%l<FROM VALUE>%x and loops to %y%l<TO VALUE>%x, increasing/decreasing by %c%l1%x (Or %y%l<STEP VALUE>%x, if specified) each time and executing %y%l<COMMAND>%x.

%[%c%lExample:  %g%l@for 3 to 7 do %(@echo%) Loop value:  $4%]%x

%PAGE
The reserved variables %y%l$4%x and %y%l$5%x are useful in an '%g%l@for%x' statement  -  These substitute the following...

%y%l$4%x substitutes the current loop value.
%y%l$5%x substitutes the total number of loops so far.

%8%c%lNOTE:  %x'%g%l@for%x' can only be used from within compound commands (Unless you're an %r%lExperienced Builder%x or above.)

The second form of '%g%l@for%x' allows you to execute a 'block' of commands.

When using '%g%l@for%x' in this form, it %c%lMUST%x be spread over multiple lines and terminated with '%g%l%(@end%)%x'.  '%g%l@for%x' and '%g%l%(@end%)%x' %c%lMUST NOT%x be preceeded by any text other than blank space, or used within %y%l{}%x's (I.e:  '%g%l{@for ...}%x'.)  The '%y%ldo%x' keyword %c%lMUST NOT%x be followed with a %y%l<COMMAND>%x.

%PAGE
The usage of '%g%l@for%x' in this form is identical to the single lined version of '%g%l@for%x', except it is spread over multiple lines, e.g:

%[%g%l@for 3 to 7 do
     %(@echo%) Loop value:  $4
     %(@echo%) Total loops so far:  $5
%(@end%)%]%x

%9%6%c%lPLEASE NOTE:  %xYou can 'nest' further '%g%l%(@if%)%x', '%g%l%(@case%)%x', '%g%l%(@for%)%x', '%g%l%(@with%)%x', '%g%l%(@while%)%x' and '%g%l%(@foreach%)%x' statements (Both single and multiple lined) within a multiple line '%g%l@if%x' statement.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@end%>%x', '%g%l%<@if%>%x', '%g%l%<@case%>%x', '%g%l%<@with%>%x', '%g%l%<@while%>%x', '%g%l%<@foreach%>%x', '%g%l%<@skip%>%x', '%g%l%<@breakloop%>%x', '%g%l%<@break%>%x', '%g%l%<@return%>%x' and '%g%l%<@goto%>%x'.

