%TOPIC @force
%TOPIC forcing
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@force%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@force <NAME> = <COMMAND>%]%x

Forces the character %y%l<NAME>%x to execute the command %y%l<COMMAND>%x (As though they typed it themself.)  %y%l<NAME>%x must be yourself or your puppet (Unless you're a %c%lWizard/%cDruid%x or above, who can force any character of a lower level to execute a given command.)

When forcing a character on the command line (I.e:  Not within a compound command), you will see the resulting output of the '%g%l@force%x' (As the user would see on their screen, if connected.)

%PAGE
%8%c%lNOTE:  %xAll forces (With the exception of those on your puppet(s)) are logged to the '%c%lForce%x' log file (See '%g%l%<@log%>%x'.)

%8%c%lNOTE:  %xUsage of '%g%l@force%x' within a %c%lcompound command%x (See '%g%l%<@command%>%x') should be protected with the '%g%l{%(@?protect%)}%x' query command (See '%g%l%<@?protect%>%x') to prevent unwanted substitutions (See '%g%l%<substitutions%>%x'), which could pose a security risk to the character you are forcing.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@remote%>%x', '%g%l%<@?protect%>%x' and '%g%l%<@notify%>%x'.

