%TITLE Help on '%w%l@entrances%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@entrances [#<ID>]%]%x

Displays a list of rooms with exits which lead to the room/thing %y%l#<ID>%x, along with the exit name (As displayed if you typed '%g%l%(look%)%x' (See '%g%l%<look%>%x') in the room.)

If %y%l#<ID>%x isn't specified, your present location is assumed.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@open%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC fuses
%TOPIC @fuse
%TOPIC makingfuses
%TOPIC creatingfuses
%TOPIC buildingfuses
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@fuse%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@fuse <NAME> [= <COMMAND>]%]%x

Creates a fuse called %y%l<NAME>%x (Building Quota used:  %c%l5%x.)  If %y%l<COMMAND>%x is specified, the %c%lcsuccess%x ('%g%l%(@csucc%)%x'  -  See '%g%l%<@csucc%>%x') of the fuse will be set to the compound command %y%l<COMMAND>%x.

A fuse starts off %c%lattached to you%x (When you create it), but it can be attached to another character (Providing they're below your level) or a room, thing or exit (Use '%g%l%(@tel%) <FUSE> = <OBJECT>%x' to attach a fuse to an object.)  The conditions which cause a fuse to 'trigger' depend on the type of object it's attached to...

%9%4%y%lCHARACTER:%x  The fuse 'triggers' each time the character types a command or moves.

  %9%4%y%lVEHICLE:%x  The fuse 'triggers' each time the vehicle is driven/ridden.  If the vehicle can be entered and a character is inside it, the same conditions that apply to a room also apply to the vehicle.

%PAGE
    %9%4%y%lTHING:%x  The fuse 'triggers' each time the thing is picked up, dropped or successfully opened, closed, locked or unlocked.  If the thing is a container, which can be entered, and a character is inside it, the same conditions that apply to a room also apply to the container.

     %9%4%y%lROOM:%x  The fuse 'triggers' each time a character in the room types a command or moves.

     %9%4%y%lEXIT:%x  The fuse 'triggers' each time a character goes through the exit, or (In the case of %y%l%(OPENABLE%)%x exits (See '%g%l%<openable flag%>%x')) the exit is successfully opened, closed, locked or unlocked.

%PAGE
Whenever a fuse is 'triggered', the value stored in its %c%ldescription%x ('%g%l%(@desc%)%x'  -  See '%g%l%<@desc%>%x') counts down by 1.  If the resulting value is greater than 0, the compound command linked via the fuses %c%lcfailure%x ('%g%l%(@cfail%)%x'  -  See '%g%l%<@cfail%>%x') will be executed, otherwise the compound command linked via its %c%lcsuccess%x ('%g%l%(@csucc%)%x'  -  See '%g%l%<@csucc%>%x') will be executed and the %c%ldescription%x of the fuse will be reset to the value held in its %c%ldrop message%x ('%g%l%(@drop%)%x'  -  See '%g%l%<@drop%>%x'.)

You can make fuses attached to rooms/characters 'trigger' %c%lonly when movement occurs%x (I.e:  When characters move into/out of the room, or the character the fuse is attached to moves) by setting the %y%l%(TOM%)%x flag on them (Which stands for '%c%lTrigger On Movement%x'), e.g:  '%g%l%(@set%) <FUSE> = %(TOM%)%x'.

You can delay the 'triggering' of a fuse until the command which the user who triggered it typed has finished executing by setting the %y%l%(STICKY%)%x flag on it (E.g:  A %y%l%(TOM%)%x and %y%l%(STICKY%)%x fuse in a room will not trigger until a character moves in that room and has arrived in their destination room.)

%PAGE
When a compound command is executed by a fuse, %y%l$1%x is set to the command the character who triggered the fuse typed (E.g:  '%g%l%(say%)%x') and %y%l$2%x is set to the command's parameters (E.g:  '%g%lHello%x'.)  %y%l$3%x is set to both (E.g:  '%g%l%(say%) Hello%x'.)

%y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above can set the %y%l%(ABORT%)%x flag (See '%g%l%<abort flag%>%x') on a fuse, which prevents the command which triggered the fuse from being executed.  For example, a fuse attached to a thing with its %y%l%(ABORT%)%x flag set would cause the fuse to trigger each time the object was picked up or dropped.  However, the '%g%l%(take%)%x'/'%g%l%(drop%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<take%>%x' and '%g%l%<drop%>%x') would be aborted by the fuse, and the object would remain in the same place.  The '%g%l%(@continue%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<@continue%>%x') can be used within the compound command executed by the fuse to prevent the effects of the %y%l%(ABORT%)%x flag.

%9%5%c%lFUSES HINT:%x  After creating a fuse, teleport it to the object you want to attach it to first ('%g%l%(@tel%) <FUSE> = <OBJECT>%x') and then set its drop message (%c%lReset%x) and description (%c%lTicks%x.)  Finally link the '%g%l%(@csucc%)%x' and/or '%g%l%(@cfail%)%x' to the appropriate compound command(s).
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@desc%>%x', '%g%l%<@drop%>%x', '%g%l%<@csucc%>%x', '%g%l%<@cfail%>%x' and '%g%l%<building%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @goto
%TOPIC @gotostatement
%TOPIC @gotolinenumber
%TOPIC skiptolinenumber
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@goto%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@goto [+/-] <LINE NUMBER>%]%x

This command can only be used from within compound commands.

'%g%l@goto%x' skips/backtracks to the given %y%l<LINE NUMBER>%x in the current compound command and continues execution from that line number.  %y%l<LINE NUMBER>%x can either be literal (E.g:  '%g%l@goto 2%x' will go to line number %c%l2%x), or an adjustment (If '%y%l+%x' or '%y%l-%x' is used in front of %y%l<LINE NUMBER>%x), e.g:  '%g%l@goto +2%x' will skip executing the next line in the compound command and execute the line which follows, and '%g%l@goto -1%x' will execute the previous line (%r%lWARNING:  %xThis will create a loop), etc.


%c%l%$Example (Compound command '%w%l%$ring%c%l%$'):%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@if%) {%(@eval%) "$1" <> "bell"} do @goto +3
%(@echo%) You ring the bell...  DING-A-LING-A-LING!
%(@return%)
%(@echo%) What would you like to ring?%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@break%>%x', '%g%l%<@breakloop%>%x', '%g%l%<@return%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?line%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @heal
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@heal%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@heal <NAME> = [+/-]<HEALTH>%]%x

This command can only be used from within a compound command with its %y%l%(COMBAT%)%x flag set (See '%g%l%<combat flag%>%x'), in a location which also has its %y%l%(COMBAT%)%x flag set.  Both must be owned by the same character.

'%g%l@heal%x' increases (Or decreases, if a negative value is specified for %y%l<HEALTH>%x) the character %y%l<NAME>%x's health by %y%l<HEALTH>%x and is ideal for creating 'food', first-aid kits, poison, etc.  E.g:  '%g%l@heal *fred = 10%x' will increase the character "%c%lFred%x"'s health by %y%l10%x.

Usually, a character's health can't exceed %c%l100%%%x, however preceeding %y%l<HEALTH>%x with a '%y%l+%x' (Which can only be used in a compound command set %y%l%(WIZARD%)%x or %y%l%(ELDER%)%x (See '%g%l%<wizard flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<elder flag%>%x')) allows the character's health to be increased to a value higher than 100%.  '%y%l+%x' is ideal for creating special health power-ups, etc.  Health above 100% automatically decreases back down to 100% at a rate similar to healing when below 100%.

%PAGE
%c%l%8NOTE:  %x'%g%l@heal%x' cannot be used on yourself if you own the compound command or location in which it is used, or the character %y%l<NAME>%x is not in the same location as you.  These restrictions can be removed by setting %y%l%(WIZARD%)%x or %y%l%(ELDER%)%x flags on the combat commands respectively (See '%g%l%<wizard flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<elder flag%>%x'.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@damage%>%x', '%g%l%<@delay%>%x', '%g%l%<substitutions%>%x', '%g%l%<combat flag%>%x', '%g%l%<wizard flag%>%x', '%g%l%<elder flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<combat%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @homeroom
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@homeroom%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@homeroom%]%x

Creates/re-creates your home room, if you do not already have one, or you have accidentally destroyed it.

If you are a Builder (See '%g%l%<builder%>%x'), you must have sufficient free Building Quota (See '%g%l%<@quota%>%x') to create your home room.

Once created, you can go to your home room by typing '%g%l%(homeroom%)%x', '%g%l%(home%)%x' (If your home room is your current home, or '%g%l%(home%)%x' %c%ltwice%x if not.)

%PAGE
While you are in your home room, you can change its %c%lname%x by using the '%g%l%(@name%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<@name%>%x'), e.g:

   %3%[%g%l%(@name%) here = Fred's House%]%x

You can also change the %c%ldescription%x, using the '%g%l%(@desc%)%x' (See '%g%l%<@desc%>%x') command ('%g%l%(@describe%)%x'), e.g:

   %3%[%g%l%(@desc%) here = Welcome to my home room.  Feel free to make yourself at home.%]%x

You can also use the editor (See '%g%l%<editor%>%x') to edit the description of your home room (This is useful for creating long descriptions, correcting mistakes or making changes without having to type the description all over again.)

%PAGE
You can change the '%y%l%uContents:%x' title to something more interesting using the '%g%l%(@cstring%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<@cstring%>%x'), e.g:

   %3%[%g%l%(@cstring%) here = In the room you see:%]%x

By setting the %y%l%(ABODE%)%x flag (See '%g%l%<abode flag%>%x'), you can allow other characters to visit your home room whenever they please (Using the '%g%l%(visit%)%x' or '%g%l%(to%)%x' commands (See '%g%l%<visit%>%x' and '%g%l%<to%>%x'), without you having to summon them using the '%g%l%(summon%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<summon%>%x')), e.g:

   %3%[%g%l%(@set%) here = abode%]%x

You can prevent them from doing this by resetting the flag, e.g:

   %3%[%g%l%(@set%) here = !abode%]%x

<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<homeroom%>%x', '%g%l%<home%>%x' and '%g%l%<builder%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC condition
%TOPIC conditions
%TOPIC conditionpart
%TOPIC conditioncommand
%TITLE Help on the %w%l<CONDITION>%x part of '%w%l@if%x', '%w%l@else%x' or '%w%l@while%x'
The %y%l<CONDITION>%x part of an '%g%l%(@if%)%x', '%g%l%(@else%)%x' or '%g%l%(@while%)%x' statement can be in any of the following four formats...

%[%g%l#<COMMAND ID>            %c%l...E.g:  %g%l@if #34 do @echo Success!; else @echo Fail!
{%(@eval%) <EXPRESSION>}     %c%l...E.g:  %g%l@if {@eval 1 < 3} do @echo 1 is less than 3!
{@?<QUERY COMMAND>}      %c%l...E.g:  %g%l@if {@?set me = male} do @echo I am male!; 
                                  else @echo I am female/neutered!
<COMMAND>                %c%l...E.g:  %g%l@if @true do @echo Always true!%]%x

In the first form, whether %y%l<CONDITION>%x is met or not is determined by whether the compound command %y%l#<ID>%x returns success or failure when executed.  In the second, whether %y%l<CONDITION>%x is met or not depends on the result of the expression evaluated with '%g%l%(@eval%)%x'.  In the third form, it's determined by the result of the given query command (See '%g%l%<queries%>%x') and in the last form, it's determined by whether %y%l<COMMAND>%x (Which can be either in-built or compound) returns success or failure.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@if%>%x', '%g%l%<@else%>%x' and '%g%l%<@while%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC if
%TOPIC @if
%TOPIC choice
%TOPIC select
%TOPIC testing
%TOPIC boolean
%TOPIC selection
%TOPIC branching
%TOPIC conditionaltesting
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@if%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@if [true|false] <CONDITION> do [<COMMAND1>[; else <COMMAND2>]]
            [<COMMANDS1>]
        [%(@else%) [<CONDITION> do]]
            [<COMMANDS2>]
        [%(@else%) ...]
        [%(@end%)]%]%x

The '%g%l@if%x' command can be used in two forms:  The first form may only be used on a %c%lSINGLE LINE%x.  By default, if %y%l<CONDITION>%x is met, %y%l<COMMAND1>%x will be executed, otherwise %y%l<COMMAND2>%x (The '%y%lelse%x' part) will be executed (If specified.)  If the keyword '%y%lfalse%x' is specified, the '%g%l@if%x' is negated (I.e:  %y%l<COMMAND1>%x will be executed if %y%l<CONDITION> %c%lISN'T%x met, otherwise %y%l<COMMAND2>%x will be executed (If specified.)

%PAGE
%[%c%lExample:  %g%l@if {%(@?set%) me = haven} do %(@echo%) You are set HAVEN.; else %(@echo%) You
          are not set HAVEN.%]%x

The second form of '%g%l@if%x' is far more flexible and sophisticated, allowing you to execute 'blocks' of commands, and have multiple conditional '%g%l%(@else%)%x' blocks (This effectively allows '%g%l@if%x' to be used like a 'case' statement (As found in many programming languages.))

When using '%g%l@if%x' in this form, it %c%lMUST%x be spread over multiple lines and terminated with '%g%l%(@end%)%x'.  '%g%l@if%x', '%g%l%(@else%)%x' and '%g%l%(@end%)%x' %c%lMUST NOT%x be preceeded by any text other than blank space, or used within %y%l{}%x's (I.e:  '%g%l{@if ...}%x'.)  The '%y%ldo%x' keyword %c%lMUST NOT%x be followed with a %y%l<COMMAND>%x.

%PAGE
The usage of '%g%l@if%x' in this form is identical to the single lined version of '%g%l@if%x', except it is spread over multiple lines, e.g:

%[%g%l@if {%(@?set%) me = neuter} do
    %(@echo%) You are neuter.
    %(@oemote%) suddenly realises that they're neutered.
%(@else%) {%(@?set%) me = male} do
    %(@echo%) You are male.
    %(@oemote%) suddenly realises that %%s's male!
%(@else%)
    %(@echo%) You are female.
    %(@oemote%) suddenly realises that %%s's female!
%(@end%)%]

%PAGE
In the above '%g%l@if%x' statement, you will notice that there are %c%lTWO%x '%g%l%(@else%)%x' parts.  This is a useful feature of the multiple lined version of '%g%l@if%x':  In the above example, if you're not set %y%l%(NEUTER%)%x, it will then test to see if you're set %y%l%(MALE%)%x.  It's effectively the same as '%g%l@if {%(@?set%) me = neuter} do %(@echo%) You are neuter.; else @if {%(@?set%) me = male} do %(@echo%) You are male.; else %(@echo%) You are female.%x' (%c%lNOTE:  %xThe '%g%l%(@oemote%)%x's are ommitted for simplicity and readability.)

%9%6%c%lPLEASE NOTE:  %xYou can 'nest' further '%g%l%(@if%)%x', '%g%l%(@case%)%x', '%g%l%(@for%)%x', '%g%l%(@with%)%x', '%g%l%(@while%)%x' and '%g%l%(@foreach%)%x' statements (Both single and multiple lined) within a multiple line '%g%l@if%x' statement.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<condition%>%x', '%g%l%<@else%>%x', '%g%l%<@end%>%x', '%g%l%<@for%>%x', '%g%l%<@with%>%x', '%g%l%<@while%>%x', '%g%l%<@foreach%>%x', '%g%l%<@skip%>%x', '%g%l%<@breakloop%>%x', '%g%l%<@break%>%x', '%g%l%<@return%>%x' and '%g%l%<@goto%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @index
%TOPIC @indexnames
%TOPIC @indexedelements
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@index%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@index <ARRAY>[<ELEMENT>] [= <INDEX NAME>]%]%x

If %y%l<INDEX NAME>%x is specified, the index name of element %y%l<ELEMENT>%x of the dynamic array %y%l<ARRAY>%x is set to %y%l<INDEX NAME>%x, otherwise the element's current index name is removed (If it has one.)

If a range of elements is given, the index name of the first element in the range will be set/changed/removed.


%c%l%$Examples:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l@index myarray[2] = test      %xGives element %c%l2%x of '%y%lmyarray%x' the index name
                              '%y%ltest%x'.
%g%l@index myarray[test] = what   %xChanges the index name of element '%y%ltest%x' of
                              '%y%lmyarray%x' to '%y%lwhat%x'.
%g%l@index myarray[what]          %xRemoves the index name of element '%y%ltest%x' of
                              '%y%lmyarray%x'.%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@array%>%x', '%g%l%<@?index%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?indexno%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @insert
%TOPIC @insertelements
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@insert%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@insert <ARRAY>[<ELEMENT>] [= <TEXT>]%]%x

This command inserts a new element into the dynamic array %y%l<ARRAY>%x in front of the element specified (Or range of elements specified), e.g:  '%g%l@insert myarray[2] = a new element%x' inserts a new element in front of the %c%l2nd%x element of '%y%lmyarray%x' and describes it to '%y%la new element%x' and '%g%l@insert myarray[test] = a new element in front of indexed element 'test'%x' inserts a new element in front of the element with the index name '%y%ltest%x' of '%y%lmyarray%x'.

If no element is specified, the new element is inserted in front of the first element of the dynamic array.  If %y%l<TEXT>%x is specified, the description of the new element is set to it.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@destroy%>%x' and '%g%l%<@array%>%x'.

