%TOPIC @loc
%TOPIC @tel
%TOPIC @tele
%TOPIC @location
%TOPIC @teleport
%TOPIC teleporting
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@teleport%x' ('%w%l@tel%x' or '%w%l@location%x')
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@teleport <OBJECT> = <DESTINATION>
        @location <OBJECT> = <DESTINATION>
        @tel <OBJECT> = <DESTINATION>%]%x

Teleports %y%l<OBJECT>%x to %y%l<DESTINATION>%x.

You must control %y%l<DESTINATION>%x and either control %y%l<OBJECT>%x or its current location.  If %y%l<DESTINATION>%x has a drop-to, %y%l<OBJECT>%x will end up in the drop-to location instead (If %y%l<OBJECT>%x is a thing.)

If %y%l<OBJECT>%x isn't specified, you'll be teleported to %y%l<DESTINATION>%x (If %y%l<DESTINATION>%x isn't a room/container, you'll be teleported to it's current location (Providing that's a room/container.))  You can't teleport to a location you don't own, unless it has its %y%l%(ABODE%)%x flag set.

To teleport an object to another character, type '%g%l%(@tel%) <OBJECT> = *<NAME>%x' (This can only be done by %c%lWizards/%cDruids%x and above.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<drop%>%x', '%g%l%<visit%>%x', '%g%l%<to%>%x' and '%g%l%<abode flag%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC locks
%TOPIC @lock
%TOPIC lockingthings
%TOPIC lockingobjects
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@lock%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@lock <OBJECT> = <KEY>%]%x

Locks %y%l<OBJECT>%x so that the lock specification %y%l<KEY>%x must be satisfied before the object can be used successfully.  %y%l<OBJECT>%x can be an %c%lCompound Command%x, %c%lExit%x, %c%lFuse%x, %c%lThing%x or %c%lRoom%x.

A lock specification consists of one or more conditions, linked together using boolean operators such as %c%lAND%x/%c%lOR%x and parentheses %c%l()%x for grouping. 

%PAGE

%c%l%$Conditions may be any of the following:
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%m%lCharacters  %c-  %xOnly those specified will satisfy the lock specification, e.g:
%y%l*<NAME>        %x'%g%l%(@lock%) JC Digita's Object = *jcdigita%x'

%m%lObjects     %c-  %xOnly characters carrying the specified object(s) will be able
%y%l<NAME>         %xto satisfy the lock specification, e.g:  '%g%l%(@lock%) Lockable Exit
%y%l#<ID>          %g%l= Key%x'

%m%lFlags	    %c-  %xOnly characters with the specified flag(s) set will be able
%y%l@<FLAG>        %xto satisfy the lock specification, e.g:  '%g%l%(@lock%) Admin only
               exit = @%(apprentice%)'%]%x

%PAGE

%[%c%l%$Boolean Operators
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%9%5%y%l!  %m(%m%lNOT%m)  %c-  %xReverse condition, e.g:  '%g%l%(@lock%) Box = !*JC Digita%x' will prevent %y%lJC Digita%x from picking up the object '%y%lBox%x'.

%9%5%y%l&  %m(%m%lAND%m)  %c-  %xBoth conditions must be met to satisfy the lock, e.g:  '%g%l%(@lock%) Secure Exit = Key1&Key2%x' will prevent anyone going through it unless they are carrying the objects '%y%lKey1%x' %c%l%uAND%x '%y%lKey2%x'.

%9%5%y%l|  %m(%m%lOR%m)   %c-  %xEither condition must be met to satisfy the lock, e.g:  '%g%l%(@lock%) Exit for Joe or Fred = *Joe|*Fred%x' will allow the users %y%lJoe %c%l%uOR%x %y%lFred%x to go through the exit.%]%x

%PAGE

%c%l%$Parentheses ()
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xParentheses are used to group expressions, in a similar manner to arithmetic equations.  For example, if you wanted to make it so only male or female characters who are carrying the object '%y%lKey%x' can pass through an exit, you would use '%g%l%(@lock%) Exit = (@%(male%)|@%(female%))&Key%x' as the lock specification.


%c%l%$How locks affect different types of objects
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%9%4%y%lCommand  %c-  %xA locked compound command can only be executed by characters who satisfy its lock, e.g:  '%g%l%(@lock%) AdminCmd = @%(apprentice%)%x' allows only %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above to execute the compound command '%y%lAdminCmd%x'.

%PAGE
%9%4%y%lExit     %c-  %xA locked exit can only be used by characters who satisfy its lock, e.g:  '%g%l%(@lock%) Admin Exit = @%(apprentice%)%x' will only allow %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above to pass through the exit.

            %9%4Alternatively, if the exit has its %y%l%(OPENABLE%)%x flag set (See '%g%l%<openable flag%>%x'), the lock will determine who may open, close, lock and unlock the exit.  While the exit is open, %c%l%uANYBODY%x will be able to go through it even if they don't satisfy the lock.  When using exits that can be opened, closed, locked and unlocked, it's worthwhile setting the %y%l%(STICKY%)%x flag (See '%g%l%<sticky flag%>%x') on the exit too, so that it will automatically close and lock itself again once a user has gone through it.

%9%4%y%lFuse     %c-  %xA locked fuse will only be triggered by characters who satisfy its lock, e.g:  '%g%l%(@lock%) Test Fuse = *Fred%x' will make '%y%lTest Fuse%x' trigger for the character '%y%lFred%x' only.

%PAGE
%9%4%y%lRoom     %c-  %xA locked room will determine who can see the room's success and failure messages.  This allows you to add extra information to the room's description based on whether the lock is satisfied or not, e.g:

%[            %g%l%(@lock%) here = Key
            %(@succ%) here = The way out is blocked by a large door with a
               strong lock.  Perhaps you should try and find a key that
               will open it.
            %(@fail%) here = The way out is blocked by a large door with a strong
               lock.  Perhaps that key you picked up will open it?%]%x

            %9%4Alternatively, if the room has its %y%l%(OPENABLE%)%x flag set (See '%g%l%<openable flag%>%x', the lock will determine who may enter the room, allowing you to keep unwanted characters out of it, even if it has its %y%l%(ABODE%)%x flag set (See '%g%l%<abode flag%>%x'.)  For example, '%g%l%(@set%) here = !enterable%x' and '%g%l%(@lock%) here = !*Joe%x' will prevent the character '%y%lJoe%x' from entering your current location.

%PAGE
            %9%4In this case, the success message (See '%g%l%<@succ%>%x') will be displayed to characters who are able to successfully enter the room (The others succcess message (See '%g%l%<@osucc%>%x') is displayed to everyone else in the room.)

            %9%4The failure message (See '%g%l%<@fail%>%x') is displayed to characters who are unable to enter the room (The others failure message (See '%g%l%<@ofail%>%x') is displayed to everyone else in their current location.)

%9%4%y%lThing    %c-  %xA locked thing can only be picked up by characters who satisfy its lock, e.g:  '%g%l%(@lock%) Fred's Object = *Fred%x' will only allow the character '%y%lFred%x' to pick up '%y%lFred's Object%x'.  You can prevent anybody from picking up an object by using '%g%lme&!me%x' as the lock specification.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Success/Failure messages
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xOn compound commands, exits, things and rooms, the success and failure messages are displayed depending on whether the lock specification was satisfied or not.  These can be used to display appropriate messages to the user ('%g%l%(@succ%)%x' and '%g%l%(@fail%)%x') and other users in the same location ('%g%l%(@osucc%)%x' and '%g%l%(@ofail%)%x'.)

For further information on success and failure messages, please see '%g%l%<@succ%>%x', '%g%l%<@osucc%>%x', '%g%l%<@fail%>%x', '%g%l%<@ofail%>%x', '%g%l%<@drop%>%x' and '%g%l%<@odrop%>%x'.


%c%l%$Examples:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l@lock entrance = !*fred
@lock no exit = me&!me
@lock builders and admin only = @%(BUILDER%)|@%(APPRENTICE%)
@lock mycommand = me|*jc digita|*joe
@lock female toilets = @%(FEMALE%)
@lock xor thing = (thing1 & !thing2) | (!thing1 & thing2)%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@unlock%>%x', '%g%l%<@key%>%x', '%g%l%<@?lock%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?evallock%>%x'.

