%TOPIC @log
%TOPIC logfiles
%TOPIC readinglogfiles
%TOPIC viewinglogfiles
%COMMENT 12 log files per page
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@log%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@log [<LOGFILE>] [= reset|reopen]
        @log [<LOGFILE>] [= <PAGE>]
        @log list%]%x

The '%g%l@log%x' command is used to view your own user log file, or the various system log files maintained by %@%m (This can only be done by %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above.)

Every Builder and above has their own log file, which records when they connect/disconnect and unrecognised commands typed by users in their rooms/areas (Providing they are not of a higher level.)  Customised entries can also be written to the log file using '%g%l%(@logentry%)%x' (See '%g%l%<@logentry%>%x'.)

%y%l<LOGFILE>%x is the name of the log file to view.  If this is omitted, or '%y%lme%x' is specified, your log file will be viewed.  '%y%l*<NAME>%x' or '%y%l#<ID>%x' can be specified to view the log file of another character (Providing you are of a higher level than them.)

%PAGE
Any other name (Without '%y%l*%x' or '%y%l#%x' in front) will view %@%m system log files, if you have permission to do so (%y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above only.)  Type '%g%l@log list%x' to see a list of available system log files.

If %y%l<PAGE>%x is omitted, the most recent entries are displayed, otherwise the log file is back-tracked by %y%l<PAGE>%x pages and entries from that page are displayed, e.g:  '%g%l@log admin = 1%x' back-tracks the '%y%lAdmin%x' log file by %c%l1 page%x and lists the entries on that page.

You can reset your log file by type '%g%l@log = reset%x'.  %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above can reset the log file of a lower level character by typing '%g%l@log *<NAME> = reset%x' or '%g%l@log #<ID> = reset%x'.

%c%l%8NOTE:  %xNo backups are made of user log files.  If you reset your log file, you will lose everything that was logged in it %r%lpermanently%x.

%PAGE
%m%lDeities%x and the %m%lSupreme Being%x may reset a %@%m system log file by typing '%g%l@log <LOGFILE> = reset%x' (The log file is moved to '%y%l<LOG FILENAME>.backup%x' and a new empty log file is created.)

A log file may also be re-opened using '%g%l@log <LOGFILE> = reopen%x' (If it is normally kept open, such as the '%c%lConnect%x' log file.)


