%TOPIC @logentry
%TOPIC logentries
%TOPIC customlogentry
%TOPIC customlogentries
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@logentry%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@logentry [<LOGFILE>] = <TITLE> = <ENTRY>%]%x

The '%g%l@logentry%x' command is used to make custom entries to user and %@%m system log files.  This can only be done from within a compound command.

Every Builder and above has their own log file, which records when they connect/disconnect and unrecognised commands typed by users in their rooms/areas (Providing they are not of a higher level.)  Customised entries can also be written to the log file using '%g%l@logentry%x'.

%y%l<LOGFILE>%x is the name of the log file to make a custom entry to.  If this is omitted, or '%y%lme%x' is specified, the entry will be made to your log file.  For a list of %@%m system log files, type '%g%l%(@log%) list%x' (See '%g%l%<@log%>%x'.)

%PAGE
'%y%l*<NAME>%x' or '%y%l#<ID>%x' can be specified to make a custom entry to the log file of another character (To do this, you must have write permission to them, and the '%g%l@logentry%x' must be done under your '%g%l%(@chpid%)%x' (See '%g%l%<@chpid%>%x') within the compound command.)

%c%l%8NOTE:  %xCustom entries can only be made to %@%m system log files within a compound command with its %y%l%(^flag WIZARD%)%x flag set (See '%g%l%<wizard flag%>%x'), owned by an %y%lApprentice Wizard/%yDruid%x or above and under their '%g%l%(@chpid%)%x' (See '%g%l%<@chpid%>%x'.)

%y%l<TITLE>%x is the title of the log file entry, which must not exceed %c%l15 characters%x in length, and may only consist of alphanumeric text.

%y%l<ENTRY>%x is the text of the log file entry.

%PAGE
%c%l%8NOTE:  %x%(ANSI%) colour and text formatting codes are stripped from all custom log file entries, and the %y%l<TITLE>%x is automatically capitalised.

When viewing log files using '%g%l%(@log%)%x' (See '%g%l%<@log%>%x'), custom entries appear with a yellow title enclosed in '%y%l[]%x', e.g:  '%y%l[TITLE]:%x'.

Details of all custom log file entries made are logged to the '%y%lLogEntry%x' log file (Unless you are making a custom entry to your own log file from within one of your compound commands.)


%c%l%$Example:
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l@logentry me = MY TEST = This is a test entry in my log file.
@logentry misc = TEST = This is a test entry in the 'Misc' system log file.
@logentry *fred = FRED TEST = This a test entry in Fred's log file.%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@log%>%x', '%g%l%<@chpid%>%x' and '%g%l%<wizard flag%>%x'.

