%TOPIC @multipleexecution
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@mexec%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@mexec {<COMMAND>}[{<COMMAND>}][{<COMMAND>}...]%]%x

'%g%l@mexec%x' is used to execute multiple commands within an alias.  It can also be used to execute multiple commands in a single-lined '%g%l%(@if%)%x', '%g%l%(@case%)%x', '%g%l%(@for%)%x', '%g%l%(@with%)%x', '%g%l%(@while%)%x' or '%g%l%(@foreach%)%x' statement.  However, it is much better and neater to use the multiple-lined versions of '%g%l%(@if%)%x', '%g%l%(@case%)%x', '%g%l%(@for%)%x', etc.)


%c%l%$Example:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@alias%) gohome = @mexec \{%(@oemote%) %%g%%lheads back to %%p home.}\{%(@tel%) me = \{%(@?destination%)}}\{%(@oemote%) %%g%%larrives in %%p home.}\{%(@echo%) %%g%%lYou arrive in your home.}%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@alias%>%x', '%g%l%<@if%>%x', '%g%l%<@case%>%x', '%g%l%<@for%>%x', '%g%l%<@with%>%x', '%g%l%<@while%>%x' and '%g%l%<@foreach%>%x'.

