%TOPIC @size
%TOPIC memory
%TOPIC memoryusage
%TOPIC databasesize
%TOPIC databaseusage
%TOPIC databasememoryusage
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@size%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@size all [= yes]
        @size [<NAME>]%]%x

Displays a database memory usage summary for yourself (Or the character %y%l<NAME>%x, if %y%l<NAME>%x is specified and you're an %y%lApprentice Wizard/%yDruid%x or above.)

This command shows you how many objects of each type you own, along with the total amount of memory used by each (Uncompressed and compressed) and the compression ratio.

%PAGE
You may notice that some of the compression ratios (Especially for particular object types) are fairly low.  This is because only text (I.e:  Descriptions, etc.) can be compressed.  Integers, pointers and other object data cannot be compressed, but are taken into account by '%g%l@size%x'.  The text itself is often compressed with a ratio of 70%% or better.

%g%lElder Wizards/%gDruids%x and above may view the database memory usage summary for all objects in the entire database, using '%g%l@size all [= yes]%x' (%r%l%f%uWARNING:%x  This may cause excessive lag, because each object in the entire database needs to be decompressed  -  For this reason, the second parameter '%y%lyes%x' must be given.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@quota%>%x', '%g%l%<@stats%>%x', '%g%l%<@count%>%x', '%g%l%<@?size%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?csize%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @skip
%TOPIC skippingblocks
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@skip%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@skip%]%x

This command can only be used from within compound commands.

'%g%l@skip%x' skips the rest of the block of commands executed by a multi-lined '%g%l%(@if%)%x', '%g%l%(@case%)%x', '%g%l%(@for%)%x', '%g%l%(@with%)%x', '%g%l%(@while%)%x' or '%g%l%(@foreach%)%x'.  Unlike the '%g%l%(@breakloop%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<@breakloop%>%x'), only the rest of the block is skipped  -  Looping commands such as '%g%l%(@for%)%x', '%g%l%(@with%)%x', '%g%l%(@while%)%x' and '%g%l%(@foreach%)%x' will continue looping.

%8%c%lNOTE:  %x'%g%l@skip%x' does not change the return value or return result (Success/failure) from the previous executed command.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Example:
%~%c~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@for%) 1 to 10 do
     %(@if%) {%(@eval%) $4 = 5} do @skip
     %(@echo%) Loop number $4.
%(@end%)%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@breakloop%>%x', '%g%l%<@break%>%x', '%g%l%<@return%>%x', '%g%l%<@if%>%x', '%g%l%<@case%>%x', '%g%l%<@for%>%x', '%g%l%<@with%>%x', '%g%l%<@while%>%x' and '%g%l%<@foreach%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @sort
%TOPIC sorting
%TOPIC @sortarray
%TOPIC sortingarrays
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@sort%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@sort <ARRAY> = <ORDER> <DIRECTION> <KEY1> [<KEY2>]%]%x

'%g%l@sort%x' sorts the elements or index names of a dynamic array into alphabetical or numerical order, using efficient internal sorting algorithms.

%y%l<ARRAY>%x is the dynamic array to sort.  %y%l<ORDER>%x is the sort order, which can either be '%y%lalpha%x' (Alphabetical sort) or '%y%lnumeric%x' (Numerical sort.)  %y%l<DIRECTION>%x is the sort direction, which can either be '%y%lascending%x' or '%y%ldescending%x'.

%y%l<KEY1>%x is the primary sort key, which can either be '%y%lelements%x' (Sort dynamic array by its elements) or '%y%lindex%x' (Sort dynamic array by its index names.)  E.g:  '%g%l@sort #12345 = alpha ascending elements%x'.

%PAGE

%c%l%$The secondary key (%w%l%$[<KEY2>]%c%l%$)...
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xOptionally, a secondary sort key may be specified, which can be in any of the following forms...

%9%9%7%g%l<NUMBER> "<SEPARATOR>"  %xIf the elements/index names of the dynamic array contain a list of items, separated by a given string (E.g:  '%y%l;%x'), you can sort the dynamic array by the given item %y%l<NUMBER>%x in each element/index name.

%9%9%7                        %[%c%lE.g:  %g%l@sort #12345 = alpha ascending elements 2 ";"%]%x

%9%9%7%g%l<NUMBER>                %xFor an alphabetical sort, the elements/index names of the dynamic array will be sorted by the %y%l<NUMBER>%x'th character onwards in the element/index name.

%PAGE
%9%9%7                        For a numerical sort, the elements/index names will be sorted by the %y%l<NUMBER>%x'th numerical value in the element/index name (I.e:  '%y%l1%x' means the %c%l1st%x numerical value found in each element/index name will be taken as the sort value, '%y%l2%x' means the %c%l2nd%x numerical value found will be taken as the sort value, etc.)  If an element/index name doesn't contain any numbers, %y%l0%x is assumed as the sort value.

%9%9%7                        %[%c%lE.g:  %g%l@sort #12345 = numerical ascending elements 2%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@array%>%x', '%g%l%<@?sortalpha%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?sortnumeric%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @suffix
%TOPIC @suffixes
%TOPIC @namesuffixes
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@suffix%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@suffix <NAME> = <SUFFIX>%]%x

This command can only be used by %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above.

Sets the name suffix of the character %y%l<NAME>%x to %y%l<SUFFIX>%x.  The name suffix of a character is added to the end of their name, e.g:  '%g%l@suffix me = the greatest%x' would add '%g%lthe greatest%x' to the end of your name, i.e:  '%g%lFred Bloggs the greatest%x'.

%8%c%lNOTE:  %xA name suffix mustn't contain %c%lembedded NEWLINE's%x, and also mustn't be longer than %c%l40 characters%x.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@prefix%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?suffix%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @nat
%TOPIC @natter
%TOPIC intercom
%TOPIC nattering
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@natter%x' (Or '%w%l@nat%x') 
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[@]natter <MESSAGE>
        [@]nat <MESSAGE>%]%x

'%g%lnatter%x' (Or '%w%lnat%x' for short) is a chatting channel reserved for administrators of %@%m only (%y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above.)  Only administrators can receive messages sent over this Admin channel (Providing their %y%l%(QUIET%)%x flag isn't set, which blocks '%g%lnatter%x' messages.)

Messages can be "posed" or "%(emote%)d" in the usual manner by placing a '%y%l:%x' in front of your message, and thoughts can be expressed by using '%y%l+%x'.

'%g%lnatter%x' messages usually begin with '%m%l[DEITY]%x', '%g%l[ELDER WIZARD]%x', '%g[ELDER DRUID]%x', '%c%l[WIZARD]%x', '%c[DRUID]%x', '%y%l[APP. WIZARD]%x' or '%y[APP. DRUID]%x', depending on the status of the character sending the message.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@alias%>%x' and '%g%l%<quiet flag%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @newpass
%TOPIC @newpassword
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@newpassword%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@newpassword <NAME> = <NEW PASSWORD>%]%x

'%g%l@newpassword%x' allows %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above to change the password of any character below their level.  This is useful if a character has forgotten their password, however, you should be absolutely certain of the user's identity before doing this.  Asking the user to E-mail you their preferred new password and checking this with the E-mail address of their character is one way to check.

%8%c%lNOTE:  %xThe new password must be %c%l6%x or more characters in length.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@password%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC odrop
%TOPIC @odrop
%TOPIC otherdropmessage
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@odrop%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@odrop <OBJECT> [= <MESSAGE>]%]%x

This command sets the others drop message for the %y%l<OBJECT>%x specified.  If %y%l<MESSAGE>%x isn't specified, the others drop message is cleared.

The others drop message of a thing is displayed when a character drops the thing (After picking it up using '%g%l%(take%)%x'), and is displayed with the character's name in front on the screens of all characters in the same room.

The others drop message of a room is displayed when a character drops a thing in that room, and is displayed with the character's name in front on the screens of all characters in the same room.

The others drop message of an exit is displayed after a character has gone through the exit and arrived in its destination room, and is displayed with the character's name in front on the screens of all characters in the destination room.

%PAGE
The others drop message of a compound command is not used, and can be freely used as a '%c%lfree%x' property (See '%g%l%<@property%>%x') for storing things in.

%9%6%c%lPLEASE NOTE:  %xThe character who causes the others drop message to be displayed %c%lWILL NOT%x see the others drop message.  Instead, they will see the drop message (See '%g%l%<@drop%>%x'), if set.

If %y%l<MESSAGE>%x isn't specified, the others drop message is cleared.


%c%l%$When is the others drop message displayed?
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%9%2%y%lRoom   %c-  %xDisplayed when an object is dropped in room.

%9%2%y%lThing  %c-  %xDisplayed when object is dropped.

%9%2%y%lExit   %c-  %xDisplayed when a character goes through the exit and arrives in the exit's destination.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@drop%>%x', '%g%l%<@osucc%>%x', '%g%l%<@ofail%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?odrop%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @oecho
%TOPIC otherecho
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@oecho%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@oecho <MESSAGE>%]%x

'%g%l@oecho%x' displays %y%l<MESSAGE>%x on the screens of every character in the same room as you (Apart from your screen), %c%lWITHOUT%x your name in front.

You must either own the room you're in, or be a %c%lWizard/%cDruid%x or above to '%g%l@oecho%x' a message.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@echo%>%x', '%g%l%<@oemote%>%x', '%g%l%<@write%>%x' and '%g%l%<@areawrite%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @oemote
%TOPIC otheremote
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@oemote%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@oemote <ACTION>%]%x

'%g%l@oemote%x' is similar to '%g%l%(emote%)%x', except it only displays the action (With your name in front) on the screens of other characters in the same room as you, e.g:

%g%l@oemote won't see this message, but everyone else will.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@echo%>%x', '%g%l%<@oecho%>%x', '%g%l%<@write%>%x' and '%g%l%<@areawrite%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC ofailure
%TOPIC @ofailure
%TOPIC otherfailuremessage
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@ofail%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@ofail <OBJECT> [= <MESSAGE>]%]%x

This command sets the others failure message for the %y%l<OBJECT>%x specified.

An object fails when a character fails to satisfy its lock (If it's a room, thing or exit), or if it's a compound command, it fails when the last command executed in it fails.

If the object fails, the others failure message is displayed with the character's name in front on the screens of every character in the same room as the character who caused it to fail.

%9%6%c%lPLEASE NOTE:  %xThe character who causes the others failure message to be displayed %c%lWILL NOT%x see the others failure message.  Instead, they will see the failure message (See '%g%l%<@fail%>%x'), if set.

If %y%l<MESSAGE>%x isn't specified, the others failure message is cleared.

%PAGE

%c%l%$When is the others failure message displayed?
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%9%4%y%lCommand  %c-  %xDisplayed when the compound command finishes executing, and the last command executed failed (Not displayed if compound command has its '%g%l%(@cfailure%)%x' branch set (See '%g%l%<@cfail%>%x'.))

%9%4%y%lExit     %c-  %xDisplayed when a character is unable to go through the exit, because they are unable to satisfy its lock (In same room as the exit.)

%9%4%y%lRoom     %c-  %xDisplayed when the lock of the room is not satisfied and a character types '%g%l%(look%)%x' (Underneath the room's description), or if the room has its %y%l%(OPENABLE%)%x flag set, it is displayed when a character is unable to enter the room because they do not satisfy its lock.

%9%4%y%lThing    %c-  %xDisplayed when a character is unable to pick up the object, because they are unable to satisfy its lock.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@fail%>%x', '%g%l%<@osucc%>%x', '%g%l%<@odrop%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?ofail%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC exits
%TOPIC doors
%TOPIC @exit
%TOPIC @open
%TOPIC doorways
%TOPIC makingexits
%TOPIC openingexits
%TOPIC creatingexits
%TOPIC buildingexits
%TUTORIAL
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@open%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@open <NAME>[;<NAME>][;<NAME>...] [= <DESTINATION>]%]%x

Creates an exit with the name(s) specified (Separated by semicolons ('%y%l;%x')) (Building Quota used:  %c%l2%x.)

The first name is the full descriptive name of the exit (E.g:  '%y%lAn old wooden door%x') and is displayed in the '%y%l%$Obvious exits:%x' list of the room/container the exit's in.

The second name should be a short, abbreviated name for the exit (E.g:  '%y%lwooden%x'.)  -  This is displayed in brackets after the full descriptive name in the '%y%l%$Obvious exits:%x' list (E.g:  'An old wooden door (%g%lWooden%x)'.)  If your exit has '%y%lout%x', '%y%lback%x', '%y%lexit%x' or '%y%lleave%x' for one of its other names, this will used instead (They're standard.)

Any other names given to the exit should be the ones you think users may try to type to go through the exit (E.g:  '%y%lAn old wooden door;wooden;old;wooden door;an old;old wooden;old wooden door%x'.)

%PAGE
If %y%l<DESTINATION>%x is specified (Which must be the %y%l#<ID>%x of a room or container), the exit is linked to that room/container.

If %y%l<DESTINATION>%x isn't specified, the exit remains unlinked and can be linked using the command '%g%l%(@link%)%x'.  Unlinked exits can be linked by anyone (They become the new owner of the exit.)

The name of the exit can be changed at any time using '%g%l%(@name%)%x'.

There should be an exit in every room you build with the names '%y%lout;back;exit;leave%x' in its name, which are the standard exit names for leaving a room.  This exit should take you back to the room you expect to end up in when you leave the room.

%PAGE
By default, when an exit is created, you (And other users) will be able to see which room the exit leads to, e.g:

A Spiral Staircase (%g%l%$Up%x) leads to The Tower Top.

You can remove the '%y%lleads to <DESTINATION>%x' part by setting the %y%l%(OPAQUE%)%x flag (See '%g%l%<opaque flag%>%x') on the exit ('%g%l%(@set%) exit = %(OPAQUE%)%x'.)  This allows you to be more descriptive with your exit names, e.g:

A winding spiral staircase to the top of the tower (%g%l%$Up%x)

('%g%l%(@set%) up = %(OPAQUE%)%x', '%g%l%(@name%) up = A winding spiral staircase to the top of the tower;up;spiral;staircase;stairs;winding;tower%x')

By default, an exit is always open, and the characters who may go through the exit is determined by its lock (E.g:  '%g%l%(@lock%) <EXIT> = me|*fred%x' will only allow yourself and the character '%y%lFred%x' to go through the exit.)

%PAGE
However, an exit can be set so it can be opened, closed, locked and unlocked (Just like a container), using the '%g%l%(open%)%x', '%g%l%(close%)%x', '%g%l%(lock%)%x' and '%g%l%(unlock%)%x' commands respectively.  The lock of an exit like this determines who may lock/unlock the exit, and/or what key they require to do so (I.e:  '%g%l%(@thing%) Large doorkey%x', '%g%l%(@lock%) exit = large doorkey%x'  -  Only characters holding the object '%y%lLarge doorkey%x' may lock/unlock the exit.)

To make an exit so it can be opened, closed, locked and unlocked, you need to set its %y%l%(OPENABLE%)%x flag ('%g%l%(@set%) <EXIT> = openable%x'  -  See '%g%l%<openable flag%>%x'.)  You can also make it so the exit automatically closes after a character goes through it by setting its %y%l%(STICKY%)%x flag (E.g:  '%g%l%(@set%) <EXIT> = sticky%x'  -  See '%g%l%<sticky flag%>%x')  -  If the lock of the exit is set, the exit will also be automatically locked again too.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@link%>%x', '%g%l%<@unlink%>%x', '%g%l%<@name%>%x', '%g%l%<opaque flag%>%x', '%g%l%<openable flag%>%x', '%g%l%<sticky flag%>%x', '%g%l%<open%>%x', '%g%l%<close%>%x', '%g%l%<lock%>%x', '%g%l%<unlock%>%x' and '%g%l%<building%>%x'.

