%TITLE Help on '%w%l@password%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@password%]%x

'%g%l@password%x' allows you to change your password.

It's strongly recommended that you change your password from time to time to prevent unauthorised access to your character.  If someone manages to connect with your character, they're more than likely to do malicious things with it/to everything you've worked so hard to build.

%c%lNOTE:%x  Your password must be %y%l6 or more characters long%x.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@newpassword%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC pay
%TOPIC @pay
%TOPIC payingplayers
%TOPIC payingcharacters
%TITLE Help on '%w%lpay%x' (Or '%w%l@pay%x')
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l[@]pay <NAME> = <AMOUNT> [= account|pocket]%]%x

The '%g%lpay%x' command is used to perform transactions with other characters.  You can use it to pay credit into the pocket or bank account of another user.

%y%l<NAME>%x is the name of the user who you would like to pay and %y%l<AMOUNT>%x is the amount of credit you would like to pay to them.  For example, '%g%lpay fred bloggs = 10%x' will pay %c%l10 credits%x to the user %y%lFred Bloggs%x.

If '%y%laccount%x' is specified, the credit will be paid directly into the user %y%l<NAME>%x's bank account.  If
'%y%lpocket%x' is specified, the credit will be paid into the user's pocket.  If neither are specified, it will
be paid into the user's pocket by default (Or their bank account, if used within a compound command.)

You can also transfer credit to users directly from your bank account, by using the '%g%l%(transfer%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<transfer%>%x'.)

%PAGE

%c%l%$Example use of '%w%l%$@pay%c%l%$' within compound commands...
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xTo make a compound command which charges a user credit, simply place the following command at the beginning of your compound command, replacing %y%l<AMOUNT>%x with the amount of credits you would like to charge...

%[%g%l   %(@if%) false {@pay {%(@?owner%) {%(@?myself%)}} = <AMOUNT>} do %(@return%)%]%x

%9%4%r%lIMPORTANT:  %xIf you build compound commands which charge for their usage, you %m%l%f%uMUST%x inform the user that they will be charged and how much.  %r%lFailure to do this may result in the earnings you have unfairly earned being taken away from you.%x

For example, if you built a bar from which users could buy drinks, its description should be something like:

   %c%lA large bar, selling just about every drink you can think of.
   All drinks cost %w%l1.50 %c%lcredits.%x

%PAGE
...And the compound command which allows users to buy drinks should be something like:

%[%g%l   %(@if%) {%(@eval%) {%(@?credit%)} < 1.50} do
       %(@echo%) Sorry, you do not have enough credit to by yourself a drink.
       %(@return%)
   %(@end%)
   %(@if%) false {@pay {%(@?owner%) {%(@?myself%)}} = 1.50} do %(@return%)
   %(@echo%) You hand the bartender 1.50 credits and ask for a $1.
   %(@echo%) You down it in one go.
   %(@oemote%) orders a $1 from the bar and downs it in one.%]%x

%PAGE
You can also pay out money to users from within compound commands by using the '%g%l%(@force%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<@force%>%x') to force yourself to pay the money to them, e.g:

%[%g%l   %(@force%) {%(@?owner%) {%(@?myself%)}} = @pay *{%(@?name%) me} = 10 = pocket%]%x

...Will pay 10 credits into the pocket of the user executing the compound command the above line is placed within.

%c%l%8NOTE:  %xYou can guard against unwanted payments by using the '%g%l%(restrict%)%x' bank command (See '%g%l%<bank%>%x') to restrict the maximum payment you can make from within a compound command.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<bank%>%x', '%g%l%<transfer%>%x', '%g%l%<@credit%>%x', '%g%l%<@?credit%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?balance%>%x'.

