%TOPIC havenflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lHAVEN%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = HAVEN
        @set <OBJECT> = !HAVEN%]%x

If a room or thing is set %y%lHAVEN%x, characters will not be able to fight in that location, even if it has its %y%l%(COMBAT%)%x flag set (See '%g%l%<combat flag%>%x'.)  Ideal for creating 'safe' zones within combat areas (E.g:  Entrance to combat area.)

If a character is set %y%lHAVEN%x, no one will be able to '%g%l%(page%)%x' or '%g%l%(tell%)%x' messages to them.  Ideal if you are working on a building project and do not wish to be disturbed by other users.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<pagelock%>%x', '%g%l%<afk%>%x', '%g%l%<combat flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC helpflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lHELP%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l%(@set%) me|*<NAME> = HELP
        %(@set%) me|*<NAME> = !HELP%]%x

This flag may only be set on %r%lExperienced Builders%x and %r%lRetired Wizards/%rDruids%x by %c%lWizards/%cDruids%x and above.

The %r%lExperienced Builder%x flag (See '%g%l%<experienced flag%>%x') is given to users with expert building and coding skills.  It gives them a number of new privileges to further improve and advance their building, and lifts some of the restrictions which apply to ordinary Builders for security.

%r%lExperienced Builders%x are not required to help or give assistance to new users.  This is a requirement of %rAssistants%x (And administrators, of course), who are given the status solely for that purpose.

%PAGE
However, if an %r%lExperienced Builder%x does wish to give help and assistance, they may ask an administrator to set their %y%lHELP%x flag, which will give them the right to use the '%g%l%(welcome%)%x' and '%g%l%(assist%)%x' commands (See '%g%l%<welcome%>%x' and '%g%l%<assist%>%x') in a similar way to %rAssistants%x when too few (Or no) administrators are connected.  It also allows them to see when new users are being created and informs them of users who need welcoming/assistance.

When an %r%lExperienced Builder%x has their %y%lHELP%x flag set, the rules which apply to %r%lAssistants%x (See '%g%l%<assistant rules%>%x') also apply to them (As well as the %r%lExperienced Builder%x rules (See '%g%l%<experienced rules%>%x'.))  If you no-longer wish to give help and assistance, please ask an administrator to reset your %y%lHELP%x flag.

%PAGE
If an %r%lExperienced Builder%x abuses privileges obtained through the %y%lHELP%x flag, but not those of the %r%lExperienced Builder%x flag, their %y%lHELP%x flag can be reset, leaving them with their %r%lExperienced Builder%x privileges, to which they are still entitled.

The %y%lHELP%x flag %c%lcannot%x be set or reset on %rAssistants%x.  It is a requirement of the %rAssistant%x status to give help and assistance to new users.  If you do not wish to do this, please ask an administrator to reset your %y%lASSISTANT%x flag.

The %y%lHELP%x flag also be set on retired administrators, giving them the ability to give users help and assistance.  If a retired administrator has their %y%lHELP%x flag set, the rules which apply to %rAssistants%x also apply to them.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<experienced builder%>%x', '%g%l%<assistant%>%x', '%g%l%<welcome%>%x', '%g%l%<assist%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC fixedflag
%TOPIC staticflag
%TOPIC immovableflag
%TOPIC staticobjects
%TOPIC immovableobjects
%TITLE Help on the %w%lIMMOVABLE%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = IMMOVABLE
        @set <OBJECT> = !IMMOVABLE%]%x

This flag cannot be set/reset on characters.

When an object has its %y%lIMMOVABLE%x flag set, it cannot be moved from its present location (With the exception of the '%g%l%(junk%)%x' command  -  See '%g%l%<junk%>%x'.)  This means that object cannot be picked up, dropped or teleported to another location.

Amongst other uses, this flag is ideal for setting on things in your locations, so that other users can't pick them up and move them to other locations (Or 'steal' them.)

For things (With the exception of vehicles), you can use '%g%l%(@lock%) <OBJECT> = me%x' as an alternative to %y%lIMMOVABLE%x, which will have the same effect, except that you can set appropriate %c%lfailure%x ('%g%l%(@fail%)%x'  -  See '%g%l%<@fail%>%x') and %c%lothers failure%x ('%g%l%(@ofail%)%x'  -  See '%g%l%<@ofail%>%x') messages, which will be displayed when a user (Other than yourself) tries to pick up the thing.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<take%>%x', '%g%l%<drop%>%x', '%g%l%<kick%>%x', '%g%l%<@tel%>%x' and '%g%l%<@lock%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC inheritable
%TOPIC inheritanceflag
%TOPIC inheritableflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lINHERITABLE%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = INHERITABLE
        @set <OBJECT> = !INHERITABLE%]%x

When an object has its %y%lINHERITABLE%x flag set, any character can make it a parent of one of their own objects (Using '%g%l%(@parent%)%x'.)

See '%g%l%<@parent%>%x' for further information on inheritance.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, '%g%l%<@parent%>%x', '%g%l%<@?parent%>%x', '%g%l%<@?myleaf%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC darkflag
%TOPIC invisibleflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lINVISIBLE%x (Or %w%lDARK%x) flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = INVISIBLE
        @set <OBJECT> = !INVISIBLE%]%x

An %y%lINVISIBLE%x thing can't be seen unless you look for it.

You can't see the contents of an %y%lINVISIBLE%x room or container.

An %y%lINVISIBLE%x exit doesn't appear in the '%c%l%$Obvious exits:%x' list.

An %y%lINVISIBLE%x compound command can only be executed from within another compound command, which must have write privileges (Or write privileges picked up via '%g%l%(@chpid%)%x'  -  See '%g%l%<@chpid%>%x') to the compound command being executed.  (I.e:  An %y%lINVISIBLE%x compound command %c%lCAN'T%x be executed from the command line.)

An %y%lINVISIBLE%x fuse will not fire/trigger.

The %y%lINVISIBLE%x flag can't be set on a character.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC notify
%TOPIC inform
%TOPIC listenflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lLISTEN%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set me|*<NAME> = LISTEN
        @set me|*<NAME> = !LISTEN%]%x

If you're set %y%lLISTEN%x, you'll receive messages telling you when characters connect/disconnect.  If you're an %y%lApprentice Wizard/%yDruid%x or above, you'll also see the Internet address they're connecting from.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<fset%>%x', '%g%l%<@set%>%x' and '%g%l%<@site%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC mailflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lMAIL%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set *<NAME> = MAIL
        @set *<NAME> = !MAIL%]%x

This flag can only be set/reset by %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above.

If a character's %y%lMAIL%x flag is removed, they will no-longer be able to send and receive new mail.

If a user is abusing the mail system, removing their %y%lMAIL%x flag will prevent them from continuing to do so.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<mail%>%x', '%g%l%<mail friend flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC sex
%TOPIC males
%TOPIC maleflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lMALE%x gender flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set me|*<NAME> = MALE
        @set me|*<NAME> = !MALE%]%x

This flag represents the gender of a character.  You can set your gender by typing '%g%l%(@set%) me = male%x', '%g%l%(@set%) me = female%x' or '%g%l%(@set%) me = neuter%x'.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<female flag%>%x', '%g%l%<neuter flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC neuterflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lNEUTER%x gender flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set me|*<NAME> = NEUTER
        @set me|*<NAME> = !NEUTER%]%x

This flag represents the gender of a character.  You can set your gender by typing '%g%l%(@set%) me = male%x', '%g%l%(@set%) me = female%x' or '%g%l%(@set%) me = neuter%x'.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<male flag%>%x', '%g%l%<female flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC numberflag
%TOPIC numbersflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lNUMBER%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set me|*<NAME> = NUMBER
        @set me|*<NAME> = !NUMBER%]%x

When you set this flag on yourself, you'll no-longer see the ID numbers of objects (Even if you own them.)  This flag is useful if you want to explore your area without all those ID numbers cluttering everything up (And extremely useful to %r%lExperienced Builders%x and above, who see ID numbers of everything.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC opaqueflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lOPAQUE%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = OPAQUE
        @set <OBJECT> = !OPAQUE%]%x

This flag can only be set on things and exits.

When a thing has its %y%l%(OPAQUE%)%x flag set, its contents will not be visible to users looking at it from the outside (Unless it's a container, which is currently open.)

When an exit has it's %y%lOPAQUE%x flag set, its destination will not be shown after the exit's name in the '%c%l%$Obvious exits:%x' list of the room/container it's in (E.g:  'The Swan Pub (%g%l%$Pub%x)' instead of 'The Swan Pub (%g%l%$Pub%x) leads to The Swan Pub.')
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<look%>%x', '%g%l%<open flag%>%x', '%g%l%<openable flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC openflag
%TOPIC containers
%TOPIC openableflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lOPEN%x and %w%lOPENABLE%x flags
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = OPENABLE
        @set <OBJECT> = !OPENABLE
        @set <OBJECT> = OPEN
        @set <OBJECT> = !OPEN%]%x

The %y%lOPEN%x and %y%lOPENABLE%x flags can only be set on %c%lrooms%x, %c%lthings%x, %c%lvehicles%x and %c%lexits%x.

When the %y%lOPEN%x flag is set on a thing, it becomes a container, which can be entered by characters (Using the '%g%l%(enter%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<enter%>%x')) and objects can be placed inside (Providing it's large enough.)

When the %y%lOPEN%x flag is set on a vehicle, the vehicle can be entered by characters and driven (Using the '%g%l%(drive%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<drive%>%x')) through exits into other locations.  A vehicle which doesn't have its %y%lOPEN%x flag set can't be entered, and must be ridden (Using the '%g%l%(ride%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<ride%>%x'.))

%PAGE
When a thing or vehicle has its %y%lOPENABLE%x flag set, it can be %c%lopened%x, %c%lclosed%x, %c%llocked%x and %c%lunlocked%x (Using the '%g%l%(open%)%x', '%g%l%(close%)%x', '%g%l%(lock%)%x' and '%g%l%(unlock%)%x' commands respectively (See '%g%l%<open%>%x', '%g%l%<close%>%x', '%g%l%<lock%>%x' and '%g%l%<unlock%>%x'.))  If it's closed, characters outside it will not be able to enter it, place objects inside it or gain access to its contents.

When a thing or vehicle is locked, characters will not be able to open or close it.  In addition to this, the %c%llock key%x ('%g%l%(@key%)%x'  -  See '%g%l%<@key%>%x') of the thing/vehicle can be used to set a lock which must be satisfied in order to lock/unlock it.

%PAGE
When an exit has its %y%lOPENABLE%x flag set, it can be opened, closed, locked and unlocked in the same way as things and vehicles.  If the exit is closed, characters will not be able to pass through it.  For the exit to be locked or unlocked, its lock ('%g%l%(@lock%)%x'  -  See '%g%l%<@lock%>%x') must be satisfied.

When a room has its %y%lOPENABLE%x flag set, characters will only be able to enter the room if they are able to satisfy its lock.  This is an easy and convenient way of selectively preventing unwanted characters from entering particular rooms of yours.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, '%g%l%<open%>%x', '%g%l%<close%>%x', '%g%l%<take%>%x', '%g%l%<drop%>%x', '%g%l%<lock%>%x', '%g%l%<unlock%>%x', '%g%l%<@key%>%x', '%g%l%<@lock%>%x', '%g%l%<@volume%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC permanent
%TOPIC permanentflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lPERMANENT%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = PERMANENT
        @set <OBJECT> = !PERMANENT%]%x

This flag can only be set/reset by %r%lExperienced Builders%x, %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above.

When an object has its %y%lPERMANENT%x flag set, it can't be destroyed accidentally with '%g%l%(@destroy%)%x'.  Unlike %y%l%(READONLY%)%x, %y%lPERMANENT%x still allows you to modify fields of the object (%c%lName%x, %c%ldescription%x, etc.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<readonly flag%>%x', '%g%l%<readonlydesc flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC plurals
%TOPIC someflag
%TOPIC pluralflag
%TOPIC pluralarticleflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lPLURAL%x article flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = PLURAL
        @set <OBJECT> = !PLURAL%]%x

This flag can only be set on %c%l%(things%)%x, %c%l%(rooms%)%x, %c%l%(exits%)%x and %c%l%(characters%)%x.

When set on one of the above types of object ('%g%l%(@set%) <OBJECT> = PLURAL%x'), the object will be given the %c%lplural%x article (%y%lSome%x), e.g:

%g%l%(@set%) sweets = PLURAL          %x(Gives '%y%lSome Sweets%x'.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<consonant flag%>%x', '%g%l%<vowel flag%>%x', '%g%l%<articles%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC privateflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lPRIVATE%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = PRIVATE
        @set <OBJECT> = !PRIVATE%]%x

When an object (Except a character) has its %y%lPRIVATE%x flag set, it can only be examined by its owner and characters of a higher level.

%7%c%lE.g:  %xIf an %y%lApprentice Wizard/%yDruid%x sets a compound command to %y%lPRIVATE%x, only themselves and %c%lWizards/%cDruids%x and above can examine it.

If a character has their %y%lPRIVATE%x flag set, it will temporarily disable the ability of their friends with the %y%l%(^friend VISIT%)%x friend flag (See '%g%l%<fset%>%x') set to visit them at will (Using the '%g%l%(visit%)%x' command  -  See '%g%l%<visit%>%x'.)  Ideal for when you are holding a private conversation or simply don't want to be disturbed.

%8%c%lNOTE:  %xQuery commands (Such as '%g%l{%(@?desc%)}%x', '%g%l{%(@?drop%)}%x', etc.) are also subject to the restrictions imposed by the %y%lPRIVATE%x flag.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<fset%>%x', '%g%l%<visit%>%x', '%g%l%<visit friend flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC quietflag
%TOPIC peaceflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lQUIET%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = QUIET
        @set <OBJECT> = !QUIET%]%x

This flag can only be set on characters, rooms and things.

When set on yourself ('%g%l%(@set%) me = quiet%x'), you'll no-longer hear shouts (With the exception of important broadcast messages), yells and messages broadcast up the area tree using '%g%l%(@areawrite%)%x'.  If you're a %y%lApprentice Wizard/%yDruid%x or above, you'll no-longer receive messages over the '%g%l%(natter%)%x' channel.

Setting yourself %y%lQUIET%x and %y%l%(!LISTEN%)%x (See '%g%l%<listen flag%>%x') allows you to build almost completely undisturbed (Except for pages and tells (You can stop these too by setting yourself %y%l%(HAVEN%)%x ('%g%l%(@set%) me = haven%x'  -  See '%g%l%<haven flag%>%x')) and messages from other characters in the same room (Unless the room is set %y%lQUIET%x too.))

When set on a room/thing, characters will no-longer be able to talk to each other in that room.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<listen flag%>%x', '%g%l%<haven flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC readonlyflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lREADONLY%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = READONLY
        @set <OBJECT> = !READONLY%]%x

This flag can only be set/reset by %r%lExperienced Builders%x, %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above.

When an object has its %y%lREADONLY%x flag set, it can't be altered in any way or destroyed (Even by higher level characters) until the flag is removed by either the object's owner or a higher level character.

%r%lExperienced Builders%x cannot reset the %y%lREADONLY%x flag on a compound command which has its %y%l%(VALIDATED%)%x flag set (See '%g%l%<validated flag%>%x'.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<readonlydesc flag%>%x', '%g%l%<permanent flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC readonlydescflag
%TOPIC readonlydescriptionflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lREADONLYDESC%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = READONLYDESC
        @set <OBJECT> = !READONLYDESC%]%x

This flag (Which can be set on any object type (Except %c%l%(fuses%)%x, %c%l%(arrays%)%x and %c%l%(alarms%)%x)) makes the description and outside description of an object read-only, so that they can't be modified in any way without removing the flag again first.

Unlike the %y%l%(READONLY%)%x and %y%l%(PERMANENT%)%x flags, this flag %c%lDOES NOT%x stop the object from being destroyed, or any of its other fields being modified.

You should set this flag on compound commands and objects which are complete to safeguard them from accidental modification (I.e:  If you (Or a %c%lWizard/%cDruid%x and above for that matter) accidentally get the #ID number wrong when using '%g%l%(@desc%)%x'/'%g%l%(@odesc%)%x' (See '%g%l%<@desc%>%x' and '%g%l%<@odesc%>%x'.))
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<readonly flag%>%x', '%g%l%<permanent flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC secret
%TOPIC secretflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lSECRET%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = SECRET
        @set <OBJECT> = !SECRET%]%x

This flag can only be set on characters, rooms and things.

You can hide yourself by setting your %y%lSECRET%x flag ('%g%l%(@set%) me = secret%x')  -  This will hide your current location on the '%g%l%(where%)%x' list, '%g%l%(scan%)%x', '%g%l%(page%)%x', etc. from other users of the same or lower level.  You can remove your %y%lSECRET%x flag by typing '%g%l%(@set%) me = !secret%x'.

The %y%lSECRET%x flag may also be set on rooms and things to make them secret, hiding the location of all characters who are currently inside them.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<where%>%x', '%g%l%<scan%>%x', '%g%l%<page%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC homeflag
%TOPIC sendhome
%TOPIC gohomeflag
%TOPIC sendhomeflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lSENDHOME%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = SENDHOME
        @set <OBJECT> = !SENDHOME%]%x

This flag can only be set on objects.

If an object has its %y%lSENDHOME%x flag set, it will be moved to its home location each time %@%m restarts (After shutdown or a crash.)  You can use this flag to ensure that objects eventually return to a set starting location.

For example, you may have objects in your areas which can be picked up and taken away by other users.  To ensure that they don't get dropped somewhere out of the way, where they will probably never be found or looked at again, you can set this flag on them.

The %y%lSENDHOME%x flag is an ideal alternative to the %y%l%(STICKY%)%x flag (See '%g%l%<sticky flag%>%x'), which only sends an object home if it's picked up and then dropped.  %y%lSENDHOME%x also allows the user carrying the object to drop it anywhere they like, without it being (Annoyingly) sent back to its home location.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<sticky flag%>%x', '%g%l%<@link%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC sharableflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lSHARABLE%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = SHARABLE
        @set <OBJECT> = !SHARABLE%]%x

This flag can be set on any type of object, except characters.
 
If a character has been given '%c%lread%x'/'%c%lwrite%x' permissions to your objects via the %y%l%(^friend READ%)%x/%y%l%(^friend WRITE%)%x friend flags, but has also been given the %y%l%(^friend SHARABLE%)%x friend flag, their extra privileges will only apply to objects which have their %y%lSHARABLE%x flag set (Allowing you to keep a tight control on which objects of yours they may examine, modify, destroy, etc.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<sharable friend flag%>%x', '%g%l%<read friend flag%>%x', '%g%l%<write friend flag%>%x', '%g%l%<group building%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC skipobjects
%TOPIC skipobjectflag
%TOPIC skipobjectsflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lSKIPOBJECTS%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = SKIPOBJECTS
        @set <OBJECT> = !SKIPOBJECTS%]%x

This flag can only be set on rooms and things.

When set, any compound commands in the room/thing, or attached to an object which is then dropped within the room/thing will be ignored (Unless owned by the owner of the room, the character executing the compound command or the compound command is Admin owned or has its %y%l%(WIZARD%)%x flag set.)

The %y%lSKIPOBJECTS%x flag is mainly intended for public locations to prevent malicious users from inconveniencing or hacking other users within the room/thing with a compound command (Attached to an object dropped within the room/thing) which shadows a built-in command (Such as '%g%l%(say%)%x', '%g%l%(page%)%x', '%g%l%(tell%)%x', '%g%l%(whisper%)%x', etc.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<wizard flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC stickyflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lSTICKY%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = STICKY
        @set <OBJECT> = !STICKY%]%x

This flag can only be set on %c%lthings%x, %c%lrooms%x, %c%lexits%x and %c%lfuses%x.

A thing with its %y%lSTICKY%x flag set will go straight to its home location (Set using '%g%l%(@link%)%x'  -  See '%g%l%<@link%>%x') when dropped.

The drop-to (Set using '%g%l%(@link%)%x') of a room with its %y%lSTICKY%x flag set will be delayed until the last connected character leaves the room.  When the last connected character leaves the room, all objects dropped there (Except objects which have their home set to the room and their %y%lSTICKY%x flag set) will be sent to the drop-to location.

If an %y%l%(OPENABLE%)%x (See '%g%l%<openable flag%>%x') exit has its %y%l%(STICKY%)%x flag set, the exit will automatically close after a character goes through it.  If the lock of the exit is set, the exit will also automatically lock.

%PAGE
The 'triggering' of a fuse with its %y%lSTICKY%x flag set will be delayed until the command which the user who triggered it typed has finished executing (E.g:  A %y%l%(TOM%)%x (See '%g%l%<tom flag%>%x') and %y%lSTICKY%x fuse in a room will not trigger until a character moves in that room and has arrived in their destination room.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@link%>%x', '%g%l%<@open%>%x', '%g%l%<openable flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC tomflag
%TOPIC triggeronmovementflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lTOM%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <FUSE> = TOM
        @set <FUSE> = !TOM%]%x

%y%lTOM%x stands for %c%lTrigger On Movement%x.  This flag can only be set on fuses.

It causes the fuse to trigger only when movement occurs in the room or container it's in, instead of whenever a command is typed by a character.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@fuse%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC trace
%TOPIC tracing
%TOPIC traceflag
%TOPIC tracingflag
%TOPIC tracesequence
%TITLE Help on the %w%lTRACING%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set me|<COMMAND>|*<NAME> = TRACING
        @set me|<COMMAND>|*<NAME> = !TRACING%]%x

When you set yourself %y%lTRACING%x ('%g%l%(@set%) me = tracing%x'), a trace sequence is displayed whenever any of your compound commands are executed (Either by yourself or another character.)

Setting yourself %y%lTRACING%x will usually result in a lot of output (Especially if other characters are executing your compound commands.)  As an alternative, you can set %c%lINDIVIDUAL%x compound commands %y%lTRACING%x ('%g%l%(@set%) <COMMAND> = tracing%x'), so you only see a trace sequence when those compound commands are executed.

For each line executed by a compound command, you'll see the following trace sequence...

%[%c[%y%l%unnn%c]  %g%l<COMMAND>  %m%l(%uEXEC%m%l)
%c(%w%l%unnn%c)  %y%l<COMMAND>  %g%l(%uSUCC%g%l)%c/%r%l(%uFAIL%r%l)%]

%PAGE
The numbers in brackets ('%c[%y%l%unnn%c]%x' and '%c(%w%l%unnn%c)%x') tell you which line number of the compound command is currently being executed.  The '%c[%y%l%unnn%c]  %g%l<COMMAND>  %m%l(%uEXEC%m%l)%x' line shows you the complete command line before the '%y%l{}%x's in it are evaluated and expanded.

The following '%c(%w%l%unnn%c)  %y%l<COMMAND>  %g%l(%uSUCC%g%l)%c/%r%l(%uFAIL%r%l)%x' lines show the result(s) of evaluating and expanding the commands in '%y%l{}%x's (If present), followed by the final result of executing the fully expanded line.  '%g%l(%uSUCC%g%l)%x' means that the command succeeded, and '%r%l(%uFAIL%r%l)%x' means it failed.

%8%c%lHINT:  %xYou can turn the trace sequence on and off at will from within a compound command by simply inserting the commands '%g%l%(@set%) {%(@?myself%)} = tracing%x' and '%g%l%(@set%) {%(@?myself%)} = !tracing%x' to switch tracing on/off respectively.  Using this method, you can cut the output from the trace sequence down significantly.

%8%c%lNOTE:  %xIf you are building under the ID of another character ('%g%l%(@chuid%)%x'  -  See '%g%l%<@chuid%>%x'), you will also receive trace sequences for any of their compound commands which are set %y%lTRACING%x.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@command%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC cars
%TOPIC vehicles
%TOPIC transport
%TOPIC automobiles
%TOPIC transporting
%TOPIC transportation
%TITLE Help on %w%ltransport%x (Vehicles)...
A vehicle is a thing which has its %y%l%(TRANSPORT%)%x flag set (See '%g%l%<transport flag%>%x'.)  Once this flag is set, the object becomes a vehicle and can no-longer be picked up, dropped, etc. (As with ordinary things.)

If the thing is a container, it becomes a vehicle which can be entered (I.e:  A %c%lcar%x, %c%llorry%x (%c%lTruck%x), etc.) and then driven through exits in its current location (Using the '%g%l%(drive%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<drive%>%x'), e.g:  '%g%l%(drive%) south%x'.)  You can also look at the vehicle's present location by typing '%g%l%(look%) outside%x'.

If the thing is not a container, it becomes a vehicle which can be ridden (I.e:  A %c%lmotorcycle%x, %c%lhorse%x, etc.) through exits in its current location (Using the '%g%l%(ride%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<ride%>%x'), e.g:  '%g%l%(ride%) horse = south%x'.)

%PAGE
The %y%l%(TRANSPORT%)%x flag also determines where vehicles can be driven/ridden.  When driving/riding a vehicle using the '%g%l%(drive%)%x' and '%g%l%(ride%)%x' commands, you must specify a destination, which can either be an %c%lexit name%x (In the vehicle's current location) or a %c%lroom #<ID>%x (I.e:  %y%l%(ABODE%)%x room  -  See '%g%l%<abode flag%>%x'.)

In order to use any of the above destinations (%c%lExit%x or %c%lroom%x), they must have their %y%l%(TRANSPORT%)%x flag set.  In addition to this, the destination room must also have its %y%l%(TRANSPORT%)%x flag set.

%PAGE
To drive/ride a vehicle, the character attempting to drive/ride it must be able to satisfy its lock (I.e:  If you lock the vehicle to yourself ('%g%l%(@lock%) <VEHICLE> = me%x'  -  See '%g%l%<@lock%>%x'), only you will be able to drive/ride it.)

If the vehicle's lock isn't satisfied, the %c%lfail message%x ('%g%l%(@fail%)%x'  -  See '%g%l%<@fail%>%x') is displayed to the driver/rider, and the %c%lothers failure message%x ('%g%l%(@ofail%)%x'  -  See '%g%l%<@ofail%>%x') is displayed to everyone in the vehicle's location.  If the vehicle is a container (Which must be entered before it can be driven), the %c%lothers failure message%x is also displayed to everyone inside the vehicle itself (Except the driver.)

%PAGE
On driving/riding the vehicle, its %c%lsuccess message%x ('%g%l%(@succ%)%x'  -  See '%g%l%<@succ%>%x') is displayed to the driver/rider, and the %c%lothers success message%x ('%g%l%(@osucc%)%x'  -  See '%g%l%<@osucc%>%x') is displayed to everyone in the vehicle's location.  If the vehicle is a container, the %c%lothers success message%x is also displayed to everyone inside the vehicle itself (Except the driver.)

On successfully reaching the destination location, its %c%ldrop message%x ('%g%l%(@drop%)%x'  -  See '%g%l%<@drop%>%x') is displayed to the driver/rider, and the %c%lothers drop message%x ('%g%l%(@odrop%)%x'  -  See '%g%l%<@odrop%>%x') is displayed to everyone in the destination location.  If the vehicle is a container, the %c%lothers drop message%x is also displayed to everyone inside the vehicle itself (Except the driver.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<drive%>%x', '%g%l%<ride%>%x' and '%g%l%<transport flag%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC vehicleflag
%TOPIC transportflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lTRANSPORT%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = TRANSPORT
        @set <OBJECT> = !TRANSPORT%]%x

This flag can only be set/reset on objects.

If a thing has its %y%lTRANSPORT%x flag set, it becomes a mode of transport (E.g:  %c%lCar%x, %c%lmotorcycle%x, %c%lhorse%x, etc.)  This vehicle can then be 'driven' using the '%g%l%(drive%)%x' or '%g%l%(ride%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<drive%>%x' and '%g%l%<ride%>%x'.)

If a room has its %y%lTRANSPORT%x flag reset, vehicles will not be allowed in that room (I.e:  A street would have its %y%lTRANSPORT%x flag set, but a bedroom, kitchen, swimming pool, etc. would not.)

If an exit has its %y%lTRANSPORT%x flag reset, then vehicles will not be able to go through it (I.e:  A road leading north would have its %y%lTRANSPORT%x flag set, but a footpath would not.)

A vehicle cannot be 'driven' into another thing.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<transport%>%x', '%g%l%<drive%>%x', '%g%l%<ride%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC validating
%TOPIC validateflag
%TOPIC validatedflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lVALIDATED%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <COMMAND> = VALIDATED
        @set <COMMAND> = !VALIDATED%]%x

This flag can only be set/reset by %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above.

If a Mortal owned compound command is made global, it must also have its %y%lVALIDATED%x flag set, otherwise it will be ignored by the global search phase.  This flag prevents Mortals who already own global compound commands (Which have been authorised by Admin) from teleporting unauthorised compound commands into them, which would allow the Mortal to make unauthorised compound commands global.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC visibleflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lVISIBLE%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = VISIBLE
        @set <OBJECT> = !VISIBLE%]%x

If an object has its %y%lVISIBLE%x flag set, other characters can examine it at their leisure (Being able to see everything (%g%l%(@desc%)%x, %g%l%(@succ%)%x, %g%l%(@fail%)%x, etc.))

Useful for sharing your coding knowledge with others.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<examine%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC visitflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lVISIT%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = VISIT
        @set <OBJECT> = !VISIT%]%x

This flag can only be set/reset on rooms and things.

When a room or thing has its %y%lVISIT%x flag reset, users will not be able to visit other characters (Using the '%g%l%(visit%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<visit%>%x')) when they are in that location, regardless of whether the room/thing has its %y%l%(ABODE%)%x flag (See '%g%l%<abode flag%>%x') set or not.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<visit%>%x', '%g%l%<visit friend flag%>%x', '%g%l%<abode flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC anflag
%TOPIC vowels
%TOPIC vowelflag
%TOPIC vowelarticleflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lVOWEL%x article flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = VOWEL
        @set <OBJECT> = !VOWEL%]%x

This flag can only be set on %c%l%(things%)%x, %c%l%(rooms%)%x, %c%l%(exits%)%x and %c%l%(characters%)%x.

When set on one of the above types of object ('%g%l%(@set%) <OBJECT> = VOWEL%x'), the object will be given the %c%lvowel%x article (%y%lAn%x), e.g:

%g%l%(@set%) orange = VOWEL          %x(Gives '%y%lAn Orange%x'.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<plural flag%>%x', '%g%l%<consonant flag%>%x', '%g%l%<articles%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC warpflag
%TOPIC warpingflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lWARP%x flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = WARP
        @set <OBJECT> = !WARP%]%x

This flag can only be set/reset on rooms and things.

When a room or thing has its %y%lWARP%x flag reset, users will never be teleported to that location by the '%g%l%(warp%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<warp%>%x'), regardless of whether the room/thing has its %y%lABODE%x flag set or not.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<warp%>%x', '%g%l%<abode flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC yellflag
%TOPIC shoutflag
%TOPIC broadcastingmessages
%TITLE Help on the %w%lYELL%x and %w%lSHOUT%x flags
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@set <OBJECT> = YELL|SHOUT
        @set <OBJECT> = !YELL|!SHOUT%]%x

%c%lPLEASE NOTE:  %xThe %y%lSHOUT%x flag is an alias for the %y%lYELL%x flag.

When set on a room or container, the %y%lYELL%x flag allows any character with a %y%lYELL%x flag to yell messages to other characters on your property.

Only %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above may set/reset a (Lower level) character's %y%lYELL%x flag.  If an %y%lApprentice Wizard/%yDruid%x or above's %y%lYELL%x flag is removed, they will no-longer be able to shout messages (Using '%g%l%(shout%)%x'.)

Newly created rooms and characters always start off with their %y%lYELL%x flag set as default.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<yell%>%x', '%g%l%<shout%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @shutdown
%TOPIC closedown
%TOPIC shuttingdown
%TOPIC emergencyshutdown
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@shutdown%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@shutdown <REASON> = <TIME>
        @shutdown cancel%]%x

This command can only be used by %m%lDeities%x and the %m%lSupreme Being%x.

'%g%l@shutdown%x' starts the server shutdown sequence, which once %y%l<TIME>%x (In minutes) has expired, shuts down %@%n in a controlled manner and dumps the database to disk, e.g:  '%g%l@shutdown for a code update = 5%x' shuts down %@%m after %c%l5 minutes%x of warnings to all connected users.

The shutdown sequence can be %c%lcancelled%x at any time by typing '%g%l@shutdown cancel%x'.  Only the %m%lSupreme Being%x can specify a value of less than %y%l5%x for %y%l<TIME>%x.

From time to time, the system administrator(s) may need to shutdown %@%n (For code updates, server maintenance, etc.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<admin%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @cont
%TOPIC @count
%TOPIC @contents
%TOPIC contentstotals
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@contents%x' (Or '%w%l@count%x')
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@contents <OBJECT> [= <NAME>]
        @count <OBJECT> [= <NAME>]%]%x

Displays the total amount of each different type of object that %y%l<OBJECT>%x contains (Characters, rooms, things, etc.)  The totals include objects carried by characters within %y%l<OBJECT>%x and the contents of rooms, things, etc. within %y%l<OBJECT>%x.

If you're an %y%lApprentice Wizard/%yDruid%x or above, you can specify the name of a character for the optional second parameter ('%y%l= <NAME>%x'.)  This has the effect of listing the contents totals of %y%l<OBJECT>%x in relation to the character %y%l<NAME>%x rather than yourself.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@stats%>%x', '%g%l%<@quota%>%x' and '%g%l%<@size%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @continue
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@continue%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@continue%]%x

If used within the compound command executed by a fuse with its %y%l%(ABORT%)%x flag set (See '%g%l%<abort flag%>%x'), '%g%l@continue%x' will prevent the effects of the %y%l%(ABORT%)%x flag (I.e:  Prevent the fuse from aborting the command which triggered the fuse's execution.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@fuse%>%x' and '%g%l%<abort flag%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @stat
%TOPIC @stats
%TOPIC @statscon
%TOPIC @statscmd
%TOPIC @statstcz
%TOPIC @statsband
%TOPIC @statshtml
%TOPIC @statsconn
%TOPIC @statschars
%TOPIC @statistics
%TOPIC @statstelnet
%TOPIC @statsusages
%TOPIC @statsothers
%TOPIC @statscommands
%TOPIC @statsbandwidth
%TOPIC @statsresources
%TOPIC @statscharacters
%TOPIC @statsconnections
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@stats%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@stats bandwidth|cmd|chars|connections|resource|tcz
        @stats other [<NAME>]
        @stats [<NAME>]%]%x

'%g%l@stats%x' displays how many of each different type of object you own, and the percentage out of the total number of each type in the %@%m database.

'%g%l@stats other%x' displays other statistics for non-objects in the database, such as %c%lfriends/enemies%x, %c%lBBS messages%x, %c%lmail%x, etc., and the percentage of the total in the entire database.  The following statistics are shown:

%[%y%lFriends/enemies   %xNumber of %(friends%)/%(enemies%) list entries you have.
%y%lArray elements    %xNumber of %(dynamic array%) elements you have.
%y%lBBS sub-topics    %xNumber of %(BBS%) %(^bbs sub-topics%) you own.
%y%lBBS messages      %xNumber of %(BBS%) %(^bbs messages%) you currently have posted.
%y%lBBS readers       %xNumber of %(BBS%) %(^bbs messages%) you have read from those on BBS.
%y%lBBS topics        %xNumber of %(BBS%) %(^bbs topics%) you own.
%y%lMail items        %xNumber of items of %(mail%) you have (Not yet implemented.)
%y%lAliases           %xNumber of %(aliases%) you have.%]

%PAGE
For the above two forms of '%g%l@stats%x' ('%g%l@stats%x' and '%g%l@stats other%x'), an optional character name may be specified.  This allows %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above to view the statistics of other characters.

%c%lThe following forms of '%g%l@stats%c%l' may only be used by %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%c%l and above...%x

'%g%l@stats bandwidth%x' displays a summary of bandwidth used by %@%n  -  The total number of bytes of data transmitted and received since it was last restarted are displayed, along with the average per day, hour and second.

%PAGE
'%g%l@stats cmd%x' displays command execution statistics (Since %@%m server was restarted.)  The total number of %c%luser-typed%x (At the '%@%m>' prompt), %c%lstandard%x (E.g:  '%g%l@%x' and '%g%l@?%x' commands), %c%leditor%x and %c%lcompound commands%x executed are displayed along with averages per second, minute, hour and day.

'%g%l@stats char%x' displays how many characters and puppets there are in the %@%m database, and how many of these are %b%lMorons%x, Mortals, Builders, %r%lExperienced Builders/%rAssistants%x, %r%lRetired Wizards/%rDruids%x, %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x, %c%lWizards/%cDruids%x, %g%lElder Wizards/%gDruids%x and %m%lDeities%x along with a percentage for each (Out of the total number of characters.)

%PAGE
'%g%l@stats connections%x' displays a summary of current %c%lTelnet%x and %c%lHTML%x (See '%g%l%<html%>%x') connections (Both normal unencrypted and %m%l%(SSL%)%x (%m%lSecure Socket Layer%x.))  The information displayed is as follows:

%9%7%y%lTotal          %xTotal number of connections.
%9%7%y%lPending        %xNew connection (User has not connected a character yet.)
%9%7%y%lActive         %xActive connection with connected character.
%9%7%y%lDelayed        %xActive connection with processing of next command delayed by more than %c%l3 seconds%x (Each time a user executes a command, their next command will be delayed by the time it took to execute.  This helps prevent users maliciously or accidentally 'lagging' %@%m by repetitively executing intensive commands/compound commands.)
%9%7%y%lDisconnected   %xLost connection (If a user disconnects without typing %g%l%(QUIT%)%x or clicking the %y%lLOGOUT%x button of the World Wide Web Interface (See '%g%l%<html%>%x'), their connection will remain open for %c%l5 minutes%x to allow them to reconnect and resume where they left off.)
%9%7%c%lInput          %xConnection has pending input (Queued user commands.)
%9%7%c%lOutput         %xConnection has pending output.

%PAGE
'%g%l@stats resource%x' displays the resource usages on %@%m's server (CPU usage, memory usage, etc.)

'%g%l@stats tcz%x' displays %@%m server statistics, which is a log of the last %y%l14 days%x, detailing the %c%lpeak number of users%x, %c%lusers connected/created%x, %c%lobjects created/destroyed%x, etc. for each day.  For each category the %c%ldaily average%x, %c%lmaximum%x and %c%ltotal%x are also displayed.  These statistics are also logged daily to the '%y%lStats%x' log file (See '%g%l%<@log%>%x.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@quota%>%x', '%g%l%<@size%>%x' and '%g%l%<@count%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @succ
%TOPIC @success
%TOPIC successmessage
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@succ%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@succ <OBJECT> [= <MESSAGE>]%]%x

This command sets the success message for the %y%l<OBJECT>%x specified.

An object succeeds when a character manages to satisfy its lock (If it's a room, thing or exit), or if it's a compound command, it succeeds when the last command executed in it succeeds.

If the object succeeds, the success message is displayed on the screen of the character who caused it to succeed.

If %y%l<MESSAGE>%x isn't specified, the success message is cleared.

%PAGE

%c%l%$When is the success message displayed?
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%9%4%y%lCommand  %c-  %xDisplayed when the compound command finishes executing, and the last command executed succeeded (Not displayed if compound command has its '%g%l%(@csuccess%)%x' branch set (See '%g%l%<@csucc%>%x'.))

%9%4%y%lExit     %c-  %xDisplayed when a character goes through the exit (In the same room as exit.)

%9%4%y%lRoom     %c-  %xDisplayed when the lock of the room is satisfied and a character types '%g%l%(look%)%x' (Underneath the room's description), or if the room has its %y%l%(OPENABLE%)%x flag set (See '%g%l%<openable flag%>%x'), it is displayed when a character successfully enters the room.

%9%4%y%lThing    %c-  %xDisplayed when object is picked up.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@osucc%>%x', '%g%l%<@fail%>%x', '%g%l%<@drop%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?succ%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC @temp
%TOPIC @label
%TOPIC @local
%TOPIC @desttemp
%TOPIC @temporary
%TOPIC @desttemporary
%TOPIC localvariables
%TOPIC temporaryvariables
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@temp%x' and '%w%l@desttemp%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@temp <NAME> [= <DESCRIPTION>]
        @desttemp <NAME>%]%x

'%g%l@temp%x' sets the description of temporary variable %y%l<NAME>%x (If a temporary variable with the name specified doesn't exist, one is created.)  Temporary variables can be destroyed using the '%g%l@desttemp%x' command.

Temporary variables can only be created from within compound commands.  Their primary use is for temporary storage, use as counters, etc.

Once created, a temporary variable is accessible throughout the rest of the compound command it was created within and all compound commands called from that compound command (Via csuccess/cfailure, '%g%l%(@if%)%x', '%g%l%(@case%)%x', '%g%l%(@for%)%x', '%g%l%(@with%)%x', '%g%l%(@while%)%x', etc.), with the exception of compound commands owned by another character.

You can reference a temporary variable using %y%l$<NAME>%x, e.g:  If you have created a temporary variable called '%y%lstore%x' (E.g:  '%g%l@temp store = <DESCRIPTION>%x'), you can echo its current description using '%g%l%(@echo%) $store%x'.

%PAGE
All temporary variables created within compound command(s) are destroyed automatically when all of the commands have finished executing.  However, Mortals are restricted to a maximum of %c%l100%x temporary variables defined simultaneously, so you should destroy any temporary variables which are no-longer needed throughout the rest of the compound command(s).

%y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above are restricted to %c%l250%x temporary variables.  %g%lElder Wizards/%gDruids%x and above are not restricted.

%9%7%m%lReturn value:  %x'%g%l@temp%x' returns %y%l<DESCRIPTION>%x as its return value, rather than %c%l%(OK%)%x/%c%l%(Error%)%x, i.e:  '%g%l@echo {@temp test = {@eval 3 * 10}}%x' will echo '%y%l30%x' to your screen and store '%y%l30%x' in the temporary variable '%y%ltest%x'.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Example compound command:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@command%) TempTest =\
@temp name = \{%(@?namec%) $3}\
