%TOPIC @recover
%TOPIC @undestroy
%TOPIC recoveringobjects
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@undestroy%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@undestroy list [<PAGE NO>] [<NAME>] [= <OBJECT TYPES>] [= <OWNER>]
        @undestroy #<ID> [#<ID>] [...] [= <NEW OWNER>]%]%x

The '%g%l@undestroy%x' command allows you to recover objects which have recently been destroyed (I.e:  If you accidentally destroy the wrong object by typing its ID number incorrectly, or destroy an object and then decide otherwise.)


%c%l%$Listing destroyed objects...
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@undestroy list [<PAGE NO>] [<NAME>] [= <OBJECT TYPES>] [= <OWNER>]%]%x

The first form allows you to list objects on the queue of destroyed objects.  This allows you to browse through the list and see which objects you may recover, along with the original ID number of each object, which you will need in order to recover any destroyed objects.

%PAGE
If %y%l<PAGE NO>%x is specified, that page of destroyed objects will be displayed, e.g:  '%g%l@undestroy list 1%x', '%g%l@undestroy list 2%x', etc.

If %y%l<NAME>%x is specified, destroyed objects which contain the text %y%l<NAME>%x in their name will only be listed, e.g:  '%g%l@undestroy list bedroom%x'.

%y%l<OBJECT TYPES>%x is the types of objects to list (By default, all object types are listed, e.g:  '%g%l@undestroy list = things rooms%x' will list destroyed %c%l%(things%)%x and %c%l%(rooms%)%x only, '%g%l@undestroy list = properties%x' will list destroyed %c%l%(properties%)%x only, etc.

If %y%l<OWNER>%x is specified, destroyed objects which were originally owned by the character %y%l<OWNER>%x will only be listed, providing you are an %r%lExperienced Builder%x or above.

%PAGE

%c%l%$Recovering destroyed objects...
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@undestroy #<ID> [#<ID>] [...] [= <NEW OWNER>]%]%x

The second form allows you to recover a destroyed object (Or several destroyed objects, if more than one ID number is specified.)

When an object is recovered from the queue of destroyed objects, '%g%l@undestroy%x' will attempt to restore the original fields of the object, along with %c%lCSUCC/CFAIL%x links, %c%lhome%x, %c%ldestination%x, %c%lparent%x, %c%llock%x, etc.  Any destroyed objects which are still in the queue of destroyed objects and were originally located in or attached to the recovered object will also be recovered, and re-attached to the recovered object.  If the object's original ID number is still available, it will be allocated that ID number again, otherwise a new (Unused) ID number will be allocated to it.

%PAGE
To recover an object, its original ID number must be specified (If you are unusure what its original ID number was, you can use '%g%l@undestroy list%x' to find out), e.g:  You destroyed object '%y%lMy Bedroom(#12345 RHy)%x'  -  To recover this object, you'd type '%g%l@undestroy #12345%x'.

If %y%l<NEW OWNER>%x is specified, the owner of the recovered object(s) will be changed to the character %y%l<NEW OWNER>%x, providing you have '%c%lwrite%x' permission to them, and they have sufficient Building Quota.

%PAGE
%9%6%c%lPLEASE NOTE:  %xDestroyed objects are placed on a queue, which is of a finite size (Presently %y%l100%x objects may be on the queue at any one time.)  If the queue is full, then the oldest objects on it are permanently destroyed to make room for newly destroyed objects.  If you accidentally destroy an object, please try to recover it as soon as possible, otherwise it may drop off the end of the queue and be lost (Destroyed) permanently.

              %9%6You must have sufficient Building Quota to recover a destroyed object.  If you do not have sufficient Building Quota, the object and/or objects which were originally attached to it may not be recovered.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@destroy%>%x' and '%g%l%<@quota%>%x'.

