%TOPIC vars
%TOPIC @var
%TOPIC variables
%TOPIC @variable
%TOPIC makingvariables
%TOPIC creatingvariables
%TOPIC buildingvariables
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@variable%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@variable <NAME> [= <INITIAL SETTING>]
        @var <NAME> [= <INITIAL SETTING>]%]%x

Creates a variable called %y%l<NAME>%x attached to yourself (Building Quota used:  %c%l5%x.)  If %y%l<INITIAL SETTING>%x is specified, the description of the variable is set to that.

Unlike properties which only have a description, variables have all %c%l8 standard fields%x (Description, success, failure, drop, etc.)  Because of this, variables use more Building Quota than properties  -  You should only use variables if you can use most of their fields for useful storage  -  Use a property instead if you only need to use one field.

You can attach a variable to almost any other object (As long as you own/control it) by using '%g%l%(drop%)%x' or '%g%l%(@tel%)%x'.  You can even drop variables within variables.

%PAGE
When a variable is on yourself, you can substitute it into any text you're typing by typing '%y%l$%x' followed by the name of the variable (E.g:  '$myvar' would substitute the description of the variable 'Myvar'.)

To reference variables attached to anything else other than yourself, you must use '%y%l#<ID>:<VARIABLE NAME>%x', e.g:  If I had a variable called '%y%lstore%x' attached to a thing called '%y%lCabinet%x' with the ID %y%l#12345%x, I could reference that variable using '%y%l#12345:store%x', e.g:  To set the variable's description, I'd type '%g%l%(@desc%) #12345:store = <DESCRIPTION>%x'.

You can freely use the '%g%l%(@desc%)%x', '%g%l%(@succ%)%x', '%g%l%(@fail%)%x', '%g%l%(@drop%)%x', '%g%l%(@odesc%)%x', '%g%l%(@osucc%)%x', '%g%l%(@ofail%)%x' and '%g%l%(@odrop%)%x' messages (See help on each of these) of a variable.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@property%>%x', '%g%l%<variable subst%>%x', '%g%l%<@tel%>%x', '%g%l%<drop%>%x', '%g%l%<@desc%>%x' and '%g%l%<building%>%x'.

