%TOPIC !!
%TOPIC historyfacility
%TOPIC lastcommandrecallingfacility
%TITLE Help on '%w%l!!%x' (Last command recalling facility)
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l!! [<PARAMETERS>]%]%x

%@%n has a last command recalling facility that works in a similar way to the '%y%lhistory%x' facility built into most UNIX systems.

%@%n always remembers the last command you typed (Until you disconnect.)

If you need to recall/re-execute the last command you typed, just simply type '%g%l!!%x' and press %c%lRETURN%x.  The last command you typed will then be executed.

You can also add text to the end of the last command you typed by typing '%g%l!!%x' followed by the text to add, e.g:  If you wanted to scan '%y%lJoe Bloggs%x' and then '%y%lFred Bloggs%x', you could type '%g%l%(scan%)%x' and press %c%lRETURN%x (See '%g%l%<scan%>%x'.)  You could then type '%g%l!! fred%x' and '%g%l!! joe%x' to scan '%y%lFred Bloggs%x' and '%y%lJoe Bloggs%x'.

The last command recalling facility is quite handy when you're using a Telnet client which doesn't have its own built-in command recalling facility.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<scan%>%x', '%g%l%<last%>%x', '%g%l%<@censor%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?lastcommand%>%x'.

