%TOPIC while
%TOPIC @while
%TOPIC whileloops
%TITLE Help on '%w%l@while%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@while [true|false] <CONDITION> do [<COMMAND>]
               [<COMMANDS>]
        [@end]%]%x

The '%g%l@while%x' command can be used in two forms:  The first form may only be used on a %c%lSINGLE LINE%x.  '%g%l@while%x' will repeatedly execute %y%l<COMMAND>%x until the command %y%l<CONDITION>%x succeeds (Or fails, if the keyword '%y%lfalse%x' is specified.)

%[%c%lExample:  %g%l@while {%(@eval%) $5 <= 5} do %(@echo%) Loop number:  $5%]%x

%PAGE
The reserved variable %y%l$5%x is useful in an '%g%l@while%x' statement  -  It substitutes the total number of times '%g%l@while%x' has looped (Repeated) so far (%y%l$4%x also substitutes the same.)

%8%c%lNOTE:  %x'%g%l@while%x' can only be used from within compound commands (Unless you're an %r%lExperienced Builder%x or above.)

The second form of '%g%l@while%x' allows you to execute a 'block' of commands.

When using '%g%l@while%x' in this form, it %c%lMUST%x be spread over multiple lines and terminated with '%g%l%(@end%)%x'.  '%g%l@while%x' and '%g%l%(@end%)%x' %c%lMUST NOT%x be preceeded by any text other than blank space, or used within %y%l{}%x's (I.e:  '%g%l{@while ...}%x'.)  The '%y%ldo%x' keyword %c%lMUST NOT%x be followed with a %y%l<COMMAND>%x.

%PAGE
The usage of '%g%l@while%x' in this form is identical to the single lined version of '%g%l@while%x', except it is spread over multiple lines, e.g:

%[%g%l@while {%(@eval%) $5 < 5} do
       %(@echo%) Loop number:  $5
       %(@echo%) {%(@eval%) 5 - $5} loops remaining.
@end%]%x

%9%6%c%lPLEASE NOTE:  %xYou can 'nest' further '%g%l%(@if%)%x', '%g%l%(@case%)%x', '%g%l%(@for%)%x', '%g%l%(@with%)%x', '%g%l%(@while%)%x' and '%g%l%(@foreach%)%x' statements (Both single and multiple lined) within a multiple line '%g%l@while%x' statement.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<condition%>%x', '%g%l%<@end%>%x', '%g%l%<@if%>%x', '%g%l%<@case%>%x', '%g%l%<@for%>%x', '%g%l%<@with%>%x', '%g%l%<@foreach%>%x', '%g%l%<@skip%>%x', '%g%l%<@breakloop%>%x', '%g%l%<@break%>%x', '%g%l%<@return%>%x' and '%g%l%<@goto%>%x'.

