%TOPIC traversinglists
%TITLE help on '%w%l@with%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%l@with [<GRP/RANGE>] [<INDEX>] <OBJECT TYPE> [<OBJECT>] do [<COMMAND>]
              [<COMMANDS>]
        [%(@end%)]%]%x

The '%g%l@with%x' command can be used in two forms:  The first form may only be used on a %c%lSINGLE LINE%x.  '%g%l@with%x' is used to traverse lists of various object types attached to a given object, the elements of a dynamic array or the list of connected characters (%c%lNOTE:  %xOnly %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above may use '%g%l@with connected do ...%x')

%[%c%lExample:  %g%l@with contents here do @echo Current item:  $6%]%x

%PAGE
The reserved variables %y%l$4%x, %y%l$5%x, %y%l$6%x and %y%l$7%x are useful in an '%g%l@with%x' statement  -  These substitute the following...

%4%y%l$4 %xsubstitutes the current item number in the list being processed (Most useful when using grouping/range operators with '%g%l@with%x'.)
%4%y%l$5 %xsubstitutes the total number of items processed so far.
%4%y%l$6 %xsubstitutes the name (Or #ID number if you control it) of the object currently being processed, or the contents/index name of the dynamic array element currently being processed.
%4%y%l$7 %xsubstitutes the description of the object currently being processed, or the index name/contents of the dynamic array element currently being processed.

%8%c%lNOTE:  %x'%g%l@with%x' can only be used from within compound commands (Unless you're an %r%lExperienced Builder%x or above.)

%PAGE
The second form of '%g%l@with%x' allows you to execute a 'block' of commands.

When using '%g%l@with%x' in this form, it %c%lMUST%x be spread over multiple lines and terminated with '%g%l%(@end%)%x'.  '%g%l@with%x' and '%g%l%(@end%)%x' %c%lMUST NOT%x be preceeded by any text other than blank space, or used within %y%l{}%x's (I.e:  '%g%l{@with ...}%x'.)  The '%y%ldo%x' keyword %c%lMUST NOT%x be followed with a %y%l<COMMAND>%x.

The usage of '%g%l@with%x' in this form is identical to the single lined version of '%g%l@with%x', except it is spread over multiple lines, e.g:

%[%g%l@with contents here do
      %(@echo%) Item:  $6
      %(@echo%) Item number (In list):  $4
%(@end%)%]%x

%PAGE
%9%6%c%lPLEASE NOTE:  %xYou can 'nest' further '%g%l%(@if%)%x', '%g%l%(@case%)%x', '%g%l%(@for%)%x', '%g%l%(@with%)%x', '%g%l%(@while%)%x' and '%g%l%(@foreach%)%x' statements (Both single and multiple lined) within a multiple line '%g%l@with%x' statement.


%c%l%$[<GRP/RANGE>]%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
Grouping/range operators may optionally be used with '%g%l@with%x' to process a given page or range of objects/elements/connected characters.  For example, you can process the %c%lfirst page%x of objects in the current room's contents list using '%g%l@with 1:default contents here do ...%x' or process the %c%l2nd%x to %c%l5th%x objects using '%g%l@with 2-5 contents here do ...%x', etc.

See '%g%l%<group%>%x' and '%g%l%<range%>%x' for more details on grouping/range operators and how to use them.

%PAGE

%c%l%$[<INDEX>]%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l[index[|<FIELD TYPE>][|<FIELD TYPE>...][|absolute]: <WILDCARD>]%]%x

Indexing allows you to only process objects with fields (%y%lName%x, %y%ldescription%x, etc.) that match a given wildcard specification.  You can specify which fields to match against %y%l<WILDCARD>%x by separating them with '%y%l|%x's, e.g:  '%g%l@with [index|name|desc: *something*] contents here do ...%x' will only process items in the contents list of the room you're in which have the text '%y%lsomething%x' in their name or description (The '%y%l*%x's are wildcards  -  See '%g%l%<wildcards%>%x' for details on how to use wildcards.)  If you don't specify any fields, name is assumed.
  
%PAGE
When processing the elements of a dynamic array, you can use '%g%l%(desc%)%x' (Contents of elements) or '%g%l%(indexname%)%x' (Index names of elements) as %y%l<FIELD TYPE>%x's, e.g:  '%g%l@with [index|desc: *test*] elements myarray do...%x' will only process elements of '%y%lmyarray%x' which contain the text '%y%ltest%x'.


%c%l%$<OBJECT TYPE>%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
This is the type of objects/list to process, and can be one of the following...

%y%lAlarms%x, %y%larrays%x, %y%lcharacters%x, %y%lcommands%x, %y%lconnected%x (Process list of connected characters), %y%lcontents%x (Process contents list of object), %y%lelements%x (Process elements of dynamic array), %y%lenemies%x, %y%lexits%x, %y%lfothers%x, %y%lfriends%x, %y%lfuses%x, %y%lindex%x (Process index names of the elements of dynamic array), %y%lplayers%x (Same as %y%lcharacters%x), %y%lproperties%x, %y%lpuppets%x, %y%lrooms%x, %y%lthings%x, %y%lvariables%x.

%PAGE

%c%l%$[<OBJECT>]%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~%x
This is the name or ID number of the object that the list of objects you'd like to process is attached to, the name of the character who's friends list you'd like to process, or the dynamic array which you'd like to process the elements/index names of.


%c%l%$Example compound command:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%[%g%l%(@echo%) {%(@?newline%)}Contents of {%(@?name%) here}...
%(@echo%) =======================================================================
@with $1 contents here do %(@echolist%) $4 = {%(@?name%) $6}({%(@?id%) $6})
%(@echo%) =======================================================================
%(@echo%) Items listed: {%(@?display%)}.{%(@?newline%)}%]
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<group%>%x', '%g%l%<range%>%x', '%g%l%<@end%>%x', '%g%l%<@if%>%x', '%g%l%<@case%>%x', '%g%l%<@for%>%x', '%g%l%<@while%>%x', '%g%l%<@foreach%>%x', '%g%l%<@skip%>%x', '%g%l%<@breakloop%>%x', '%g%l%<@break%>%x', '%g%l%<@return%>%x', '%g%l%<@goto%>%x' and '%g%l%<@?totalitems%>%x'

