%TITLE Help on %w%lPersonal Friends/Enemies Lists%x
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%lfothers [<PAGE NO>] [<NAME>] [= <FLAG SPEC>]
        fset <NAME> [=] [!]<FLAG> [[!]<FLAG>] [...]
        flist [<PAGE NO>] [<NAME>] [= <FLAG SPEC>]
        friends|fwho [<PAGE NO>] [<NAME>|<FLAGS>]
        fwhere [<PAGE NO>] [<NAME>|<FLAGS>]
        fchat on|off|<MESSAGE>
        fremove <NAME>
        fadd <NAME>%]%x

Every user on %@%m has their own %c%lpersonal friends list%x.  You can add the names of all your friends and any new friends you make by using the '%g%l%(fadd%)%x' (See '%g%l%<fadd%>%x') command.  If you fall out with one of your friends, you can either remove them using the '%g%l%(fremove%)%x' (See '%g%l%<fremove%>%x') command or make them one of your enemies using '%g%l%(fset%) <NAME> = enemy%x' (See '%g%l%<fset%>%x'.)

%PAGE
You can list all of your friends who are currently connected by typing '%g%l%(fwho%)%x' (See '%g%l%<fwho%>%x') and see where they currently are by typing '%g%l%(fwhere%)%x' (See '%g%l%<fwhere%>%x'.)

There's even a special friends chatting channel ('%g%l%(fchat%)%x'  -  See '%g%l%<fchat%>%x') over which you can talk to all your friends (Providing they're connected of course) at once (Including those who aren't on your friends list, but you're on theirs.)

If you're set %y%l%(LISTEN%)%x ('%g%l%(@set%) me = listen%x'  -  See '%g%l%<listen flag%>%x'), any friends/enemies who connect will have '%y%l(Friend)%x'/'%y%l(Enemy)%x' after their name on their connect message (E.g:  '%y%l[%w%lFred Bloggs%y%l (Friend) has connected.]%x'.)  If you give a friend the %y%lINFORM%x friend flag, you'll get their connect message regardless of whether you're set %y%l%(LISTEN%)%x or not.  Also, people who are your friends/enemies appear in the '%y%l%$Contents:%x' list of the room they're in with '%y%l(Friend)%x'/'%y%l(Enemy)%x' after their name.

%PAGE
'%g%l%(fset%)%x' (See '%g%l%<fset%>%x') is used to set/reset friend flags on your friends.

'%g%l%(flist%)%x' (See '%g%l%<flist%>%x') and '%g%l%(fothers%)%x' (See '%g%l%<fothers%>%x') are used to list people on your friends list and people who have you on their friends list respectively.
<-SEPARATOR->
For a more detailed explanation of the above friends list commands, please see their individual help screens  -  '%g%l%<fadd%>%x', '%g%l%<fremove%>%x', '%g%l%<fchat%>%x', '%g%l%<fwho%>%x', '%g%l%<fwhere%>%x', '%g%l%<fset%>%x', '%g%l%<flist%>%x' and '%g%l%<fothers%>%x'.

