%TOPIC writeflag
%TOPIC writefriendflag
%TOPIC friendwriteflag
%TOPIC friendswriteflag
%TITLE Help on the %w%lWRITE%x friend flag
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%lfset <NAME> [=] WRITE
        fset <NAME> [=] !WRITE%]%x

When this friend flag is set on one of your friends, they will be granted '%c%lwrite%x' permission to all of your objects (With the exception of your character), providing they are a %y%l%(BUILDER%)%x (See '%g%l%<builder%>%x') or above.

Due to the dangers of giving '%c%lwrite%x' permission to other users, the %y%l%(^friends SHARABLE%)%x friend flag (See '%g%l%<sharable friend flag%>%x') is also set automatically and the %y%l%(^friend COMMANDS%)%x friend flag (See '%g%l%<commands friend flag%>%x') is reset automatically (This restricts their '%c%lwrite%x' permission to objects of yours (Excluding compound commands) which have their %y%l%(SHARABLE%)%x flag (See '%g%l%<sharable flag%>%x') set only.)

If you want to give full '%c%lwrite%x' permission to a user (Which is %r%l%f%u*EXTREMELY DANGEROUS*%x), simply reset their %y%l%(^friend SHARABLE%)%x friend flag ('%g%l%(fset%) <NAME> = !sharable%x') and set their %y%l%(^friend COMMANDS%)%x friend flag ('%g%l%(fset%) <NAME> = commands%x'.)

%PAGE
Friend who have been granted '%c%lwrite%x' permission will be able to modify, move, '%g%l%(examine%)%x', list and perform query commands on your objects.  However, they will not be able to destroy objects or create new ones (Unless you set their %y%l%(^friend DESTROY%)%x and/or %y%l%(^friend CREATE%)%x (See '%g%l%<destroy friend flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<create friend flag%>%x') friend flags respectively.)

The '%c%lwrite%x' permission will not apply to compound commands, unless the %y%l%(^friend COMMANDS%)%x friend flag is also set.

Giving out '%c%lwrite%x' permission to your objects is %r%linheritantly dangerous%x, however their are some sensible precautions you can take:

%4%m%l*  %xEnsure each user with '%c%lwrite%x' permission also has their %y%l%(^friend SHARABLE%)%x friend flag set (This will only allow objects of yours with the %y%l%(SHARABLE%)%x flag set to be modified.)

%PAGE
%4%m%l*  %xEnsure that their %y%l%(^friend COMMANDS%)%x friend flag is not set, and that they do not have access to any of your compound commands, otherwise they will be able to modify your compound commands.  This will allow them to modify a compound command of yours to give them full '%c%lread%x' and '%c%lwrite%x' privileges to your objects %r%l%uAND%x your character.

   %9%2%c%lNOTE:  %xThe %y%l%(^friend CREATE%)%x friend flag will allow them to create a compound command under your ownership, if their %y%l%(^friend COMMANDS%)%x friend flag is set.

%9%6%c%lPLEASE NOTE:  %xFor security, efficiency and integrity, %y%l%(^friend READ%)%x, %y%l%(^friend WRITE%)%x, %y%l%(^friend CREATE%)%x and %y%l%(^friend DESTROY%)%x privileges gained via friend flags do not apply within compound commands.  They are only effective when used on the command-line (Outside of a compound command.)

%9%2%r%l%uWARNING%r%l:  %xThis friend flag should be set with %m%l%f*EXTREME CAUTION*%x.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<builder%>%x', '%g%l%<sharable friend flag%>%x', '%g%l%<examine%>%x', '%g%l%<destroy friend flag%>%x', '%g%l%<create friend flag%>%x', '%g%l%<commands friend flag%>%x', '%g%l%<@chpid%>%x' and '%g%l%<fset%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC fwhere
%TOPIC fwherelist
%TOPIC friendswherelist
%TITLE Help on '%w%lfwhere%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%lfwhere [<PAGE NO>] [<NAME>|<FLAGS>]%]%x

Displays a list of all your friends who are currently connected and where they currently are (Similar to the '%g%l%(where%)%x' (See '%g%l%<where%>%x' command.)

Any names displayed in square brackets ('%y%l[]%x') are people who have you in their friends list, but you don't have them in yours.  Any name displayed in '%y%l<>%x's is a friend (Either in your friends list or you're in theirs) who has turned off the friends chatting channel (See '%g%l%<fchat%>%x'), have removed your %y%lFCHAT%x friend flag (See '%g%l%<fset%>%x') in their friends list, or you've removed theirs (These characters wont receive messages sent by you over '%g%l%(fchat%)%x', and you wont receive messages from them.)  Any names displayed in '%y%l{}%x's are people who are your enemies.

%PAGE
If %y%l<PAGE NO>%x is specified, the list of users will be split up into pages and the page number specified will be displayed, e.g:  '%g%lfwhere 1%x', '%g%lfwhere 2%x', etc.

If %y%l<NAME>%x is specified, just that one character is listed.  If one or more flags (Separated by spaces) are specified instead of %y%l<NAME>%x, only characters with those flags are listed, e.g:  '%g%lfwhere admin%x', '%g%lfwhere mortals%x', '%g%lfwhere haven quiet%x', etc.

In addition to '%g%l%(fwho%)%x' and '%g%lfwhere%x', you can also type '%g%l%(who%) friends%x' to list your connected friends in the format given by the '%g%l%(who%)%x' command (Single column with titles, etc.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<fwho%>%x', '%g%l%<who%>%x' and '%g%l%<friends%>%x'.

