%TOPIC drive
%TOPIC driving
%TOPIC movingvehicles
%TOPIC drivingvehicles
%TITLE Help on '%w%ldrive%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%ldrive <DIRECTION>%]%x

The '%g%ldrive%x' command is used to drive a vehicle which can be entered (Using the '%g%l%(enter%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<enter%>%x')), such as a %c%lcar%x, %c%llorry%x, %c%lbus%x, etc.

In order to drive a vehicle, you must first be inside it (Type '%g%l%(enter%) <VEHICLE>%x' to attempt to enter it.)  If the vehicle can't be entered, it must be ridden, using the '%g%l%(ride%)%x' command (See '%g%l%<ride%>%x'.)

Once inside the vehicle, you can look out of it (At it's current location) by typing '%g%l%(look%) outside%x'.  You can then drive the vehicle, using '%g%ldrive <DIRECTION>%x'.  %y%l<DIRECTION>%x is the name of the %c%l%(exit%)%x to drive it through, the %c%l#ID number%x of an %y%l%(ABODE%)%x room (See '%g%l%<abode flag%>%x') or the name of a %c%lconnected character%x, e.g:  '%g%ldrive east%x'.

%8%c%lNOTE:  %xA vehicle can only be driven into locations which have their %y%l%(TRANSPORT%)%x flag set (See '%g%l%<transport flag%>%x'.)  A vehicle can't be driven through an exit which doesn't have its %y%l%(TRANSPORT%)%x flag set.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<ride%>%x', '%g%l%<transport%>%x', '%g%l%<transport flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<abode flag%>%x'.

