%TITLE Help on '%w%lset lftocr%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%lset lftocr [=] lfcr|crlf|lf|cr
        set lftocr%]%x

Some Telnet clients don't return the cursor to the far left of the screen when they receive a %y%lLF%x (%c%lLine Feed%x) character.  This results in a grossly messed up display.

To solve this problem, '%g%lset lftocr%x' is provided, which allows you to change the end-of-line termination sequence that %@%m uses to suit your Telnet client.

In most cases, typing either '%g%lset lftocr lfcr%x' or '%g%lset lftocr crlf%x' fixes display problems.  The other options are '%g%lset lftocr cr%x' and '%g%lset lftocr lf%x' (Default.)  %y%lLF%x is a %c%lLine Feed%x character, and %y%lCR%x is a %c%lCarriage Return%x.

Typing '%g%lset lftocr%x' without any parameters will display your current end-of-line termination sequence.

%8%c%lNOTE:  %xYour preferred end-of-line termination sequence is remembered when you disconnect.
<-SEPARATOR->
Type '%g%l%<set term%>%x' for help on the next '%g%l%(set%)%x' command...

