%TOPIC pagingfacility
%TOPIC morepagingfacility
%TITLE Help on '%w%lmore%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%lmore [<COMMAND>]
        more on|off%]%x

%@%n features a 'more' paging facility, which can be used to page the subsequent output of any command, so you can read it a page at a time rather than it uselessly scrolling past continuously.

You can turn the 'more' paging facility on by typing '%g%lmore on%x' or '%g%l%(set%) more on%x' (See '%g%l%<set more%>%x'.)  This will automatically page the output of the following commands (Which usually produce a lot of output):  '%g%l%(look%)%x', '%g%l%(scan%)%x', '%g%l%(inventory%)%x', '%g%l%(examine%)%x', the BBS '%g%lread%x' command (See '%g%l%<BBS%>%x'), the mail '%g%lread%x' command (See '%g%l%<mail%>%x'), '%g%l%(@list%)%x', '%g%l%(@find%)%x', '%g%l%(@entrances%)%x' and the various user lists (I.e:  '%g%l%(who%)%x', '%g%l%(swho%)%x', etc.)

However, some Telnet clients have a 'more' paging or scroll-back facility built into them ('%g%l/more on%x' in %c%lTinyFugue%x for example), in which case you may like to disable 'more' paging in %@%m, by typing '%g%lmore off%x' or '%g%l%(set%) more off%x'.

%PAGE
Regardless of whether the 'more' paging facility is on or off, you can force the subsequent output of %c%lANY%x command to be paged by typing '%g%lmore <COMMAND>%x', e.g:  '%g%lmore %(@list%) me = all%x'.

When the output of a command is paged with %@%m's 'more' paging facility, you'll see a line which looks something like the following:

%c[%c%l%uMORE%c:  %y%l(Page 1 of 3)  %c-  %c%l(%w%l%uN%c%l)ext/(%w%l%uP%c%l)revious page, (%w%l%uR%c%l)e-display or (%w%l%uS%c%l)kip...%c]%x

This shows you which page you are currently looking at, and how many pages there are in total.  You can display the next page by pressing the %c%lRETURN%x/%c%lENTER%x key on your computer/terminal, or by typing '%g%ln%x' ('%g%lnext%x'.)

%PAGE
You can re-display the current page by typing '%g%lr%x' ('%g%lredisplay%x'), go back to the previous page by typing '%g%lp%x' ('%g%lprevious%x'.)  You can also go to the first page by typing '%g%lf%x' ('%g%lfirst%x') and last page by typing '%g%ll%x' ('%g%llast%x'.)

You can skip the rest of the pages and leave the 'more' paging facility by typing '%g%ls%x' ('%g%lskip%x'.)  You can also execute any %@%m command whilst in the 'more' paging facility by typing '%g%l.<COMMAND>%x' or '%g%l.x <COMMAND>%x', e.g:  '%g%l.%(page%) fred = hello%x' (%c%lPLEASE NOTE:  %xThe output of any commands executed from within the 'more' paging facility %c%lWILL NOT%x be paged.)

%8%c%lHINT:  %xYou can make a compound command that automatically pages its output (Depending on the 'more' paging preference of the character executing it) by placing the command '%g%lmore%x' (Without any parameters) at the beginning of the compound command.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<look%>%x', '%g%l%<scan%>%x', '%g%l%<profile%>%x', '%g%l%<inventory%>%x', '%g%l%<page%>%x', '%g%l%<examine%>%x', '%g%l%<BBS%>%x', '%g%l%<mail%>%x', '%g%l%<@list%>%x', '%g%l%<@find%>%x', '%g%l%<@entrances%>%x', '%g%l%<set%>%x' and '%g%l%<set more%>%x'.

