%TITLE Help on '%w%ltell%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%ltell <NAME>[,<NAME>][,<NAME>][...] [=] <MESSAGE>
        ><NAME>[,<NAME>][,<NAME>][...] [=] <MESSAGE>
        .<NAME>[,<NAME>][,<NAME>][...] [=] <MESSAGE>%]%x

This command is used to tell a message to any character who's connected, or a group of connected characters, regardless of whether they're in the same room as you.

If all of the characters are in the same room as you, everyone else will hear what you say to them (Making '%g%ltell%x' a great way of directing messages to particular characters when having a big conversation in a room.)  If one or more recipients aren't in the same room as you, only the recipients will receive your message.

Characters who aren't connected, set %y%l%(HAVEN%)%x (See '%g%l%<haven flag%>%x') or have reset your %y%lPAGETELL%x friend flag (See '%g%l%<fset%>%x') will only receive your message if they're in the same room as you.

%PAGE
You can tell a message to more than one person at once by giving a list of names separated by '%y%l,%x' or '%y%l;%x', e.g:  '%g%ltell fred;joe = hello%x' will tell the users %c%lFred%x and %c%lJoe%x "%y%lHello%x".  If you use '%g%ltell%x' without an '%y%l=%x' to separate the name(s) and message, the list of names must contain %c%lNO%x spaces.

When telling a message to someone, only the first unique characters of their name are needed (E.g:  To tell '%y%lFred Bloggs%x' something, you can type '%g%ltell fred = <MESSAGE>%x'.)

You can tell all your connected friends or enemies a message by typing '%g%ltell %(friends%) <MESSAGE>%x' or '%g%ltell enemies <MESSAGE>%x' and tell all connected Admin (%y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above) a message by typing '%g%ltell admin <MESSAGE>%x'.  You can also use '%g%l%(tf%) <MESSAGE>%x' to tell a message to all your connected friends.

The second and third forms (A '%g%l>%x' or '%g%l.%x' followed by your message) are easier to type, e.g:  '%g%l.fred hello%x' to tell %c%lFred%x "%y%lHello%x".
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<page%>%x', '%g%l%<recall%>%x', '%g%l%<reply%>%x', '%g%l%<repeat%>%x', '%g%l%<tf%>%x', '%g%l%<tellblock%>%x', '%g%l%<.message%>%x' and '%g%l%<.tell%>%x'.

