%TOPIC flaglistings
%TOPIC flagslistings
%TOPIC flagscommands
%TITLE Help on '%g%lsettings%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%lsettings <OBJECT>%]%x

Displays brief information about the object %y%l<OBJECT>%x, providing you either own/control it, or you're an %r%lExperienced Builder%x or an %y%lApprentice Wizard/%yDruid%x or above.

The information displayed includes the object's %c%lname%x, %c%lowner%x, %c%lBuilding Quota%x used/in use, %c%lflags%x currently set on object and its %c%llock%x specification (If it has a lock.)

The '%g%lsettings%x' command is useful for finding out what flags are currently set or the lock specification of an object without having to use the '%g%l%(examine%)%x' command to examine it (Which can produce a lot of output.)

The '%g%l%(examine%)%x' command can be used to obtain more detailed information about a particular object.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<examine%>%x', '%g%l%<flags%>%x', '%g%l%<locks%>%x' and '%g%l%<@set%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC !
%TOPIC shout
%TOPIC @wall
%TITLE Help on '%w%lshout%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%lshout <MESSAGE>
        shout :<MESSAGE>
        shout ;<MESSAGE>%]%x

'%g%lshout%x' can only be used by %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x and above, providing their %y%l%(SHOUT%)%x flag hasn't been reset.

The first form shouts "%y%l<MESSAGE>%x" to every character connected.

The second form (Putting a '%y%l:%x' in front of your message) broadcasts '%y%l[ANNOUNCEMENT:  %w%l<NAME> <MESSAGE>%y%l]%x' to every character connected (It works just like emoting (Or posing) a message.)

The third form (Putting a '%y%l;%x' in front of your message, which can only be used by %c%lWizards/%cDruids%x and above) broadcasts '%r%l[BROADCAST MESSAGE from %y%l<NAME>%r%l:  %w%l<MESSAGE>%r%l]%x' to every character connected and makes their terminal beep.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<yell%>%x', '%g%l%<yell flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<shout flag%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC summon
%TOPIC summoning
%TOPIC summoningusers
%TITLE Help on '%w%lsummon%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%lsummon <NAME> [= <REASON>]
        summon accept|refuse%]%x

The '%g%lsummon%x' command allows you to summon a user to your current location.

If no reason is given (I.e:  '%g%lsummon <NAME>%x'), the user %y%l<NAME>%x will be told that you wish to summon them to your present location, and can accept by typing '%g%lsummon accept%x' or refuse by typing '%g%lsummon refuse%x'.  If they accept, then they will be teleported to your current location.

This usage of '%g%lsummon%x' can be used by anyone (Including Mortal users) and is ideal for allowing users into your private rooms/areas without having to set %y%l%(ABODE%)%x flags (See '%g%l%<abode flag%>%x'), unlock exits, etc.  It's also ideal for summoning your Puppet to your current location (As you control your puppet, they do not need to accept your summon  -  They'll be immediately teleported to your current location.)

%PAGE
If you're an %y%lApprentice Wizard/%yDruid%x and above, and give a reason, the summon will be unconditional and the user will be immediately teleported to your current location (The reason you give will be shown to the user being summoned and logged to the '%c%lSummon%x' log file (See '%g%l%<@log%>%x'.))  This usage of '%g%lsummon%x' is useful when dealing with abusive/problem users.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<visit%>%x', '%g%l%<@teleport%>%x', '%g%l%<abode flag%>%x' and '%g%l%<@log%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC swho
%TOPIC shortwho
%TOPIC shortwholisting
%TITLE Help on '%w%lswho%x' (Or '%w%lshortwho%x')
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%lshortwho [<PAGE NO>] [<NAME>|<FLAGS>]
        swho [<PAGE NO>] [<NAME>|<FLAGS>]%]%x

Displays a full list of all characters connected to %@%n in multiple columns (Names of characters only.)

If %y%l<PAGE NO>%x is specified, the list of users will be split up into pages and the page number specified will be displayed, e.g:  '%g%lswho 1%x', '%g%lswho 2%x', etc.

If %y%l<NAME>%x is specified, just that one character is listed.  If one or more flags (Separated by spaces) are specified instead of %y%l<NAME>%x, only characters with those flags are listed, e.g:  '%g%lswho admin%x', '%g%lswho mortals%x', '%g%lswho haven quiet%x', etc.

%PAGE
Some characters in the list may have a symbol to the left of their name.  The symbol indicates their rank/status, which is as follows:

%[   %g%l@   Elder Wizard/%gDruid%x or above.
   %c%l*   Wizard/%cDruid%x.
   %y%l~   Apprentice Wizard/%yDruid%x.
   %r%l=   Experienced Builder/Retired Wizard%x.
   %r+   Assistant/Retired Druid%x.
   `   Puppet.
   %b%l!   Moron.%]%x
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<who%>%x' and '%g%l%<where%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC use
%TOPIC .use
%TOPIC useobject
%TOPIC usingobjects
%TITLE Help on '%w%luse%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%luse <OBJECT> [[on|in|with|to] <PARAMETERS>]
        use <OBJECT> [= <PARAMETERS>]%]%x

Allows you to use the specified object (If it can be used), where %y%l<OBJECT>%x is the name of the object.

%y%l<PARAMETERS>%x are optional parameters that can be given when using the object, for example, if the object was a weapon, its parameters could be the name of the character to use it on, e.g:  '%g%luse sword on fred bloggs%x', '%g%luse armour on me%x', etc.

%PAGE
%y%l<OBJECT>%x can be any type of object (I.e:  It doesn't necessarily have to be a thing.)

The following types of objects have a default use (If they do not have a '%g%l.use%x' compound command attached):

  %r%l%6*  %m%lCompound Command  %c-  %xExecutes with optional parameters given to '%g%luse%x'.
  %y%l%6*  %m%lThing/Room        %c-  %xLooks at room/thing (See '%g%l%<look%>%x'.)
  %r%l%6*  %m%lCharacter         %c-  %xShows character's '%g%l%(scan%)%x' (See '%g%l%<look%>%x'.)
  %y%l%6*  %m%lExit              %c-  %xGo through exit.

%PAGE

%c%l%$The '%w%l%$.use%c%l%$' compound command
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%xIn order for an object to be used, it must have a compound command named '%c%l.use%x' attached to it.  To attach a '%c%l.use%x' compound command to an object, simply teleport it into the object, e.g:  '%g%l%(@tel%) .use = <OBJECT>%x' (See '%g%l%<@tel%>%x'.)

When the object is used (By typing '%g%luse <OBJECT>%x'), its '%c%l.use%x' compound command is executed.  If optional %y%l<PARAMETERS>%x have been specified by the user, these will be given as parameters to the compound command in the usual manner (I.e:  %y%l$1%x, %y%l$2%x, %y%l$3%x, etc.)

%8%c%lNOTE:  %xAny type of object which can have compound commands attached to it can be used using the '%g%luse%x' command, even compound commands.

       %8%xA compound command with multiple names can include '%c%l.use%x', e.g:  '%y%lattack;.use%x'.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<take%>%x', '%g%l%<drop%>%x', '%g%l%<give%>%x', '%g%l%<@command%>%x' and '%g%l%<@tel%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC who
%TOPIC users
%TOPIC wholist
%TOPIC userlist
%TOPIC wholisting
%TOPIC connectedplayers
%TOPIC connectedcharacters
%TITLE Help on '%w%lwho%x' ('%w%lusers%x' or '%w%luserlist%x')
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%luserlist [<PAGE NO>] [<NAME>|<FLAGS>]
        users [<PAGE NO>] [<NAME>|<FLAGS>]
        who [<PAGE NO>] [<NAME>|<FLAGS>]%]%x

Displays a full list of all characters connected to %@%n, along with their login time, title, flags and idle time (You can set your title (The message that appears after your name) by typing '%g%l%(title%) <TITLE>%x'  -  See '%g%l%<title%>%x'.)

If %y%l<PAGE NO>%x is specified, the list of users will be split up into pages and the page number specified will be displayed, e.g:  '%g%lwho 1%x', '%g%lwho 2%x', etc.

If %y%l<NAME>%x is specified, just that one character is listed.  If one or more flags (Separated by spaces) are specified instead of %y%l<NAME>%x, only characters with those flags are listed, e.g:  '%g%lwho admin%x',  '%g%lwho mortals%x', '%g%lwho haven quiet%x', etc.

You can also type '%g%lwho %(friends%)%x' to list your connected friends (As an alternative to '%g%l%(fwho%)%x' (See '%g%l%<fwho%>%x') or '%g%l%(fwhere%)%x' (See '%g%l%<fwhere%>%x'.))

%PAGE

%c%l%$The flags displayed for each character are as follows:%x
%~%c~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%x
H    Character is %y%l%(HAVEN%)%x and doesn't wish to be disturbed.
Q    Character is %y%l%(QUIET%)%x and wont see connects, %(shout%)s, etc.
F    Character is one of your %(friends%).
!    Character is one of your enemies.

%b%lM    %xCharacter is a %b%l%(Moron%)%x.
p    Character is a %(puppet%) under the control of another user.
b    Character is a virtual %(Being%) under computer control.
B    Character is a %(Builder%) and may build locations, areas, etc.
%r%lX %rx  %xCharacter is an %r%lExperienced Builder%x or %rAssistant%x.
%r%lR %rr  %xCharacter is a %r%lRetired Wizard%x or %rRetired Druid%x.
%y%lA %ya  %xCharacter is an %y%l%(Apprentice Wizard%)%x or %y%(Apprentice Druid%)%x.
%c%lW %cw  %xCharacter is a %c%l%(Wizard%)%x or %c%(Druid%)%x.
%g%lE %ge  %xCharacter is an %g%l%(Elder Wizard%)%x or %g%(Elder Druid%)%x.
%m%lD    %xCharacter is a %m%l%(Deity%)%x or the %m%l%(Supreme Being%)%x.

%PAGE
%9%y%lTime:   %xHow long each character has been connected to %@%n.

%9%y%lIdle:   %xHow long each character has been %(idle%) (Doing nothing.)


%9%y%lUsers:  %xTells you how many users are currently connected and how many of them are %m%lDeities%x, %g%lElder Wizards/%gDruids%x, %c%lWizards/%cDruids%x, %y%lApprentice Wizards/%yDruids%x, Builders/%r%lExperienced Builders%x, Mortals, Puppets and %b%lMorons%x.  For Admin, the percentage of users who are currently idle and the percentage of users who are Admin are also displayed.

%9%y%lPeak:   %xTells you the largest number of users connected simultaneously so far today (Since midnight) and the average daily peak.

%9%y%lUp:     %xHow long %@%m has been running without being shutdown by the administrator(s).

%9%c%lNOTE:   %xThe peak number of users, etc. and the up time are also displayed on the other user lists too (E.g:  '%g%l%(swho%)%x', '%g%l%(where%)%x', etc.)
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<title%>%x', '%g%l%<swho%>%x', '%g%l%<where%>%x'.

%COMMENT --------------------------------------------------------------------->

%TOPIC uptime
%TOPIC serveruptime
%TITLE Help on '%w%luptime%x'
%[%c%lUSAGE:  %g%luptime%]%x

%m%l%$The '%y%l%$uptime%m%l%$' command shows the following:
%~%m~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
%4%r%l*  %xThe time and date when %@%n was last restarted.

%4%y%l*  %xHow long it has been running for (Without being shutdown) since that date.

%4%r%l*  %xThe time and date when the database was created.

%4%y%l*  %xThe accumulated up-time since the database was created (The total accumulated time %@%n has been running for since the database was created, excluding periods when it was down.)

%4%r%l*  %xThe average up-time (Worked out by dividing the accumulated up-time by the number of times %@%n has been restarted.)

%4%y%l*  %xThe longest recorded up-time and the time/date it occurred.
<-SEPARATOR->
Also, see '%g%l%<@?uptime%>%x'.

